{Hello and welcome to my first Chessable course! My name is Aljoscha Feuerstack and I have been an International Master for over 10 years. The Sicilian Four Knights has been an integral and successful part of my black repertoire since 2006. I am delighted to have the opportunity to share my many years of experience with this exciting opening. What makes the Sicilian Four Knights worthwhile to learn? With this opening you can...  * fight for the initiative with the black pieces right from the start;  * achieve dynamic positions with winning chances for both sides;  * surprise many of your opponents;  * start the game with a knowledge advantage. The repertoire I propose is based on side lines, which offers a great practical advantage over other, better-known Sicilians. But you will also start the game with a healthy position against a well-prepared opponent, because despite the surprise effect, we don't play for tricks. I have tested all the suggested variations with modern engines and have played many of them in tournament practice. The course consists of four parts 1) The Quickstarter Guide [/course/199209/2] is ideal for a quick introduction to the repertoire. It contains the most important variations and ideas. The knowledge in this chapter is a good basis for initial practical experience. I recommend that you start your study of the course here. 2) The theory chapters naturally form the main content of the course. I have organised them according to the importance of the variations: We start with the main moves 6.Ndb5 and 6.Nxc6 and deal with the less frequent and less critical moves in the later chapters. The chapters can, however, be studied in any order. 3) In the Model Games chapter [/course/199209/14] you will find a selection of annotated example games. These give an impression of how the game can develop in practice, beyond theoretical knowledge. 4) You can test your knowledge in the exercises [/course/199209/15]. The positions are taken from practical games related to this repertoire and teach both tactical and positional motifs for both sides. Many thanks to IM Dirk Sebastian and FM Martin Voigt for helping me with the research. Let's now move on to an overview of the theory chapters.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 ({I will deal with alternatives to this - such as the Alapin (} 2. c3 {) or the Closed Sicilian (}) (2. Nc3 {) – in a separate course on the Anti-Sicilians.}) 2... e6 3. d4 {The Open Sicilian. This course contains a complete repertoire against 3.d4. Third-move alternatives are also covered in my anti-Sicilian course.} cxd4 4. Nxd4 {Normally this is the automatic reply. White has, however, also tried other moves, which we will look at in the eleventh chapter [/course/199209/13].} Nf6 5. Nc3 ({The e4-pawn was under attack and 5.Nc3 is the most natural defensive move.} 5. Bd3 {is a valid alternative here. Together with rarer alternatives we look at it in the eleventh chapter [/course/199209/13].}) 5... Nc6 6. Ndb5 ({The fourth knight is developed - we have now reached the starting position of the Sicilian Four Knights. The main variations are now} 6. Ndb5 {and}) (6. Nxc6 {, but White can choose from a number of alternative moves.}) ({The most common continuation. The knight sets its sights on the squares d6 and c7. Alternatives A) The exchange} 6. Nxc6 {is in second place on the popularity scale.} bxc6 7. e5 {(7.Bd3 poses no problems and is discussed along with other side lines in the fifth chapter [/course/199209/7])} Nd5 8. Ne4 {( for 8.Nxd5 also see the fifth chapter [/course/199209/7])} Qc7 9. f4 Qb6 10. c4 {. White has a number of alternatives to this, all of which are discussed in the fifth chapter [/course/199209/7].} Ne3 $5 {. This is the basic position of the fourth chapter [/course/199209/6]. The variations are comparatively long and complicated, so it is worth studying them in depth.}) ({B) The developing move} 6. Be2 {is normally associated with a pawn sacrifice. Black doesn't have any problems, but precision is important. Details can be found in the sixth chapter [/course/199209/8].}) ({C) The fianchetto} 6. g3 {is a comparatively slow, positional development plan. We deal with it in the seventh chapter [/course/199209/9].}) ({D) With} 6. a3 $5 {White prevents ...Bb4. The battle now takes on a less forced character, as you will see in chapter eight [/course/199209/10].}) ({E)} 6. Be3 {is a popular, but not particularly strong way of developing. In the ninth chapter [/course/199209/11] I'll show why. F) There are a few more alternatives for White on the sixth move, which will be examined in the tenth chapter [/course/199209/12].}) 6... Bc5 $5 ({This comparatively rare move is known as the 'Cobra Variation'. It leads to unusual and dynamic positions, which are explored in the first three chapters. I'm less fond of the more popular} 6... Bb4 {, where Black faces a long struggle for equality.}) 7. Bf4 {O-O Bc7! Qe7 Bd6 Bxd6 Qxd6 Qd8! O-O-O a6 Nd4 Ne7! I have expanded on this variation at some length because it is a good opportunity to tell you about my personal relationship with the Sicilian Four Knights: In 2006, I attended a lecture by IM Vadim Cernov as a participant in a preparatory camp for the German Youth Championship. Cernov is one of the pioneers of the Cobra Variation. This variation was an absolute niche at the time, but I was fascinated by the energetic character of Black's play and the resulting unusual positions. I was able to convert my newly acquired knowledge into two victories in the aforementioned tournament. But I have to admit: My enthusiasm didn't last long. In the main line, the present position, Black had problems and my analyses did not produce a satisfactory solution. For a long time, I therefore only played the Sicilian Four Knights as an occasional surprise weapon or in blitz chess. It wasn't until 2017 that a solution was found with} Ne7 {, which has led to a renaissance of the Cobra Variation and has also restored my own confidence in this opening. Black avoids the knight exchange and achieves full counterplay on the queenside. I am very grateful to Vadim Cernov for generously sharing his knowledge. Although the theory has evolved a lot since 2006, I still very much agree with his general approach: his handwriting can be found in many parts of the course. Finally, it only remains for me to wish you much joy and success with the Sicilian Four Knights! I look forward to your feedback and your experiences with the material. If you have any questions about specific positions, find a mistake or feel that a particular move needs to be analysed, I would be grateful if you could leave a comment. The interactivity of Chessable allows us to improve the course together in this way.} *

