Nb5 {.}) 5. Nc3 ({Develops the knight and reinforces White's influence on the central square d5. Moreover, the diagonal a5-e1 is now interrupted, so that e4-e5 becomes a strong threat.} 5. e5 $2 {allows the double attack} Qa5+ {followed by -- Qxe5 .}) 5... Nc6 {Another natural developing move that continues the fight for the central squares. Black, at least temporarily, is preventing e4-e5 and threatening ...Bb4 with pressure on the white center. The starting position of the Sicilian Four Knights has now been reached. This method of play was first used in the second half of the 19th century. Early adopters included the masters Schiffers, Blackburne, Mieses, and Janowski. White now has a multitude of options.} 6. Ndb5 ({White moves the knight for the third time, but there are good reasons for this time loss. Due to the pawn moves, Black has weakened the squares d6 and c7 . Specifically, an unpleasant knight check on d6 is threatened. For a long time, 6.Ndb5 was considered the main variation. However, at the highest level there has recently been a trend towards} 6. Nxc6 {. The reason for this is that after}) (6. Ndb5 {, Black can transition into the Sveshnikov Sicilian, where White currently struggles to prove an opening advantage. However, 6.Ndb5 still remains the most common move, especially below grandmaster level.}) 6... Bc5 $5 ({A rare move that will come as a surprise to many of our opponents. More popular are} 6... d6 {(which usually leads to the Sveshnikov variation) or}) (6... Bb4 {. With}) (6... Bc5 {, Black prepares to castle and targets the tactically vulnerable point f2. Additionally, Black can now respond to the knight check on d6 with a king move without blocking the development of the bishop on f8.}) 7. Bf4 {The most common continuation. White is threatening a knight fork on c7 and simultaneously targets the weakened d6 square. The move e4-e5 is also a threat.} O-O ({The only good move. Black secures their king, dodges the knight checks, and provides the knight on f6 a retreat square on e8. If Black now manages to liberate the queenside with ...d7-d5, they would already be better. Therefore, White should now aim to blockade the pawn on d7.} 7... e5 $2 8. Be3 $1 Bxe3 9. Nd6+ Ke7 10. fxe3 {. A very similar position arises after 7.Be3 Bxe3 8.Nd6+ Ke7 9.fxe3 . The only difference is that the black e-pawn is already on e5 here. This small difference turns out to be fatal for Black, because the squares f5 and d5 are accessible to the white pieces, and Bc4 with an attack on f7 is also an option.}) 8. Bc7 {The strongest continuation. The black queen is driven to an unfavorable square, after which White can exchange bishops and occupy the blockade square d6 with tempo.} Qe7 9. Bd6 {The idea of the previous move.} Bxd6 10. Qxd6 Qd8 $1 {The direct queen trade leads to a slightly worse position for Black because the d-pawn is backward and weak and the bishop on c8 is undeveloped. Therefore, Black accepts a loss of time and relies on counterplay on the queenside. White now has two critical continuations: The main line 11.0-0-0 and 11.Nc7 .} 11. Nc7 ({An interesting move which requires a precise response. The idea is to maintain the blockade on the dark squares by ensuring the queen can no longer be driven away from d6. After ...Nf6-e8, a knight exchange will now always follow. It's important for White to play Nc7 directly and not as a response to ...a7-a6. For example, after} 11. O-O-O a6 {,} 12. Nc7 {would be a gross mistake, as after} Ra7 {the knight would be trapped and can be attacked through a move of the b-pawn.}) 11... Rb8 12. Be2 {Black must act energetically so as not to end up in a passive position. The pawn is attacked three times, but if White takes it, the b-file opens for the black rook. The advance of the b-pawn has several functions:  * The white knight on c3 can be attacked with ...b5-b4.  * The development of the bishop is prepared.  * The maneuver ...Rb6 is now also possible, which can drive the White queen away from its strong position.} e5 13. Ne8 Rxe8 14. O-O {Now White is ready to take the pawn on b5. b4} Nxe4 {Bb7 The bishop is now developed but cannot yet make its influence felt because it is blocked by Black's own knight. This determines the plan for the coming moves. The knight should be regrouped via e7. Often a preparatory move like ...Ba8 or ...a7-a5 is necessary to defend the pawns on the queenside. Black has equal chances. Chapter, extended analyses, and model games  * Chapter 1: [/course/199209/3] Cobra Main Line I 7.Bf4 O-O 8.Bc7  * Variation: [/variation/31422885/#/16/b] Main Line I with 11.Nc7 and 17.Nc5  * Variation: [/variation/31422886/#/16/b] Main Line I with 11.Nc7 and 17.Rfd1  * Variation: [/variation/31422887/#/16/b] Main Line I with 11.Nc7 and 17.Bd3  * Variation: [/variation/31422892/#/16/b] Main Line I with 11.Nc7 and 17.Qc5} *

