Nb5 {.}) 5. Nc3 ({Develops the knight and reinforces White's influence on the central square d5. Moreover, the diagonal a5-e1 is now interrupted, so that e4-e5 becomes a strong threat.} 5. e5 $2 {allows the double attack} Qa5+ {followed by -- Qxe5 .}) 5... Nc6 {Another natural developing move that continues the fight for the central squares. Black, at least temporarily, is preventing e4-e5 and threatening ...Bb4 with pressure on the white center. The starting position of the Sicilian Four Knights has now been reached. This method of play was first used in the second half of the 19th century. Early adopters included the masters Schiffers, Blackburne, Mieses, and Janowski. White now has a multitude of options.} 6. Ndb5 ({White moves the knight for the third time, but there are good reasons for this time loss. Due to the pawn moves, Black has weakened the squares d6 and c7 . Specifically, an unpleasant knight check on d6 is threatened. For a long time, 6.Ndb5 was considered the main variation. However, at the highest level there has recently been a trend towards} 6. Nxc6 {. The reason for this is that after}) (6. Ndb5 {, Black can transition into the Sveshnikov Sicilian, where White currently struggles to prove an opening advantage. However, 6.Ndb5 still remains the most common move, especially below grandmaster level.}) 6... Bc5 $5 ({A rare move that will come as a surprise to many of our opponents. More popular are} 6... d6 {(which usually leads to the Sveshnikov variation) or}) (6... Bb4 {. With}) (6... Bc5 {, Black prepares to castle and targets the tactically vulnerable point f2. Additionally, Black can now respond to the knight check on d6 with a king move without blocking the development of the bishop on f8.}) 7. Nd6+ ({Less popular than} 7. Bf4 {, but quite natural. Now Black loses the right to castle.}) 7... Ke7 $1 ({Not} 7... Bxd6 $2 8. Qxd6 {. Black can't castle here either, and the dark squares are firmly under White's control.} Qe7 9. Bf4 $16 {. It is important to dislodge the d6 knight from its strong blockade position. White is not sufficiently developed to directly pose problems for Black's centralized king.}) 8. Nxc8+ $6 {This exchange is quite popular and has even been played by many strong grandmasters. However, the hope for an advantage due to the bishop pair is misplaced here, as the white bishops lack activity. Still, I find it somewhat surprising that White already has to fight for equality.} Rxc8 9. Bd3 Qc7 10. O-O h5 $1 {[%eval 32764,0] With this strong move, Black secures the initiative. All black pieces are now well placed - even the rook on h8 is joining the action. The threat is ...Ng4. White would then have to play g2-g3 to prevent checkmate on h2. This later allows Black to create the pawn break ...h5-h4, opening up the h-file. White lacks defenders on the kingside. Chapter, extended analyses, and model games  * Chapter 2: [/course/199209/4] Cobra Main Line II 7.Nd6+  * Variation: [/variation/31422914/#/10/b] Main Line II with 8.Nxc8+ and 11.Na4  * Variation: [/variation/31422915/#/10/b] Main Line II with 8.Nxc8+ and 11.Bg5 #1  * Variation: [/variation/31422916/#/10/b] Main Line II with 8.Nxc8+ and 11.Bg5} *

