rtant to dislodge the d6 knight from its strong blockade position. White is not sufficiently developed to directly pose problems for Black's centralized king.}) 8. Bf4 {The strongest move. The knight on d6 restricts the black position and is therefore fortified.} e5 {A move that Black does not like to make, but here it is forced. Otherwise, the d6 knight cannot be dislodged. In exchange for that, Black has to accept a weakening of the light squares.} 9. Nf5+ Kf8 10. Bg5 {This solid developing move has been established as best. Black can now take on f5 if necessary. Usually, however, the bishop goes to e6, where it stabilizes the position. On the kingside, Black plans the pawn moves ...h6 and ...g6, forcing the white pieces to retreat or be exchanged. The king then goes to g7, where it is relatively safe and no longer in the way of the rook on h8. Ne3 This prevents ...Bxf5 and threatens Ned5. Be6 Ncd5? This misses Black's answer.} Qa5 {The typical response, which leads to Black winning material. c3 Nxe4} 11. Z0 ({Black wins an important central pawn without any compensation and has a winning position.} 11. b4 {doesn't help:} Nxb4 {cxb4 Bxb4+} 12. Ke2 {Bxd5 Nxd5 Nxg5-+ . Chapter, extended analyses, and model games  * Chapter 2: [/course/199209/4] Cobra Main Line II 7.Nd6+  * Variation: [/variation/31422937/#/13/b] Main Line II with 11.Ne3 and 12.Ncd5}) *

