{Black decides to ignore b2-b4. Equally possible was a6 , giving the bishop a retreat square. However, it's not so clear which side benefits more from the exchange on e3. By taking the knight, Black loses the bishop pair but gains more control over d5. We have reached a typical position for the line with 6.Nd6+. The pawn structure and the placement of the white knights resemble the Sveshnikov Sicilian. Only the bishop on c5 doesn't quite fit this picture. Objectively, the position is balanced, but is slightly more pleasant for White to play. Especially the pawn break f2-f4 is a danger that Black should keep in mind. The opening of the f-file could lead to uncomfortable pressure against Black's king. To preemptively counter that, it would be desirable for Black to exchange some minor pieces. For this purpose, ...Ne7-xd5 and ...Bxe3 are options. However, we should avoid exchanging the light-squared bishop, as it serves an important defensive function. After the exchange of minor pieces, it is sometimes possible to trade the backward d6 pawn with ...d6-d5. The typical counterplay in the Sveshnikov Sicilian with ...f7-f5 usually doesn't work so well here. After an exchange on f5, the black king becomes too exposed. However, it wouldn't hurt to play ...Rf8 to further prepare against f2-f4. On the queenside, both sides will try to gain space through pawn moves. Chapter, extended analyses, and model games  * Chapter 2: [/course/199209/4] Cobra Main Line II 7.Nd6+  * Variation: [/variation/31422940/#/16/b] Main Line II with 11.Ne3 and 12.Bd3} 1. e4 c5 {The Sicilian Opening stands for a sharp fight. Black somewhat neglects their piece development in order to prevent White from establishing a full pawn center with d2-d4.} 2. Nf3 e6 ({The third most common move after} 2... d6 {and}) (2... Nc6 {. With this, Black primarily prepares the development of the dark-squared bishop, but the center push ...d7-d5 becomes a possibility as well.}) 3. d4 {The Open Sicilian and the starting 