that after}) (6. Ndb5 {, Black can transition into the Sveshnikov Sicilian, where White currently struggles to prove an opening advantage. However, 6.Ndb5 still remains the most common move, especially below grandmaster level.}) 6... Bc5 $5 ({A rare move that will come as a surprise to many of our opponents. More popular are} 6... d6 {(which usually leads to the Sveshnikov variation) or}) (6... Bb4 {. With}) (6... Bc5 {, Black prepares to castle and targets the tactically vulnerable point f2. Additionally, Black can now respond to the knight check on d6 with a king move without blocking the development of the bishop on f8.}) 7. Nd6+ ({Less popular than} 7. Bf4 {, but quite natural. Now Black loses the right to castle.}) 7... Ke7 $1 ({Not} 7... Bxd6 $2 8. Qxd6 {. Black can't castle here either, and the dark squares are firmly under White's control.} Qe7 9. Bf4 $16 {. It is important to dislodge the d6 knight from its strong blockade position. White is not sufficiently developed to directly pose problems for Black's centralized king.}) 8. Bf4 {The strongest move. The knight on d6 restricts the black position and is therefore fortified.} e5 {A move that Black does not like to make, but here it is forced. Otherwise, the d6 knight cannot be dislodged. In exchange for that, Black has to accept a weakening of the light squares.} 9. Nf5+ Kf8 10. Bg5 {This solid developing move has been established as best. Black can now take on f5 if necessary. Usually, however, the bishop goes to e6, where it stabilizes the position. On the kingside, Black plans the pawn moves ...h6 and ...g6, forcing the white pieces to retreat or be exchanged. The king then goes to g7, where it is relatively safe and no longer in the way of the rook on h8. Ne3 This prevents ...Bxf5 and threatens Ned5. Be6 Bd3} ({Protects e4 and therefore threatens} 10. Z0 {Ned5 Bxd5} Nd5 {.}) {Bxf6 Qxf6 O-O} 10... g6 {The usual procedure to connect the rooks.} 11. Nd5 {Qd8 c3} *

