{After exf6 Qxf6! , Black wins back the piece under favorable circumstances. This double attack on the pawns e5 and b2 poses greater practical problems for White than Bxd6 , which is also a good move. Now White has to play very precisely to keep the balance. Chapter, extended analyses, and model games  * Chapter 3: [/course/199209/5] Cobra Side Lines  * Variation: [/variation/31422980/#/10/b] Side Line 8.e5} 1. e4 c5 {The Sicilian Opening stands for a sharp fight. Black somewhat neglects their piece development in order to prevent White from establishing a full pawn center with d2-d4.} 2. Nf3 e6 ({The third most common move after} 2... d6 {and}) (2... Nc6 {. With this, Black primarily prepares the development of the dark-squared bishop, but the center push ...d7-d5 becomes a possibility as well.}) 3. d4 {The Open Sicilian and the starting position of this course. I examine alternatives for White on the second and third moves in a separate course on the Anti-Sicilians. The Open Sicilian is White's most principled attempt to fight for the opening advantage. White has more space and wants to open up the position, relying on rapid piece development. In return, Black gets the semi-open c-file, which can often be used for counterplay later on. Moreover, the exchange of the d-pawn for the c-pawn is a minor positional concession, as White now has only one pawn in the center and therefore can no longer fight quite as well for the important central squares.} cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 ({A very logical move - the knight is developed and simultaneously attacks the e4 pawn. Black takes advantage of the fact that the knight cannot be directly attacked with e4-e5 .} 4... Nc6 {is also possible, but gives White the additional option} 5. Nb5 {.}) 5. Nc3 ({Develops the knight and reinforces White's influence on the central square d5. Moreover, the diagonal a5-e1 is now interrupted, so that e4-e5 becomes a strong threat.} 5. e5 $2 {allows the double attack} Qa5+ {followed by -- Qxe5 .}) 5... Nc6 {Another natural developing move that continues the fight for the central squares. Black, at least temporarily, is preventing e4-e5 and threatening ...Bb4 with pressure on the white center. The starting position of the Sicilian Four Knights has now been reached. This method of play was first used in the second half of the 19th century. Early adopters included the masters Schiffers, Blackburne, Mieses, and Janowski. White now has a multitude of options.} 6. Ndb5 ({White moves the knight for the third time, but there are good reasons for this time loss. Due to the pawn moves, Black has weakened the squares d6 and c7 . Specifically, an unpleasant knight check on d6 is threatened. For a long time, 6.Ndb5 was considered the main variation. However, at the highest level there has recently been a trend towards} 6. Nxc6 {. The reason for this is that after}) (6. Ndb5 {, Black can transition into the Sveshnikov Sicilian, where White currently struggles to prove an opening advantage. However, 6.Ndb5 still remains the most common move, especially below grandmaster level.}) 6... Bc5 $5 ({A rare move that will come as a surprise to many of our opponents. More popular are} 6... d6 {(which usually leads to the Sveshnikov variation) or}) (6... Bb4 {. With}) (6... Bc5 {, Black prepares to castle and targets the tactically vulnerable point f2. Additionally, Black can now respond to the knight check on d6 with a king move without blocking the development of the bishop on f8.}) 7. Bf4 ({The only good move. Black secures their king, dodges the knight checks, and provides the knight on f6 a retreat square on e8. If Black now manages to liberate the queenside with ...d7-d5, they would already be better. Therefore, White should now aim to blockade the pawn on d7.} 7. e5 $2 Be3 $1 8. Bxe3 {Nd6+} Ke7 {fxe3+- . A very similar position arises after 7.Be3 Bxe3 8.Nd6+ Ke7 9.fxe3 . The only difference is that the black e-pawn is already on e5 here. This small difference turns out to be fatal for Black, because the squares f5 and d5 are accessible to the white pieces, and Bc4 with an attack on f7 is also an option.}) 7... e5 ({This intermediate move is more accurate than the immediate 8...Ne8. Primarily, Black wants to drive away the b5 knight in order to have the option of ...Bd4 later. Ne8} 7... Nxe4 {is slightly better for White, because Black does not have the active reaction ...Bd4 here.}) 8. Nd6+ {Ne8 Nce4 Bd4} *

