he knight on f6 a retreat square on e8. If Black now manages to liberate the queenside with ...d7-d5, they would already be better. Therefore, White should now aim to blockade the pawn on d7.} 7... e5 $2 8. Be3 $1 Bxe3 9. Nd6+ Ke7 10. fxe3 {. A very similar position arises after 7.Be3 Bxe3 8.Nd6+ Ke7 9.fxe3 . The only difference is that the black e-pawn is already on e5 here. This small difference turns out to be fatal for Black, because the squares f5 and d5 are accessible to the white pieces, and Bc4 with an attack on f7 is also an option.}) 8. Bd6 {Thanks to this tactical detail, Black manages to activate their queen. White must not capture the rook. Bxc5} ({Bxf8?? Bxf2+} 8. Kd2 {Qe3# .}) {Qxc5 Black is now threatening ...d7-d5, after which the white knights can subsequently be driven to bad squares with ...a7-a6 or ...d5-d4. Qd6 Bc7, White hopes for a blockade of the opponent's queenside. However, unlike there, the black queen is already activated here, giving Black dangerous threats and preventing White from castling queenside due to the attack on f2.} 8... Qb6 {Black is threatening ...a7-a6. Qc7 The most common move. Faced with the opponent's threats, White tries to repeat moves. Black can go along with it or keep the game alive. Qxc7} ({Qc5 Qd6} 8... Qb6 {leads to a repetition of moves.}) 9. Nc7 Rb8 {[%eval 32764,0] This is a good way to avoid the repetition. Black is threatening ...a7-a6, after which the c7-knight would have no retreat square. Chapter, extended analyses, and model games  * Chapter 3: [/course/199209/5] Cobra Side Lines  * Variation: [/variation/31422995/#/12/b] Side Line 8.Bd6 with 13.O-O-O #1  * Variation: [/variation/31422996/#/12/b] Side Line 8.Bd6 with 13.O-O-O #2  * Variation: [/variation/31422998/#/12/b] Side Line 8.Bd6 with 13.O-O-O #3  * Variation: [/variation/31422999/#/12/b] Side Line 8.Bd6 with 13.N7b5 #1  * Variation: [/variation/31423000/#/12/b] Side Line 8.Bd6 with 13.N7b5} *

