s the bishop on c8, which is blocked by Black's own pawns and cannot be activated easily.} Qc7 ({The main move. Black attacks the e5-pawn and forces a weakening of White's position. The alternative} 8... Bb7 {is also popular nowadays. Black wants to play ...c6-c5 and quickly solve the problem of the 'bad' light-squared bishop.}) 9. f4 {The queen has fulfilled its purpose on c7 and moves to a better square. On b6, the queen performs a number of functions:  * It controls the weakened a7-g1 diagonal.  * It threatens the double attack 10...Qb4+.  * It attacks the b2-pawn, complicating the development of the c1-bishop.  * It supports ...Ne3.  * It supports the attempt to exchange the light-squared bishops with ...Ba6. c4 Qd3 Obviously the best square for the queen, as it also needs to protect c2.} {I pondered for a long time whether to recommend the knight move or the main line Bb4+ . The latter is discussed at the highest level and, from a theoretical standpoint, Black is in good shape. On the other hand, after Ne3 , White achieves a slightly better position with best play from both sides. Still, I decided on 10...Ne3. The downside of 10...Bb4+ is that the theory is quite far advanced and leads to very complicated positions where one misstep can be fatal. In my opinion, 10...Ne3 is easier to play because the variations resulting from it are more straightforward.} Bb4+ {With this check, Black gains some time. Not only because the bishop is developed with a tempo, but also because after the main move 12.Bd2, the knight on e3 is no longer attacked.} 10. Bd2 Ba6 $5 ({The bishop on d2 is pinned, so Black can leave the knight on e3 for now. ➤} 10... Ba6 {attacks the c4 pawn and forces White to make a decision: defend the pawn or engage in the complications after} 11. Bxb4 {.}) ({➤ The more frequently played} 10... O-O {is less appealing to me because after} 11. Rc1 {(with the threat of c4-c5) Black cannot avoid exchanges and risks being left with a passive light-squared bishop against a strong knight.}) 11. Rc1 {By capturing on c4, Black gets a rook and two pawns for two minor pieces. Rxc4 Nxc4 Qxc4} Bxd2+ {Regardless of how White recaptures, Black next takes on b2. The position is dynamically equal. Chapter, extended analyses, and model games  * Chapter 4: [/course/199209/6] Exchange Variation (6.Nxc6) Main Line 10.c4  * Variation: [/variation/31423007/#/15/b] Main Line 10.c4 with 13.Rc1 and 16.Nxd2  * Variation: [/variation/31423008/#/15/b] Main Line 10.c4 with 13.Rc1 and 16.Kxd2  * Model game: [/variation/31423248/#/15/b] Olexiy Bilych – Emil Risteski} *

