s. Black, at least temporarily, is preventing e4-e5 and threatening ...Bb4 with pressure on the white center. The starting position of the Sicilian Four Knights has now been reached. This method of play was first used in the second half of the 19th century. Early adopters included the masters Schiffers, Blackburne, Mieses, and Janowski. White now has a multitude of options.} 6. Nxc6 {This initiates one of the sharpest and most complex variations in the Sicilian Four Knights. We will see very unusual positions that are unfamiliar from any other opening. 6.Nxc6 is the second most common move after 6.Ndb5.} bxc6 ({Black would now like to play ...d7-d5 and would then have a solid position with good central control.} 6... dxc6 {leads to a queenless middlegame that is slightly better for White.} 7. Qxd8+ Kxd8 8. Bf4 $14 {. The main problem in Black's position is the passive bishop on c8.}) 7. e5 {The critical move. White prevents ...d7-d5 – the d7 pawn is now backward. In addition, White prepares to put pressure on the weakened d6-square. A third advantage from White's perspective is that a defender of the kingside is driven away, making future attacks there more promising. Of course, the pawn move also has its drawbacks. We will see in the following variations that the pawn on e5 itself becomes a target of Black's counterplay. White will have to accept weaknesses in their own camp to defend the exposed pawn.} Nd5 8. Ne4 {White avoids exchanging knights and targets the weakened d6-square. A subsequent c2-c4 could drive the black knight away from its central position and also give the white queen access to d6. The main problem for Black is the bishop on c8, which is blocked by Black's own pawns and cannot be activated easily.} Qc7 ({The main move. Black attacks the e5-pawn and forces a weakening of White's position. The alternative} 8... Bb7 {is also popular nowadays. Black wants to play ...c6-c5 and quickly solve the problem of the 'bad' light-squared bishop.}) 9. f4 {The queen has fulfilled its purpose on c7 and moves to a better square. On b6, the queen performs a number of functions:  * It controls the weakened a7-g1 diagonal.  * It threatens the double attack 10...Qb4+.  * It attacks the b2-pawn, complicating the development of the c1-bishop.  * It supports ...Ne3.  * It supports the attempt to exchange the light-squared bishops with ...Ba6. c4 Qd3 Obviously the best square for the queen, as it also needs to protect c2.} {I pondered for a long time whether to recommend the knight move or the main line Bb4+ . The latter is discussed at the highest level and, from a theoretical standpoint, Black is in good shape. On the other hand, after Ne3 , White achieves a slightly better position with best play from both sides. Still, I decided on 10...Ne3. The downside of 10...Bb4+ is that the theory is quite far advanced and leads to very complicated positions where one misstep can be fatal. In my opinion, 10...Ne3 is easier to play because the variations resulting from it are more straightforward.} Bb4+ {With this check, Black gains some time. Not only because the bishop is developed with a tempo, but also because after the main move 12.Bd2, the knight on e3 is no longer attacked.} 10. Bd2 Ba6 $5 ({The bishop on d2 is pinned, so Black can leave the knight on e3 for now. ➤} 10... Ba6 {attacks the c4 pawn and forces White to make a decision: defend the pawn or engage in the complications after} 11. Bxb4 {.}) ({➤ The more frequently played} 10... O-O {is less appealing to me because after} 11. Rc1 {(with the threat of c4-c5) Black cannot avoid exchanges and risks being left with a passive light-squared bishop against a strong knight.}) 11. Bxb4 {With this, White demonstrates good theoretical knowledge. White initiates a forced sequence, at the end of which there is an unusual material balance. Qxb4+ Kf2 Qxb2+!} ({Black should engage in the complications. Nxc4? is a tactical mistake. After Qb3 , Black loses a piece, for example Rb8} 11. Bc4 Bxc4 {Qxc4! Qxc4} 12. Nd6+ {.}) {Nf5?! Qc3!? Qxc3 bxc3 . The problem child of the black position is the bishop on a6. I don’t see how it can be activated. White has the advantage.} 11... Be2 {Now the rook on a1 is protected and, in addition to capturing the knight, Rhb1 (or Rab1) is a threat. Nxc4! Again, Black should not shy away from the complications. Rhd1} 12. Qd4 {Nb2 It's best to give back some material in return for immediately escaping the unpleasant pin.} {The queen is safer here than on b2 and also protects the bishop on a6. After Ke1 or Kg3 , Black can simply play O-O , after which White cannot exploit the pin of the c4-knight and doesn’t have enough play for the two pawns. Therefore, White's response is forced.} Ba6 {White wins two pieces for a rook. Nxd1+} 13. Rd1 {Qxd4+} ({But not Qxa6?? Qxd7+ Kf8} 13. Ng5 {and Black is soon checkmated.}) *

