Nb5 {.}) 5. Nc3 ({Develops the knight and reinforces White's influence on the central square d5. Moreover, the diagonal a5-e1 is now interrupted, so that e4-e5 becomes a strong threat.} 5. e5 $2 {allows the double attack} Qa5+ {followed by -- Qxe5 .}) 5... Nc6 {Another natural developing move that continues the fight for the central squares. Black, at least temporarily, is preventing e4-e5 and threatening ...Bb4 with pressure on the white center. The starting position of the Sicilian Four Knights has now been reached. This method of play was first used in the second half of the 19th century. Early adopters included the masters Schiffers, Blackburne, Mieses, and Janowski. White now has a multitude of options.} 6. Nxc6 {This initiates one of the sharpest and most complex variations in the Sicilian Four Knights. We will see very unusual positions that are unfamiliar from any other opening. 6.Nxc6 is the second most common move after 6.Ndb5.} bxc6 ({Black would now like to play ...d7-d5 and would then have a solid position with good central control.} 6... dxc6 {leads to a queenless middlegame that is slightly better for White.} 7. Qxd8+ Kxd8 8. Bf4 $14 {. The main problem in Black's position is the passive bishop on c8.}) 7. Bd3 {With this natural developing move, White keeps the option of e4-e5 open for later.} d5 {A recurring theme in this course. Against slow moves by White, Black can often establish a pawn presence in the center and comfortably equalize.} 8. O-O {The position now resembles a popular line of the Taimanov Sicilian: 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 e6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nc6 5.Nc3 a6 6.Nxc6 bxc6 7.Bd3 d5 8.O-O Nf6 . Unlike in that line, here Black does not lose a tempo for ...a7-a6 and thus has a significantly better version.} Be7 ({In positions after 7.Bd3, e7 is usually the right square for the bishop. Next, Black wants to castle and has comfortable play.} 8... Bd6 {looks more active, but after} 9. Qe2 {, Black needs to worry about the threat of e4-e5. If Black guards this square with} Qc7 {,} 10. exd5 $1 {follows. Now,} Nxd5 {is necessary because the desirable 10...cxd5? is met with 11.Nb5 and an exchange of the important bishop. After our text move 8….Be7, White lacks the resource 11.Nb5 at this point. On 10...Bxh2? , 11.Kh1 follows, and due to the threats of 12.g3 or 12.f4, Black can't recapture on d5. Chapter, extended analyses, and model games  * Chapter 5: [/course/199209/7] Exchange Variation (6.Nxc6) Side Lines  * Variation 5A: [/variation/31423049/#/8/b] Side line 7.Bd3 with 9.Re1 #1  * Variation 5A: [/variation/31423050/#/8/b] Side line 7.Bd3 with 9.Re1 #2  * Variation 5A: [/variation/31423051/#/8/b] Side line 7.Bd3 with 9.e5 #1  * Variation 5A: [/variation/31423052/#/8/b] Side line 7.Bd3 with 9.e5 #2  * Variation 5A: [/variation/31423053/#/8/b] Side line 7.Bd3 with 9.Qe2}) *

