Nb5 {.}) 5. Nc3 ({Develops the knight and reinforces White's influence on the central square d5. Moreover, the diagonal a5-e1 is now interrupted, so that e4-e5 becomes a strong threat.} 5. e5 $2 {allows the double attack} Qa5+ {followed by -- Qxe5 .}) 5... Nc6 {Another natural developing move that continues the fight for the central squares. Black, at least temporarily, is preventing e4-e5 and threatening ...Bb4 with pressure on the white center. The starting position of the Sicilian Four Knights has now been reached. This method of play was first used in the second half of the 19th century. Early adopters included the masters Schiffers, Blackburne, Mieses, and Janowski. White now has a multitude of options.} 6. Nxc6 {This initiates one of the sharpest and most complex variations in the Sicilian Four Knights. We will see very unusual positions that are unfamiliar from any other opening. 6.Nxc6 is the second most common move after 6.Ndb5.} bxc6 ({Black would now like to play ...d7-d5 and would then have a solid position with good central control.} 6... dxc6 {leads to a queenless middlegame that is slightly better for White.} 7. Qxd8+ Kxd8 8. Bf4 $14 {. The main problem in Black's position is the passive bishop on c8.}) 7. e5 {The critical move. White prevents ...d7-d5 – the d7 pawn is now backward. In addition, White prepares to put pressure on the weakened d6-square. A third advantage from White's perspective is that a defender of the kingside is driven away, making future attacks there more promising. Of course, the pawn move also has its drawbacks. We will see in the following variations that the pawn on e5 itself becomes a target of Black's counterplay. White will have to accept weaknesses in their own camp to defend the exposed pawn.} Nd5 8. Nxd5 {This exchange rather helps Black.} cxd5 {The doubled pawn can be resolved at will with ...d7-d6. However, Black does not need to rush this, as the e5-pawn can also serve as a target for the queen. Besides, Black has the other pawn break ...f7-f6, after which the central pawns might become very strong.} 9. Bd3 Qc7 $5 {The attack on the e5-pawn is more dangerous than it appears. All defensive moves have drawbacks.} 10. Qe2 Bb4+ $1 {Now, White loses the right to castle.} 11. Kf1 (11. c3 $2 Bxc3+ {wins material for Black.} 12. bxc3 Qxc3+ {followed by -- Qxa1 .}) 11... Rb8 {A useful move with the hidden threat ...Bc3. Black has comfortable equality. Chapter, extended analyses, and model games  * Chapter 5: [/course/199209/7] Exchange Variation (6.Nxc6) Side Lines  * Variation 5C: [/variation/31423060/#/11/b] Side line 8.Nxd5 with 12.h4  * Variation 5C: [/variation/31423061/#/11/b] Side line 8.Nxd5 with 12.Bf4} *

