{Welcome to the Quickstarter Chapter! Here, you'll find a compilation of the most important variations and most common ideas. I recommend starting your engagement with the course here. Studying this chapter enables you to acquire a repertoire in the Open Sicilian with minimal time investment. This will allow you to gather initial practical experience, making your learning process more personal and effective. If your interest in a particular variation is sparked – whether through engagement with the theory or through practical play – you can deepen your knowledge by studying the relevant chapter. There, you will often find additional comments and deeper analysis.} 1. e4 c5 {The Sicilian Opening stands for a sharp fight. Black somewhat neglects their piece development in order to prevent White from establishing a full pawn center with d2-d4.} 2. Nf3 e6 ({The third most common move after} 2... d6 {and}) (2... Nc6 {. With this, Black primarily prepares the development of the dark-squared bishop, but the center push ...d7-d5 becomes a possibility as well.}) 3. d4 {The Open Sicilian and the starting position of this course. I examine alternatives for White on the second and third moves in a separate course on the Anti-Sicilians. The Open Sicilian is White's most principled attempt to fight for the opening advantage. White has more space and wants to open up the position, relying on rapid piece development. In return, Black gets the semi-open c-file, which can often be used for counterplay later on. Moreover, the exchange of the d-pawn for the c-pawn is a minor positional concession, as White now has only one pawn in the center and therefore can no longer fight quite as well for the important central squares.} cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 ({A very logical move - the knight is developed and simultaneously attacks the e4 pawn. Black takes advantage of the fact that the knight cannot be directly attacked with e4-e5 .} 4... Nc6 {is also possible, but gives White the additional option} 5. Nb5 {.}) 5. Nc3 ({Develops the knight and reinforces White's influence on the central square d5. Moreover, the diagonal a5-e1 is now interrupted, so that e4-e5 becomes a strong threat.} 5. e5 $2 {allows the double attack} Qa5+ {followed by -- Qxe5 .}) 5... Nc6 {Another natural developing move that continues the fight for the central squares. Black, at least temporarily, is preventing e4-e5 and threatening ...Bb4 with pressure on the white center. The starting position of the Sicilian Four Knights has now been reached. This method of play was first used in the second half of the 19th century. Early adopters included the masters Schiffers, Blackburne, Mieses, and Janowski. White now has a multitude of options.} 6. Nxc6 {This initiates one of the sharpest and most complex variations in the Sicilian Four Knights. We will see very unusual positions that are unfamiliar from any other opening. 6.Nxc6 is the second most common move after 6.Ndb5.} bxc6 ({Black would now like to play ...d7-d5 and would then have a solid position with good central control.} 6... dxc6 {leads to a queenless middlegame that is slightly better for White.} 7. Qxd8+ Kxd8 8. Bf4 $14 {. The main problem in Black's position is the passive bishop on c8.}) 7. e5 {The critical move. White prevents ...d7-d5 – the d7 pawn is now backward. In addition, White prepares to put pressure on the weakened d6-square. A third advantage from White's perspective is that a defender of the kingside is driven away, making future attacks there more promising. Of course, the pawn move also has its drawbacks. We will see in the following variations that the pawn on e5 itself becomes a target of Black's counterplay. White will have to accept weaknesses in their own camp to defend the exposed pawn.} Nd5 8. Ne4 {White avoids exchanging knights and targets the weakened d6-square. A subsequent c2-c4 could drive the black knight away from its central position and also give the white queen access to d6. The main problem for Black is the bishop on c8, which is blocked by Black's own pawns and cannot be activated easily.} Qc7 ({The main move. Black attacks the e5-pawn and forces a weakening of White's position. The alternative} 8... Bb7 {is also popular nowadays. Black wants to play ...c6-c5 and quickly solve the problem of the 'bad' light-squared bishop.}) 9. f4 {The queen has fulfilled its purpose on c7 and moves to a better square. On b6, the queen performs a number of functions:  * It controls the weakened a7-g1 diagonal.  * It threatens the double attack 10...Qb4+.  * It attacks the b2-pawn, complicating the development of the c1-bishop.  * It supports ...Ne3.  * It supports the attempt to exchange the light-squared bishops with ...Ba6. Bd3 The second most common move after 10.c4. White develops the bishop and defends against Black's threats.} Ba6 {The downside of White's last move. Black can now force the exchange of bishops.} 10. Bxa6 (10. c4 $2 {is bad due to the counterattack Qd4! . See this variation [/variation/31423073/#/11/b].}) {Qxa6 Qe2 Qxe2+ Black should acquiesce to the exchange of queens. Kxe2} 10... f5 $1 {Black can't do without this move. The knight on e4 is too strong.} 11. Nf2 {The knight usually ends up on d3 later, where it covers f4 and b4 and can potentially go to c5.} c5 ({The main move} 11... Rb8 {is playable as well, but it's not so clear yet if the rook belongs there. It also takes away the option to castle queenside. With}) (11... c5 {, Black is threatening ...c5-c4, which would take away the d3 square from the knight. Therefore, White should play c2-c4 themselves.}) 12. c4 Nb4 {There's no other good square for the knight. From b4, it covers d3, so it can be exchanged for the white knight if needed, and it can potentially be transferred to d4 via c2.} 13. Bd2 {White is threatening to exchange on b4. a5 Now, the exchange on b4 is no longer a concern for Black, as they can recapture with the a-pawn. White now appears somewhat more comfortable visually, but there is no breakthrough into Black's very solid position. A draw is the likely outcome. Chapter, extended analyses, and model games  * Chapter 5: [/course/199209/7] Exchange Variation (6.Nxc6) Side Lines  * Variation 5D: [/variation/31423078/#/16/b] Sideline 10.Bd3 with 11.Bxa6} *

