Nb5 {.}) 5. Nc3 ({Develops the knight and reinforces White's influence on the central square d5. Moreover, the diagonal a5-e1 is now interrupted, so that e4-e5 becomes a strong threat.} 5. e5 $2 {allows the double attack} Qa5+ {followed by -- Qxe5 .}) 5... Nc6 {Another natural developing move that continues the fight for the central squares. Black, at least temporarily, is preventing e4-e5 and threatening ...Bb4 with pressure on the white center. The starting position of the Sicilian Four Knights has now been reached. This method of play was first used in the second half of the 19th century. Early adopters included the masters Schiffers, Blackburne, Mieses, and Janowski. White now has a multitude of options.} 6. Be2 {O-O Black should accept the invitation. White was already threatening to exchange on c6 and play e4-e5. bxc3} Nxe4 7. Qd3 ({Black has won a pawn and is threatening to capture another on c3. However, Black must be cautious: their king is still in the center, and White's pair of bishops can become very powerful. The most popular attempts for White are now} 7. Bd3 {and}) (7. Qd3 {. Additionally, the long-forgotten}) (7. Nxc6 {has been rediscovered in recent years, infusing the 6.Be2 variation with new life.}) {The second most popular move. White protects the c3-pawn and attacks the knight.} 7... d5 {[%eval 32762,0] Ba3 The knight interrupts the a3-f8 diagonal, so Black manages to castle. White can later regain the pawn, which leads to a battle with equal chances. Chapter, extended analyses, and model games  * Chapter 6: [/course/199209/8] Pawn Sacrifice Variation (6.Be2)  * Variation 6D: [/variation/31423103/#/10/b] Pawn Sacrifice Variation with 9.Qd3 and 11.Qb5+  * Variation 6D: [/variation/31423104/#/10/b] Pawn Sacrifice Variation with 9.Qd3 and 11.c4 #1  * Variation 6D: [/variation/31423105/#/10/b] Pawn Sacrifice Variation with 9.Qd3 and 11.c4 #2  * Variation 6D: [/variation/31423106/#/10/b] Pawn Sacrifice Variation with 9.Qd3 and 11.c4} *

