Nb5 {.}) 5. Nc3 ({Develops the knight and reinforces White's influence on the central square d5. Moreover, the diagonal a5-e1 is now interrupted, so that e4-e5 becomes a strong threat.} 5. e5 $2 {allows the double attack} Qa5+ {followed by -- Qxe5 .}) 5... Nc6 {Another natural developing move that continues the fight for the central squares. Black, at least temporarily, is preventing e4-e5 and threatening ...Bb4 with pressure on the white center. The starting position of the Sicilian Four Knights has now been reached. This method of play was first used in the second half of the 19th century. Early adopters included the masters Schiffers, Blackburne, Mieses, and Janowski. White now has a multitude of options.} 6. Be2 {O-O Black should accept the invitation. White was already threatening to exchange on c6 and play e4-e5. bxc3} Nxe4 7. Bd3 ({Black has won a pawn and is threatening to capture another on c3. However, Black must be cautious: their king is still in the center, and White's pair of bishops can become very powerful. The most popular attempts for White are now} 7. Bd3 {and}) (7. Qd3 {. Additionally, the long-forgotten}) (7. Nxc6 {has been rediscovered in recent years, infusing the 6.Be2 variation with new life.}) {This forceful move is the most popular choice here and has several advantages from White's point of view: The threat of ...Nxc3 is neutralized, as now only the queen would be attacked, not the bishop on e2 at the same time. In addition, from d3 the bishop keeps an eye on the black kingside, and the white queen can also attack the kingside via g4 or h5. Last but not least, the move comes with a tempo, allowing White to maintain the initiative.} 7... d5 {The knight is well placed on e4 and should be maintained there for the time being. Black's next goal is to castle, after which White would have little to show for being a pawn down. The main idea for White, therefore, is to stop Black from castling with Ba3. 10.Ba3 is the most common move, but the prior exchanges on e4 or c6 are also possible. Ba3 Qc1 On another occasion, I advised against continuing to play for pawn grabbing. Here, however, it is correct to capture the pawn, especially as it comes with a tempo on the d4-knight. White was already threatening 12.Nb3 followed by c3-c4 to open up the position, which would have quickly become uncomfortable for the centralized black king.} 8. Nb3 {The knight retreats with tempo, but is somewhat misplaced on b3.} Qc7 {Black is planning ...f7-f6 followed by ...Kf7. The knight on c3 can be defended with ...d5-d4 if necessary. White's compensation for the pawns is sufficient to keep the balance. Chapter, extended analyses, and model games  * Chapter 6: [/course/199209/8] Pawn Sacrifice Variation (6.Be2)  * Variation 6D: [/variation/31423118/#/12/b] Pawn Sacrifice Variation with 9.Bd3 and 13.Qe3  * Variation 6D: [/variation/31423119/#/12/b] Pawn Sacrifice Variation with 9.Bd3 and 13.Qe1  * Variation 6D: [/variation/31423120/#/12/b] Pawn Sacrifice Variation with 9.Bd3 and 13.Re1} *

