Nb5 {.}) 5. Nc3 ({Develops the knight and reinforces White's influence on the central square d5. Moreover, the diagonal a5-e1 is now interrupted, so that e4-e5 becomes a strong threat.} 5. e5 $2 {allows the double attack} Qa5+ {followed by -- Qxe5 .}) 5... Nc6 {Another natural developing move that continues the fight for the central squares. Black, at least temporarily, is preventing e4-e5 and threatening ...Bb4 with pressure on the white center. The starting position of the Sicilian Four Knights has now been reached. This method of play was first used in the second half of the 19th century. Early adopters included the masters Schiffers, Blackburne, Mieses, and Janowski. White now has a multitude of options.} 6. g3 {White fianchettoes the bishop. An understandable approach – after many other moves, Black achieves quick pressure against the e4-pawn with ...Bb4. From g2, White's bishop supports the center and counteracts this plan. On the other hand, White uses two moves instead of just one for the bishop's development. Therefore, it's not surprising that this move is not particularly critical.} d5 ({Against most of the sidelines on move six, I recommend either 6...Bb4 or 6...d5. Here,} 6... Bb4 {is the most common move and is perfectly playable, but I find}) (6... d5 {more appealing, as it is more direct. Black accepts an isolated queen's pawn but gains active piece play in return.}) 7. exd5 {The most common move. White immediately resolves the tension in the center.} exd5 8. Bg2 {The bishop is developed with tempo. Qd3} Bc5 {The next bishop is developed with tempo. White now has to make a concession.} 9. Be3 Qb6 $1 {White can no longer maintain the blockade on d4.} 10. Nxc6 ({Black wins a piece after} 10. Na4 $4 Qb4+ {or 11.Nb3?? Nb4! for example 12.Qd2 d4 13.Bxd4 Bxd4 14.Nxd4 Qxd4 15.Qxd4 Nxc2+ 16.Kf1 Nxd4-+ .}) 10... Bxe3 {Compromises White's pawn structure. Qxe3+ Qxe3+} 11. fxe3 bxc6 {Black has solved all their opening problems. Chapter, extended analyses, and model games  * Chapter 7: [/course/199209/9] Fianchetto Variation (6.g3)  * Variation 7B: [/variation/31423141/#/13/b] Fianchetto Variation with 7.exd5 and 9.Qd3} *

