{Welcome to the Quickstarter Chapter! Here, you'll find a compilation of the most important variations and most common ideas. I recommend starting your engagement with the course here. Studying this chapter enables you to acquire a repertoire in the Open Sicilian with minimal time investment. This will allow you to gather initial practical experience, making your learning process more personal and effective. If your interest in a particular variation is sparked – whether through engagement with the theory or through practical play – you can deepen your knowledge by studying the relevant chapter. There, you will often find additional comments and deeper analysis.} 1. e4 c5 {The Sicilian Opening stands for a sharp fight. Black somewhat neglects their piece development in order to prevent White from establishing a full pawn center with d2-d4.} 2. Nf3 e6 ({The third most common move after} 2... d6 {and}) (2... Nc6 {. With this, Black primarily prepares the development of the dark-squared bishop, but the center push ...d7-d5 becomes a possibility as well.}) 3. d4 {The Open Sicilian and the starting position of this course. I examine alternatives for White on the second and third moves in a separate course on the Anti-Sicilians. The Open Sicilian is White's most principled attempt to fight for the opening advantage. White has more space and wants to open up the position, relying on rapid piece development. In return, Black gets the semi-open c-file, which can often be used for counterplay later on. Moreover, the exchange of the d-pawn for the c-pawn is a minor positional concession, as White now has only one pawn in the center and therefore can no longer fight quite as well for the important central squares.} cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 ({A very logical move - the knight is developed and simultaneously attacks the e4 pawn. Black takes advantage of the fact that the knight cannot be directly attacked with e4-e5 .} 4... Nc6 {is also possible, but gives White the additional option} 5. Nb5 {.}) 5. Nc3 ({Develops the knight and reinforces White's influence on the central square d5. Moreover, the diagonal a5-e1 is now interrupted, so that e4-e5 becomes a strong threat.} 5. e5 $2 {allows the double attack} Qa5+ {followed by -- Qxe5 .}) 5... Nc6 {Another natural developing move that continues the fight for the central squares. Black, at least temporarily, is preventing e4-e5 and threatening ...Bb4 with pressure on the white center. The starting position of the Sicilian Four Knights has now been reached. This method of play was first used in the second half of the 19th century. Early adopters included the masters Schiffers, Blackburne, Mieses, and Janowski. White now has a multitude of options.} 6. a3 {White prevents ...Bb4, reducing the possibilities for forcing play. Therefore, the move is particularly popular among players who want to avoid long theoretical battles. However, the downside is also clear: a2-a3 contributes little to White's development. It is therefore not surprising that Black gets good play with simple developing moves.} d6 {This is only the fourth most common move, but it avoids White's idea of Nxc6 followed by e4-e5 and thus seems simplest to me. The pawn structure in the center (e4 vs. d6+e6) can be reached in many Sicilian variations and is known as the Scheveningen structure. It is famous for complex and dynamic play, as both sides have many ideas and the structure in the center is not yet fixed. For example, Black could play ...e6-e5 or ...d6-d5 at the right moment – an important resource against aggressive flank attacks. From Black's point of view, this is a favorable version of the Scheveningen structure. This becomes clear when compared with the classical Scheveningen Variation: 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 d6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 e6 . In the current position, the additional moves a2-a3 and ...Nc6 are played. While the knight participates in the fight for the center, the pawn move on the edge is almost meaningless. The loss of tempo means that aggressive attacking moves like an early g2-g4 are not as effective here. While in the Scheveningen Variation, the direct 6.g4! is considered the most dangerous continuation, here 7.g4? fails due to the pawn loss after 7...Nxd4 8.Qxd4 Nxg4 . Therefore, White usually opts for the classical setup: Be3, Be2, O-O, and f2-f4.} 7. Be2 {White aims for a quick kingside castling.} Be7 8. O-O O-O 9. Be3 {White sets up their pieces according to the so-called Classical Variation in the Najdorf or Taimanov Sicilian. This style of play was favored by the 12th World Champion Anatoly Karpov. Usually, however, White has played the more useful f2-f4 instead of a2-a3 in those lines. A typical setup for White (after f2-f4) is Kh1, Qe1-g3, Rae1. White then tries to push e4-e5 or f4-f5. This would open up the position and give White good chances for a kingside attack. The typical antidote for Black in those positions is queenside play: ...a7-a6, ...Qc7, ...Nxd4, and ...b7-b5. If Black opts for this setup here, then a2-a3 does make a lot of sense after all: it prevents ...b5-b4. Therefore, I believe that play in the center is a better solution for Black.} Qc7 {The queen is well-placed on c7. It supports ideas like ...e6-e5 and ...Ne5-c4 and also clears the way for the rooks.} 10. f4 {White continues with the plan outlined above.} Nxd4 11. Bxd4 e5 {This gives Black a bit more space for their pieces.} 12. Be3 a6 {This is more precise than the immediate exchange on f4. Black prevents Nb5.} 13. Kh1 exf4 14. Bxf4 Be6 {The position is equal. A typical idea for Black is to relocate the knight to the outpost on e5. This also opens up the possibility of activating the bishop via f6. Of course, Black can also improve their rooks first. The a8 rook usually goes to c8, while the f8 rook has to choose between the equally viable squares e8 and d8. Chapter, extended analyses, and model games  * Chapter 5: [/course/199209/7] Prophylaxis Variation (6.a3)  * Variation 8D: [/variation/31423160/#/14/b] Prophylaxis Variation with 7.Be2} *

