Nb5 {.}) 5. Nc3 ({Develops the knight and reinforces White's influence on the central square d5. Moreover, the diagonal a5-e1 is now interrupted, so that e4-e5 becomes a strong threat.} 5. e5 $2 {allows the double attack} Qa5+ {followed by -- Qxe5 .}) 5... Nc6 {Another natural developing move that continues the fight for the central squares. Black, at least temporarily, is preventing e4-e5 and threatening ...Bb4 with pressure on the white center. The starting position of the Sicilian Four Knights has now been reached. This method of play was first used in the second half of the 19th century. Early adopters included the masters Schiffers, Blackburne, Mieses, and Janowski. White now has a multitude of options.} 6. Be3 {After 6.Ndb5 and 6.Nxc6, this is the third most common move in tournament practice. In the database of online games played on Lichess, it is even the most frequent move! White develops their pieces according to a plan familiar from other variations of the Sicilian. For example, the so-called English Attack against the Najdorf Variation is very popular: 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 d6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 a6 6.Be3 and now, for example, 6...e5 7.Nb3 Be6 8.f3 . The white setup includes further moves such as Qd2, O-O-O, and g2-g4 with an attack on the kingside. In the Four Knights Sicilian, 6.Be3 is usually a sign that White is not familiar with the theory. It is practically not seen at the Grandmaster level. The reason for this is that 6.Be3 does nothing against Black's play in the center.} Bb4 {Attacking the pawn on e4.} 7. Bd3 d5 {Continues the attack on the white center. Here, Black doesn't even have to accept an isolated pawn. White has nothing better than resolving the tension in the center, after which Black has comfortable play.} 8. Nxc6 bxc6 9. e5 {exf6 dxe3!} ({The correct decision. Black should not be tempted by the possibility of winning a pawn after dxc3? : A) Here, fxg7?? would be a mistake due to cxb2} 9. Ke2 {bxa1=Q . The rook on h8 is protected! B) However, after b3 Qxf6 Qg4 , White has more than enough compensation for the pawn. The white bishops are more active than their counterparts and are ready to attack Black's king. Moreover, the black pawns on the queenside are weak.}) {fxg7 exf2+ Kf1! The pawn on f2 actually serves as a shield for the white king.} 9... Rg8 10. Qg4 {The only good move in this chaotic position. From here the queen defends the pawn on g7 and attacks the bishop on b4.} Bxc3+ 11. bxc3 {Qf6 The most direct approach. Black captures the pawn on g7 before it becomes dangerous. The position is dynamically equal. Chapter, extended analyses, and model games  * Chapter 9: [/course/199209/11] Prophylaxis Variation (6.a3)  * Variation 9C: [/variation/31423179/#/14/b] 6.Be3 with 7.Bd3} *

