{Welcome to the Quickstarter Chapter! Here, you'll find a compilation of the most important variations and most common ideas. I recommend starting your engagement with the course here. Studying this chapter enables you to acquire a repertoire in the Open Sicilian with minimal time investment. This will allow you to gather initial practical experience, making your learning process more personal and effective. If your interest in a particular variation is sparked – whether through engagement with the theory or through practical play – you can deepen your knowledge by studying the relevant chapter. There, you will often find additional comments and deeper analysis.} 1. e4 c5 {The Sicilian Opening stands for a sharp fight. Black somewhat neglects their piece development in order to prevent White from establishing a full pawn center with d2-d4.} 2. Nf3 e6 ({The third most common move after} 2... d6 {and}) (2... Nc6 {. With this, Black primarily prepares the development of the dark-squared bishop, but the center push ...d7-d5 becomes a possibility as well.}) 3. d4 {The Open Sicilian and the starting position of this course. I examine alternatives for White on the second and third moves in a separate course on the Anti-Sicilians. The Open Sicilian is White's most principled attempt to fight for the opening advantage. White has more space and wants to open up the position, relying on rapid piece development. In return, Black gets the semi-open c-file, which can often be used for counterplay later on. Moreover, the exchange of the d-pawn for the c-pawn is a minor positional concession, as White now has only one pawn in the center and therefore can no longer fight quite as well for the important central squares.} cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 ({A very logical move - the knight is developed and simultaneously attacks the e4 pawn. Black takes advantage of the fact that the knight cannot be directly attacked with e4-e5 .} 4... Nc6 {is also possible, but gives White the additional option} 5. Nb5 {.}) 5. Bd3 {White places the bishop on a good square and protects the e-pawn. This natural developing move is the second most popular move after 5.Nc3. Compared to 5.Nc3, the nature of the position is now somewhat slower, as White is not threatening e4-e5.} Nc6 {Here as well, this is the correct move. The knight on d4 is facing a decision.} 6. Nxc6 bxc6 {Next, Black wants to fight for the center with d7-d5. O-O d5 We reach the typical pawn structure in this variation. White must now respond to the attack on the e4-pawn. Nd2 The main move. The knight is less likely to be attacked on d2 than on c3, and it does not block the c-pawn. White can later develop the dark-squared bishop to b2.} 7. Nc3 Be7 {is a transposition [/variation/31423049/#/8/b] to 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 e6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 Nc6 6.Nxc6 bxc6 7.Bd3 d5 8.O-O Be7 . Bd6 I prefer this here over the more passive Be7 . For one thing, White cannot play e4-e5. For another, Black can later play ...e6-e5 themselves. This can be advantageous, for example, if White develops the bishop to b2. After Be7 , I am bothered by} 8. e5 {Nd7 Qh5!? or 10.Qg4 . Qe2 Prevents e4-e5 and attacks the h2-pawn. h3 O-O As is often the case with this pawn structure, Black has a natural development and no problems. If White threatens e4-e5 (after Re1 or b2-b3 and Bb2), Black can advance the e-pawn to e5 themselves. Chapter, extended analyses, and model games  * Chapter 11: [/course/199209/13] Side Lines on move 4 and 5  * Variation 11G: [/variation/31423241/#/10/b] Sideline 5.Bd3 with 11.b3  * Variation 11G: [/variation/31423242/#/10/b] Sideline 5.Bd3 with 11.Re1  * Variation 11G: [/variation/31423243/#/10/b] Sideline 5.Bd3 with 11.c4} *

