ts to refute the opening.}) ({➤} 6... d5 $2 {is positionally desirable, but tactically a mistake:} 7. exd5 exd5 8. Bf4 {and the Nc7+ fork can hardly be prevented.}) ({➤ After} 6... d6 {White has nothing better than the aforementioned transition into the Sveshnikov Sicilian:} 7. Bf4 e5 8. Bg5 {. This position usually arises through the move order 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 e5 6.Ndb5 d6 7.Bg5 . In this move order, however, White also has the additional options of 7.Nd5 and 3.Bb5, which is why some Black players try to reach the Sveshnikov Sicilian via 2...e6.}) ({➤} 6... Bb4 {is a solid variation, with which Black has good chances of equalizing the game. However, we do not see the typical attacking play of the Sicilian Defense here. Therefore, I prefer the more adventurous 6...Bc5.} 7. a3 {As the e4 pawn is under attack, White forces the exchange of the bishop.} Bxc3+ 8. Nxc3 d5 {Liberates the queenside and fights for the center.} 9. exd5 exd5 {Black accepts positional disadvantages (the isolated pawn d5 and the opposing bishop pair) in exchange for rapid development and control of the central squares. Nevertheless, a long fight for equality lies ahead.}) 7. Bf4 {The most common continuation. White is threatening a knight fork on c7 and simultaneously targets the weakened d6 square. The move e4-e5 is also a threat.} O-O ({The only good move. Black secures their king, dodges the knight checks, and provides the knight on f6 a retreat square on e8. If Black now manages to liberate the queenside with ...d7-d5, they would already be better. Therefore, White should now aim to blockade the pawn on d7.} 7... e5 $2 8. Be3 $1 Bxe3 9. Nd6+ Ke7 10. fxe3 {. A very similar position arises after 7.Be3 Bxe3 8.Nd6+ Ke7 9.fxe3 . The only difference is that the black e-pawn is already on e5 here. This small difference turns out to be fatal for Black, because the squares f5 and d5 are accessible to the white pieces, and Bc4 with an attack on f7 is also an option.}) 8. Bc7 $1 Qe7 (8... Qe8 $2 {Takes away the last retreat square from the knight:} 9. e5 {.}) 9. Bd6 {, Black now has to exchange the bishops themselves.} Bxd6 10. Qxd6 Qd8 $1 {The direct queen trade leads to a slightly worse position for Black because the d-pawn is backward and weak and the bishop on c8 is undeveloped. Therefore, Black accepts a loss of time and relies on counterplay on the queenside. White now has two critical continuations: The main line 11.0-0-0 and 11.Nc7. Besides, we will examine other continuations that are occasionally played. 10...Ne8 is the old main line, which is only rarely seen nowadays. 11.Qxe7 Nxe7 12.O-O-O f5 13.e5 $14 . Black is very solid, but has not yet solved the problem of developing the queenside. White is slightly better.} 11. Qc7 {This harmless move has been played by some strong grandmasters. Perhaps White interprets Black's last move as an invitation to further pursue a queen trade.} d5 ({This advance is usually strong, threatening ...d5-d4.} 11... Qxc7 12. Nxc7 Rb8 {is a good alternative. We analyze [/variation/31422995/#/12/b] this position via the move order 8.Bd6 Qb6 9.Bxc5 Qxc5 10.Qd6 Qb6 11.Qc7 Qxc7 .}) 12. exd5 exd5 ({Black now has a pleasant choice.} 12... Nxd5 {leads to a relatively simple, balanced position.}) (12... exd5 {is also balanced with best play but leads to a more complicated position where White needs to navigate some pitfalls.}) {An ambitious move, with which Black, according to my database, has a success rate of over 80% in 14 games. Black accepts a pawn weakness on d5 in exchange for dynamic play. In particular, the pawn advance ...d5-d4 presents a threat.} 13. Qxd8 Rxd8 14. Ne2 $1 {This may seem strange because it neglects development. But it's more important to give the b5 knight a good retreat route. 14.Ne2 is the only move that keeps the balance for White.} d4 $5 ({Now White cannot block the d-pawn with Nb5-d4 . Other moves are also good but lead to less direct play, for instance} 14... a6 15. Nbd4 Re8 16. Rd1 Nxd4 17. Rxd4 Bf5 {with equality.}) 15. Rd1 $1 {Nbxd4 Nxd4 Nxd4 Bxa2 Black wins the pawn back and equalises. White is too underdeveloped to be able to trap the bishop on a2 . b3} a5 {To play ...a5-a4 and free the bishop. Bb5} ({Or Bc4 a4 O-O} 15... Ne4 {followed by ...Nc5. White can't attack the bishop.}) {Ne4} 16. Rd3 a4 {bxa4 Nc5= The position is equal.} *

