c7 $1 Qe7 (8... Qe8 $2 {Takes away the last retreat square from the knight:} 9. e5 {.}) 9. Bd6 {, Black now has to exchange the bishops themselves.} Bxd6 10. Qxd6 Qd8 $1 {The direct queen trade leads to a slightly worse position for Black because the d-pawn is backward and weak and the bishop on c8 is undeveloped. Therefore, Black accepts a loss of time and relies on counterplay on the queenside. White now has two critical continuations: The main line 11.0-0-0 and 11.Nc7. Besides, we will examine other continuations that are occasionally played. 10...Ne8 is the old main line, which is only rarely seen nowadays. 11.Qxe7 Nxe7 12.O-O-O f5 13.e5 $14 . Black is very solid, but has not yet solved the problem of developing the queenside. White is slightly better.} 11. Qc7 {This harmless move has been played by some strong grandmasters. Perhaps White interprets Black's last move as an invitation to further pursue a queen trade.} d5 ({This advance is usually strong, threatening ...d5-d4.} 11... Qxc7 12. Nxc7 Rb8 {is a good alternative. We analyze [/variation/31422995/#/12/b] this position via the move order 8.Bd6 Qb6 9.Bxc5 Qxc5 10.Qd6 Qb6 11.Qc7 Qxc7 .}) 12. exd5 Nxd5 ({Black now has a pleasant choice.} 12... Nxd5 {leads to a relatively simple, balanced position.}) (12... exd5 {is also balanced with best play but leads to a more complicated position where White needs to navigate some pitfalls.}) {This avoids weakening the pawn structure and achieves comfortable equality for Black. Surprisingly, this move has not been tried in practice.} 13. Nxd5 Qxd5 14. Nc3 {Black has a slight initiative because White has not yet completed development. Objectively, however, the position is completely balanced. Neither side has any pawn weaknesses.} *

