ts to refute the opening.}) ({➤} 6... d5 $2 {is positionally desirable, but tactically a mistake:} 7. exd5 exd5 8. Bf4 {and the Nc7+ fork can hardly be prevented.}) ({➤ After} 6... d6 {White has nothing better than the aforementioned transition into the Sveshnikov Sicilian:} 7. Bf4 e5 8. Bg5 {. This position usually arises through the move order 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 e5 6.Ndb5 d6 7.Bg5 . In this move order, however, White also has the additional options of 7.Nd5 and 3.Bb5, which is why some Black players try to reach the Sveshnikov Sicilian via 2...e6.}) ({➤} 6... Bb4 {is a solid variation, with which Black has good chances of equalizing the game. However, we do not see the typical attacking play of the Sicilian Defense here. Therefore, I prefer the more adventurous 6...Bc5.} 7. a3 {As the e4 pawn is under attack, White forces the exchange of the bishop.} Bxc3+ 8. Nxc3 d5 {Liberates the queenside and fights for the center.} 9. exd5 exd5 {Black accepts positional disadvantages (the isolated pawn d5 and the opposing bishop pair) in exchange for rapid development and control of the central squares. Nevertheless, a long fight for equality lies ahead.}) 7. Bf4 {The most common continuation. White is threatening a knight fork on c7 and simultaneously targets the weakened d6 square. The move e4-e5 is also a threat.} O-O ({The only good move. Black secures their king, dodges the knight checks, and provides the knight on f6 a retreat square on e8. If Black now manages to liberate the queenside with ...d7-d5, they would already be better. Therefore, White should now aim to blockade the pawn on d7.} 7... e5 $2 8. Be3 $1 Bxe3 9. Nd6+ Ke7 10. fxe3 {. A very similar position arises after 7.Be3 Bxe3 8.Nd6+ Ke7 9.fxe3 . The only difference is that the black e-pawn is already on e5 here. This small difference turns out to be fatal for Black, because the squares f5 and d5 are accessible to the white pieces, and Bc4 with an attack on f7 is also an option.}) 8. Bc7 $1 Qe7 (8... Qe8 $2 {Takes away the last retreat square from the knight:} 9. e5 {.}) 9. Bd6 {, Black now has to exchange the bishops themselves.} Bxd6 10. Qxd6 Qd8 $1 {The direct queen trade leads to a slightly worse position for Black because the d-pawn is backward and weak and the bishop on c8 is undeveloped. Therefore, Black accepts a loss of time and relies on counterplay on the queenside. White now has two critical continuations: The main line 11.0-0-0 and 11.Nc7. Besides, we will examine other continuations that are occasionally played. 10...Ne8 is the old main line, which is only rarely seen nowadays. 11.Qxe7 Nxe7 12.O-O-O f5 13.e5 $14 . Black is very solid, but has not yet solved the problem of developing the queenside. White is slightly better.} 11. Be2 Nd4 12. O-O-O {The knight exchange would be disadvantageous, so Black avoids it. In the present position, Ne7 has not been played yet in tournament practice. The following moves are therefore an example of how the game could develop. Worse is} Ne8 $6 {Nxc6 bxc6} 13. Qc5 {. Such positions should be avoided because both the d- and the a-pawn are weak in the long run. O-O White follows the path taken with 11.Be2. Ne8 A typical move to free the queenside. b5 would be hasty here: a4! bxa4 Rxa4 . The a-pawn is weak. White is slightly better. Qb4 d6 Rad1 e5} Qc7 {is also good, but Black should play ...e6-e5 at some point anyway to liberate the bishop. Nb3 Rb8 The position is reminiscent of a Najdorf Sicilian, with the unusual circumstance that the dark-squared bishops are already exchanged. Black must therefore temporarily accept a passive knight position to protect the d6 pawn. The last move addresses this problem: Black wants to play ...b7-b5 and would then threaten ...Nc6 with the gain of material. If necessary, the d-pawn can be covered by the rook afterwards. The absence of the dark-squared bishops also means that White cannot build up pressure on the queenside. The position is balanced. Rd2 Bxa6 This tactical possibility must be checked. Nc6 and now: A) 18.Qa4? Ra8-+ B) 18.Qb5? Nc7-+ C) 18.Qc4 Be6 19.Nd5 The only move. The queen must continue to attack the knight. 19...Bxd5 20.exd5 ( 20.Rxd5? Ne7-+ ) 20...Na7 21.Bb5 Rc8 22.Qe2 Nxb5 23.Qxb5 Rxc2 . Black has regained the pawn and is slightly better. b5 Rfd1? This is a mistake: White does not have time to put further pressure on the d-pawn. Nc6 Qa3 b4-+ Black wins material.} *

