c7 $1 Qe7 (8... Qe8 $2 {Takes away the last retreat square from the knight:} 9. e5 {.}) 9. Bd6 {, Black now has to exchange the bishops themselves.} Bxd6 10. Qxd6 Qd8 $1 {The direct queen trade leads to a slightly worse position for Black because the d-pawn is backward and weak and the bishop on c8 is undeveloped. Therefore, Black accepts a loss of time and relies on counterplay on the queenside. White now has two critical continuations: The main line 11.0-0-0 and 11.Nc7. Besides, we will examine other continuations that are occasionally played. 10...Ne8 is the old main line, which is only rarely seen nowadays. 11.Qxe7 Nxe7 12.O-O-O f5 13.e5 $14 . Black is very solid, but has not yet solved the problem of developing the queenside. White is slightly better.} 11. Nc7 ({An interesting move which requires a precise response. The idea is to maintain the blockade on the dark squares by ensuring the queen can no longer be driven away from d6. After ...Nf6-e8, a knight exchange will now always follow. It's important for White to play Nc7 directly and not as a response to ...a7-a6. For example, after} 11. O-O-O a6 {,} 12. Nc7 {would be a gross mistake, as after} Ra7 {the knight would be trapped and can be attacked through a move of the b-pawn.}) 11... Rb8 (11... Ne8 {is weaker.} 12. Nxe8 Rxe8 13. Bb5 $1 {. This novelty appears most convincing. Black should now move the knight away but is still far from completing development. White is clearly better. After} a6 $6 14. Bxc6 dxc6 15. O-O-O Qxd6 16. Rxd6 e5 {, the bishop can indeed be activated, but after} 17. Na4 $1 {followed by Nc5 and Rhd1, White's pieces dominate the board.}) 12. O-O-O {Played among others by Harikrishna against Duda in a rapid game. In combination with 11.Nc7, this move is not very logical.} a6 {The knight on c7 is now trapped. However, Black still needs three moves to attack it.} 13. Be2 e5 14. Bg4 $132 {Qg5+ Kb1 Qxg4 Rhe1 White prophylactically defends the e5 pawn. Qf4 A very double-edged position has arisen, which is assessed as equal by the engines. In the black camp, the weakened black color complex is noticeable, as well as the bishop on c8, which is blocked by its own pawns. On the pro side, there are the vulnerable white kingside pawns and the unresolved fate of the knight on c7. Black could attack it with ...Bb7 and ...Rc8 and even the maneuver ...Qg5-d8 .} *

