c7 $1 Qe7 (8... Qe8 $2 {Takes away the last retreat square from the knight:} 9. e5 {.}) 9. Bd6 {, Black now has to exchange the bishops themselves.} Bxd6 10. Qxd6 Qd8 $1 {The direct queen trade leads to a slightly worse position for Black because the d-pawn is backward and weak and the bishop on c8 is undeveloped. Therefore, Black accepts a loss of time and relies on counterplay on the queenside. White now has two critical continuations: The main line 11.0-0-0 and 11.Nc7. Besides, we will examine other continuations that are occasionally played. 10...Ne8 is the old main line, which is only rarely seen nowadays. 11.Qxe7 Nxe7 12.O-O-O f5 13.e5 $14 . Black is very solid, but has not yet solved the problem of developing the queenside. White is slightly better.} 11. Nc7 ({An interesting move which requires a precise response. The idea is to maintain the blockade on the dark squares by ensuring the queen can no longer be driven away from d6. After ...Nf6-e8, a knight exchange will now always follow. It's important for White to play Nc7 directly and not as a response to ...a7-a6. For example, after} 11. O-O-O a6 {,} 12. Nc7 {would be a gross mistake, as after} Ra7 {the knight would be trapped and can be attacked through a move of the b-pawn.}) 11... Rb8 (11... Ne8 {is weaker.} 12. Nxe8 Rxe8 13. Bb5 $1 {. This novelty appears most convincing. Black should now move the knight away but is still far from completing development. White is clearly better. After} a6 $6 14. Bxc6 dxc6 15. O-O-O Qxd6 16. Rxd6 e5 {, the bishop can indeed be activated, but after} 17. Na4 $1 {followed by Nc5 and Rhd1, White's pieces dominate the board.}) 12. Be2 ({Black must act energetically so as not to end up in a passive position. The pawn is attacked three times, but if White takes it, the b-file opens for the black rook. The advance of the b-pawn has several functions:  * The white knight on c3 can be attacked with ...b5-b4.  * The development of the bishop is prepared.  * The maneuver ...Rb6 is now also possible, which can drive the White queen away from its strong position. b6?! is too passive and gives White an edge:} 12. e5 Ne8 13. Nxe8 Rxe8 14. f4 {. As we will see, Black has sufficient counterplay when the b-pawn is already on b5. Bb7 This position was reached in two grandmaster games. After the simple O-O-O Black ends up in a joyless position with a pawn weakness on d7 and no counterplay.}) {Bxb5? Rb7! Now the knight is trapped and Black wins material.} 12... e5 {Nh5} ({Na6 Rxb5 Nxb5 Bxa6 wins for Black. Here this is better than} 12... Ng4 {, because the knight can sometimes go to f4.}) (12... Ng4 {Bxc6 dxc6} 13. h3 {. Black now has to play the passive} Nh6 {.}) ({Bxc6 There is nothing better. dxc6 Qxd8 Na6 Qa5 Nc5 Rxb2 leads to the collapse of the white position, e.g. N5e4 Rd8} 12... Qe7 13. Ba6 {and the white king cannot find safety.}) {Rxd8} 13. Na6 {Rxb2 Nc5 White saves the knight but not the game. Rxc2 N3e4 f5 exf6 gxf6 The threat is ...f6-f5. White will lose more material. Black is winning.} *

