c7 $1 Qe7 (8... Qe8 $2 {Takes away the last retreat square from the knight:} 9. e5 {.}) 9. Bd6 {, Black now has to exchange the bishops themselves.} Bxd6 10. Qxd6 Qd8 $1 {The direct queen trade leads to a slightly worse position for Black because the d-pawn is backward and weak and the bishop on c8 is undeveloped. Therefore, Black accepts a loss of time and relies on counterplay on the queenside. White now has two critical continuations: The main line 11.0-0-0 and 11.Nc7. Besides, we will examine other continuations that are occasionally played. 10...Ne8 is the old main line, which is only rarely seen nowadays. 11.Qxe7 Nxe7 12.O-O-O f5 13.e5 $14 . Black is very solid, but has not yet solved the problem of developing the queenside. White is slightly better.} 11. Nc7 ({An interesting move which requires a precise response. The idea is to maintain the blockade on the dark squares by ensuring the queen can no longer be driven away from d6. After ...Nf6-e8, a knight exchange will now always follow. It's important for White to play Nc7 directly and not as a response to ...a7-a6. For example, after} 11. O-O-O a6 {,} 12. Nc7 {would be a gross mistake, as after} Ra7 {the knight would be trapped and can be attacked through a move of the b-pawn.}) 11... Rb8 (11... Ne8 {is weaker.} 12. Nxe8 Rxe8 13. Bb5 $1 {. This novelty appears most convincing. Black should now move the knight away but is still far from completing development. White is clearly better. After} a6 $6 14. Bxc6 dxc6 15. O-O-O Qxd6 16. Rxd6 e5 {, the bishop can indeed be activated, but after} 17. Na4 $1 {followed by Nc5 and Rhd1, White's pieces dominate the board.}) 12. Be2 ({Black must act energetically so as not to end up in a passive position. The pawn is attacked three times, but if White takes it, the b-file opens for the black rook. The advance of the b-pawn has several functions:  * The white knight on c3 can be attacked with ...b5-b4.  * The development of the bishop is prepared.  * The maneuver ...Rb6 is now also possible, which can drive the White queen away from its strong position. b6?! is too passive and gives White an edge:} 12. e5 Ne8 13. Nxe8 Rxe8 14. f4 {. As we will see, Black has sufficient counterplay when the b-pawn is already on b5. Bb7 This position was reached in two grandmaster games. After the simple O-O-O Black ends up in a joyless position with a pawn weakness on d7 and no counterplay.}) 12... e5 13. Ne8 Rxe8 14. O-O {Now White is ready to take the pawn on b5. b4} Nxe4 {Bb7 Nc5 An obvious move. The weak pawn on d7 is attacked. Ne7! It turns out that it's not beneficial for White to take on d7. This means that 17.Nc5 was actually pointless. Next, Black wants to play ...Bc6. Nxb7 Rxb7} {The bishop is now developed but cannot yet make its influence felt because it is blocked by Black's own knight. This determines the plan for the coming moves. The knight should be regrouped via e7. Often a preparatory move like ...Ba8 or ...a7-a5 is necessary to defend the pawns on the queenside. After the alternative Rb6 Stockfish shows a dangerous idea for White: a4! White gains space and occasionally threatens a4-a5 (after the queen's departure from d6). After bxa3 Rxa3 White's rook is activated via the third rank. Black now needs to find Rb4! to stay in the game. If instead 18...Rxb2? , White has 19.Rg3! , threatening Nf6+ and winning. Black's defenders are missing on the kingside. White can also bring their queen into the attack, e.g., Qd2-h6. A) Nxd7? Rc8 not only threatens to capture on c2, but also trapping the queen with ...Nd5 followed by ...Rc6. Nc5 Qxd6 exd6 Rxc5 dxe7 Rxc2 . Black remains a healthy pawn up. B) Bd3 Bc6 is equal. Next, the annoying white queen could be driven away from d6 with ...Rb6. The knight can go to d5 and ideally to f4 later. C) Qxd7?! Qxd7 Nxd7 Rbc8 . The knight on d7 is trapped. Therefore, White has no time to worry about the attacked pawn on c2. C.1) 20.Bd3 Bd5-+ followed by ...Red8. C.2) 20.a3 Rxc2 21.Bb5 bxa3 22.Rxa3 Ra8 . Black is slightly better. White has not yet managed to free the knight.} 15. Z0 ({Black doesn't have any problems. The rapid game Mammadzada–Yoo is a good example of how the game can continue:} 15. Rfd1 {Nf5 Qd2} Qc7 16. Bf3 {. After this, Black takes the initiative. A better attempt is the modest 21.Re1. Rbb8 Re1 Rb5 . 22...Red8 followed by ...d7-d5. is also strong. Black has pressure on the queenside. Rac1?! Rxe5 . A) Necessary was Rxe5 Qxe5 Qxd7 which maintains the balance. B) 24.Qxb4? Rb8 25.Qa3 Ra5 26.Qd3 Rxb2-+ With an extra pawn, to which in Mammadzada–Yoo [/variation/31423319/#/26/b], chess24.com 2021 (½-½) another was added soon after.}) *

