{Directed against Rd6 , which would now be met by Qxe5 . The position is equal. Some possible continuations: A) 21.f4? Bb7 22.Rd6 Qe7 $17 , White's position gets under pressure. B) 21.exf6 is answered by 21...Rxf6= . Black is now about to complete development with ...Bb7. C) 21.Be2 leads to an endgame with equal chances after 21...Bb7 22.Rd6 Qxe5 23.Qxe5 fxe5 24.Rxd7 Bc6 .} 1. e4 c5 {The Sicilian Opening stands for a sharp fight. Black somewhat neglects their piece development in order to prevent White from establishing a full pawn center with d2-d4.} 2. Nf3 e6 ({The third most common move after} 2... d6 {and}) (2... Nc6 {. With this, Black primarily prepares the development of the dark-squared bishop, but the center push ...d7-d5 becomes a possibility as well.}) (2... Nc6 {is an alternative way to reach the Four Knights Sicilian:} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6 {and we have landed in our repertoire via transposition. I decided against this path because White has a very serious and popular alternative in 3.Bb5 , the Rossolimo Variation. With 2...e6 the Rossolimo Variation is avoided.}) 3. d4 {The Open Sicilian and the starting position of this course. I examine alternatives for White on the second and third moves in a separate course on the Anti-Sicilians. The Open Sicilian is White's most principled attempt to fight for the opening advantage. White has more space and wants to open up the position, relying on rapid piece development. In return, Black gets the semi-open c-file, which can often be used for counterplay later on. Moreover, the exchange of the d-pawn for the c-pawn is a minor positional concession, as White now has only one pawn in the center and therefore can no longer fight quite as well for the important central squares.} cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 ({A very logical move - the knight is developed and simultaneously attacks the e4 pawn. Black takes advantage of the fact that the knight cannot be directly attacked with e4-e5 .} 4... Nc6 {is also possible, but gives White the additional option} 5. Nb5 {.}) 5. Nc3 ({Develops the knight and reinforces White's influence on the central square d5. Moreover, the diagonal a5-e1 is now interrupted, so that e4-e5 becomes a strong threat.} 5. e5 $2 {allows the double attack} Qa5+ {followed by -- Qxe5 .}) 5... Nc6 {Another natural developing move that continues the fight for the central squares. Black, at least temporarily, is preventing e4-e5 and threatening ...Bb4 with pressure on the white center. The starting position of the Sicilian Four Knights has now been reached. This method of play was first used in the second half of the 19th century. Early adopters included the masters Schiffers, Blackburne, Mieses, and Janowski. White now has a multitude of options.} 6. Ndb5 ({White moves the knight for the third time, but there are good reasons for this time loss. Due to the pawn moves, Black has weakened the squares d6 and c7 . Specifically, an unpleasant knight check on d6 is threatened. For a long time, 6.Ndb5 was considered the main variation. However, at the highest level there has recently been a trend towards} 6. Nxc6 {. The reason for this is that after}) (6. Ndb5 {, Black can transition into the Sveshnikov Sicilian, where White currently struggles to prove an opening advantage. However, 6.Ndb5 still remains the most common move, especially below grandmaster level.}) 6... Bc5 $5 ({A rare move that will come as a surprise to many of our opponents. More popular are} 6... d6 {(which usually leads to the Sveshnikov variation) or}) (6... Bb4 {.}) ({➤ With} 6... Bc5 {, Black prepares to castle and targets the tactically vulnerable point f2. Additionally, Black can now respond to the knight check on d6 with a king move without blocking the development of the bishop on f8. 6...Bc5 is known as the 'Cobra Variation', tracing back to an article by Swedish IM Jesper Hall. According to my database, the Cobra was first played in 1963 by Soviet IM Viacheslav Osnos, but it remained a niche for a long time. Nowadays, some strong grandmasters have discovered the move for themselves, especially in faster time controls. I can confirm from my own experience: In blitz, the Cobra is a particularly dangerous weapon, as many opponents do not know the variation well enough, react poorly and/or consume a lot of time. The 'holes ' on d6 and c7 also invite (unsuccessful) attempts to refute the opening.}) ({➤} 6... d5 $2 {is positionally desirable, but tactically a mistake:} 7. exd5 exd5 8. Bf4 {and the Nc7+ fork can hardly be prevented.}) ({➤ After} 6... d6 {White has nothing better than the aforementioned transition into the Sveshnikov Sicilian:} 7. Bf4 e5 8. Bg5 {. This position usually arises through the move order 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 e5 6.Ndb5 d6 7.Bg5 . In this move order, however, White also has the additional options of 7.Nd5 and 3.Bb5, which is why some Black players try to reach the Sveshnikov Sicilian via 2...e6.}) ({➤} 6... Bb4 {is a solid variation, with which Black has good chances of equalizing the game. However, we do not see the typical attacking play of the Sicilian Defense here. Therefore, I prefer the more adventurous 6...Bc5.} 7. a3 {As the e4 pawn is under attack, White forces the exchange of the bishop.} Bxc3+ 8. Nxc3 d5 {Liberates the queenside and fights for the center.} 9. exd5 exd5 {Black accepts positional disadvantages (the isolated pawn d5 and the opposing bishop pair) in exchange for rapid development and control of the central squares. Nevertheless, a long fight for equality lies ahead.}) 7. Bf4 {The most common continuation. White is threatening a knight fork on c7 and simultaneously targets the weakened d6 square. The move e4-e5 is also a threat.} O-O ({The only good move. Black secures their king, dodges the knight checks, and provides the knight on f6 a retreat square on e8. If Black now manages to liberate the queenside with ...d7-d5, they would already be better. Therefore, White should now aim to blockade the pawn on d7.} 7... e5 $2 8. Be3 $1 Bxe3 9. Nd6+ Ke7 10. fxe3 {. A very similar position arises after 7.Be3 Bxe3 8.Nd6+ Ke7 9.fxe3 . The only difference is that the black e-pawn is already on e5 here. This small difference turns out to be fatal for Black, because the squares f5 and d5 are accessible to the white pieces, and Bc4 with an attack on f7 is also an option.}) 8. Bc7 $1 Qe7 (8... Qe8 $2 {Takes away the last retreat square from the knight:} 9. e5 {.}) 9. Bd6 {, Black now has to exchange the bishops themselves.} Bxd6 10. Qxd6 Qd8 $1 {The direct queen trade leads to a slightly worse position for Black because the d-pawn is backward and weak and the bishop on c8 is undeveloped. Therefore, Black accepts a loss of time and relies on counterplay on the queenside. White now has two critical continuations: The main line 11.0-0-0 and 11.Nc7. Besides, we will examine other continuations that are occasionally played. 10...Ne8 is the old main line, which is only rarely seen nowadays. 11.Qxe7 Nxe7 12.O-O-O f5 13.e5 $14 . Black is very solid, but has not yet solved the problem of developing the queenside. White is slightly better.} 11. O-O-O {The most common move by far. White brings the king to safety and increases pressure along the d-file. We reach an opposite side castling situation so typical of the Sicilian Defense. Both sides will now try to attack the opponent's king.} a6 {Drives away the knight and prepares ...b7-b5.} 12. Nd4 Ne7 $1 13. Qg3 {Black cannot prevent e4-e5 and therefore focuses on their own play on the queenside. There's a threat of ...b5-b4.} e5 ({With Bd3 , White protects the e4-pawn and thus defends against the threat ...b5-b4, but this is too slow to pose any problems.} 13... d6 {and now: A) The game Das–Krause [/variation/36055951], Walsrode 2023 (0-1) continued} 14. h4 $2 {b4 Nce2} e5 15. Nb3 Qc7 {. White cannot counter the impending attack on the queenside ...a6-a5-a4 and lost after a few more moves. B) Necessary was 15.f4 , for instance 15...Nh5 (or 15...b4) 16.Qe3 Nxf4 17.Qxf4 e5 18.Qf2 exd4 19.Qxd4 Be6 with equality.}) ({Nfd5 Weaker is} 13... Ne8 $6 14. Bd3 {Bb7 Ne4 , which gave White a mighty kingside attack in the game Smirnov-Kezin [/variation/36055952], Khanty Mansiysk 2022 (1-0).}) {Ne4 White brings the pieces towards the kingside. Next the bishop could participate in the attack via d3. Qb6 The queen move serves two purposes: firstly, it prevents Bd3 by attacking the knight on d4, and secondly, it prepares to move the f-pawn. The direct f6? doesn't work for tactical reasons: exf6 Nxf6 Nxe6!+- and White wins material. Nf6+ After other moves as well, White cannot hope for an advantage, for example: A) Be2 f6!= this typical pawn break allows Black to include the f8-rook in the defense of the kingside. B) 16.Nd6 Bb7 17.Bd3 f5! (since the white knight has left e4 17...Qxd4?? fails to 18.Bxh7+ Kxh7 19.Rxd4+- .) The pawn on f5 hinders White's minor pieces, so there is nothing better than the exchange 18.exf6 Rxf6= , after which Black's rook gets active and helps to defend the kingside. Black has no problems. This variation was given by Miloš Perunović in Sicilian Defense: Four Knights Variation. Kh8} 14. Nd5 {Nxd5} Nf5 {With this small tactic, White secures the better pawn structure.} 15. exf5 {Rxd5 Qe6! This gives Black good counterplay. If the attacked rook moves away, ...Qxa2 can follow. c4 f6=} Z0 *

