s. Black, at least temporarily, is preventing e4-e5 and threatening ...Bb4 with pressure on the white center. The starting position of the Sicilian Four Knights has now been reached. This method of play was first used in the second half of the 19th century. Early adopters included the masters Schiffers, Blackburne, Mieses, and Janowski. White now has a multitude of options.} 6. Ndb5 ({White moves the knight for the third time, but there are good reasons for this time loss. Due to the pawn moves, Black has weakened the squares d6 and c7 . Specifically, an unpleasant knight check on d6 is threatened. For a long time, 6.Ndb5 was considered the main variation. However, at the highest level there has recently been a trend towards} 6. Nxc6 {. The reason for this is that after}) (6. Ndb5 {, Black can transition into the Sveshnikov Sicilian, where White currently struggles to prove an opening advantage. However, 6.Ndb5 still remains the most common move, especially below grandmaster level.}) 6... Bc5 $5 ({A rare move that will come as a surprise to many of our opponents. More popular are} 6... d6 {(which usually leads to the Sveshnikov variation) or}) (6... Bb4 {.}) ({➤ With} 6... Bc5 {, Black prepares to castle and targets the tactically vulnerable point f2. Additionally, Black can now respond to the knight check on d6 with a king move without blocking the development of the bishop on f8. 6...Bc5 is known as the 'Cobra Variation', tracing back to an article by Swedish IM Jesper Hall. According to my database, the Cobra was first played in 1963 by Soviet IM Viacheslav Osnos, but it remained a niche for a long time. Nowadays, some strong grandmasters have discovered the move for themselves, especially in faster time controls. I can confirm from my own experience: In blitz, the Cobra is a particularly dangerous weapon, as many opponents do not know the variation well enough, react poorly and/or consume a lot of time. The 'holes ' on d6 and c7 also invite (unsuccessful) attempts to refute the opening.}) ({➤} 6... d5 $2 {is positionally desirable, but tactically a mistake:} 7. exd5 exd5 8. Bf4 {and the Nc7+ fork can hardly be prevented.}) ({➤ After} 6... d6 {White has nothing better than the aforementioned transition into the Sveshnikov Sicilian:} 7. Bf4 e5 8. Bg5 {. This position usually arises through the move order 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 e5 6.Ndb5 d6 7.Bg5 . In this move order, however, White also has the additional options of 7.Nd5 and 3.Bb5, which is why some Black players try to reach the Sveshnikov Sicilian via 2...e6.}) ({➤} 6... Bb4 {is a solid variation, with which Black has good chances of equalizing the game. However, we do not see the typical attacking play of the Sicilian Defense here. Therefore, I prefer the more adventurous 6...Bc5.} 7. a3 {As the e4 pawn is under attack, White forces the exchange of the bishop.} Bxc3+ 8. Nxc3 d5 {Liberates the queenside and fights for the center.} 9. exd5 exd5 {Black accepts positional disadvantages (the isolated pawn d5 and the opposing bishop pair) in exchange for rapid development and control of the central squares. Nevertheless, a long fight for equality lies ahead.}) 7. Bf4 {The most common continuation. White is threatening a knight fork on c7 and simultaneously targets the weakened d6 square. The move e4-e5 is also a threat.} O-O ({The only good move. Black secures their king, dodges the knight checks, and provides the knight on f6 a retreat square on e8. If Black now manages to liberate the queenside with ...d7-d5, they would already be better. Therefore, White should now aim to blockade the pawn on d7.} 7... e5 $2 8. Be3 $1 Bxe3 9. Nd6+ Ke7 10. fxe3 {. A very similar position arises after 7.Be3 Bxe3 8.Nd6+ Ke7 9.fxe3 . The only difference is that the black e-pawn is already on e5 here. This small difference turns out to be fatal for Black, because the squares f5 and d5 are accessible to the white pieces, and Bc4 with an attack on f7 is also an option.}) 8. Bc7 $1 Qe7 (8... Qe8 $2 {Takes away the last retreat square from the knight:} 9. e5 {.}) 9. Bd6 {, Black now has to exchange the bishops themselves.} Bxd6 10. Qxd6 Qd8 $1 {The direct queen trade leads to a slightly worse position for Black because the d-pawn is backward and weak and the bishop on c8 is undeveloped. Therefore, Black accepts a loss of time and relies on counterplay on the queenside. White now has two critical continuations: The main line 11.0-0-0 and 11.Nc7. Besides, we will examine other continuations that are occasionally played. 10...Ne8 is the old main line, which is only rarely seen nowadays. 11.Qxe7 Nxe7 12.O-O-O f5 13.e5 $14 . Black is very solid, but has not yet solved the problem of developing the queenside. White is slightly better.} 11. O-O-O {The most common move by far. White brings the king to safety and increases pressure along the d-file. We reach an opposite side castling situation so typical of the Sicilian Defense. Both sides will now try to attack the opponent's king.} a6 {Drives away the knight and prepares ...b7-b5.} 12. Nd4 Ne7 $1 13. Qg3 {The queen retreat was first played in the grandmaster game Nevednichy-Navara [/variation/36056606], Patras 2019 (½-½) and has since found some followers. White avoids a potential attack on the queen by ...Ne8 and thus now threatens e4-e5 with a subsequent piece attack on the kingside. Black should respond precisely.} b5 {Black cannot prevent e4-e5 and therefore focuses on their own play on the queenside. There's a threat of ...b5-b4.} 14. e5 ({With} 14. Bd3 {, White protects the e4-pawn and thus defends against the threat ...b5-b4, but this is too slow to pose any problems.} d6 {and now: A) The game Das–Krause [/variation/36055951], Walsrode 2023 (0-1) continued} 15. h4 $2 b4 16. Nce2 e5 17. Nb3 Qc7 {. White cannot counter the impending attack on the queenside ...a6-a5-a4 and lost after a few more moves. B) Necessary was 15.f4 , for instance 15...Nh5 (or 15...b4) 16.Qe3 Nxf4 17.Qxf4 e5 18.Qf2 exd4 19.Qxd4 Be6 with equality.}) 14... Nfd5 ({Weaker is} 14... Ne8 $6 15. Bd3 Bb7 16. Ne4 {, which gave White a mighty kingside attack in the game Smirnov-Kezin [/variation/36055952], Khanty Mansiysk 2022 (1-0).}) 15. Nxd5 {This exchange is connected to a concrete idea.} Nxd5 16. Nf5 $5 {White forces the weakening of the opponent's pawn structure. Other moves allow Black to strengthen their kingside defense with ...f7-f5.} exf5 17. Rxd5 Bb7 ({The precise move order. Navara instead went for} 17... Qa5 18. a3 Bb7 {, but was slightly worse after} 19. Rd4 $1 {( Instead, 19.Rxd7?! Rad8! transposes to our main line).}) 18. Rd4 Qb6 $1 ({Directed against} 18... Qa5 {, after which White now can play} 19. a3 {without allowing ...b5-b4. Worse is 18.Rd6?! , because after 18...Qa5 , there is no good defense for the a2-pawn. 19.Kb1?? fails to 19...Qe1+ and mate next move, while after 19.a3 b4 , Black has an attack.}) {This strong pawn sacrifice gives Black active play.} 19. Rxd7 Qa5 $1 {The queen attacks the a2-pawn and simultaneously keeps an eye on the e1-square.} 20. a3 (20. Qc3 {is met by} Qxa2 $1 {, as} 21. Rxb7 $2 {fails to} Qa1+ 22. Kd2 Rfd8+ {with a decisive attack. There might follow} 23. Ke3 Qc1+ 24. Kf3 Qd1+ 25. Ke3 Qd5 {and the double threat of ...Qe4# and ...Qxb7 wins for Black.}) 20... Rad8 {Black creates strong threats against White's king.} 21. Rxd8 ({After ther alternative} 21. b4 Qb6 22. Rxd8 Rxd8 {(Perunović) the weakened white king's position and control over the d-file give Black good compensation. There's a threat of ...Qd4.}) 21... Rxd8 22. Bd3 ({The most natural defense against the mating threat on e1. Or} 22. Qc3 {, after which both} Qxc3 23. bxc3 Re8 24. f4 g5 {and 22...Qb6!?= are possible.}) 22... b4 $1 {Black continues to play for an attack.} 23. Bxf5 bxa3 24. Qxa3 (24. bxa3 {looks very risky. However, it is playable as well and leads to equality, for example after} Qd2+ 25. Kb2 Be4 26. Bxe4 Qd4+ 27. Ka2 Qxe4 {, when Black likely either wins back the pawns or gives perpetual.}) 24... Qxe5 25. Z0 ({Black will soon regain the pawn. The position is dynamically equal, but due to the opponent's activity and the vulnerable king's position, White should be cautious, as shown in the game Begmuratov-Fedorov [/variation/36056776], Tashkent 2023 (0-1):} 25. Qh3 Qf4+ 26. Kb1 g6 27. Bd3 $2 {(Necessary was 27.Bg4 Qxf2 28.Bf3= ) 27...Qxf2 28.Rf1 Qxg2 . White had nothing to show for the minus pawn and lost after a few more moves.}) *

