c7 $1 Qe7 (8... Qe8 $2 {Takes away the last retreat square from the knight:} 9. e5 {.}) 9. Bd6 {, Black now has to exchange the bishops themselves.} Bxd6 10. Qxd6 Qd8 $1 {The direct queen trade leads to a slightly worse position for Black because the d-pawn is backward and weak and the bishop on c8 is undeveloped. Therefore, Black accepts a loss of time and relies on counterplay on the queenside. White now has two critical continuations: The main line 11.0-0-0 and 11.Nc7. Besides, we will examine other continuations that are occasionally played. 10...Ne8 is the old main line, which is only rarely seen nowadays. 11.Qxe7 Nxe7 12.O-O-O f5 13.e5 $14 . Black is very solid, but has not yet solved the problem of developing the queenside. White is slightly better.} 11. O-O-O {The most common move by far. White brings the king to safety and increases pressure along the d-file. We reach an opposite side castling situation so typical of the Sicilian Defense. Both sides will now try to attack the opponent's king.} a6 {Drives away the knight and prepares ...b7-b5.} 12. Nd4 Ne7 $1 {This unusual move was first played in 2017 and has led to a renaissance of the entire Cobra Variation. Black avoids exchanging knights and is ready to initiate the typical counterplay on the queenside with ...b7-b5 and ...Bb7. White has now tried a whole range of moves, most of which aim at the black king.} 13. Nb3 $5 {Provides the queen with the option to retreat on the d-file.} b5 14. h4 Bb7 15. f3 h5 {An interesting move to slow down White's play on the kingside. However, this also weakens the king's position - especially the pawn break g2-g4 can become dangerous. Black should therefore play for a queen exchange to take the sting out of a potential kingside attack. One possible way is ...Re8, ...Rc8, and ...Qc7. White is somewhat more comfortable, but not more.} *

