ts to refute the opening.}) ({➤} 6... d5 $2 {is positionally desirable, but tactically a mistake:} 7. exd5 exd5 8. Bf4 {and the Nc7+ fork can hardly be prevented.}) ({➤ After} 6... d6 {White has nothing better than the aforementioned transition into the Sveshnikov Sicilian:} 7. Bf4 e5 8. Bg5 {. This position usually arises through the move order 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 e5 6.Ndb5 d6 7.Bg5 . In this move order, however, White also has the additional options of 7.Nd5 and 3.Bb5, which is why some Black players try to reach the Sveshnikov Sicilian via 2...e6.}) ({➤} 6... Bb4 {is a solid variation, with which Black has good chances of equalizing the game. However, we do not see the typical attacking play of the Sicilian Defense here. Therefore, I prefer the more adventurous 6...Bc5.} 7. a3 {As the e4 pawn is under attack, White forces the exchange of the bishop.} Bxc3+ 8. Nxc3 d5 {Liberates the queenside and fights for the center.} 9. exd5 exd5 {Black accepts positional disadvantages (the isolated pawn d5 and the opposing bishop pair) in exchange for rapid development and control of the central squares. Nevertheless, a long fight for equality lies ahead.}) 7. Bf4 {The most common continuation. White is threatening a knight fork on c7 and simultaneously targets the weakened d6 square. The move e4-e5 is also a threat.} O-O ({The only good move. Black secures their king, dodges the knight checks, and provides the knight on f6 a retreat square on e8. If Black now manages to liberate the queenside with ...d7-d5, they would already be better. Therefore, White should now aim to blockade the pawn on d7.} 7... e5 $2 8. Be3 $1 Bxe3 9. Nd6+ Ke7 10. fxe3 {. A very similar position arises after 7.Be3 Bxe3 8.Nd6+ Ke7 9.fxe3 . The only difference is that the black e-pawn is already on e5 here. This small difference turns out to be fatal for Black, because the squares f5 and d5 are accessible to the white pieces, and Bc4 with an attack on f7 is also an option.}) 8. Bc7 $1 Qe7 (8... Qe8 $2 {Takes away the last retreat square from the knight:} 9. e5 {.}) 9. Bd6 {, Black now has to exchange the bishops themselves.} Bxd6 10. Qxd6 Qd8 $1 {The direct queen trade leads to a slightly worse position for Black because the d-pawn is backward and weak and the bishop on c8 is undeveloped. Therefore, Black accepts a loss of time and relies on counterplay on the queenside. White now has two critical continuations: The main line 11.0-0-0 and 11.Nc7. Besides, we will examine other continuations that are occasionally played. 10...Ne8 is the old main line, which is only rarely seen nowadays. 11.Qxe7 Nxe7 12.O-O-O f5 13.e5 $14 . Black is very solid, but has not yet solved the problem of developing the queenside. White is slightly better.} 11. O-O-O {The most common move by far. White brings the king to safety and increases pressure along the d-file. We reach an opposite side castling situation so typical of the Sicilian Defense. Both sides will now try to attack the opponent's king.} a6 {Drives away the knight and prepares ...b7-b5.} 12. Nd4 Ne7 $1 {This unusual move was first played in 2017 and has led to a renaissance of the entire Cobra Variation. Black avoids exchanging knights and is ready to initiate the typical counterplay on the queenside with ...b7-b5 and ...Bb7. White has now tried a whole range of moves, most of which aim at the black king.} 13. Nb3 $5 {Provides the queen with the option to retreat on the d-file.} b5 14. f3 {Qd2} ({The queen is better here than on g3. On g3, it gets in the way of its own pawns. On d2, it also keeps an eye on the queenside and can disrupt Black's attack there.} 14. Qg3 b4 15. Na4 d6 {is comfortable for Black. In the blitz game Geller–Perunovic [/variation/31423326/#/16/b], Moskau 2019 (0-1) Qf2 Rb8} 16. e5 $15 {Nd5 exd6 Nxd6 followed. The knights have taken good squares. Black is slightly better.}) ({d6!? Normally, Black places the bishop on b7, but here White has already fortified the center. Now the bishop gets new perspectives. The pawn move also serves as preparation for ...b5-b4. Another interesting idea is} 14. Qc7 {a3 f5!? followed by an exchange on e4. Black gains counterplay against the white center.}) ({After the direct b4} 14. Na4 Rb8 {,} 15. Nac5 {with an attack on the d7 and a6 pawns can follow.}) 14... e5 ({After g4?! , Black's concrete idea becomes apparent:} 14... b4 15. Na4 Rb8 16. Kb1 {Qd7 Nac5 Qa7 , and now the white knight would have to either retreat to the vulnerable a4 square, or clear the path for Black's a-pawn.}) {Bb7 After the white e-pawn has moved, the bishop is at its best on this diagonal again. exd6 Cuts off the white d-pawn from it's defense.} 15. Nc5 {Bc6 d7 Nef6 Black had to first secure the point d5, but is now ready to win back the pawn. The position is dynamically equal.} *

