ts to refute the opening.}) ({➤} 6... d5 $2 {is positionally desirable, but tactically a mistake:} 7. exd5 exd5 8. Bf4 {and the Nc7+ fork can hardly be prevented.}) ({➤ After} 6... d6 {White has nothing better than the aforementioned transition into the Sveshnikov Sicilian:} 7. Bf4 e5 8. Bg5 {. This position usually arises through the move order 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 e5 6.Ndb5 d6 7.Bg5 . In this move order, however, White also has the additional options of 7.Nd5 and 3.Bb5, which is why some Black players try to reach the Sveshnikov Sicilian via 2...e6.}) ({➤} 6... Bb4 {is a solid variation, with which Black has good chances of equalizing the game. However, we do not see the typical attacking play of the Sicilian Defense here. Therefore, I prefer the more adventurous 6...Bc5.} 7. a3 {As the e4 pawn is under attack, White forces the exchange of the bishop.} Bxc3+ 8. Nxc3 d5 {Liberates the queenside and fights for the center.} 9. exd5 exd5 {Black accepts positional disadvantages (the isolated pawn d5 and the opposing bishop pair) in exchange for rapid development and control of the central squares. Nevertheless, a long fight for equality lies ahead.}) 7. Bf4 {The most common continuation. White is threatening a knight fork on c7 and simultaneously targets the weakened d6 square. The move e4-e5 is also a threat.} O-O ({The only good move. Black secures their king, dodges the knight checks, and provides the knight on f6 a retreat square on e8. If Black now manages to liberate the queenside with ...d7-d5, they would already be better. Therefore, White should now aim to blockade the pawn on d7.} 7... e5 $2 8. Be3 $1 Bxe3 9. Nd6+ Ke7 10. fxe3 {. A very similar position arises after 7.Be3 Bxe3 8.Nd6+ Ke7 9.fxe3 . The only difference is that the black e-pawn is already on e5 here. This small difference turns out to be fatal for Black, because the squares f5 and d5 are accessible to the white pieces, and Bc4 with an attack on f7 is also an option.}) 8. Bc7 $1 Qe7 (8... Qe8 $2 {Takes away the last retreat square from the knight:} 9. e5 {.}) 9. Bd6 {, Black now has to exchange the bishops themselves.} Bxd6 10. Qxd6 Qd8 $1 {The direct queen trade leads to a slightly worse position for Black because the d-pawn is backward and weak and the bishop on c8 is undeveloped. Therefore, Black accepts a loss of time and relies on counterplay on the queenside. White now has two critical continuations: The main line 11.0-0-0 and 11.Nc7. Besides, we will examine other continuations that are occasionally played. 10...Ne8 is the old main line, which is only rarely seen nowadays. 11.Qxe7 Nxe7 12.O-O-O f5 13.e5 $14 . Black is very solid, but has not yet solved the problem of developing the queenside. White is slightly better.} 11. O-O-O {The most common move by far. White brings the king to safety and increases pressure along the d-file. We reach an opposite side castling situation so typical of the Sicilian Defense. Both sides will now try to attack the opponent's king.} a6 {Drives away the knight and prepares ...b7-b5.} 12. Nd4 Ne7 $1 {This unusual move was first played in 2017 and has led to a renaissance of the entire Cobra Variation. Black avoids exchanging knights and is ready to initiate the typical counterplay on the queenside with ...b7-b5 and ...Bb7. White has now tried a whole range of moves, most of which aim at the black king.} 13. h4 ({The kingside attack begins. White wants to advance the pawn further, preferably to h6. If Black themselves play ...h7-h6, White gets the dangerous pawn break g2-g4-g5. The move of the h-pawn is more direct and dangerous than} 13. g4 {, which is similar in spirit.}) 13... b5 (13... Ne8 14. Qh2 $1 {is another advantage of White's last move. The queen is not obstructing its own pawns here and cannot be easily attacked.}) 14. h5 h6 ({Black should stop the pawn, either directly or after} 14... Ne8 15. Qh2 h6 {.}) (14... Bb7 $2 15. h6 g6 16. Nb3 {is advantageous for White. Black now has to constantly keep an eye on the checkmate motif on g7, such as after} Nxe4 $4 17. Nxe4 Bxe4 18. Qe5 Bc6 19. Qg7# {.}) 15. g4 $1 {Other moves have been played as well, but it is not clear why White should wait with this. Black cannot afford to capture on g4 in this position.} Bb7 (15... Nxg4 $2 16. Rg1 Nf6 {( 16...Nxf2 17.Qg3+- ) 17.Bd3 . Next, White will bring the queen to the kingside (f4 or g3) and play e4-e5, with an overwhelming attack.}) 16. f3 Re8 $1 ({Black should aim to neutralize the white attack. It is important to exchange queens for that purpose. Black defends the e7 knight and prepares ...Qb8.} 16... Nc6 $6 {, similar to my suggestion after 16.Bd3, would not be as effective here:} 17. Nb3 $1 Qb8 18. Qd2 $16 {. The threats are g4-g5 and Nc5. After 16.Bd3, White doesn't have this retreat for the queen.}) 17. a3 ({An illustrative variation. White has many other moves. In the only practical example,} 17. Rh2 Qb8 $1 18. Nb3 Bc6 19. a3 {followed, Nevednichy–Pastar [/variation/31423329/#/19/w], Plankenburg 2021 (1-0). Here, I like} a5 {followed by ...b5-b4. Black has no problems.}) 17... Qb8 18. Nb3 Bc6 19. Qxb8 (19. Qd2 {is not dangerous. The white queen is not particularly well placed here. On the other hand, the black queen controls the diagonal b8-h2 and supports the counterplay ...a6-a5 and ...b5-b4. Black should first stop g4-g5 with} Nh7 {.}) 19... Rexb8 $1 {, Oradea By taking with the kingside rook, Black clears the path for the king, which can help in defending the backward pawn on d7. Black now has various plans.} *

