ts to refute the opening.}) ({➤} 6... d5 $2 {is positionally desirable, but tactically a mistake:} 7. exd5 exd5 8. Bf4 {and the Nc7+ fork can hardly be prevented.}) ({➤ After} 6... d6 {White has nothing better than the aforementioned transition into the Sveshnikov Sicilian:} 7. Bf4 e5 8. Bg5 {. This position usually arises through the move order 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 e5 6.Ndb5 d6 7.Bg5 . In this move order, however, White also has the additional options of 7.Nd5 and 3.Bb5, which is why some Black players try to reach the Sveshnikov Sicilian via 2...e6.}) ({➤} 6... Bb4 {is a solid variation, with which Black has good chances of equalizing the game. However, we do not see the typical attacking play of the Sicilian Defense here. Therefore, I prefer the more adventurous 6...Bc5.} 7. a3 {As the e4 pawn is under attack, White forces the exchange of the bishop.} Bxc3+ 8. Nxc3 d5 {Liberates the queenside and fights for the center.} 9. exd5 exd5 {Black accepts positional disadvantages (the isolated pawn d5 and the opposing bishop pair) in exchange for rapid development and control of the central squares. Nevertheless, a long fight for equality lies ahead.}) 7. Bf4 {The most common continuation. White is threatening a knight fork on c7 and simultaneously targets the weakened d6 square. The move e4-e5 is also a threat.} O-O ({The only good move. Black secures their king, dodges the knight checks, and provides the knight on f6 a retreat square on e8. If Black now manages to liberate the queenside with ...d7-d5, they would already be better. Therefore, White should now aim to blockade the pawn on d7.} 7... e5 $2 8. Be3 $1 Bxe3 9. Nd6+ Ke7 10. fxe3 {. A very similar position arises after 7.Be3 Bxe3 8.Nd6+ Ke7 9.fxe3 . The only difference is that the black e-pawn is already on e5 here. This small difference turns out to be fatal for Black, because the squares f5 and d5 are accessible to the white pieces, and Bc4 with an attack on f7 is also an option.}) 8. Bc7 $1 Qe7 (8... Qe8 $2 {Takes away the last retreat square from the knight:} 9. e5 {.}) 9. Bd6 {, Black now has to exchange the bishops themselves.} Bxd6 10. Qxd6 Qd8 $1 {The direct queen trade leads to a slightly worse position for Black because the d-pawn is backward and weak and the bishop on c8 is undeveloped. Therefore, Black accepts a loss of time and relies on counterplay on the queenside. White now has two critical continuations: The main line 11.0-0-0 and 11.Nc7. Besides, we will examine other continuations that are occasionally played. 10...Ne8 is the old main line, which is only rarely seen nowadays. 11.Qxe7 Nxe7 12.O-O-O f5 13.e5 $14 . Black is very solid, but has not yet solved the problem of developing the queenside. White is slightly better.} 11. O-O-O {The most common move by far. White brings the king to safety and increases pressure along the d-file. We reach an opposite side castling situation so typical of the Sicilian Defense. Both sides will now try to attack the opponent's king.} a6 {Drives away the knight and prepares ...b7-b5.} 12. Nd4 Ne7 $1 {This unusual move was first played in 2017 and has led to a renaissance of the entire Cobra Variation. Black avoids exchanging knights and is ready to initiate the typical counterplay on the queenside with ...b7-b5 and ...Bb7. White has now tried a whole range of moves, most of which aim at the black king.} 13. h4 ({The kingside attack begins. White wants to advance the pawn further, preferably to h6. If Black themselves play ...h7-h6, White gets the dangerous pawn break g2-g4-g5. The move of the h-pawn is more direct and dangerous than} 13. g4 {, which is similar in spirit.}) 13... b5 (13... Ne8 14. Qh2 $1 {is another advantage of White's last move. The queen is not obstructing its own pawns here and cannot be easily attacked.}) 14. h5 h6 ({Black should stop the pawn, either directly or after} 14... Ne8 15. Qh2 h6 {.}) (14... Bb7 $2 15. h6 g6 16. Nb3 {is advantageous for White. Black now has to constantly keep an eye on the checkmate motif on g7, such as after} Nxe4 $4 17. Nxe4 Bxe4 18. Qe5 Bc6 19. Qg7# {.}) 15. g4 $1 {Other moves have been played as well, but it is not clear why White should wait with this. Black cannot afford to capture on g4 in this position.} Bb7 (15... Nxg4 $2 16. Rg1 Nf6 {( 16...Nxf2 17.Qg3+- ) 17.Bd3 . Next, White will bring the queen to the kingside (f4 or g3) and play e4-e5, with an overwhelming attack.}) 16. Bd3 Nc6 ({A strong move preparing the exchange of queens. An interesting alternative is the typical Sicilian exchange sacrifice} 16... Rc8 17. Rhg1 Rxc3 $1 18. bxc3 Bxe4 {which leads to a complicated position. The weakened white pawn structure and the central pawn are reasonable compensation for the sacrificed material. The critical continuation is} 19. g5 hxg5 20. Rxg5 {, leading to significant complications.}) 17. Nxc6 {After other moves, ...Qb8 follows.} Bxc6 18. Rhg1 Qb8 {Raxb8 In this endgame, the bishop on d3 is not positioned particularly well, as Black can now play ...d7-d6. Black generally wants to place the pawns on dark squares to provide space for their own bishop and obstruct the opponent's bishop.} 19. e5 $1 {Otherwise, White cannot pose any problems.} Nh7 20. Be4 ({A novelty that allows White to still pose problems. After the exchange of bishops, the black pawns on the queenside become weak. After} 20. f4 {, Grandmaster Khenkin demonstrated how to neutralize the white initiative: After} f6 $1 {, the black pieces become active.} 21. exf6 Nxf6 22. g5 {, Reuker-Khenkin [/variation/31423330/#/23/w], Budweis 2021 (½-½). The simplest way forward now is} Nxh5 {, leading to multiple exchanges and an equal position.}) 20... f6 $1 ({This secures sufficient counterplay for Black. Both rook and knight are activated. Bad is} 20... Bxe4 $2 21. Nxe4 {followed by Nc5. Black loses a pawn.}) 21. Bxc6 dxc6 22. exf6 Rxf6 23. Ne4 {Nc5} Rxf2 {Nxa6 Re8! Due to the weaknesses in Black's pawn structure, White has the initiative in this endgame, but Black can hold their ground. Black's biggest asset is the e-pawn, which is only seemingly a weakness. With 26...Re8, the pawn's advance is supported. The knight will also later support the pawn. Black should spend as little time as possible defending the queenside. Quick counterplay is more important.} *

[Event "The Venomous Four Knights Sicilian"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "2024.03.13"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Cobra (6.Ndb5) Main Line I"]
[Black "2 | Cobra Main Line 7.Nd6+ | "]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B40"]
[PlyCount "20"]
[EventDate "2024.??.??"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.co"]

1. e4 c5 {The Sicilian Opening stands for a sharp fight. Black somewhat neglects their piece development in order to prevent White from establishing a full pawn center with d2-d4.} 2. Nf3 e6 ({The third most common move after} 2... d6 {and}) (2... Nc6 {. With this, Black primarily prepares the development of the dark-squared bishop, but the center push ...d7-d5 becomes a possibility as well.}) (2... Nc6 {is an alternative way to reach the Four Knights Sicilian:} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6 {and we have landed in our repertoire via transposition. I decided against this path because White has a very serious and popular alternative in 3.Bb5 , the Rossolimo Variation. With 2...e6 the Rossolimo Variation is avoided.}) 3. d4 {The Open Sicilian and the starting position of this course. I examine alternatives for White on the second and third moves in a separate course on the Anti-Sicilians. The Open Sicilian is White's most principled attempt to fight for the opening advantage. White has more space and wants to open up the position, relying on rapid piece development. In return, Black gets the semi-open c-file, which can often be used for counterplay later on. Moreover, the exchange of the d-pawn for the c-pawn is a minor positional concession, as White now has only one pawn in the center and therefore can no longer fight quite as well for the important central squares.} cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 ({A very logical move - the knight is developed and simultaneously attacks the e4 pawn. Black takes advantage of the fact that the knight cannot be directly attacked with e4-e5 .} 4... Nc6 {is also possible, but gives White the additional option} 5. Nb5 {.}) 5. Nc3 ({Develops the knight and reinforces White's influence on the central square d5. Moreover, the diagonal a5-e1 is now interrupted, so that e4-e5 becomes a strong threat.} 5. e5 $2 {allows the double attack} Qa5+ {followed by -- Qxe5 .}) 5... Nc6 {Another natural developing move that continues the fight for the central squares. Black, at least temporarily, is preventing e4-e5 and threatening ...Bb4 with pressure on the white center. The starting position of the Sicilian Four Knights has now been reached. This method of play was first used in the second half of the 19th century. Early adopters included the masters Schiffers, Blackburne, Mieses, and Janowski. White now has a multitude of options.} 6. Ndb5 ({White moves the knight for the third time, but there are good reasons for this time loss. Due to the pawn moves, Black has weakened the squares d6 and c7 . Specifically, an unpleasant knight check on d6 is threatened. For a long time, 6.Ndb5 was considered the main variation. However, at the highest level there has recently been a trend towards} 6. Nxc6 {. The reason for this is that after}) (6. Ndb5 {, Black can transition into the Sveshnikov Sicilian, where White currently struggles to prove an opening advantage. However, 6.Ndb5 still remains the most common move, especially below grandmaster level.}) 6... Bc5 ({A rare move that will come as a surprise to many of our opponents. More popular are} 6... d6 {(which usually leads to the Sveshnikov variation) or}) (6... Bb4 {.}) ({➤ With} 6... Bc5 {, Black prepares to castle and targets the tactically vulnerable point f2. Additionally, Black can now respond to the knight check on d6 with a king move without blocking the development of the bishop on f8. 6...Bc5 is known as the 'Cobra Variation', tracing back to an article by Swedish IM Jesper Hall. According to my database, the Cobra was first played in 1963 by Soviet IM Viacheslav Osnos, but it remained a niche for a long time. Nowadays, some strong grandmasters have discovered the move for themselves, especially in faster time controls. I can confirm from my own experience: In blitz, the Cobra is a particularly dangerous weapon, as many opponents do not know the variation well enough, react poorly and/or consume a lot of time. The 'holes ' on d6 and c7 also invite (unsuccessful) attempts to refute the opening.}) ({➤} 6... d5 $2 {is positionally desirable, but tactically a mistake:} 7. exd5 exd5 8. Bf4 {and the Nc7+ fork can hardly be prevented.}) ({➤ After} 6... d6 {White has nothing better than the aforementioned transition into the Sveshnikov Sicilian:} 7. Bf4 e5 8. Bg5 {. This position usually arises through the move order 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 e5 6.Ndb5 d6 7.Bg5 . In this move order, however, White also has the additional options of 7.Nd5 and 3.Bb5, which is why some Black players try to reach the Sveshnikov Sicilian via 2...e6.}) ({➤} 6... Bb4 {is a solid variation, with which Black has good chances of equalizing the game. However, we do not see the typical attacking play of the Sicilian Defense here. Therefore, I prefer the more adventurous 6...Bc5.} 7. a3 {As the e4 pawn is under attack, White forces the exchange of the bishop.} Bxc3+ 8. Nxc3 d5 {Liberates the queenside and fights for the center.} 9. exd5 exd5 {Black accepts positional disadvantages (the isolated pawn d5 and the opposing bishop pair) in exchange for rapid development and control of the central squares. Nevertheless, a long fight for equality lies ahead.}) 7. Nd6+ ({Less popular than} 7. Bf4 {, but quite natural. Now Black loses the right to castle.}) 7... Ke7 $1 ({Not} 7... Bxd6 $2 8. Qxd6 {. Black can't castle here either, and the dark squares are firmly under White's control.} Qe7 9. Bf4 $16 {. It is important to dislodge the d6 knight from its strong blockade position. White is not sufficiently developed to directly pose problems for Black's centralized king.}) 8. Nc4 $2 {An unfortunate square for the knight.} d5 $1 {Black is better developed and can afford to open the position, despite the centralized king.} 9. Nd2 $1 {This limits the damage.} d4 10. Na4 Bd6 {Black is better. White is underdeveloped and the knight on a4 is poorly placed. The direct threat is ...Qa5.} *

