to refute the opening.}) ({➤} 6... d5 $2 {is positionally desirable, but tactically a mistake:} 7. exd5 exd5 8. Bf4 {and the Nc7+ fork can hardly be prevented.}) ({➤ After} 6... d6 {White has nothing better than the aforementioned transition into the Sveshnikov Sicilian:} 7. Bf4 e5 8. Bg5 {. This position usually arises through the move order 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 e5 6.Ndb5 d6 7.Bg5 . In this move order, however, White also has the additional options of 7.Nd5 and 3.Bb5, which is why some Black players try to reach the Sveshnikov Sicilian via 2...e6.}) ({➤} 6... Bb4 {is a solid variation, with which Black has good chances of equalizing the game. However, we do not see the typical attacking play of the Sicilian Defense here. Therefore, I prefer the more adventurous 6...Bc5.} 7. a3 {As the e4 pawn is under attack, White forces the exchange of the bishop.} Bxc3+ 8. Nxc3 d5 {Liberates the queenside and fights for the center.} 9. exd5 exd5 {Black accepts positional disadvantages (the isolated pawn d5 and the opposing bishop pair) in exchange for rapid development and control of the central squares. Nevertheless, a long fight for equality lies ahead.}) 7. Nd6+ ({Less popular than} 7. Bf4 {, but quite natural. Now Black loses the right to castle.}) 7... Ke7 $1 ({Not} 7... Bxd6 $2 8. Qxd6 {. Black can't castle here either, and the dark squares are firmly under White's control.} Qe7 9. Bf4 $16 {. It is important to dislodge the d6 knight from its strong blockade position. White is not sufficiently developed to directly pose problems for Black's centralized king.}) 8. Nc4 $2 {An unfortunate square for the knight.} d5 $1 {Black is better developed and can afford to open the position, despite the centralized king.} 9. exd5 $2 ({By far the most common continuation, but after this, Black is already winning. Also bad is} 9. e5 $2 Nd7 {. To avoid losing the e5 pawn for nothing, White sacrificed a piece in the game Dervishi-Vocaturo [/variation/31423331/#/9/b], Batumi 2019 (0-1):} 10. Bg5+ f6 11. exf6+ gxf6 12. Nxd5+ exd5 13. Qxd5 Qg8 {Black opts for the pragmatic solution – White does not have enough pieces in the attack ( 13...fxg5-+ was also good).}) 9... exd5 10. Nd2 Ng4 {White is unable to protect the f2 pawn. Black is winning.} *

