All black pieces are now well placed - even the rook on h8 is joining the action. The threat is ...Ng4. White would then have to play g2-g3 to prevent checkmate on h2. This later allows Black to play the pawn break ...h5-h4, opening up the h-file. White lacks defenders on the kingside.} 11. Bg5 {Steps out of the pin and renews the threat of ...Ng4. Bxf6} ({The most direct defense against ...Ng4.} 11. Na4 $2 {runs into an already familiar tactical motif:} Ng4 12. g3 Nxf2 13. Rxf2 Bxf2+ 14. Kxf2 Qa5 {. The double attack wins material. Grötzbach-Feuerstack [/variation/31423334/#/15/b], Hamburg 2014 (0-1).}) {gxf6 A weakening of Black's pawn structure, not without its advantages. The pawn on f6 provides additional stability to the black king in the center. Furthermore, play on the half-open g-file is now possible. Kh1} 11... a6 12. Z0 ({A useful move, avoiding the annoying Nxb5 and preparing the regrouping ...Ba7-b8. Black has the more active pieces and is therefore slightly better. The white position, however, is very solid. A practical example is the game Paveto-Flores [/variation/31423336/#/13/b], Buenos Aires 2022 (1-0): f4} 12. h4 {. White would be better off stopping this pawn with 15.h3. a3} Bd4 13. Qe1 {h3 g3 Ne7 Attacks the knight. After Nd1 , Black could have obtained a big advantage with} d5 $1 {with the idea of} 14. exd5 {f5! The king on h1 is now very unsafe, and a check on the long diagonal would be the end. In the game, Black chose a weaker continuation and later lost due to a miscalculation.}) *

