loss of material. 10.Rb1 Qa3 11.Rb3 Qa5 12.Rb5 , winning a piece. B) 9...Bxf2+ . We encounter this tactical motif elsewhere, but here it is not good. 10.Qxf2 Qxb2 11.Kd2! Qxa1 12.Qc5+- . Black has won material, but their king comes under attack, and the queen is far away from the action.}) 9. Nxc8+ {Exchanging the strong knight for the undeveloped bishop is not more sensible now than it was one move earlier.} Rxc8 10. Bg5 {A typical move. On the one hand, it prevents Nd5+, and on the other, Black can later capture on c3 and play against the weakened pawn structure. Qd2 Threatens Nd5+ again. Bxc3! Qxc3} {bxc3 Qc7 followed by ...Nd8 is slightly better for Black. The white pawns on the queenside are weak.} Nd4 {Qb4+ d6} 11. Bd3 {The only move.} Nxc2+ 12. Bxc2 {Rxc2 Qxb7+ , Cappelle la Grande} *

