loss of material. 10.Rb1 Qa3 11.Rb3 Qa5 12.Rb5 , winning a piece. B) 9...Bxf2+ . We encounter this tactical motif elsewhere, but here it is not good. 10.Qxf2 Qxb2 11.Kd2! Qxa1 12.Qc5+- . Black has won material, but their king comes under attack, and the queen is far away from the action.}) 9. Nf5+ Kf8 10. Be3 {White wants to exchange the defender of the d6-square.} Bb4 $1 {Of course, Black does not agree to the exchange. From b4, the bishop still covers d6 and also puts pressure on the white center, threatening ...d7-d5.} 11. Bg5 $6 {This position is usually reached via 6...Bb4 7.Nd6+ Ke7 8.Bf4 e5 9.Nf5+ Kf8 10.Bg5?! . By pinning the knight, White fights for the d5 square.} d5 $1 {This typical pawn sacrifice opens the position in favor of Black. White has lost too much time.} 12. Bxf6 Qxf6 13. Qxd5 Bxf5 14. exf5 Rd8 {Black could have also taken on f5, but the pawn is not so important here.} 15. Qe4 (15. Qf3 e4 $1 $15 {.}) 15... g6 16. Z0 ({Black is clearly better. White has neglected development and now has to worry about their king. If} 16. fxg6 $6 hxg6 {the rook on h8 also joins the game.}) *

