loss of material. 10.Rb1 Qa3 11.Rb3 Qa5 12.Rb5 , winning a piece. B) 9...Bxf2+ . We encounter this tactical motif elsewhere, but here it is not good. 10.Qxf2 Qxb2 11.Kd2! Qxa1 12.Qc5+- . Black has won material, but their king comes under attack, and the queen is far away from the action.}) 9. Nf5+ Kf8 10. Be3 {White wants to exchange the defender of the d6-square.} Bb4 $1 {Of course, Black does not agree to the exchange. From b4, the bishop still covers d6 and also puts pressure on the white center, threatening ...d7-d5.} 11. Bc4 {Logical. Black was threatening ...d7-d5, so White protects the square one more time.} d5 $1 ({Nevertheless! Black frees themselves and obtains a good position. This is tactically possible because the knight on f5 is under attack. Not a good idea would be} 11... Nxe4 $2 12. Qd5 Qf6 13. Qxe4 d5 $1 14. Qxd5 Bxf5 15. O-O-O {. Black was able to avoid losing the piece, but the king is not yet safe and White is fully mobilized. White has the advantage.}) 12. Bxd5 {White has to take with the bishop first.} Bxf5 ({I prefer this over} 12... Nxd5 {, which is objectively of equal value:} 13. Qxd5 Qxd5 14. exd5 Bxf5 15. dxc6 bxc6 16. O-O-O Bxc3 17. bxc3 f6 {with a drawish endgame. exd5 Bxf5 dxc6 Qxd1+ Rxd1 bxc6 O-O Ke7= . The position is equal, but I don't like Black's unsafe king position. Zhang–Nagy [/variation/31423339/#/16/b], Budapest 2005 (½-½).}) 13. Bxc6 Nxe4 $1 (13... Bxe4 14. Bxe4 Nxe4 15. Qg4 $1 {is dangerous for Black.}) 14. Bxb7 {bxc3} Bxc3+ 15. Ke2 {Bxa1 Bxa8} Bd4 ({The last moves were forced. But not Qxa8?} 15... Qd6 {Kg8} 16. Rb1 $1 {followed by Rb8+, winning the queen.}) 16. c3 $1 {Qxa8 cxd4} {Bf3 Qe7 . There is a threat of ...Bxe3 followed by ...e5-e4. Black can later bring their king to safety on g7 and will then have a slightly better position.} Ke7 {A sharp, but objectively balanced position has been reached. However, the black game seems easier to me. The g2 pawn is attacked and the black rook will be activated via the c-line.} *

