loss of material. 10.Rb1 Qa3 11.Rb3 Qa5 12.Rb5 , winning a piece. B) 9...Bxf2+ . We encounter this tactical motif elsewhere, but here it is not good. 10.Qxf2 Qxb2 11.Kd2! Qxa1 12.Qc5+- . Black has won material, but their king comes under attack, and the queen is far away from the action.}) 9. Nf5+ Kf8 10. Be3 {White wants to exchange the defender of the d6-square.} Bb4 $1 {Of course, Black does not agree to the exchange. From b4, the bishop still covers d6 and also puts pressure on the white center, threatening ...d7-d5.} 11. a3 Bxc3+ 12. bxc3 d5 ({After} 12... Nxe4 $2 {,} 13. Qd5 {is even stronger than 13.Qg4.} Nf6 14. Qd6+ Kg8 15. Bg5 $16 {. Black cannot easily break free from the bind.}) 13. Bc5+ $2 {This tempting check comes too soon.} Kg8 14. exd5 Qa5 $1 {exd5 Nxd5 Bc5+ Kg8 The text move is a strong novelty which exploits the tactical vulnerability of the white position. Bb4 cxb4 axb4 is even worse, as now the c-pawn falls: Qc7} 15. Ne3 Qxc3+ 16. Ke2 Bd7 {. After the better move cxb4 , White has an extra pawn on a3 in this position. Qc7 Ne3 Qc3+ Ke2 Bd7 Black threatens ...Bb5+. White will find it hard to get their king to safety and develop the kingside. Black is clearly better.} *

