1. e4 c5 {The Sicilian Opening stands for a sharp fight. Black somewhat neglects their piece development in order to prevent White from establishing a full pawn center with d2-d4.} 2. Nf3 e6 ({The third most common move after} 2... d6 {and}) (2... Nc6 {. With this, Black primarily prepares the development of the dark-squared bishop, but the center push ...d7-d5 becomes a possibility as well.}) (2... Nc6 {is an alternative way to reach the Four Knights Sicilian:} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6 {and we have landed in our repertoire via transposition. I decided against this path because White has a very serious and popular alternative in 3.Bb5 , the Rossolimo Variation. With 2...e6 the Rossolimo Variation is avoided.}) 3. d4 {The Open Sicilian and the starting position of this course. I examine alternatives for White on the second and third moves in a separate course on the Anti-Sicilians. The Open Sicilian is White's most principled attempt to fight for the opening advantage. White has more space and wants to open up the position, relying on rapid piece development. In return, Black gets the semi-open c-file, which can often be used for counterplay later on. Moreover, the exchange of the d-pawn for the c-pawn is a minor positional concession, as White now has only one pawn in the center and therefore can no longer fight quite as well for the important central squares.} cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 ({A very logical move - the knight is developed and simultaneously attacks the e4 pawn. Black takes advantage of the fact that the knight cannot be directly attacked with e4-e5 .} 4... Nc6 {is also possible, but gives White the additional option} 5. Nb5 {.}) 5. Nc3 ({Develops the knight and reinforces White's influence on the central square d5. Moreover, the diagonal a5-e1 is now interrupted, so that e4-e5 becomes a strong threat.} 5. e5 $2 {allows the double attack} Qa5+ {followed by -- Qxe5 .}) 5... Nc6 {Another natural developing move that continues the fight for the central squares. Black, at least temporarily, is preventing e4-e5 and threatening ...Bb4 with pressure on the white center. The starting position of the Sicilian Four Knights has now been reached. This method of play was first used in the second half of the 19th century. Early adopters included the masters Schiffers, Blackburne, Mieses, and Janowski. White now has a multitude of options.} 6. Ndb5 ({White moves the knight for the third time, but there are good reasons for this time loss. Due to the pawn moves, Black has weakened the squares d6 and c7 . Specifically, an unpleasant knight check on d6 is threatened. For a long time, 6.Ndb5 was considered the main variation. However, at the highest level there has recently been a trend towards} 6. Nxc6 {. The reason for this is that after}) (6. Ndb5 {, Black can transition into the Sveshnikov Sicilian, where White currently struggles to prove an opening advantage. However, 6.Ndb5 still remains the most common move, especially below grandmaster level.}) 6... Bc5 ({A rare move that will come as a surprise to many of our opponents. More popular are} 6... d6 {(which usually leads to the Sveshnikov variation) or}) (6... Bb4 {.}) ({➤ With} 6... Bc5 {, Black prepares to castle and targets the tactically vulnerable point f2. Additionally, Black can now respond to the knight check on d6 with a king move without blocking the development of the bishop on f8. 6...Bc5 is known as the 'Cobra Variation', tracing back to an article by Swedish IM Jesper Hall. According to my database, the Cobra was first played in 1963 by Soviet IM Viacheslav Osnos, but it remained a niche for a long time. Nowadays, some strong grandmasters have discovered the move for themselves, especially in faster time controls. I can confirm from my own experience: In blitz, the Cobra is a particularly dangerous weapon, as many opponents do not know the variation well enough, react poorly and/or consume a lot of time. The 'holes ' on d6 and c7 also invite (unsuccessful) attempts to refute the opening.}) ({➤} 6... d5 $2 {is positionally desirable, but tactically a mistake:} 7. exd5 exd5 8. Bf4 {and the Nc7+ fork can hardly be prevented.}) ({➤ After} 6... d6 {White has nothing better than the aforementioned transition into the Sveshnikov Sicilian:} 7. Bf4 e5 8. Bg5 {. This position usually arises through the move order 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 e5 6.Ndb5 d6 7.Bg5 . In this move order, however, White also has the additional options of 7.Nd5 and 3.Bb5, which is why some Black players try to reach the Sveshnikov Sicilian via 2...e6.}) ({➤} 6... Bb4 {is a solid variation, with which Black has good chances of equalizing the game. However, we do not see the typical attacking play of the Sicilian Defense here. Therefore, I prefer the more adventurous 6...Bc5.} 7. a3 {As the e4 pawn is under attack, White forces the exchange of the bishop.} Bxc3+ 8. Nxc3 d5 {Liberates the queenside and fights for the center.} 9. exd5 exd5 {Black accepts positional disadvantages (the isolated pawn d5 and the opposing bishop pair) in exchange for rapid development and control of the central squares. Nevertheless, a long fight for equality lies ahead.}) 7. Nd6+ ({Less popular than} 7. Bf4 {, but quite natural. Now Black loses the right to castle.}) 7... Ke7 $1 ({Not} 7... Bxd6 $2 8. Qxd6 {. Black can't castle here either, and the dark squares are firmly under White's control.} Qe7 9. Bf4 $16 {. It is important to dislodge the d6 knight from its strong blockade position. White is not sufficiently developed to directly pose problems for Black's centralized king.}) 8. Bf4 {The strongest move. The knight on d6 restricts the black position and is therefore fortified.} e5 ({A move that Black does not like to make, but here it is forced. Otherwise, the d6 knight cannot be dislodged. In exchange for that, Black has to accept a weakening of the light squares. The double attack} 8... Qb6 $2 {is too optimistic here.} 9. Qd2 {, and now: A) 9...Qxb2? leads to the loss of material. 10.Rb1 Qa3 11.Rb3 Qa5 12.Rb5 , winning a piece. B) 9...Bxf2+ . We encounter this tactical motif elsewhere, but here it is not good. 10.Qxf2 Qxb2 11.Kd2! Qxa1 12.Qc5+- . Black has won material, but their king comes under attack, and the queen is far away from the action.}) 9. Nf5+ Kf8 10. Be3 {White wants to exchange the defender of the d6-square.} Bb4 $1 {Of course, Black does not agree to the exchange. From b4, the bishop still covers d6 and also puts pressure on the white center, threatening ...d7-d5.} 11. a3 Bxc3+ 12. bxc3 d5 ({After} 12... Nxe4 $2 {,} 13. Qd5 {is even stronger than 13.Qg4.} Nf6 14. Qd6+ Kg8 15. Bg5 $16 {. Black cannot easily break free from the bind.}) 13. exd5 $1 (13. Qxd5 $6 Qxd5 {Nxd5} 14. Bc5+ Kg8 15. c4 $14 {.}) {Bc5+} 13... Kg8 14. Nd6 Be6 15. Z0 ({This was played in the rapid game Majdan–Kuzmicz [/variation/31423342/#/15/b], Opole 2021 (0-1). Black threatens ...b7-b6. The white player should have now ventured into the complications after} 15. Qf3 $1 b6 {(Simpler here is 16...Qc7 with mutual chances.) 17.Bc4! and now: A) 17...bxc5 18.Bxd5 Qxd6 19.Bxc6= . B) 17...Nce7!? 18.Nxf7! B.1) 18...Bxf7? 19.Bxe7 Qxe7 20.Bxd5 $16 . B.2) 18...Qc7 (19.Bxe7 Qxc4 $17 ) 19.Ng5! Qxc5 20.Bb3 e4! 21.Nxe6 exf3 22.Nxc5 fxg2 23.Rg1 bxc5 24.O-O-O Rd8 25.Rxg2 and White regains the material with an equal position. 16.Nxb7? was played instead, but with the king on e1, this is far too optimistic. 16...Qc7 17.Nd6 and here, 17...Nce7 would have been the strongest move. Black is winning, for example, 18.Bb4 Rd8 19.Nb5 Qc8-+ . The threats are ...Nxb4 and ...a7-a6.}) *

