loss of material. 10.Rb1 Qa3 11.Rb3 Qa5 12.Rb5 , winning a piece. B) 9...Bxf2+ . We encounter this tactical motif elsewhere, but here it is not good. 10.Qxf2 Qxb2 11.Kd2! Qxa1 12.Qc5+- . Black has won material, but their king comes under attack, and the queen is far away from the action.}) 9. Nf5+ Kf8 10. Bg5 {Qd2} ({This solid developing move has been established as best. Black can now take on f5 if necessary. Usually, however, the bishop goes to e6, where it stabilizes the position. On the kingside, Black plans the pawn moves ...h6 and ...g6, forcing the white pieces to retreat or be exchanged. The king then goes to g7, where it is relatively safe and no longer in the way of the rook on h8. We will frequently encounter this setup. White has now tried a range of moves, the most common are} 10. Bc4 {and}) (10. Ne3 {.}) {White prepares long castling. Also, the queen supports Nd5 followed by b2-b4 in some lines, after which the black bishop does not have many squares to retreat. Bxf5! exf5} 10... Bb4 {A good reaction to White's plan. Black obtains good counterplay. O-O-O Rc8 Black now wants to capture on c3. After that, White would have to recapture with the pawn because Qxc3 would be met with ...Nd4. In this complicated position, both sides have equal chances. In Bulmaga-Donchenko [/variation/31423347/#/13/b], Caleta 2020 (0-1), Black gained the upper hand after mutual mistakes.} *

