{Nxe7 Kxe7 O-O-O White was already threatening b2-b4. With the queens still on the board, the black king is vulnerable in the center. Qxf4 exf4 Rd2 d5!? After this, the black king feels safe on f6. The d-pawn might be lost later, but that wouldn't be too bad, as then rooks would be exchanged on the d-file. In endgames with bishops of opposite color, king safety is more important than the number of pawns. A draw is the most likely outcome here.} 1. e4 c5 {The Sicilian Opening stands for a sharp fight. Black somewhat neglects their piece development in order to prevent White from establishing a full pawn center with d2-d4.} 2. Nf3 e6 ({The third most common move after} 2... d6 {and}) (2... Nc6 {. With this, Black primarily prepares the development of the dark-squared bishop, but the center push ...d7-d5 becomes a possibility as well.}) (2... Nc6 {is an alternative way to reach the Four Knights Sicilian:} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6 {and we have landed in our repertoire via transposition. I decided against this path because White has a very serious and popular alternative in 3.Bb5 , the Rossolimo Variation. With 2...e6 the Rossolimo Variation is avoided.}) 3. d4 {The Open Sicilian and the starting position of this course. I examine alternatives for White on the second and third moves in a separate course on the Anti-Sicilians. The Open Sicilian is White's most principled attempt to fight for the opening advantage. White has more space and wants to open up the position, relying on rapid piece development. In return, Black gets the semi-open c-file, which can often be used for counterplay later on. Moreover, the exchange of the d-pawn for the c-pawn is a minor positional concession, as White now has only one pawn in the center and therefore can no longer fight quite as well for the important central squares.} cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 ({A very logical move - the knight is developed and simultaneously attacks the e4 pawn. Black takes advantage of the fact that the knight cannot be directly attacked with e4-e5 .} 4... Nc6 {is also possible, but gives White the additional option} 5. Nb5 {.}) 5. Nc3 ({Develops the knight and reinforces White's influence on the central square d5. Moreover, the diagonal a5-e1 is now interrupted, so that e4-e5 becomes a strong threat.} 5. e5 $2 {allows the double attack} Qa5+ {followed by -- Qxe5 .}) 5... Nc6 {Another natural developing move that continues the fight for the central squares. Black, at least temporarily, is preventing e4-e5 and threatening ...Bb4 with pressure on the white center. The starting position of the Sicilian Four Knights has now been reached. This method of play was first used in the second half of the 19th century. Early adopters included the masters Schiffers, Blackburne, Mieses, and Janowski. White now has a multitude of options.} 6. Ndb5 ({White moves the knight for the third time, but there are good reasons for this time loss. Due to the pawn moves, Black has weakened the squares d6 and c7 . Specifically, an unpleasant knight check on d6 is threatened. For a long time, 6.Ndb5 was considered the main variation. However, at the highest level there has recently been a trend towards} 6. Nxc6 {. The reason for this is that after}) (6. Ndb5 {, Black can transition into the Sveshnikov Sicilian, where White currently struggles to prove an opening advantage. However, 6.Ndb5 still remains the most common move, especially below grandmaster level.}) 6... Bc5 ({A rare move that will come as a surprise to many of our opponents. More popular are} 6... d6 {(which usually leads to the Sveshnikov variation) or}) (6... Bb4 {.}) ({➤ With} 6... Bc5 {, Black prepares to castle and targets the tactically vulnerable point f2. Additionally, Black can now respond to the knight check on d6 with a king move without blocking the development of the bishop on f8. 6...Bc5 is known as the 'Cobra Variation', tracing back to an article by Swedish IM Jesper Hall. According to my database, the Cobra was first played in 1963 by Soviet IM Viacheslav Osnos, but it remained a niche for a long time. Nowadays, some strong grandmasters have discovered the move for themselves, especially in faster time controls. I can confirm from my own experience: In blitz, the Cobra is a particularly dangerous weapon, as many opponents do not know the variation well enough, react poorly and/or consume a lot of time. The 'holes ' on d6 and c7 also invite (unsuccessful) attempts to refute the opening.}) ({➤} 6... d5 $2 {is positionally desirable, but tactically a mistake:} 7. exd5 exd5 8. Bf4 {and the Nc7+ fork can hardly be prevented.}) ({➤ After} 6... d6 {White has nothing better than the aforementioned transition into the Sveshnikov Sicilian:} 7. Bf4 e5 8. Bg5 {. This position usually arises through the move order 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 e5 6.Ndb5 d6 7.Bg5 . In this move order, however, White also has the additional options of 7.Nd5 and 3.Bb5, which is why some Black players try to reach the Sveshnikov Sicilian via 2...e6.}) ({➤} 6... Bb4 {is a solid variation, with which Black has good chances of equalizing the game. However, we do not see the typical attacking play of the Sicilian Defense here. Therefore, I prefer the more adventurous 6...Bc5.} 7. a3 {As the e4 pawn is under attack, White forces the exchange of the bishop.} Bxc3+ 8. Nxc3 d5 {Liberates the queenside and fights for the center.} 9. exd5 exd5 {Black accepts positional disadvantages (the isolated pawn d5 and the opposing bishop pair) in exchange for rapid development and control of the central squares. Nevertheless, a long fight for equality lies ahead.}) 7. Nd6+ ({Less popular than} 7. Bf4 {, but quite natural. Now Black loses the right to castle.}) 7... Ke7 $1 ({Not} 7... Bxd6 $2 8. Qxd6 {. Black can't castle here either, and the dark squares are firmly under White's control.} Qe7 9. Bf4 $16 {. It is important to dislodge the d6 knight from its strong blockade position. White is not sufficiently developed to directly pose problems for Black's centralized king.}) 8. Bf4 {The strongest move. The knight on d6 restricts the black position and is therefore fortified.} e5 ({A move that Black does not like to make, but here it is forced. Otherwise, the d6 knight cannot be dislodged. In exchange for that, Black has to accept a weakening of the light squares. The double attack} 8... Qb6 $2 {is too optimistic here.} 9. Qd2 {, and now: A) 9...Qxb2? leads to the loss of material. 10.Rb1 Qa3 11.Rb3 Qa5 12.Rb5 , winning a piece. B) 9...Bxf2+ . We encounter this tactical motif elsewhere, but here it is not good. 10.Qxf2 Qxb2 11.Kd2! Qxa1 12.Qc5+- . Black has won material, but their king comes under attack, and the queen is far away from the action.}) 9. Nf5+ Kf8 10. Bg5 {Bxf6} ({This solid developing move has been established as best. Black can now take on f5 if necessary. Usually, however, the bishop goes to e6, where it stabilizes the position. On the kingside, Black plans the pawn moves ...h6 and ...g6, forcing the white pieces to retreat or be exchanged. The king then goes to g7, where it is relatively safe and no longer in the way of the rook on h8. We will frequently encounter this setup. White has now tried a range of moves, the most common are} 10. Bc4 {and}) (10. Ne3 {.}) {In other variations, we often have to play ...h7-h6 to force this exchange. Qxf6} 10... Nd5 {Qd8 Black wants to adopt the standard setup: ...g7-g6, ...Kg7, and ...Be6.} 11. Qd2 $1 {A novelty, but this is the only way White can justify the voluntary exchange on f6. After other moves, Black plays 13...g6 and compared to other variations, has saved the tempo ...h7-h6. Bxf5 exf5} ({g6?? Qh6+ is the idea behind White's last move. Ke8 . White threatens, among other things,} 11. Z0 f6 {gxf6 Qh6+ .}) ({Black defends against f5-f6 by covering the h6 square. From h4, the queen also attacks f2 and prevents b2-b4. c3 Ne7 The pawn capture Qe4+} 11. Be2 {Qxf5 O-O with a later b2-b4 or f2-f4 is dangerous.}) *

