loss of material. 10.Rb1 Qa3 11.Rb3 Qa5 12.Rb5 , winning a piece. B) 9...Bxf2+ . We encounter this tactical motif elsewhere, but here it is not good. 10.Qxf2 Qxb2 11.Kd2! Qxa1 12.Qc5+- . Black has won material, but their king comes under attack, and the queen is far away from the action.}) 9. Nf5+ Kf8 10. Bg5 {Ne3} ({This solid developing move has been established as best. Black can now take on f5 if necessary. Usually, however, the bishop goes to e6, where it stabilizes the position. On the kingside, Black plans the pawn moves ...h6 and ...g6, forcing the white pieces to retreat or be exchanged. The king then goes to g7, where it is relatively safe and no longer in the way of the rook on h8. We will frequently encounter this setup. White has now tried a range of moves, the most common are} 10. Bc4 {and}) (10. Ne3 {.}) ({This prevents ...Bxf5 and threatens Ned5. Be6 Ned5 exd5} 10. Nd5 $2 {is, as so often, bad due to} Qa5+ 11. c3 Bxf2+ 12. Kxf2 Nxe4+ 13. Kg1 Ng5 $17 {.}) 10... Ne7 {From here, the knight puts pressure on d5. The exchange on f6 may lead to a deterioration of Black's pawn structure, but it also grants the rook a semi-open file.} 11. Bxf6 (11. Qf3 Bd4 $1 12. Bxf6 gxf6 {Qxf6 Rg8 . Black is likely to soon regain the pawn on d5 and has a good position.}) 11... gxf6 12. Qh5 Bb4 13. Z0 ({The knight is a potential attacking piece, so it is eliminated. Additionally, the exchange creates weaknesses in White's pawn structure. Black obtains good counterplay. It should be noted that Black is not yet threatening ...Nxd5.} 13. Qh6+ Kg8 14. Qxf6 $6 Nd5 $15 {is slightly better for Black.}) (13. Bd3 {is the computer move, and now: A) 16...Nxd5? 17.Bc4! The knight is pinned due to the mating threat on f7. 17...Bxc3+ 18.bxc3 Qa5 19.O-O! Threatening Rad1. 19...Rc8 20.Bb3 Rc5 21.Rfd1 Threatening to double on the d-file. Black still cannot break free. 21...Rg8 22.Qxh7+- . The knight remains pinned. B) 16...Bxc3+ 17.bxc3 Rg8 18.O-O Rg7 19.c4 f5! . With this pawn sacrifice, Black free themselves. If White captures the pawn, 20.Bxf5 Nxf5 21.Qxf5 Qc7 , the white weaknesses on the c-file provide Black with sufficient compensation.}) *

