loss of material. 10.Rb1 Qa3 11.Rb3 Qa5 12.Rb5 , winning a piece. B) 9...Bxf2+ . We encounter this tactical motif elsewhere, but here it is not good. 10.Qxf2 Qxb2 11.Kd2! Qxa1 12.Qc5+- . Black has won material, but their king comes under attack, and the queen is far away from the action.}) 9. Nf5+ Kf8 10. Bg5 {Ne3} ({This solid developing move has been established as best. Black can now take on f5 if necessary. Usually, however, the bishop goes to e6, where it stabilizes the position. On the kingside, Black plans the pawn moves ...h6 and ...g6, forcing the white pieces to retreat or be exchanged. The king then goes to g7, where it is relatively safe and no longer in the way of the rook on h8. We will frequently encounter this setup. White has now tried a range of moves, the most common are} 10. Bc4 {and}) (10. Ne3 {.}) ({This prevents ...Bxf5 and threatens Ned5. Be6 Bd3 Protects e4 and therefore threatens} 10. Z0 {Ned5 Bxd5} Nd5 {.}) {Bxf6 Qxf6 O-O} 10... g6 {The usual procedure to connect the rooks.} 11. Nd5 {Qd8 c3} ({Black decides to ignore b2-b4. Equally possible was a6 , giving the bishop a retreat square. However, it's not so clear which side benefits more from the exchange on e3. By taking the knight, Black loses the bishop pair but gains more control over d5. We have reached a typical position for the line with 6.Nd6+. The pawn structure and the placement of the white knights resemble the Sveshnikov Sicilian. Only the bishop on c5 doesn't quite fit this picture. Objectively, the position is balanced, but is slightly more pleasant for White to play. Especially the pawn break f2-f4 is a danger that Black should keep in mind. The opening of the f-file could lead to uncomfortable pressure against Black's king. To preemptively counter that, it would be desirable for Black to exchange some minor pieces. For this purpose, ...Ne7-xd5 and ...Bxe3 are options. However, we should avoid exchanging the light-squared bishop, as it serves an important defensive function. After the exchange of minor pieces, it is sometimes possible to trade the backward d6 pawn with ...d6-d5. The typical counterplay in the Sveshnikov Sicilian with ...f7-f5 usually doesn't work so well here. After an exchange on f5, the black king becomes too exposed. However, it wouldn't hurt to play ...Rf8 to further prepare against f2-f4. On the queenside, both sides will try to gain space through pawn moves. A) In the game Hajnal-Nagy [/variation/31423349/#/16/b], Hungary 2019 (½-½), there followed Kg7 Kh1 Rc8 (simpler was 17...Bxe3 18.Nxe3 d5= )} 11. Qe2 {( 18.f4 exf4 19.Rxf4 Bxe3!? 20.Nxe3 Rf8= followed by ...Ne5)} Ne7 {Bc4 . The best moves here were} 12. Nd5 {or 19...Rf8 , but Black made the strategically unfortunate decision of 19...Bxe3 20.Nxe3 Bxc4 21.Nxc4 Qc7 22.Ne3 . White is better, as f2-f4 is threatened and the d5 square is under White's control. B) 17.b4 Bxe3 18.Nxe3 Rc8 followed by ...Ne7 and, if possible, ...d6-d5.}) *

