loss of material. 10.Rb1 Qa3 11.Rb3 Qa5 12.Rb5 , winning a piece. B) 9...Bxf2+ . We encounter this tactical motif elsewhere, but here it is not good. 10.Qxf2 Qxb2 11.Kd2! Qxa1 12.Qc5+- . Black has won material, but their king comes under attack, and the queen is far away from the action.}) 9. Nf5+ Kf8 10. Bg5 {Bc4} ({This solid developing move has been established as best. Black can now take on f5 if necessary. Usually, however, the bishop goes to e6, where it stabilizes the position. On the kingside, Black plans the pawn moves ...h6 and ...g6, forcing the white pieces to retreat or be exchanged. The king then goes to g7, where it is relatively safe and no longer in the way of the rook on h8. We will frequently encounter this setup. White has now tried a range of moves, the most common are} 10. Bc4 {and}) (10. Ne3 {.}) ({White develops the bishop and increases control over the important d5 square. Be6 Qe2 This interesting idea was recently tested in some tournament games. White not only defends the bishop on c4 but also prepares for queenside castling. The queen's move entails a pawn sacrifice. Rc8 Black increases the pressure against the bishop on c4. Instead, Black could win a pawn with} 10. Bc4 $5 {Qxc4} Bxf2+ $1 {, but White gets good compensation, for example with} 11. Kd2 {( 14.Kxf2 is answered by 14...Ng4+ followed by ...Qxg5) 14...Rc8 15.Raf1 Bd4 16.Bxf6 Bxc3+! 17.Qxc3 Qxf6 18.Kc1 . White has pressure on the f-file, and Black has not yet managed to connect their rooks.  The schematic 12...h6 is playable as well, but White has a firm grip on the center after 13.Bxf6 Qxf6 14.Nd5 Qd8 15.c3 g6 16.Nfe3 , as in the game Unat-Tadic [/variation/36055953], Ustron 2023 (1-0).}) 10... Nd5 ({Finally, this move is possible – White's queen defends against the typical tactical ideas in connection with ...Bxf2+. Instead, Black still benefits from the exchange of bishops Bxe6?! fxe6 , as the important d5-square is now under control. In Dyachuk-Schleicher [/variation/36055954], Walsrode 2023 (1-0), Ne3 followed and now} 10... h6 11. Bxf6 Qxf6 {O-O Kg8= followed by ...Kh7 looks simplest.}) {Bxf5! The defender of the d4-square is exchanged. Black must play concretely here to avoid ending up in a bad position. exf5} 11. Nd4 {Qd2} ({Now White is threatening Bxf6 followed by Qh6+. If instead} 11. Qd3 {there follows} Qa5 {and now: A)} 12. Bd2 Qa4 $5 {(or 16...Nxc2+!? , with the idea 17.Qxc2 Bxf2+! 18.Kd1 Qxd5! 19.Bxd5 Rxc2 20.Kxc2 Nxd5 $17 ) is good for Black. B) Therefore, White should play 16.c3 . The complications after 16...Nxd5 17.O-O!? (or 17.Bxd5 Ba3!) eventually lead to equality.  White might also start with 15.Bxf6 , resulting in a transposition after 15...gxf6 16.Qd2 Bb4! 17.c3 Rxc4 .}) 11... Bb4 $1 {With this tactical resource, Black forces the exchange of bishops and thus takes the sting out of the opponent's attack. c3 Rxc4} {Of course not Qxb4?? Nxc2+ Ke2 Nxb4 , while 16.Nxb4 Rxc4 17.c3 Nxf5= doesn't pose any problems.} 12. Bf6 ({The exchange leads to a weakening of the black king's position. White plays for an attack. Nxb4} 12. Nf5 {is harmless.}) 12... gxf6 {Qh6+ Ke8 Nxf6+} ({O-O Nxf5} 12... Nxf6 {Ke7 Nd5+ Kd7 is a transposition.}) {Ke7 O-O White can afford to take time in regaining the piece, as Black is unable to extricate both minor pieces from the attack.} 13. Nf5 $1 ({The attempt to keep the extra piece with} 13. Nde2 $2 {Kh1} Ba5 {is punished by Rfe1} 14. Nf4 {Rad1!+- . Black does not succeed in bringing the king to safety.}) {Nd5+ Forced. Qg5? loses a piece after Ke6 . Kd7 Qh5 Once again both of Black's minor pieces are attacked, as well as the pawn on f7. Ke6! The king actively participates in the battle, defending the knight and the f7-pawn. Black's central pawns ensure that the king is relatively safe. Nxb4 Material equality is restored, but the position remains complicated.} 13... Rg8 {Black gains counterplay on the g-file. There's a threat of ...Rcg4 with an attack.} 14. Qf3 {Threatens Qd5+ and Qxb7. Qc8 A nice square for the queen. By defending the rook and the b7-pawn, Black's queen neutralizes the threats of the white queen. It also keeps an eye on the knight on f5, which gives Black the option to move their king from its exposed position to a safer one via e7 to f8. A sharp middlegame is ahead, in which the chances are evenly distributed.} *

