s. Black, at least temporarily, is preventing e4-e5 and threatening ...Bb4 with pressure on the white center. The starting position of the Sicilian Four Knights has now been reached. This method of play was first used in the second half of the 19th century. Early adopters included the masters Schiffers, Blackburne, Mieses, and Janowski. White now has a multitude of options.} 6. Ndb5 ({White moves the knight for the third time, but there are good reasons for this time loss. Due to the pawn moves, Black has weakened the squares d6 and c7 . Specifically, an unpleasant knight check on d6 is threatened. For a long time, 6.Ndb5 was considered the main variation. However, at the highest level there has recently been a trend towards} 6. Nxc6 {. The reason for this is that after}) (6. Ndb5 {, Black can transition into the Sveshnikov Sicilian, where White currently struggles to prove an opening advantage. However, 6.Ndb5 still remains the most common move, especially below grandmaster level.}) 6... Bc5 ({A rare move that will come as a surprise to many of our opponents. More popular are} 6... d6 {(which usually leads to the Sveshnikov variation) or}) (6... Bb4 {.}) ({➤ With} 6... Bc5 {, Black prepares to castle and targets the tactically vulnerable point f2. Additionally, Black can now respond to the knight check on d6 with a king move without blocking the development of the bishop on f8. 6...Bc5 is known as the 'Cobra Variation', tracing back to an article by Swedish IM Jesper Hall. According to my database, the Cobra was first played in 1963 by Soviet IM Viacheslav Osnos, but it remained a niche for a long time. Nowadays, some strong grandmasters have discovered the move for themselves, especially in faster time controls. I can confirm from my own experience: In blitz, the Cobra is a particularly dangerous weapon, as many opponents do not know the variation well enough, react poorly and/or consume a lot of time. The 'holes ' on d6 and c7 also invite (unsuccessful) attempts to refute the opening.}) ({➤} 6... d5 $2 {is positionally desirable, but tactically a mistake:} 7. exd5 exd5 8. Bf4 {and the Nc7+ fork can hardly be prevented.}) ({➤ After} 6... d6 {White has nothing better than the aforementioned transition into the Sveshnikov Sicilian:} 7. Bf4 e5 8. Bg5 {. This position usually arises through the move order 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 e5 6.Ndb5 d6 7.Bg5 . In this move order, however, White also has the additional options of 7.Nd5 and 3.Bb5, which is why some Black players try to reach the Sveshnikov Sicilian via 2...e6.}) ({➤} 6... Bb4 {is a solid variation, with which Black has good chances of equalizing the game. However, we do not see the typical attacking play of the Sicilian Defense here. Therefore, I prefer the more adventurous 6...Bc5.} 7. a3 {As the e4 pawn is under attack, White forces the exchange of the bishop.} Bxc3+ 8. Nxc3 d5 {Liberates the queenside and fights for the center.} 9. exd5 exd5 {Black accepts positional disadvantages (the isolated pawn d5 and the opposing bishop pair) in exchange for rapid development and control of the central squares. Nevertheless, a long fight for equality lies ahead.}) 7. Nd6+ ({Less popular than} 7. Bf4 {, but quite natural. Now Black loses the right to castle.}) 7... Ke7 $1 ({Not} 7... Bxd6 $2 8. Qxd6 {. Black can't castle here either, and the dark squares are firmly under White's control.} Qe7 9. Bf4 $16 {. It is important to dislodge the d6 knight from its strong blockade position. White is not sufficiently developed to directly pose problems for Black's centralized king.}) 8. Bf4 {The strongest move. The knight on d6 restricts the black position and is therefore fortified.} e5 ({A move that Black does not like to make, but here it is forced. Otherwise, the d6 knight cannot be dislodged. In exchange for that, Black has to accept a weakening of the light squares. The double attack} 8... Qb6 $2 {is too optimistic here.} 9. Qd2 {, and now: A) 9...Qxb2? leads to the loss of material. 10.Rb1 Qa3 11.Rb3 Qa5 12.Rb5 , winning a piece. B) 9...Bxf2+ . We encounter this tactical motif elsewhere, but here it is not good. 10.Qxf2 Qxb2 11.Kd2! Qxa1 12.Qc5+- . Black has won material, but their king comes under attack, and the queen is far away from the action.}) 9. Nf5+ Kf8 10. Bg5 {Bc4} ({This solid developing move has been established as best. Black can now take on f5 if necessary. Usually, however, the bishop goes to e6, where it stabilizes the position. On the kingside, Black plans the pawn moves ...h6 and ...g6, forcing the white pieces to retreat or be exchanged. The king then goes to g7, where it is relatively safe and no longer in the way of the rook on h8. We will frequently encounter this setup. White has now tried a range of moves, the most common are} 10. Bc4 {and}) (10. Ne3 {.}) ({White develops the bishop and increases control over the important d5 square. Be6 Qe2 This interesting idea was recently tested in some tournament games. White not only defends the bishop on c4 but also prepares for queenside castling. The queen's move entails a pawn sacrifice. Rc8 Black increases the pressure against the bishop on c4. Instead, Black could win a pawn with} 10. Bc4 $5 {Qxc4} Bxf2+ $1 {, but White gets good compensation, for example with} 11. Kd2 {( 14.Kxf2 is answered by 14...Ng4+ followed by ...Qxg5) 14...Rc8 15.Raf1 Bd4 16.Bxf6 Bxc3+! 17.Qxc3 Qxf6 18.Kc1 . White has pressure on the f-file, and Black has not yet managed to connect their rooks.  The schematic 12...h6 is playable as well, but White has a firm grip on the center after 13.Bxf6 Qxf6 14.Nd5 Qd8 15.c3 g6 16.Nfe3 , as in the game Unat-Tadic [/variation/36055953], Ustron 2023 (1-0).}) {O-O-O By castling queenside, White not only brings their king to safety but also increases the pressure on the d-file. Again, Black must play energetically.} 10... Nd4 $1 {This initiates an exchange operation, through which Black can relieve pressure.} 11. Nxd4 $16 {Bxc4} ({Bxd4? is bad, because after} 11. Nd5 {White keeps control over d5.}) {Qxc4} 11... Bxd4 {Qb4 The best square for the queen, as it attacks the pawns on b7 and d6. Bxc3} ({It's important to prevent White's knight from coming to d5. Black now loses a pawn, but in return disrupts White's pawn structure. There is no time for a defensive move like} 11... b6 $2 {, as after} 12. Bxf6 Qxf6 13. Nd5 {White's knight cannot be chased away from its dominant central position.}) ({bxc3 Rc6 Black was unable to protect both pawns. Qxb7 Qd7 Despite being a pawn down, the exchange of queens would be favorable for Black given the opponent's weakened pawn structure. Instead, winning back the pawn with Rxc3 is weaker. With Rhe1! , White defends the pawn on e4 and threatens to increase the pressure, for instance with Re3 or f2-f4. Qb8+ After Qxd7 Nxd7 Black has nothing to worry about. A possible continuation is Rd5 f6 Be3} 11... Ke7 {Rhd1 Rhc8= with good play on the queenside.}) ({Qe8 Equally playable is Rc8 : A) Qb4 Rc6= B) 20.Qxd6+ Qxd6 21.Rxd6 Nxe4 22.Rd8+ Rxd8 23.Bxd8 and now 23...f6= followed by Kf7 is most precise. Qb4 Protects e4 and attacks d6. Instead, after Qxa7} 11... Nxe4 {it is already White who needs to play precisely to keep the balance, while in the endgame after 20.Qxe8+ Kxe8 21.Bxf6 gxf6= Black has full compensation for the pawn due to White's weaknesses on the queenside.}) ({Qd7 An interesting alternative is Rb6 Qa3!? ( 21.Qc4 Rc6=)} 11... Nxe4 12. Be3 {Rc6 , leading to a sharp position. After 20...Qd7 , Black's queen defends the d6-pawn and might later go to c7 to increase the pressure on the c-file. Now, White might enter a repetition of moves with 21.Qb8+ . If instead White decides to continue the fight, Black has good play against the white queenside. A possible continuation is 21.Rhe1 h6 ( not 21...Ke7 22.f4!) 22.Bxf6 gxf6 23.Rd5 Ke7= . Next, Black can increase the pressure with ...Rhc8.}) *

