loss of material. 10.Rb1 Qa3 11.Rb3 Qa5 12.Rb5 , winning a piece. B) 9...Bxf2+ . We encounter this tactical motif elsewhere, but here it is not good. 10.Qxf2 Qxb2 11.Kd2! Qxa1 12.Qc5+- . Black has won material, but their king comes under attack, and the queen is far away from the action.}) 9. Nf5+ Kf8 10. Bg5 {Bc4} ({This solid developing move has been established as best. Black can now take on f5 if necessary. Usually, however, the bishop goes to e6, where it stabilizes the position. On the kingside, Black plans the pawn moves ...h6 and ...g6, forcing the white pieces to retreat or be exchanged. The king then goes to g7, where it is relatively safe and no longer in the way of the rook on h8. We will frequently encounter this setup. White has now tried a range of moves, the most common are} 10. Bc4 {and}) (10. Ne3 {.}) {White develops the bishop and increases control over the important d5 square. Be6 Fights for the d5 square. The moves Bxf5 and h6 are also playable. Bb3 Bxf6 White gives up the bishop pair, but in exchange removes a defender of d5. Qxf6 Ne3 White brings the attacked knight to safety and increases control over d5.} 10... g6 {Black goes for the standard setup.} 11. Qd2 $5 {This continuation, yet to be tested in practice, was recommended by top GM and theoretician Anish Giri in his Lifetime Repertoires: Giri's 1. e4 - Part 3. White wants to castle queenside and then attack on the kingside without having to worry about their own king's safety. Kg7 O-O-O Here Giri concludes his analysis by emphasizing that White controls d5 and can play for an attack with f2-f4. This is correct, but as further analysis shows, Black can also be satisfied with the outcome of the opening.} Rb8 $1 {The correct plan for Black consists of counterplay on the queenside. Rhf1 White prepares f2-f4. b5 Kb1! Qd8} ({This move also serves to prepare f2-f4. The immediate f4?! exf4 Rxf4?! leads to a queen trade favorable for Black after Qd4 $17 . The queen would soon have been driven away from f6 anyway. Now it can swing over to the queenside. After the natural} 11... a5 {,} 12. f4 $1 {is possible, the point being} exf4 {Rxf4!} 13. Qd4 $2 {( 20...Qd8 $14 ) Qf2! Qxe3 (no check; that's why White first had to bring the king to c1) Rxf7+ Bxf7 Qxf7 .}) 12. f4 exf4 {Rxf4 Ne5 On this outpost, the knight covers the tactically vulnerable f7-square and also keeps an eye on c4, which can be used for an attack under favorable circumstances. The position promises a sharp battle. White will try to break through Black's defense on the kingside, while Black will attack with their pawns on the queenside.} *

