to refute the opening.}) ({➤} 6... d5 $2 {is positionally desirable, but tactically a mistake:} 7. exd5 exd5 8. Bf4 {and the Nc7+ fork can hardly be prevented.}) ({➤ After} 6... d6 {White has nothing better than the aforementioned transition into the Sveshnikov Sicilian:} 7. Bf4 e5 8. Bg5 {. This position usually arises through the move order 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 e5 6.Ndb5 d6 7.Bg5 . In this move order, however, White also has the additional options of 7.Nd5 and 3.Bb5, which is why some Black players try to reach the Sveshnikov Sicilian via 2...e6.}) ({➤} 6... Bb4 {is a solid variation, with which Black has good chances of equalizing the game. However, we do not see the typical attacking play of the Sicilian Defense here. Therefore, I prefer the more adventurous 6...Bc5.} 7. a3 {As the e4 pawn is under attack, White forces the exchange of the bishop.} Bxc3+ 8. Nxc3 d5 {Liberates the queenside and fights for the center.} 9. exd5 exd5 {Black accepts positional disadvantages (the isolated pawn d5 and the opposing bishop pair) in exchange for rapid development and control of the central squares. Nevertheless, a long fight for equality lies ahead.}) 7. Nd6+ ({Less popular than} 7. Bf4 {, but quite natural. Now Black loses the right to castle.}) 7... Ke7 $1 ({Not} 7... Bxd6 $2 8. Qxd6 {. Black can't castle here either, and the dark squares are firmly under White's control.} Qe7 9. Bf4 $16 {. It is important to dislodge the d6 knight from its strong blockade position. White is not sufficiently developed to directly pose problems for Black's centralized king.}) 8. Bf4 {The strongest move. The knight on d6 restricts the black position and is therefore fortified.} e5 ({A move that Black does not like to make, but here it is forced. Otherwise, the d6 knight cannot be dislodged. In exchange for that, Black has to accept a weakening of the light squares. The double attack} 8... Qb6 $2 {is too optimistic here.} 9. Qd2 {, and now: A) 9...Qxb2? leads to the loss of material. 10.Rb1 Qa3 11.Rb3 Qa5 12.Rb5 , winning a piece. B) 9...Bxf2+ . We encounter this tactical motif elsewhere, but here it is not good. 10.Qxf2 Qxb2 11.Kd2! Qxa1 12.Qc5+- . Black has won material, but their king comes under attack, and the queen is far away from the action.}) 9. Nf5+ Kf8 10. Bg5 {Bc4} ({This solid developing move has been established as best. Black can now take on f5 if necessary. Usually, however, the bishop goes to e6, where it stabilizes the position. On the kingside, Black plans the pawn moves ...h6 and ...g6, forcing the white pieces to retreat or be exchanged. The king then goes to g7, where it is relatively safe and no longer in the way of the rook on h8. We will frequently encounter this setup. White has now tried a range of moves, the most common are} 10. Bc4 {and}) (10. Ne3 {.}) {White develops the bishop and increases control over the important d5 square. Be6 Fights for the d5 square. The moves Bxf5 and h6 are also playable. Bb3 Bxf6 White gives up the bishop pair, but in exchange removes a defender of d5. Qxf6 O-O!? White doesn't want to waste time and offers a pawn sacrifice. Bxf5 There's nothing wrong with accepting the sacrifice.} 10... Nd5 {Qg6 exf5 Qxf5 c3 White controls the d4 square and prepares Bc2 followed by b2-b4. White has good compensation for the pawn: their king is safer than it's black counterpart, and the white bishop exerts dangerous pressure against f7, while the black bishop only serves a stabilizing function. In this type of position, Black should watch out for two ideas from the opponent: the displacement of the bishop with b2-b4 and the pawn break f2-f4, which can lead to a dangerous opening of the f-file. In this case, the presence of opposite-colored bishops would favor White, as Black's bishop cannot help fending off the attack on the light squares. h5!?} ({A novelty that I prefer over the twice-played} 10... Ne7 {. For one thing,}) (10... h5 {allows the rook to develop via h6 . The second, and more important, idea behind this move is quite deep: it serves as a preparation for ...g7-g6 because in some variations g2-g4 would be strong for White. The analysis of 17...g6 demonstrates the concrete reasons:}) ({A)} 10... g6 $6 {This is usually the ideal setup. The king goes to g7, after which the rooks are connected, and the f7 square can be defended with ...Rf8 if necessary. However, it is too slow in this position. Bc2!} 11. Qxd7 {b4} Bb6 {Qf3! . This strong move is the concrete refutation of 17...g6. Bxg6 is threatened. Black would like to respond with f5 , but} 12. g4 $1 {opens up the black king's position. Terrible is also 20...Kg7 21.b5 Na5 22.Qf6+ Kh7 23.Nxb6 axb6 24.f4 . Better defensive chances, however, are offered by 20...Ne7 .}) ({B)} 10... Ne7 {led to quick equality after Kh1} 11. Nd5 {Qxd5} g6 $1 {Qxb7 Kg7 in the game Vocaturo-Guseinov [/variation/31423351/#/20/b], Terme Čatež 2022 (½-½). Black consolidated and reliably defended the f7 square. However, critical was 19.Bxd5! after which White retains a slightly more pleasant game. The idea is then a quick advance of the pawns on the queenside, which disturbs Black's coordination: For example, 19...g6 20.b4 Bb6 21.a4 . The pawn threatens to go all the way to a6. Black still has problems to solve here.}) {Bc2 Qd7} 11. b4 Bb6 12. a4 g6 13. Z0 ({Black achieves the desired setup and has no problems. A) After} 13. Qf3 {, of course, follows} gxf5 $1 {That's why we played 17...h5. White no longer has the attacking resource g2-g4. B) 21.a5 Bd8 22.f4 exf4 (22...f5!?) 23.Nxf4 Kg7 followed by ...Bf6 or ...Ne5. The black position is stable.}) *

