ts to refute the opening.}) ({➤} 6... d5 $2 {is positionally desirable, but tactically a mistake:} 7. exd5 exd5 8. Bf4 {and the Nc7+ fork can hardly be prevented.}) ({➤ After} 6... d6 {White has nothing better than the aforementioned transition into the Sveshnikov Sicilian:} 7. Bf4 e5 8. Bg5 {. This position usually arises through the move order 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 e5 6.Ndb5 d6 7.Bg5 . In this move order, however, White also has the additional options of 7.Nd5 and 3.Bb5, which is why some Black players try to reach the Sveshnikov Sicilian via 2...e6.}) ({➤} 6... Bb4 {is a solid variation, with which Black has good chances of equalizing the game. However, we do not see the typical attacking play of the Sicilian Defense here. Therefore, I prefer the more adventurous 6...Bc5.} 7. a3 {As the e4 pawn is under attack, White forces the exchange of the bishop.} Bxc3+ 8. Nxc3 d5 {Liberates the queenside and fights for the center.} 9. exd5 exd5 {Black accepts positional disadvantages (the isolated pawn d5 and the opposing bishop pair) in exchange for rapid development and control of the central squares. Nevertheless, a long fight for equality lies ahead.}) 7. Be2 $6 {With this slow developing move, the early knight jump to b5 cannot be justified.} O-O ({Not} 7... a6 $2 8. Nd6+ Ke7 9. Bf4 e5 10. Nf5+ Kf8 11. Be3 Bb4 12. O-O $1 $16 {. In contrast to the line 7.Nd6+ Ke7 8.Bf4 e5 9.Nf5+ Kf8 10.Be3 Bb4 , White is faster with their king already castled. Black's play against the white center now falls short. The attempt to win a pawn is refuted tactically:} Bxc3 $2 13. Bb6 $1 Qxb6 14. Qd6+ Kg8 {( 14...Ke8 15.Nxg7 Kd8 16.Qxf6 Kc7 17.bxc3+- )} 15. Ne7+ Nxe7 16. Qxb6 {.}) 8. Nd6 Ne8 ({The simplest. The blockade of the d-pawn is shaken off.} 8... Qc7 {is also good. White should now find} 9. Bf4 e5 10. Ndb5 Qb6 11. O-O $1 {, where White wins back the piece after} exf4 12. Na4 {with a complicated position.}) 9. Nc4 f5 $5 ({I also like} 9... Nc7 {. Black threatens ...d7-d5, after which the c4-knight does not have a good retreat square.} 10. Bf4 d5 $1 11. Bxc7 Qxc7 12. exd5 Rd8 13. O-O a6 $13 {.}) 10. exf5 $2 d5 11. Nd2 Nd6 $17 {Black's pieces are much more active than White's.} *

