s. Black, at least temporarily, is preventing e4-e5 and threatening ...Bb4 with pressure on the white center. The starting position of the Sicilian Four Knights has now been reached. This method of play was first used in the second half of the 19th century. Early adopters included the masters Schiffers, Blackburne, Mieses, and Janowski. White now has a multitude of options.} 6. Ndb5 ({White moves the knight for the third time, but there are good reasons for this time loss. Due to the pawn moves, Black has weakened the squares d6 and c7 . Specifically, an unpleasant knight check on d6 is threatened. For a long time, 6.Ndb5 was considered the main variation. However, at the highest level there has recently been a trend towards} 6. Nxc6 {. The reason for this is that after}) (6. Ndb5 {, Black can transition into the Sveshnikov Sicilian, where White currently struggles to prove an opening advantage. However, 6.Ndb5 still remains the most common move, especially below grandmaster level.}) 6... Bc5 $5 ({A rare move that will come as a surprise to many of our opponents. More popular are} 6... d6 {(which usually leads to the Sveshnikov variation) or}) (6... Bb4 {.}) ({➤ With} 6... Bc5 {, Black prepares to castle and targets the tactically vulnerable point f2. Additionally, Black can now respond to the knight check on d6 with a king move without blocking the development of the bishop on f8. 6...Bc5 is known as the 'Cobra Variation', tracing back to an article by Swedish IM Jesper Hall. According to my database, the Cobra was first played in 1963 by Soviet IM Viacheslav Osnos, but it remained a niche for a long time. Nowadays, some strong grandmasters have discovered the move for themselves, especially in faster time controls. I can confirm from my own experience: In blitz, the Cobra is a particularly dangerous weapon, as many opponents do not know the variation well enough, react poorly and/or consume a lot of time. The 'holes ' on d6 and c7 also invite (unsuccessful) attempts to refute the opening.}) ({➤} 6... d5 $2 {is positionally desirable, but tactically a mistake:} 7. exd5 exd5 8. Bf4 {and the Nc7+ fork can hardly be prevented.}) ({➤ After} 6... d6 {White has nothing better than the aforementioned transition into the Sveshnikov Sicilian:} 7. Bf4 e5 8. Bg5 {. This position usually arises through the move order 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 e5 6.Ndb5 d6 7.Bg5 . In this move order, however, White also has the additional options of 7.Nd5 and 3.Bb5, which is why some Black players try to reach the Sveshnikov Sicilian via 2...e6.}) ({➤} 6... Bb4 {is a solid variation, with which Black has good chances of equalizing the game. However, we do not see the typical attacking play of the Sicilian Defense here. Therefore, I prefer the more adventurous 6...Bc5.} 7. a3 {As the e4 pawn is under attack, White forces the exchange of the bishop.} Bxc3+ 8. Nxc3 d5 {Liberates the queenside and fights for the center.} 9. exd5 exd5 {Black accepts positional disadvantages (the isolated pawn d5 and the opposing bishop pair) in exchange for rapid development and control of the central squares. Nevertheless, a long fight for equality lies ahead.}) 7. Be3 $6 {White wants to strengthen their control over the d6-square by exchanging bishops. However, it turns out that White can't maintain the blockade on this square.} Bxe3 8. Nd6+ Ke7 9. fxe3 Qc7 $1 ({It is important to immediately attack the knight so that it cannot permanently establish itself on the strong blockading square d6. Black doesn't have time for the preparatory move} 9... a6 $2 {because of} 10. Qd2 Qc7 11. O-O-O Ne8 12. e5 $1 {. With this strong pawn sacrifice, White can maintain the blockade on d6.} Nxe5 13. Nce4 Nxd6 14. Nxd6 b6 {This defends against the threat of Qb4, to which Black can now respond with ...Qc5. We have been following the game Saptarshi-Sequera Paolini [/variation/31423352/#/14/b], Barbera del Valles 2013 (½-½). Black wants to consolidate with ...f7-f6 and ...Nf7. Therefore,} 15. g4 $1 {would have been very strong, to open up the black king's position after} f6 16. g5 {. White has a clear advantage.}) 10. Ncb5 Qb6 11. Qd2 Ng4 $1 {Now White can no longer defend the e3-pawn.} 12. O-O-O Qxe3 $17 {White has no compensation for the lost pawn.} *

