 Therefore,} 15. g4 $1 {would have been very strong, to open up the black king's position after} f6 16. g5 {. White has a clear advantage.}) 10. Ndb5 Z0 ({The white knight is pushed back. White is left with pawn weaknesses on e3 and e4. Additionally, the square e5 can no longer be attacked by a white pawn and is therefore firmly under Black's control. In the game Wells-Hall [/variation/31423353/#/10/b], Germany 1999 (0-1), there followed Qd2} 10... a6 11. Nd4 b5 {O-O-O Bb7} 12. Nf3 {Qc5 a3 Rac8 and Black later converted the advantage.}) *

