ts to refute the opening.}) ({➤} 6... d5 $2 {is positionally desirable, but tactically a mistake:} 7. exd5 exd5 8. Bf4 {and the Nc7+ fork can hardly be prevented.}) ({➤ After} 6... d6 {White has nothing better than the aforementioned transition into the Sveshnikov Sicilian:} 7. Bf4 e5 8. Bg5 {. This position usually arises through the move order 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 e5 6.Ndb5 d6 7.Bg5 . In this move order, however, White also has the additional options of 7.Nd5 and 3.Bb5, which is why some Black players try to reach the Sveshnikov Sicilian via 2...e6.}) ({➤} 6... Bb4 {is a solid variation, with which Black has good chances of equalizing the game. However, we do not see the typical attacking play of the Sicilian Defense here. Therefore, I prefer the more adventurous 6...Bc5.} 7. a3 {As the e4 pawn is under attack, White forces the exchange of the bishop.} Bxc3+ 8. Nxc3 d5 {Liberates the queenside and fights for the center.} 9. exd5 exd5 {Black accepts positional disadvantages (the isolated pawn d5 and the opposing bishop pair) in exchange for rapid development and control of the central squares. Nevertheless, a long fight for equality lies ahead.}) 7. Bf4 {The most common continuation. White is threatening a knight fork on c7 and simultaneously targets the weakened d6 square. The move e4-e5 is also a threat.} O-O ({The only good move. Black secures their king, dodges the knight checks, and provides the knight on f6 a retreat square on e8. If Black now manages to liberate the queenside with ...d7-d5, they would already be better. Therefore, White should now aim to blockade the pawn on d7.} 7... e5 $2 8. Be3 $1 Bxe3 9. Nd6+ Ke7 10. fxe3 {. A very similar position arises after 7.Be3 Bxe3 8.Nd6+ Ke7 9.fxe3 . The only difference is that the black e-pawn is already on e5 here. This small difference turns out to be fatal for Black, because the squares f5 and d5 are accessible to the white pieces, and Bc4 with an attack on f7 is also an option.}) 8. Be2 {This is too slow to pose problems for Black.} e5 $5 ({The transformation of the pawn structure after} 8... e5 {resembles the Sveshnikov Sicilian. However, an important difference is the active positioning of the bishop on c5. Also playable are 8...a6 and 8...d5.}) (8... a6 {is the most common move. With it, Black can shake off the pressure on the dark squares and equalize: A)} 9. Bc7 Qe7 10. Bd6 Bxd6 11. Nxd6 Ne8 12. Nxe8 Rxe8 {. B) 9.Nd6 Ne8 10.Nxe8 Rxe8 11.O-O b5= with very natural development for Black.}) 9. Be3 {White accepts a weakening of their pawn structure.} Bxe3 10. fxe3 Qb6 {Attacks the e3 pawn and prepares the next move.} 11. Qd2 d6 {Black will complete their development with ...Be6 and ...Rad8. The d-pawn is weak, but White can't capture it easily without running into an uncomfortable pin or losing the e3 pawn. The position is equal.} *

