e2 {This is too slow to pose problems for Black.} e5 $5 ({The transformation of the pawn structure after} 8... e5 {resembles the Sveshnikov Sicilian. However, an important difference is the active positioning of the bishop on c5. Also playable are 8...a6 and 8...d5.}) (8... a6 {is the most common move. With it, Black can shake off the pressure on the dark squares and equalize: A)} 9. Bc7 Qe7 10. Bd6 Bxd6 11. Nxd6 Ne8 12. Nxe8 Rxe8 {. B) 9.Nd6 Ne8 10.Nxe8 Rxe8 11.O-O b5= with very natural development for Black.}) 9. Bg5 {Black does not need to hurry, as 10.Nd5 is not good for tactical reasons. Black now threatens ...a7-a6, after which the white knight would have to move to the passive square a3. After the immediate 9...a6 White has a better square for the knight: 10.Nd6= .} Nd5 $2 {Bxf2+!} 10. Kf1 {Bc5 Black is better. The pin seems annoying, but it's not a real pin: Black threatens ...Nxd5 followed by a fork on e3. White should therefore directly take on f6. Ke1?!} ({Kxf2 Nxe4+ would be very bad for White. Intended against the threat of} 10. Z0 {Nxd5 Bxd8} Ne3 {.}) ({Nxd5!? Nevertheless! Also good is Be6} 10. Nc7 {Bxd5 Nxd5} Bxf2+ $1 11. Kf1 {Nxd5 Bxd8} Ne3+ 12. Kxf2 Nxd1+ 13. Rhxd1 $17 {Raxd8 with an extra pawn.}) {Bxd8} 10... Ne3+ {Qd2?! It would be better to immediately give back the queen. But even then, Black is clearly better. Rxd8 Threatening ...Nxg2+ and ...d6-d5. The white king is not safe. Despite the material deficit, Black is winning.} *

