e2 {This is too slow to pose problems for Black.} e5 $5 ({The transformation of the pawn structure after} 8... e5 {resembles the Sveshnikov Sicilian. However, an important difference is the active positioning of the bishop on c5. Also playable are 8...a6 and 8...d5.}) (8... a6 {is the most common move. With it, Black can shake off the pressure on the dark squares and equalize: A)} 9. Bc7 Qe7 10. Bd6 Bxd6 11. Nxd6 Ne8 12. Nxe8 Rxe8 {. B) 9.Nd6 Ne8 10.Nxe8 Rxe8 11.O-O b5= with very natural development for Black.}) 9. Bg5 {Black does not need to hurry, as 10.Nd5 is not good for tactical reasons. Black now threatens ...a7-a6, after which the white knight would have to move to the passive square a3. After the immediate 9...a6 White has a better square for the knight: 10.Nd6= . Bxf6 Probably best. This ensures a good retreat route for the b5-knight via c7 and d5. Qxf6 O-O Qg5 Black has the better minor pieces and therefore is a little better. White can only place one knight on the outpost square d5, so the other knight has no clear purpose. Black can play on both wings. On the queenside, gaining space with ...a7-a6 and ...b7-b5 is a good plan. On the kingside, Black has the pawn break ...f7-f5, which activates the rook on f8.} *

