1. e4 c5 {The Sicilian Opening stands for a sharp fight. Black somewhat neglects their piece development in order to prevent White from establishing a full pawn center with d2-d4.} 2. Nf3 e6 ({The third most common move after} 2... d6 {and}) (2... Nc6 {. With this, Black primarily prepares the development of the dark-squared bishop, but the center push ...d7-d5 becomes a possibility as well.}) (2... Nc6 {is an alternative way to reach the Four Knights Sicilian:} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6 {and we have landed in our repertoire via transposition. I decided against this path because White has a very serious and popular alternative in 3.Bb5 , the Rossolimo Variation. With 2...e6 the Rossolimo Variation is avoided.}) 3. d4 {The Open Sicilian and the starting position of this course. I examine alternatives for White on the second and third moves in a separate course on the Anti-Sicilians. The Open Sicilian is White's most principled attempt to fight for the opening advantage. White has more space and wants to open up the position, relying on rapid piece development. In return, Black gets the semi-open c-file, which can often be used for counterplay later on. Moreover, the exchange of the d-pawn for the c-pawn is a minor positional concession, as White now has only one pawn in the center and therefore can no longer fight quite as well for the important central squares.} cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 ({A very logical move - the knight is developed and simultaneously attacks the e4 pawn. Black takes advantage of the fact that the knight cannot be directly attacked with e4-e5 .} 4... Nc6 {is also possible, but gives White the additional option} 5. Nb5 {.}) 5. Nc3 ({Develops the knight and reinforces White's influence on the central square d5. Moreover, the diagonal a5-e1 is now interrupted, so that e4-e5 becomes a strong threat.} 5. e5 $2 {allows the double attack} Qa5+ {followed by -- Qxe5 .}) 5... Nc6 {Another natural developing move that continues the fight for the central squares. Black, at least temporarily, is preventing e4-e5 and threatening ...Bb4 with pressure on the white center. The starting position of the Sicilian Four Knights has now been reached. This method of play was first used in the second half of the 19th century. Early adopters included the masters Schiffers, Blackburne, Mieses, and Janowski. White now has a multitude of options.} 6. Ndb5 ({White moves the knight for the third time, but there are good reasons for this time loss. Due to the pawn moves, Black has weakened the squares d6 and c7 . Specifically, an unpleasant knight check on d6 is threatened. For a long time, 6.Ndb5 was considered the main variation. However, at the highest level there has recently been a trend towards} 6. Nxc6 {. The reason for this is that after}) (6. Ndb5 {, Black can transition into the Sveshnikov Sicilian, where White currently struggles to prove an opening advantage. However, 6.Ndb5 still remains the most common move, especially below grandmaster level.}) 6... Bc5 $5 ({A rare move that will come as a surprise to many of our opponents. More popular are} 6... d6 {(which usually leads to the Sveshnikov variation) or}) (6... Bb4 {.}) ({➤ With} 6... Bc5 {, Black prepares to castle and targets the tactically vulnerable point f2. Additionally, Black can now respond to the knight check on d6 with a king move without blocking the development of the bishop on f8. 6...Bc5 is known as the 'Cobra Variation', tracing back to an article by Swedish IM Jesper Hall. According to my database, the Cobra was first played in 1963 by Soviet IM Viacheslav Osnos, but it remained a niche for a long time. Nowadays, some strong grandmasters have discovered the move for themselves, especially in faster time controls. I can confirm from my own experience: In blitz, the Cobra is a particularly dangerous weapon, as many opponents do not know the variation well enough, react poorly and/or consume a lot of time. The 'holes ' on d6 and c7 also invite (unsuccessful) attempts to refute the opening.}) ({➤} 6... d5 $2 {is positionally desirable, but tactically a mistake:} 7. exd5 exd5 8. Bf4 {and the Nc7+ fork can hardly be prevented.}) ({➤ After} 6... d6 {White has nothing better than the aforementioned transition into the Sveshnikov Sicilian:} 7. Bf4 e5 8. Bg5 {. This position usually arises through the move order 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 e5 6.Ndb5 d6 7.Bg5 . In this move order, however, White also has the additional options of 7.Nd5 and 3.Bb5, which is why some Black players try to reach the Sveshnikov Sicilian via 2...e6.}) ({➤} 6... Bb4 {is a solid variation, with which Black has good chances of equalizing the game. However, we do not see the typical attacking play of the Sicilian Defense here. Therefore, I prefer the more adventurous 6...Bc5.} 7. a3 {As the e4 pawn is under attack, White forces the exchange of the bishop.} Bxc3+ 8. Nxc3 d5 {Liberates the queenside and fights for the center.} 9. exd5 exd5 {Black accepts positional disadvantages (the isolated pawn d5 and the opposing bishop pair) in exchange for rapid development and control of the central squares. Nevertheless, a long fight for equality lies ahead.}) 7. Bf4 {The most common continuation. White is threatening a knight fork on c7 and simultaneously targets the weakened d6 square. The move e4-e5 is also a threat.} O-O ({The only good move. Black secures their king, dodges the knight checks, and provides the knight on f6 a retreat square on e8. If Black now manages to liberate the queenside with ...d7-d5, they would already be better. Therefore, White should now aim to blockade the pawn on d7.} 7... e5 $2 8. Be3 $1 Bxe3 9. Nd6+ Ke7 10. fxe3 {. A very similar position arises after 7.Be3 Bxe3 8.Nd6+ Ke7 9.fxe3 . The only difference is that the black e-pawn is already on e5 here. This small difference turns out to be fatal for Black, because the squares f5 and d5 are accessible to the white pieces, and Bc4 with an attack on f7 is also an option.}) 8. e5 {Nd6} {This intermediate move is more accurate than the immediate 8...Ne8. Primarily, Black wants to drive away the b5 knight in order to have the option of ...Bc5-d4 later. Ne8 Ne4 is slightly better for White, because Black does not have the active reaction ...Bc5-d4 here. After exf6 Qxf6! , Black wins back the piece under favorable circumstances.} Ne8 9. Ne4 Bd4 ({This double attack on the pawns on e5 and b2 poses greater practical problems for White than} 9... Bd6 {, which is also a good move.}) ({Nxe8 Nc4?} 9... f5 10. Ng5 $17 {b5 . White is losing the e5 pawn, and the king remains vulnerable in the center.}) {Rxe8} 10. Qh5 $1 {This hasn't been played yet, but only with a kingside attack can White maintain the balance. There is a threat of Ng5. After Nd6 , Rf8 is simpler than 12...Bxb2. White cannot avoid losing a pawn: ( 12...Bxb2 13.Bd3! Rf8 (not 13...Bxa1 14.Bxh7+ Kxh7 15.Qh5+ Kg8 16.Qxf7+ with perpetual check.) 14.O-O Bxa1 15.Qxa1 . White has some compensation as Black cannot free the c8 bishop easily.) 13.Bd3 f5 . Black had a slightly better position in the rapid game Warszawski–Heberla [/variation/31423354/#/13/b], Warsaw 2009 (0-1). Next, Black will capture on e5.} Qa5+ ({Black has too few defenders on the kingside and therefore also goes for an attack against the opponent's king.} 10... Bxe5 $5 {is also playable and leads to an unclear position:} 11. Ng5 $1 Bxf4 12. Qxf7+ Kh8 13. Qxf4 {Rf8 .}) 11. c3 (11. Kd1 $2 h6 $1 {is good for Black, as White has no tactics and the e5 pawn is lost.}) 11... Bxe5 {There are alternatives, but they also only lead to perpetual check. Black is now threatening the discovered attack ...Bxc3+ followed by Qxh5.} 12. Ng5 $1 {This double attack forces Black to give a perpetual.} Bxc3+ 13. bxc3 ({Not} 13. Ke2 {Qf5 bxc3 Qxf4 Qxh7+ Kf8 Qh8+ Ke7 Qxg7} b6 $17 {and the black king is safer than White's.}) 13... Qxc3+ 14. Ke2 $1 ({White needs to play accurately. First, the black knight needs to be lured to d4.} 14. Kd1 $2 {loses after} Qxa1+ 15. Bc1 Ne5 {. The check on h7 is not dangerous as the black king can escape.}) 14... Nd4+ 15. Kd1 Qc2+ (15... Qxa1+ $2 {is bad because with the knight on d4, Black cannot defend the f7 square after} 16. Bc1 {and would lose to a deadly attack after Rd8 Bd3 .}) 16. Ke1 Qc3+ {With perpetual check.} *

