d6 {Bc7} Qe7 {Bd6 . Qb6! Thanks to this tactical detail, Black manages to activate their queen. White must not capture the rook. Bxc5 Bxf8?? Bxf2+} 9. Kd2 {Qe3# . Qxc5 Black is now threatening ...d7-d5, after which the white knights can subsequently be driven to bad squares with ...a7-a6 or ...d5-d4. Qd6 Bc7, White hopes for a blockade of the opponent's queenside. However, unlike there, the black queen is already activated here, giving Black dangerous threats and preventing White from castling queenside due to the attack on f2. Qb6 Black is threatening ...a7-a6. a4?! To drive back the active black queen with a4-a5. Ne8} a6 {, played by me once, is weaker: a5 Qd8 A)} 10. Nd4 $6 Na5 $15 {. B) 13.Nc7! . The knight has no retreat square anymore, but Black can't attack it. 13...Rb8 14.Bd3 b5 15.axb6 Rxb6= , Jansen–Feuerstack [/variation/31423356/#/15/b], Neustadt an der Weinstraße 2017 (0-1). Qa3 a6 a5 Qd8 Nd6 The last moves were forced. Now, Black can win a pawn. Nxd6 Qxd6 Nxa5 Black has an extra pawn and is better. Queenside development with ...b7-b5 is next on the agenda.} *

