ts to refute the opening.}) ({➤} 6... d5 $2 {is positionally desirable, but tactically a mistake:} 7. exd5 exd5 8. Bf4 {and the Nc7+ fork can hardly be prevented.}) ({➤ After} 6... d6 {White has nothing better than the aforementioned transition into the Sveshnikov Sicilian:} 7. Bf4 e5 8. Bg5 {. This position usually arises through the move order 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 e5 6.Ndb5 d6 7.Bg5 . In this move order, however, White also has the additional options of 7.Nd5 and 3.Bb5, which is why some Black players try to reach the Sveshnikov Sicilian via 2...e6.}) ({➤} 6... Bb4 {is a solid variation, with which Black has good chances of equalizing the game. However, we do not see the typical attacking play of the Sicilian Defense here. Therefore, I prefer the more adventurous 6...Bc5.} 7. a3 {As the e4 pawn is under attack, White forces the exchange of the bishop.} Bxc3+ 8. Nxc3 d5 {Liberates the queenside and fights for the center.} 9. exd5 exd5 {Black accepts positional disadvantages (the isolated pawn d5 and the opposing bishop pair) in exchange for rapid development and control of the central squares. Nevertheless, a long fight for equality lies ahead.}) 7. Bf4 {The most common continuation. White is threatening a knight fork on c7 and simultaneously targets the weakened d6 square. The move e4-e5 is also a threat.} O-O ({The only good move. Black secures their king, dodges the knight checks, and provides the knight on f6 a retreat square on e8. If Black now manages to liberate the queenside with ...d7-d5, they would already be better. Therefore, White should now aim to blockade the pawn on d7.} 7... e5 $2 8. Be3 $1 Bxe3 9. Nd6+ Ke7 10. fxe3 {. A very similar position arises after 7.Be3 Bxe3 8.Nd6+ Ke7 9.fxe3 . The only difference is that the black e-pawn is already on e5 here. This small difference turns out to be fatal for Black, because the squares f5 and d5 are accessible to the white pieces, and Bc4 with an attack on f7 is also an option.}) 8. Bd6 {Bc7} Qe7 {Bd6 . Qb6! Thanks to this tactical detail, Black manages to activate their queen. White must not capture the rook. Bxc5 Bxf8?? Bxf2+} 9. Kd2 {Qe3# . Qxc5 Black is now threatening ...d7-d5, after which the white knights can subsequently be driven to bad squares with ...a7-a6 or ...d5-d4. Qd6 Bc7, White hopes for a blockade of the opponent's queenside. However, unlike there, the black queen is already activated here, giving Black dangerous threats and preventing White from castling queenside due to the attack on f2. Qb6 Black is threatening ...a7-a6. Qd2 The thematic liberation of the queenside. Black gains active play and therefore does not have to fear the pawn weakness on d5.} a6 {is also good.} 10. Na4 Qd8 {Nd6 b5= , Papp–Pashikian [/variation/31423358/#/13/b], Iraklio 2002 (0-1). exd5 exd5 O-O-O The easiest way to equalize. However, Black can also maintain the tension and has good play, for example with 13...Bf5 and active play on the queenside. Nd4 Ne4 Nxe4 dxe4 White now has to play precisely to equalize. Nxc6 Qxc6 Qd6 Qa4 a3 Bg4 Black doesn't have any problems. The tactical justification of the last move is: Rd4 Qxd4! Qxd4 Rfd8 Black wins back the queen and reaches an equal endgame.} *

