1. e4 c5 {The Sicilian Opening stands for a sharp fight. Black somewhat neglects their piece development in order to prevent White from establishing a full pawn center with d2-d4.} 2. Nf3 e6 ({The third most common move after} 2... d6 {and}) (2... Nc6 {. With this, Black primarily prepares the development of the dark-squared bishop, but the center push ...d7-d5 becomes a possibility as well.}) (2... Nc6 {is an alternative way to reach the Four Knights Sicilian:} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6 {and we have landed in our repertoire via transposition. I decided against this path because White has a very serious and popular alternative in 3.Bb5 , the Rossolimo Variation. With 2...e6 the Rossolimo Variation is avoided.}) 3. d4 {The Open Sicilian and the starting position of this course. I examine alternatives for White on the second and third moves in a separate course on the Anti-Sicilians. The Open Sicilian is White's most principled attempt to fight for the opening advantage. White has more space and wants to open up the position, relying on rapid piece development. In return, Black gets the semi-open c-file, which can often be used for counterplay later on. Moreover, the exchange of the d-pawn for the c-pawn is a minor positional concession, as White now has only one pawn in the center and therefore can no longer fight quite as well for the important central squares.} cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 ({A very logical move - the knight is developed and simultaneously attacks the e4 pawn. Black takes advantage of the fact that the knight cannot be directly attacked with e4-e5 .} 4... Nc6 {is also possible, but gives White the additional option} 5. Nb5 {.}) 5. Nc3 ({Develops the knight and reinforces White's influence on the central square d5. Moreover, the diagonal a5-e1 is now interrupted, so that e4-e5 becomes a strong threat.} 5. e5 $2 {allows the double attack} Qa5+ {followed by -- Qxe5 .}) 5... Nc6 {Another natural developing move that continues the fight for the central squares. Black, at least temporarily, is preventing e4-e5 and threatening ...Bb4 with pressure on the white center. The starting position of the Sicilian Four Knights has now been reached. This method of play was first used in the second half of the 19th century. Early adopters included the masters Schiffers, Blackburne, Mieses, and Janowski. White now has a multitude of options.} 6. Ndb5 ({White moves the knight for the third time, but there are good reasons for this time loss. Due to the pawn moves, Black has weakened the squares d6 and c7 . Specifically, an unpleasant knight check on d6 is threatened. For a long time, 6.Ndb5 was considered the main variation. However, at the highest level there has recently been a trend towards} 6. Nxc6 {. The reason for this is that after}) (6. Ndb5 {, Black can transition into the Sveshnikov Sicilian, where White currently struggles to prove an opening advantage. However, 6.Ndb5 still remains the most common move, especially below grandmaster level.}) 6... Bc5 $5 ({A rare move that will come as a surprise to many of our opponents. More popular are} 6... d6 {(which usually leads to the Sveshnikov variation) or}) (6... Bb4 {.}) ({➤ With} 6... Bc5 {, Black prepares to castle and targets the tactically vulnerable point f2. Additionally, Black can now respond to the knight check on d6 with a king move without blocking the development of the bishop on f8. 6...Bc5 is known as the 'Cobra Variation', tracing back to an article by Swedish IM Jesper Hall. According to my database, the Cobra was first played in 1963 by Soviet IM Viacheslav Osnos, but it remained a niche for a long time. Nowadays, some strong grandmasters have discovered the move for themselves, especially in faster time controls. I can confirm from my own experience: In blitz, the Cobra is a particularly dangerous weapon, as many opponents do not know the variation well enough, react poorly and/or consume a lot of time. The 'holes ' on d6 and c7 also invite (unsuccessful) attempts to refute the opening.}) ({➤} 6... d5 $2 {is positionally desirable, but tactically a mistake:} 7. exd5 exd5 8. Bf4 {and the Nc7+ fork can hardly be prevented.}) ({➤ After} 6... d6 {White has nothing better than the aforementioned transition into the Sveshnikov Sicilian:} 7. Bf4 e5 8. Bg5 {. This position usually arises through the move order 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 e5 6.Ndb5 d6 7.Bg5 . In this move order, however, White also has the additional options of 7.Nd5 and 3.Bb5, which is why some Black players try to reach the Sveshnikov Sicilian via 2...e6.}) ({➤} 6... Bb4 {is a solid variation, with which Black has good chances of equalizing the game. However, we do not see the typical attacking play of the Sicilian Defense here. Therefore, I prefer the more adventurous 6...Bc5.} 7. a3 {As the e4 pawn is under attack, White forces the exchange of the bishop.} Bxc3+ 8. Nxc3 d5 {Liberates the queenside and fights for the center.} 9. exd5 exd5 {Black accepts positional disadvantages (the isolated pawn d5 and the opposing bishop pair) in exchange for rapid development and control of the central squares. Nevertheless, a long fight for equality lies ahead.}) 7. Bf4 {The most common continuation. White is threatening a knight fork on c7 and simultaneously targets the weakened d6 square. The move e4-e5 is also a threat.} O-O ({The only good move. Black secures their king, dodges the knight checks, and provides the knight on f6 a retreat square on e8. If Black now manages to liberate the queenside with ...d7-d5, they would already be better. Therefore, White should now aim to blockade the pawn on d7.} 7... e5 $2 8. Be3 $1 Bxe3 9. Nd6+ Ke7 10. fxe3 {. A very similar position arises after 7.Be3 Bxe3 8.Nd6+ Ke7 9.fxe3 . The only difference is that the black e-pawn is already on e5 here. This small difference turns out to be fatal for Black, because the squares f5 and d5 are accessible to the white pieces, and Bc4 with an attack on f7 is also an option.}) 8. Bd6 {Bc7} Qe7 {Bd6 . Qb6! Thanks to this tactical detail, Black manages to activate their queen. White must not capture the rook. Bxc5 Bxf8?? Bxf2+} 9. Kd2 {Qe3# . Qxc5 Black is now threatening ...d7-d5, after which the white knights can subsequently be driven to bad squares with ...a7-a6 or ...d5-d4. Qd6 Bc7, White hopes for a blockade of the opponent's queenside. However, unlike there, the black queen is already activated here, giving Black dangerous threats and preventing White from castling queenside due to the attack on f2. Qb6 Black is threatening ...a7-a6. Qc7 The most common move. Faced with the opponent's threats, White tries to repeat moves. Black can go along with it or keep the game alive. O-O-O? has been tried in some games, but after Qxf2 , White has no compensation for the pawn. Qxc7!? In my opinion, it is worth avoiding the repetition of moves. There are some pitfalls that White must avoid. d5!? is another attempt, along with 11...Qxc7, to avoid the repetition of moves. With precise play, however, White is slightly better. exd5 exd5 Qxb6 axb6 and now: A) O-O-O is not so good. After} Rd8 {Black is threatening ...d5-d4 and after} 10. Nd4 {there follows the thematic} Ng4 $1 {Rd2 Nxd4 Rxd4 Nxf2} 11. Rg1 $17 {Be6= . B) 14.Ne2 with the idea of Ned4 and blockading the isolated pawn is a good option. C) 14.Bd3 d4 15.Ne2 Rd8 16.O-O $14 . Usually, after ...d5-d4, Black doesn't have any problems. However, this position is an exception, since the knight on b5 can no longer be driven away with ...a7-a6. White is slightly better, because the pawn on d4 is weak. Nxc7 Rb8 Black wants to play ...a7-a6 next, depriving the knight on c7 of its last escape square. If White is careless, the knight will be lost. O-O-O!? The continuation favored by Stockfish. From a human perspective, it seems very risky to have the knight trapped on c7. No wonder this has not been tested in tournament chess yet. a6 Be2?! A naive move to demonstrate how Black can profit from the trapped knight. It's not that easy! b5 ...b5-b4 is threatened, winning the e4 pawn. Rd8 threatens ...d7-d6 followed by ...Rd8-d7. However, White can defend against it by, among other moves, Rd6! . f3 After a3? Bb7 followed by ...Rc8, White loses at least a pawn. Bb7 The threat is ...Rfc8, but White can still defend. a4! Na2 It may seem like everything is in order for White now. The Nc7 has an escape route via a6. However, the position remains tactical. Nb1? leads to a beautiful finale. Rfc8! Nxa6 Ra8 Nc5} Na5 {. White can no longer defend the knight, and if it moves away... Nxb7} 12. Nb3 $1 {. b3! Takes advantage of the white king's position and wins a pawn. Nc3 cxb3 Rfc8 Nxa6 Nb4+ winning a piece. bxc2 Rd6 Nb4 Black is threatening ...Rfc8 and is slightly better. The a6 pawn is poisoned: Nxa6? Bxa6 Bxa6 Ne8 White can no longer defend the bishop.} *

