one move to stay in the game. Rd6! The blockade with the rook is unusual, but Black cannot dislodge it. Kf8 Be2 Ke7 Rhd1 Black should not allow White to strenghten the blockade with f2-f4 and e4-e5. If White continues with this plan even after 17...g5, a file opens up on the kingside and Black gets counterplay. In any case, Black now wants to gain more space on the kingside and activate the d8 rook. On the queenside, the status quo can be maintained. Although the rook and bishop are not yet in play, the white pieces are also tied up in the blockade. The position is equal.} *

