be better, White would need to block the d-pawn with Nd4. Otherwise, Black always threatens to drive the knights to bad squares with ...d5-d4 or ...a7-a6. O-O-O Nd4 Nc7? allows a tactic that is thematic in this line: d4 N3d5 Ne4! . White cannot defend the f-pawn, and f3} Nxf2 {doesn't improve the situation. Ng4! The specific point that gives Black comfortable equality. White cannot simultaneously defend the f2 square and maintain the blockade construction. Rd2 Nxd4 Rxd4 Nxf2 Rg1 Be6= White will regain the pawn, after which the position is completely equal. The material is reduced and both sides have no pawn weaknesses.} *

