{Bd2! Now White is mated. Bxd2 Nxd2+ Kg4 h5+ Kh3 g5 Nf5+ The knight had taken away the king's escape square, but of course, the sacrifice doesn't help either. exf5 Rae1 Bxa6 g4+ Kh4 Qf6 Engel–Feuerstack [/variation/31423371/#/25/b], Rapid chess 2018.} 1. e4 c5 {The Sicilian Opening stands for a sharp fight. Black somewhat neglects their piece development in order to prevent White from establishing a full pawn center with d2-d4.} 2. Nf3 e6 ({The third most common move after} 2... d6 {and}) (2... Nc6 {. With this, Black primarily prepares the development of the dark-squared bishop, but the center push ...d7-d5 becomes a possibility as well.}) (2... Nc6 {is an alternative way to reach the Four Knights Sicilian:} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6 {and we have landed in our repertoire via transposition. I decided against this path because White has a very serious and popular alternative in 3.Bb5 , the Rossolimo Variation. With 2...e6 the Rossolimo Variation is avoided.}) 3. d4 {The Open Sicilian and the starting position of this course. I examine alternatives for White on the second and third moves in a separate course on the Anti-Sicilians. The Open Sicilian is White's most principled attempt to fight for the opening advantage. White has more space and wants to open up the position, relying on rapid piece development. In return, Black gets the semi-open c-file, which can often be used for counterplay later on. Moreover, the exchange of the d-pawn for the c-pawn is a minor positional concession, as White now has only one pawn in the center and therefore can no longer fight quite as well for the important central squares.} cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 ({A very logical move - the knight is developed and simultaneously attacks the e4 pawn. Black takes advantage of the fact that the knight cannot be directly attacked with e4-e5 .} 4... Nc6 {is also possible, but gives White the additional option} 5. Nb5 {.}) 5. Nc3 ({Develops the knight and reinforces White's influence on the central square d5. Moreover, the diagonal a5-e1 is now interrupted, so that e4-e5 becomes a strong threat.} 5. e5 $2 {allows the double attack} Qa5+ {followed by -- Qxe5 .}) 5... Nc6 {Another natural developing move that continues the fight for the central squares. Black, at least temporarily, is preventing e4-e5 and threatening ...Bb4 with pressure on the white center. The starting position of the Sicilian Four Knights has now been reached. This method of play was first used in the second half of the 19th century. Early adopters included the masters Schiffers, Blackburne, Mieses, and Janowski. White now has a multitude of options.} 6. Nxc6 ({This initiates one of the sharpest and most complex variations in the Sicilian Four Knights. We will see very unusual positions that are unfamiliar from any other opening. 6.Nxc6 is the second most common move after 6.Ndb5. It is chosen primarily by players who are not comfortable transitioning into the Sveshnikov Variation after} 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bf4 e5 8. Bg5 {.}) 6... bxc6 ({Black would now like to play ...d7-d5 and would then have a solid position with good central control.} 6... dxc6 {leads to a queenless middlegame that is slightly better for White.} 7. Qxd8+ Kxd8 8. Bf4 $14 {. The main problem in Black's position is the passive bishop on c8.}) 7. e5 {The critical move. White prevents ...d7-d5 – the d7 pawn is now backward. In addition, White prepares to put pressure on the weakened d6-square. A third advantage from White's perspective is that a defender of the kingside is driven away, making future attacks there more promising. Of course, the pawn move also has its drawbacks. We will see in the following variations that the pawn on e5 itself becomes a target of Black's counterplay. White will have to accept weaknesses in their own camp to defend the exposed pawn. Alternatives to 7.e5 are discussed in the following chapter [/course/199209/7].} Nd5 8. Ne4 ({White avoids exchanging knights and targets the weakened d6-square. A subsequent c2-c4 could drive the black knight away from its central position and also give the white queen access to d6. The main problem for Black is the bishop on c8, which is blocked by Black's own pawns and cannot be activated easily. In this tabiya, Black has tried a variety of options, some of which have established their place in opening theory.} 8. Nxd5 cxd5 {is examined in chapter 5 [/course/199209/7].}) 8... Qc7 ({The main move. Black attacks the e5-pawn and forces a weakening of White's position. The alternative} 8... Bb7 {is also popular nowadays. Black wants to play ...c6-c5 and quickly solve the problem of the 'bad' light-squared bishop.}) 9. f4 {The queen has fulfilled its purpose on c7 and moves to a better square. On b6, the queen performs a number of functions:  * It controls the weakened a7-g1 diagonal.  * It threatens the double attack 10...Qb4+.  * It attacks the b2-pawn, complicating the development of the c1-bishop.  * It supports ...Ne3.  * It supports the attempt to exchange the light-squared bishops with ...Ba6. c4 Qd3 Obviously the best square for the queen, as it also needs to protect c2.} {I pondered for a long time whether to recommend the knight move or the main line Bb4+ . The latter is discussed at the highest level and, from a theoretical standpoint, Black is in good shape. On the other hand, after Ne3 , White achieves a slightly better position with best play from both sides. Still, I decided on 10...Ne3. The downside of 10...Bb4+ is that the theory is quite far advanced and leads to very complicated positions where one misstep can be fatal. In my opinion, 10...Ne3 is easier to play because the variations resulting from it are more straightforward.} Bb4+ {With this check, Black gains some time. Not only because the bishop is developed with a tempo, but also because after the main move 12.Bd2, the knight on e3 is no longer attacked.} 10. Ke2 $6 $17 {This is a tactical mistake, but one that occurs often, especially in blitz games: in the database of online games played on Lichess, White went for this in almost 45% of the games. The reason is probably that Ke2 a move earlier is the correct reaction to the bishop check ( 10...Bb4+ 11.Ke2 ), and White players confuse the two positions. Here, the king move loses a pawn. The position remains tricky, however, so it is worthwhile to take a closer look at it. Nxc4! Black takes advantage of the fact that the king and queen are on the same diagonal. Kf3 Now the knight on c4 is attacked and has no good retreat square.} Ba6+ {Black is threatening to win the queen with ...Nxe5+ and ...Bxd3. Qc2 The queen protects the knight and also gives Black attacking opportunities. Be2?} ({The right idea, but White should include a3} 10... Be7 {.}) ({f5! exf6 Against} 10... Nc3+ $2 {, both g5 and 16...Bc5 are good enough, but 16...Nxe5+! is the strongest: 17.fxe5 Bc5 . The queen is threatening mate on f2 and g4. After 18.Kg3 g5! , mate is threatened on h4. 19.Bxg5 Rg8 - Black regains the piece and the attack continues.}) ({Against Nf2? , Nd2+ is the simplest. After} 10... Bd2 11. Bxd2 {, Black is threatening to win with Qxf4#, Qe3#, but also with Qd5+. In Cieslak–Berdnyk [/variation/31423360/#/18/b], Riga 2018,} Ba6+ {Qe3# followed.}) ({d5 That was the idea behind 15...f5. Now the opponent's knight is attacked and our own is defended. Black has a clear advantage. I reached this position in a rapid game against the then 15-year-old future GM Luis Engel and was able to secure a quick victory: f7+ Ng5 Qxf6 . Ke7 Time is very important in this position. Kxf7? would have allowed White to save the knight with check. Ng3? It is difficult to find a good response for White in this position.} 10... Nc3+ {would be the most resilient defense.}) *

