{Bxd2+! Black should trade queens now. After a direct retreat of the knight, 18.O-O-O would have followed, leaving Black's king in danger. Qxd2 Qxd2+ Kxd2 Nh4= Black has equalized. A good setup now is ...d7-d6, ...Ke7, and ...Bd7. In the long term, Black could try to activate the minor pieces with ...Ng6 and ...e6-e5. However, Black should generally avoid ...d7-d5, as this would leave the c5-square in White's control.} 1. e4 c5 {The Sicilian Opening stands for a sharp fight. Black somewhat neglects their piece development in order to prevent White from establishing a full pawn center with d2-d4.} 2. Nf3 e6 ({The third most common move after} 2... d6 {and}) (2... Nc6 {. With this, Black primarily prepares the development of the dark-squared bishop, but the center push ...d7-d5 becomes a possibility as well.}) (2... Nc6 {is an alternative way to reach the Four Knights Sicilian:} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6 {and we have landed in our repertoire via transposition. I decided against this path because White has a very serious and popular alternative in 3.Bb5 , the Rossolimo Variation. With 2...e6 the Rossolimo Variation is avoided.}) 3. d4 {The Open Sicilian and the starting position of this course. I examine alternatives for White on the second and third moves in a separate course on the Anti-Sicilians. The Open Sicilian is White's most principled attempt to fight for the opening advantage. White has more space and wants to open up the position, relying on rapid piece development. In return, Black gets the semi-open c-file, which can often be used for counterplay later on. Moreover, the exchange of the d-pawn for the c-pawn is a minor positional concession, as White now has only one pawn in the center and therefore can no longer fight quite as well for the important central squares.} cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 ({A very logical move - the knight is developed and simultaneously attacks the e4 pawn. Black takes advantage of the fact that the knight cannot be directly attacked with e4-e5 .} 4... Nc6 {is also possible, but gives White the additional option} 5. Nb5 {.}) 5. Nc3 ({Develops the knight and reinforces White's influence on the central square d5. Moreover, the diagonal a5-e1 is now interrupted, so that e4-e5 becomes a strong threat.} 5. e5 $2 {allows the double attack} Qa5+ {followed by -- Qxe5 .}) 5... Nc6 {Another natural developing move that continues the fight for the central squares. Black, at least temporarily, is preventing e4-e5 and threatening ...Bb4 with pressure on the white center. The starting position of the Sicilian Four Knights has now been reached. This method of play was first used in the second half of the 19th century. Early adopters included the masters Schiffers, Blackburne, Mieses, and Janowski. White now has a multitude of options.} 6. Nxc6 ({This initiates one of the sharpest and most complex variations in the Sicilian Four Knights. We will see very unusual positions that are unfamiliar from any other opening. 6.Nxc6 is the second most common move after 6.Ndb5. It is chosen primarily by players who are not comfortable transitioning into the Sveshnikov Variation after} 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bf4 e5 8. Bg5 {.}) 6... bxc6 ({Black would now like to play ...d7-d5 and would then have a solid position with good central control.} 6... dxc6 {leads to a queenless middlegame that is slightly better for White.} 7. Qxd8+ Kxd8 8. Bf4 $14 {. The main problem in Black's position is the passive bishop on c8.}) 7. e5 {The critical move. White prevents ...d7-d5 – the d7 pawn is now backward. In addition, White prepares to put pressure on the weakened d6-square. A third advantage from White's perspective is that a defender of the kingside is driven away, making future attacks there more promising. Of course, the pawn move also has its drawbacks. We will see in the following variations that the pawn on e5 itself becomes a target of Black's counterplay. White will have to accept weaknesses in their own camp to defend the exposed pawn. Alternatives to 7.e5 are discussed in the following chapter [/course/199209/7].} Nd5 8. Ne4 ({White avoids exchanging knights and targets the weakened d6-square. A subsequent c2-c4 could drive the black knight away from its central position and also give the white queen access to d6. The main problem for Black is the bishop on c8, which is blocked by Black's own pawns and cannot be activated easily. In this tabiya, Black has tried a variety of options, some of which have established their place in opening theory.} 8. Nxd5 cxd5 {is examined in chapter 5 [/course/199209/7].}) 8... Qc7 ({The main move. Black attacks the e5-pawn and forces a weakening of White's position. The alternative} 8... Bb7 {is also popular nowadays. Black wants to play ...c6-c5 and quickly solve the problem of the 'bad' light-squared bishop.}) 9. f4 {The queen has fulfilled its purpose on c7 and moves to a better square. On b6, the queen performs a number of functions:  * It controls the weakened a7-g1 diagonal.  * It threatens the double attack 10...Qb4+.  * It attacks the b2-pawn, complicating the development of the c1-bishop.  * It supports ...Ne3.  * It supports the attempt to exchange the light-squared bishops with ...Ba6. c4 Qd3 Obviously the best square for the queen, as it also needs to protect c2.} {I pondered for a long time whether to recommend the knight move or the main line Bb4+ . The latter is discussed at the highest level and, from a theoretical standpoint, Black is in good shape. On the other hand, after Ne3 , White achieves a slightly better position with best play from both sides. Still, I decided on 10...Ne3. The downside of 10...Bb4+ is that the theory is quite far advanced and leads to very complicated positions where one misstep can be fatal. In my opinion, 10...Ne3 is easier to play because the variations resulting from it are more straightforward.} Bb4+ 10. Nc3 $5 {A quite rare but interesting move. White gives up the central position of the knight, but now Black must address the position of their own knight on e3. Nf5 Bd2 b3} {This indirectly pressures the pawn on b2, thereby complicating queenside castling for White. Alternatively, it is possible to play Bb7 followed by ...c6-c5 to activate the light-squared bishop. White stabilizes the queenside. Some alternatives: A) After O-O-O?! the tactic Ba3! wins the b2-pawn. B) 14.Be2 was once played in an online blitz game against me, but since White cannot castle kingside anyway, the move does little to improve White's position. There followed O-O 15.a3?! Be7 16.b4 Buchenau-Feuerstack [/variation/36055957], Playchess.com (0-1) and now 16...c5 $15 would have opened the position in favour of Black. C) 14.g4 Nd4 transposes to the variation 13.g4 Nd4 14.Bd2 Rb8 . D) The position after 14.Na4 Qa5 15.b3 f6 is a transposition.} f6 ({Black should not waste time and attack White's center immediately, so that the pawn on d7 becomes mobile. In the game Haubro-Nielsen [/variation/36055958] Svendborg 2023 (1-0)} 10... h5 {was played instead, after which Na4! Qa5 Bxb4 Rxb4} 11. Qd2 {followed by Bd3 or a2-a3 would have given White the slightly better chances.}) {Na4 Generally speaking, the exchange of dark-squared bishops is favorable for White, but here Black gets sufficient counterplay in the center. Qa5} 11. exf6 {Bxb4? now fails to Rxb4 , threatening both a discovered check as well as winning the pawn on e5.} gxf6 12. g4 ({O-O-O is answered by d5 (or 17...c5!?) and if now} 12. g4 {, the knight has a nice retreat square on d6. Nd6 .}) *

