as tried a variety of options, some of which have established their place in opening theory.} 8. Nxd5 cxd5 {is examined in chapter 5 [/course/199209/7].}) 8... Qc7 ({The main move. Black attacks the e5-pawn and forces a weakening of White's position. The alternative} 8... Bb7 {is also popular nowadays. Black wants to play ...c6-c5 and quickly solve the problem of the 'bad' light-squared bishop.}) 9. f4 {The queen has fulfilled its purpose on c7 and moves to a better square. On b6, the queen performs a number of functions:  * It controls the weakened a7-g1 diagonal.  * It threatens the double attack 10...Qb4+.  * It attacks the b2-pawn, complicating the development of the c1-bishop.  * It supports ...Ne3.  * It supports the attempt to exchange the light-squared bishops with ...Ba6. c4 Qd3 Obviously the best square for the queen, as it also needs to protect c2.} {I pondered for a long time whether to recommend the knight move or the main line Bb4+ . The latter is discussed at the highest level and, from a theoretical standpoint, Black is in good shape. On the other hand, after Ne3 , White achieves a slightly better position with best play from both sides. Still, I decided on 10...Ne3. The downside of 10...Bb4+ is that the theory is quite far advanced and leads to very complicated positions where one misstep can be fatal. In my opinion, 10...Ne3 is easier to play because the variations resulting from it are more straightforward.} Bb4+ 10. Nc3 $5 {A quite rare but interesting move. White gives up the central position of the knight, but now Black must address the position of their own knight on e3. Nf5 Bd2 b3} {This indirectly pressures the pawn on b2, thereby complicating queenside castling for White. Alternatively, it is possible to play Bb7 followed by ...c6-c5 to activate the light-squared bishop. White stabilizes the queenside. Some alternatives: A) After O-O-O?! the tactic Ba3! wins the b2-pawn. B) 14.Be2 was once played in an online blitz game against me, but since White cannot castle kingside anyway, the move does little to improve White's position. There followed O-O 15.a3?! Be7 16.b4 Buchenau-Feuerstack [/variation/36055957], Playchess.com (0-1) and now 16...c5 $15 would have opened the position in favour of Black. C) 14.g4 Nd4 transposes to the variation 13.g4 Nd4 14.Bd2 Rb8 . D) The position after 14.Na4 Qa5 15.b3 f6 is covered via the move order 14.b3 f6 15.Na4 Qa5 .} f6 ({Black should not waste time and attack White's center immediately, so that the pawn on d7 becomes mobile. In the game Haubro-Nielsen [/variation/36055958] Svendborg 2023 (1-0)} 10... h5 {was played instead, after which Na4! Qa5 Bxb4 Rxb4} 11. Qd2 {followed by Bd3 or a2-a3 would have given White the slightly better chances.}) 11. exf6 {Good news for Black: The exchange of pawns has removed the threat of being squeezed on the dark squares. If White tries to keep the pawn on e5, e.g. by playing O-O-O , Black gets good counterplay against the weakened white pawns: fxe5 fxe5 Qa5 . Now the threat is not only to win the pawn on e5, but also on a2 after ...Bxc3 and ...Qxa2..} gxf6 12. g4 {Nd4! There is no reason for a passive retreat to e7 or g7. Rd1} {The right moment to challenge the knight. If Black had already played ...d7-d5, the knight would have a good retreat square on d6. After O-O-O , d5 follows. Later, Black can increase the pressure on White's king position by playing ...Nd6. O-O-O?? Nxb3! axb3 Ba3+ Kb1 Qxb3+ leads to mate.} e5 ({White had threatened to win a piece by playing Na4. It's equally possible to protect the knight by playing} 12... c5 {.}) {Na4 After Bg2 , d5 is an interesting continuation, and now: A) cxd5?? does not work for White: Ba6 20.Qe4 Bxc3 21.Bxc3 cxd5 22.Qxd5 Rd8 23.Qe4 Nc2+! 24.Qxc2 Qe3+ with checkmate in the next move. B) Therefore, White should play 19.Na4 dxc4 20.Nxb6 cxd3 21.Nxc8 Nc2+ 22.Kf2 Rxc8 , leading to a complicated, but dynamically equal position. Qa5} 13. Bg2 d6 {Black has succeeded in activating the light-squared bishop. Now the pawn on g4 is attacked.} 14. h3 f5 $5 {Black gains space in the center and renews the attack on the g4-pawn. Both sides are likely to castle kingside soon. A sharp battle is ahead, as both kings are inadequately protected by pawns. The chances are evenly distributed.} *

