{Nxc3 Bxc3 Qa3+ The intermediate check is important, so that after the trade of bishops the queen is not attacked, as the exchange of queens would be unfavorable for Black. Ka1 After Kb1 , play would develop similarly. Bxc3+ Qxc3 Bc8 What looks like a passive defensive move simultaneously pursues aggressive intentions: it clears the way for the a-pawn! Besides advancing the a-pawn to a4, Black would like to take on e5 to inflict a pawn weakness. If White preempts this plan by exchanging on f6, Black's d-pawn is no longer backward, and the bishop can be activated with ...d7-d5 and ...Bd7. Another possibility to open prospects for the bishop is ...c6-c5 followed by ...Bb7. The position is dynamically equal. An interesting middlegame lies ahead, as seen in the recent game Shirov-Nisipeanu [/variation/36055961], Budva 2023 (½-½).} 1. e4 c5 {The Sicilian Opening stands for a sharp fight. Black somewhat neglects their piece development in order to prevent White from establishing a full pawn center with d2-d4.} 2. Nf3 e6 ({The third most common move after} 2... d6 {and}) (2... Nc6 {. With this, Black primarily prepares the development of the dark-squared bishop, but the center push ...d7-d5 becomes a possibility as well.}) (2... Nc6 {is an alternative way to reach the Four Knights Sicilian:} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6 {and we have landed in our repertoire via transposition. I decided against this path because White has a very serious and popular alternative in 3.Bb5 , the Rossolimo Variation. With 2...e6 the Rossolimo Variation is avoided.}) 3. d4 {The Open Sicilian and the starting position of this course. I examine alternatives for White on the second and third moves in a separate course on the Anti-Sicilians. The Open Sicilian is White's most principled attempt to fight for the opening advantage. White has more space and wants to open up the position, relying on rapid piece development. In return, Black gets the semi-open c-file, which can often be used for counterplay later on. Moreover, the exchange of the d-pawn for the c-pawn is a minor positional concession, as White now has only one pawn in the center and therefore can no longer fight quite as well for the important central squares.} cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 ({A very logical move - the knight is developed and simultaneously attacks the e4 pawn. Black takes advantage of the fact that the knight cannot be directly attacked with e4-e5 .} 4... Nc6 {is also possible, but gives White the additional option} 5. Nb5 {.}) 5. Nc3 ({Develops the knight and reinforces White's influence on the central square d5. Moreover, the diagonal a5-e1 is now interrupted, so that e4-e5 becomes a strong threat.} 5. e5 $2 {allows the double attack} Qa5+ {followed by -- Qxe5 .}) 5... Nc6 {Another natural developing move that continues the fight for the central squares. Black, at least temporarily, is preventing e4-e5 and threatening ...Bb4 with pressure on the white center. The starting position of the Sicilian Four Knights has now been reached. This method of play was first used in the second half of the 19th century. Early adopters included the masters Schiffers, Blackburne, Mieses, and Janowski. White now has a multitude of options.} 6. Nxc6 ({This initiates one of the sharpest and most complex variations in the Sicilian Four Knights. We will see very unusual positions that are unfamiliar from any other opening. 6.Nxc6 is the second most common move after 6.Ndb5. It is chosen primarily by players who are not comfortable transitioning into the Sveshnikov Variation after} 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bf4 e5 8. Bg5 {.}) 6... bxc6 ({Black would now like to play ...d7-d5 and would then have a solid position with good central control.} 6... dxc6 {leads to a queenless middlegame that is slightly better for White.} 7. Qxd8+ Kxd8 8. Bf4 $14 {. The main problem in Black's position is the passive bishop on c8.}) 7. e5 {The critical move. White prevents ...d7-d5 – the d7 pawn is now backward. In addition, White prepares to put pressure on the weakened d6-square. A third advantage from White's perspective is that a defender of the kingside is driven away, making future attacks there more promising. Of course, the pawn move also has its drawbacks. We will see in the following variations that the pawn on e5 itself becomes a target of Black's counterplay. White will have to accept weaknesses in their own camp to defend the exposed pawn. Alternatives to 7.e5 are discussed in the following chapter [/course/199209/7].} Nd5 8. Ne4 ({White avoids exchanging knights and targets the weakened d6-square. A subsequent c2-c4 could drive the black knight away from its central position and also give the white queen access to d6. The main problem for Black is the bishop on c8, which is blocked by Black's own pawns and cannot be activated easily. In this tabiya, Black has tried a variety of options, some of which have established their place in opening theory.} 8. Nxd5 cxd5 {is examined in chapter 5 [/course/199209/7].}) 8... Qc7 ({The main move. Black attacks the e5-pawn and forces a weakening of White's position. The alternative} 8... Bb7 {is also popular nowadays. Black wants to play ...c6-c5 and quickly solve the problem of the 'bad' light-squared bishop.}) 9. f4 {The queen has fulfilled its purpose on c7 and moves to a better square. On b6, the queen performs a number of functions:  * It controls the weakened a7-g1 diagonal.  * It threatens the double attack 10...Qb4+.  * It attacks the b2-pawn, complicating the development of the c1-bishop.  * It supports ...Ne3.  * It supports the attempt to exchange the light-squared bishops with ...Ba6. c4 Qd3 Obviously the best square for the queen, as it also needs to protect c2.} {I pondered for a long time whether to recommend the knight move or the main line Bb4+ . The latter is discussed at the highest level and, from a theoretical standpoint, Black is in good shape. On the other hand, after Ne3 , White achieves a slightly better position with best play from both sides. Still, I decided on 10...Ne3. The downside of 10...Bb4+ is that the theory is quite far advanced and leads to very complicated positions where one misstep can be fatal. In my opinion, 10...Ne3 is easier to play because the variations resulting from it are more straightforward.} Bb4+ {With this check, Black gains some time. Not only because the bishop is developed with a tempo, but also because after the main move 12.Bd2, the knight on e3 is no longer attacked.} 10. Bd2 Ba6 ({The bishop on d2 is pinned, so Black can leave the knight on e3 for now. ➤} 10... Ba6 {attacks the c4 pawn and forces White to make a decision: defend the pawn or engage in the complications after} 11. Bxb4 {.}) ({➤ The more frequently played} 10... O-O {is less appealing to me because after} 11. Rc1 {(with the threat of c4-c5) Black cannot avoid exchanges and risks being left with a passive light-squared bishop against a strong knight.}) 11. b3 {White's most common choice: The c4-pawn is defended and the b-pawn is now on a protected square.} O-O $14 12. Nc3 $5 {By retreating the knight, White breaks the pin on the bishop on d2 and thus drives away the knight from its active post on e3. Subsequently, White can castle queenside, thus moving the king to a somewhat safer position. In practice, 14.Nc3 has been rarely played so far, but this is likely to change soon. The move is a favorite of Stockfish, and Black must play accurately to avoid ending up in a slightly inferior position. Nd5} ({Black also opts for a knight retreat, thus maintaining the tension in the position. The alternatives are worse: In Friedel-Sammour Hasbun [/variation/36055959], Connecticut 2003 (½-½) there followed Ng4?} 12. Qf3 f5 {and now White could have, instead of the mysterious Ke2? d5-+ , gotten an advantage with 16.h3 or 16.Rd1. After}) ({Nxf1 Rxf1 it is difficult for Black to activate the light-squared bishop and exchange the backward d-pawn. O-O-O! White loses no time and brings the king to safety. The move comes with a pawn sacrifice, which should not be accepted. A slow move like} 12. g3 {does not pose any problems, e.g.} Nc3 13. Bxc3 Bb7 {O-O-O c5= . Black has succeeded in activating the light-squared bishop and can play for an attack on the queenside with ...a7-a5-a4 next.  15.Na4 is a tactical mistake, allowing Black to win a pawn with 15...Nxf4! 16.Nxb6 Nxd3+ 17.Bxd3 Bxd2+ 18.Kxd2 axb6 .}) 12... Qa5 ({Attacks the knight and avoids the positional threat of Na4. Instead, winning a pawn with} 12... Bxc3 $2 13. Bxc3 Nxf4 {is bad, as White gets full control over the dark squares and a strong kingside attack after} 14. Qd2 Ng6 15. h4 {. Another mistake would be the exchange 15...Nxc3 16.Bxc3 . The pawn on d7 is weak and the kingside is insufficiently guarded. White will soon attack h7 with queen and bishop.}) ({Kb2 The pawn on e5 prevents the pawn on d7 from moving, therefore Black wants to exchange it. In Krassowizkij-Dauner [/variation/36055960], Ostfildern 2023 (½-½),} 12... Rab8 $2 {followed, but now} 13. Ne4 $16 {would have given White a firm grip on the dark squares. However, 16...Rad8 is a viable alternative, preemptively protecting the d-pawn. 17.Ne4 can now be answered with 17...Bxd2 18.Qxd2 Qxd2+ 19.Rxd2 Nxf4 .}) ({Qh3 Stepping out of the pin and thus attacking the knight on d5. It matters little which square White chooses for the queen - it will shortly end up on c3 anyway. Instead, exf6} 12... Nf6 {followed by ...d7-d5 is comfortable for Black, while 17.Ne4 is playable, but after 17...fxe5 18.fxe5 Black gets good counterplay due to the weakness of the e5-pawn. A possible continuation is 18...Bxd2 19.Qxd2 Nb4 20.a3 Qxe5+ 21.Qd4 Qxd4+ 22.Rxd4 Nd5! .}) *

