as tried a variety of options, some of which have established their place in opening theory.} 8. Nxd5 cxd5 {is examined in chapter 5 [/course/199209/7].}) 8... Qc7 ({The main move. Black attacks the e5-pawn and forces a weakening of White's position. The alternative} 8... Bb7 {is also popular nowadays. Black wants to play ...c6-c5 and quickly solve the problem of the 'bad' light-squared bishop.}) 9. f4 {The queen has fulfilled its purpose on c7 and moves to a better square. On b6, the queen performs a number of functions:  * It controls the weakened a7-g1 diagonal.  * It threatens the double attack 10...Qb4+.  * It attacks the b2-pawn, complicating the development of the c1-bishop.  * It supports ...Ne3.  * It supports the attempt to exchange the light-squared bishops with ...Ba6. c4 Qd3 Obviously the best square for the queen, as it also needs to protect c2.} {I pondered for a long time whether to recommend the knight move or the main line Bb4+ . The latter is discussed at the highest level and, from a theoretical standpoint, Black is in good shape. On the other hand, after Ne3 , White achieves a slightly better position with best play from both sides. Still, I decided on 10...Ne3. The downside of 10...Bb4+ is that the theory is quite far advanced and leads to very complicated positions where one misstep can be fatal. In my opinion, 10...Ne3 is easier to play because the variations resulting from it are more straightforward.} Bb4+ {With this check, Black gains some time. Not only because the bishop is developed with a tempo, but also because after the main move 12.Bd2, the knight on e3 is no longer attacked.} 10. Bd2 Ba6 ({The bishop on d2 is pinned, so Black can leave the knight on e3 for now. ➤} 10... Ba6 {attacks the c4 pawn and forces White to make a decision: defend the pawn or engage in the complications after} 11. Bxb4 {.}) ({➤ The more frequently played} 10... O-O {is less appealing to me because after} 11. Rc1 {(with the threat of c4-c5) Black cannot avoid exchanges and risks being left with a passive light-squared bishop against a strong knight.}) 11. b3 {White's most common choice: The c4-pawn is defended and the b-pawn is now on a protected square.} O-O $15 {Black finally has time for getting the king out of the center.} 12. Bxb4 {Qxb4+ Kf2 Nd5! Qf3? A tactically weak move. In the game Sieber–Lubbe [/variation/31423366/#/16/w], the German national player impressively showed why.} {There are hardly any other productive moves for White. Ke2?! has been played a few times, but it's not surprising that the king isn't placed well here. After Nd5 , Black wants to open the position with ...d7-d6 or ...f7-f5/...f7-f6 and attack the centralized king. Defense will be difficult for White. Attacks the f4-pawn and supports ...f7-f6 as well as ...f7-f5. Nxf1? Rhxf1+- is the nightmare scenario for Black. The bishop is out of play, and the queen is sidelined. White will either conduct an attack on the kingside or win through dominance over the black squares on the queenside.} f5 $1 {Nothing new so far. The knight on d5 is attacked, so Black cannot delay the counterattack.} 13. Nd6 (13. exf6 $2 {is weaker because of} Nxf6 $17 {. White's king is very vulnerable. Black has a variety of ideas, such as ...e6-e5, ...d7-d5 or ...Bb7 and ...c6-c5.}) 13... g5 $1 ({Qd2+? Kg3! accomplishes nothing.} 13... g5 {is a very strong move that exploits the concrete circumstances of the position. In fact, Black is already worse after other moves! The main point of 17...g5 is that the white king cannot hide on g3. White should probably give up the f4-pawn now and defend a worse position. Let's consider some variations:}) 14. h4 ({Perhaps the best choice. Alternatives A) The game continuation Rd1? poses no great challenge: First, the king is forced to a worse square with Qc5+! Kg3 Nxf4-+ Sieber–Lubbe [/variation/31423366/#/19/b], Magdeburg 2021 (0-1). 19...gxf4+ would have led to a winning position as well. B) White cannot maintain the structure with} 14. g3 $2 {because of Qd2+} Be2 15. Qd4 {Kg2} Ne3 {. White must walk into a discovered check now, as Kh3} 16. g4 {loses even faster.}) ({C)} 14. fxg5 $2 {Qd2+ and now... C.1)} Be2 $2 15. Qd4 {. The king cannot move to the back rank because the rook on a1 is hanging. After Kg3 Qxe5+ , the attack continues, and the knight on d6 is no longer defended. Black is winning. C.2) 19.Kg3 Qxg5+ 20.Kf2 Qd2+ 21.Kg3 Kh8 $17 with a mating attack.}) ({D) cxd5!?} 14. Qd4 $17 {and Black wins material. Qe3 Qxa1 Bxa6! , the best chance, Qxh1 . Possibly White has practical chances here because the black king is quite exposed. Objectively, however, Black has the advantage.}) 14... gxf4 $15 {Kg1 At least the king is safe now. Qc5+ Kh2 Ne3 Qxf4 Ng4+ Kg3 Qxe5 Black is a healthy pawn up.} *

