as tried a variety of options, some of which have established their place in opening theory.} 8. Nxd5 cxd5 {is examined in chapter 5 [/course/199209/7].}) 8... Qc7 ({The main move. Black attacks the e5-pawn and forces a weakening of White's position. The alternative} 8... Bb7 {is also popular nowadays. Black wants to play ...c6-c5 and quickly solve the problem of the 'bad' light-squared bishop.}) 9. f4 {The queen has fulfilled its purpose on c7 and moves to a better square. On b6, the queen performs a number of functions:  * It controls the weakened a7-g1 diagonal.  * It threatens the double attack 10...Qb4+.  * It attacks the b2-pawn, complicating the development of the c1-bishop.  * It supports ...Ne3.  * It supports the attempt to exchange the light-squared bishops with ...Ba6. c4 Qd3 Obviously the best square for the queen, as it also needs to protect c2.} {I pondered for a long time whether to recommend the knight move or the main line Bb4+ . The latter is discussed at the highest level and, from a theoretical standpoint, Black is in good shape. On the other hand, after Ne3 , White achieves a slightly better position with best play from both sides. Still, I decided on 10...Ne3. The downside of 10...Bb4+ is that the theory is quite far advanced and leads to very complicated positions where one misstep can be fatal. In my opinion, 10...Ne3 is easier to play because the variations resulting from it are more straightforward.} Bb4+ {With this check, Black gains some time. Not only because the bishop is developed with a tempo, but also because after the main move 12.Bd2, the knight on e3 is no longer attacked.} 10. Bd2 Ba6 ({The bishop on d2 is pinned, so Black can leave the knight on e3 for now. ➤} 10... Ba6 {attacks the c4 pawn and forces White to make a decision: defend the pawn or engage in the complications after} 11. Bxb4 {.}) ({➤ The more frequently played} 10... O-O {is less appealing to me because after} 11. Rc1 {(with the threat of c4-c5) Black cannot avoid exchanges and risks being left with a passive light-squared bishop against a strong knight.}) 11. b3 {White's most common choice: The c4-pawn is defended and the b-pawn is now on a protected square.} O-O $15 {Black finally has time for getting the king out of the center.} 12. Bxb4 {Qxb4+ Kf2 Nd5! g3 Kf3} {There are hardly any other productive moves for White. Ke2?! has been played a few times, but it's not surprising that the king isn't placed well here. After Nd5 , Black wants to open the position with ...d7-d6 or ...f7-f5/...f7-f6 and attack the centralized king. Defense will be difficult for White. Attacks the f4-pawn and supports ...f7-f6 as well as ...f7-f5. Nxf1? Rhxf1+- is the nightmare scenario for Black. The bishop is out of play, and the queen is sidelined. White will either conduct an attack on the kingside or win through dominance over the black squares on the queenside. An important intermediate check that brings the queen to a protected square. After the immediate f6 , White has the resource Qd2 . A queen exchange is not in Black's interest, but on the other hand, the knight on d5 is now under attack. In some games, Black therefore tried the piece sacrifice 17...fxe5 18.cxd5 Qxe4 19.Bxa6 exf4 , but with 20.Rhf1! , White is able to cover the infiltration squares on the f-file. After 20...fxg3+ 21.Kxg3 , White has slightly better chances. Compared to Kg2 , the king is less safe on f3, but it has the advantage that Black cannot play ...Ne3+ later on.} f6 {, Black played c5 . Qd2 c5 With the exposed king, White cannot afford to accept the piece sacrifice. After cxd5? cxd5 , the black pawn mass in the center is very strong and White's king comes under attack, for example: A} 13. Nf2 Bb7 $15 {Re1 e4+ Kg2 e5 leading to a winning position for Black. B Also 20.Nc5!? to prevent ...Bb7 does not help. Black plays 20...Bxf1 , and now: B.1 21.Nxd7 e4+ 22.Kg4 Qd8 23.Nxf8 h5+! 24.Kxh5 Qxf8 with imminent checkmate. B.2 After 21.Na4 e4+ 22.Kg4 h5+! 23.Kxh5 Qb5! 24.Rhxf1 e3! Black is winning due to the mobile central pawns in combination with the exposed position of White's king. Qb7 Nd6 At first glance, it seems as if White can win the bishop on a6. Qb4! With this resource, Black saves the bishop, which will be protected by the knight. Qxb4 Nxb4 a3 Nd3 Bxf1 is possible as well. Bxd3 Bxd3 We have followed the correspondence game Soberano–Soltau [/variation/31423368/#/23/b], 2008. Black has an extra pawn and slightly better chances.} *

