hedlishvili–Abdusattorov [/variation/31423369/#/19/w], Tashkent 2021 (½-½) and here} d5 15. Nxf6+ Rxf6 {would have been stronger.}) 13. Be2 ({This seems to me the most logical. The bishop can go to f3 and defend the long diagonal. Kf2 is one of the engine's suggestions, but since White just played Kf2-g2, it's probably not a very likely choice by a human opponent. Regardless, Black doesn't have any problems after f6 exf6} 13. Nf6+ Nxf6 {Rxf6= .}) 13... Nxb4 {Qc3} ({This is the best square for the queen because from here it protects the f3-square – and thus soon the white bishop. Here too, Qxd7? is not a good idea due to the open king position. Black wins an exchange with Nc2 , because Rac1? Nd4 followed by ...Rad8 and ...Bb7 only makes matters worse. After Qd2 , the game proceeds similarly to 19.Qc3, but it's a slightly better version for Black. d5 exd6} 13... Bb7 14. Bf3 {Nc6 . Now ...Nd4 is threatening, and the white queen should go back to the third rank to cover the bishop on f3.}) {d5! Black gets rid of the weak d-pawn. The pawn can be regained later. If Black plays Nc6 directly, then White has the resource Nd6 . Of course, this is no longer possible if a white pawn occupies that square. exd6 Nc6 The knight is on its way to d4. Paired with the moves ...Bb7 and ...f7-f5, this is a strong threat. White should initiate energetic countermeasures. Rhd1 Increases control over d4. Nd4} 14. Nc5 $1 {Qe5 The knight on e2 is trapped. 23.Qe3? Rac8 24.b4 Bxc4 $17 . Nc3 White cannot yet capture the knight, as this would give up the defense of the c5-knight. Re1!} {The analysis of 24.Rdc1 shows that the rook is needed on the e-file: After Rdc1? , f6! is very strong. The queen is distracted from defending the c5-knight. 25.Qxe6+ Kh8 26.Nxa6 ( 26.Rxc3 Qxc5 is better, but White still has big problems due to their unsafe king position and should still lose.) 26...Rae8 Black switches to a mating attack. If White had played 24.Re1, this move would not be possible due to Qxe8. 27.Qg4 Re2+ 28.Kh3 f5 and White must give up the queen to avoid being checkmated.} Bb7 ({Now,} 14... f6 $2 {doesn't work because of Qxe6+ Kh8} 15. Nxa6 Qxa6 $16 {Qe3 . White wins the knight and keeps at least one extra pawn.}) {Kh3?} 15. f5 $17 {This is threatening both ...Rf6 with a mating attack and provides the knight an escape square on e4. The position remains complicated, but Black has the advantage.} *

