1. e4 c5 {The Sicilian Opening stands for a sharp fight. Black somewhat neglects their piece development in order to prevent White from establishing a full pawn center with d2-d4.} 2. Nf3 e6 ({The third most common move after} 2... d6 {and}) (2... Nc6 {. With this, Black primarily prepares the development of the dark-squared bishop, but the center push ...d7-d5 becomes a possibility as well.}) (2... Nc6 {is an alternative way to reach the Four Knights Sicilian:} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6 {and we have landed in our repertoire via transposition. I decided against this path because White has a very serious and popular alternative in 3.Bb5 , the Rossolimo Variation. With 2...e6 the Rossolimo Variation is avoided.}) 3. d4 {The Open Sicilian and the starting position of this course. I examine alternatives for White on the second and third moves in a separate course on the Anti-Sicilians. The Open Sicilian is White's most principled attempt to fight for the opening advantage. White has more space and wants to open up the position, relying on rapid piece development. In return, Black gets the semi-open c-file, which can often be used for counterplay later on. Moreover, the exchange of the d-pawn for the c-pawn is a minor positional concession, as White now has only one pawn in the center and therefore can no longer fight quite as well for the important central squares.} cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 ({A very logical move - the knight is developed and simultaneously attacks the e4 pawn. Black takes advantage of the fact that the knight cannot be directly attacked with e4-e5 .} 4... Nc6 {is also possible, but gives White the additional option} 5. Nb5 {.}) 5. Nc3 ({Develops the knight and reinforces White's influence on the central square d5. Moreover, the diagonal a5-e1 is now interrupted, so that e4-e5 becomes a strong threat.} 5. e5 $2 {allows the double attack} Qa5+ {followed by -- Qxe5 .}) 5... Nc6 {Another natural developing move that continues the fight for the central squares. Black, at least temporarily, is preventing e4-e5 and threatening ...Bb4 with pressure on the white center. The starting position of the Sicilian Four Knights has now been reached. This method of play was first used in the second half of the 19th century. Early adopters included the masters Schiffers, Blackburne, Mieses, and Janowski. White now has a multitude of options.} 6. Nxc6 ({This initiates one of the sharpest and most complex variations in the Sicilian Four Knights. We will see very unusual positions that are unfamiliar from any other opening. 6.Nxc6 is the second most common move after 6.Ndb5. It is chosen primarily by players who are not comfortable transitioning into the Sveshnikov Variation after} 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bf4 e5 8. Bg5 {.}) 6... bxc6 ({Black would now like to play ...d7-d5 and would then have a solid position with good central control.} 6... dxc6 {leads to a queenless middlegame that is slightly better for White.} 7. Qxd8+ Kxd8 8. Bf4 $14 {. The main problem in Black's position is the passive bishop on c8.}) 7. e5 {The critical move. White prevents ...d7-d5 – the d7 pawn is now backward. In addition, White prepares to put pressure on the weakened d6-square. A third advantage from White's perspective is that a defender of the kingside is driven away, making future attacks there more promising. Of course, the pawn move also has its drawbacks. We will see in the following variations that the pawn on e5 itself becomes a target of Black's counterplay. White will have to accept weaknesses in their own camp to defend the exposed pawn. Alternatives to 7.e5 are discussed in the following chapter [/course/199209/7].} Nd5 8. Ne4 ({White avoids exchanging knights and targets the weakened d6-square. A subsequent c2-c4 could drive the black knight away from its central position and also give the white queen access to d6. The main problem for Black is the bishop on c8, which is blocked by Black's own pawns and cannot be activated easily. In this tabiya, Black has tried a variety of options, some of which have established their place in opening theory.} 8. Nxd5 cxd5 {is examined in chapter 5 [/course/199209/7].}) 8... Qc7 ({The main move. Black attacks the e5-pawn and forces a weakening of White's position. The alternative} 8... Bb7 {is also popular nowadays. Black wants to play ...c6-c5 and quickly solve the problem of the 'bad' light-squared bishop.}) 9. f4 {The queen has fulfilled its purpose on c7 and moves to a better square. On b6, the queen performs a number of functions:  * It controls the weakened a7-g1 diagonal.  * It threatens the double attack 10...Qb4+.  * It attacks the b2-pawn, complicating the development of the c1-bishop.  * It supports ...Ne3.  * It supports the attempt to exchange the light-squared bishops with ...Ba6. c4 Qd3 Obviously the best square for the queen, as it also needs to protect c2.} {I pondered for a long time whether to recommend the knight move or the main line Bb4+ . The latter is discussed at the highest level and, from a theoretical standpoint, Black is in good shape. On the other hand, after Ne3 , White achieves a slightly better position with best play from both sides. Still, I decided on 10...Ne3. The downside of 10...Bb4+ is that the theory is quite far advanced and leads to very complicated positions where one misstep can be fatal. In my opinion, 10...Ne3 is easier to play because the variations resulting from it are more straightforward.} Bb4+ {With this check, Black gains some time. Not only because the bishop is developed with a tempo, but also because after the main move 12.Bd2, the knight on e3 is no longer attacked.} 10. Bd2 Ba6 ({The bishop on d2 is pinned, so Black can leave the knight on e3 for now. ➤} 10... Ba6 {attacks the c4 pawn and forces White to make a decision: defend the pawn or engage in the complications after} 11. Bxb4 {.}) ({➤ The more frequently played} 10... O-O {is less appealing to me because after} 11. Rc1 {(with the threat of c4-c5) Black cannot avoid exchanges and risks being left with a passive light-squared bishop against a strong knight.}) 11. b3 {White's most common choice: The c4-pawn is defended and the b-pawn is now on a protected square.} O-O $15 {Black finally has time for getting the king out of the center.} 12. Bxb4 {Qxb4+ Kf2 Nd5! g3} {There are hardly any other productive moves for White. Ke2?! has been played a few times, but it's not surprising that the king isn't placed well here. After Nd5 , Black wants to open the position with ...d7-d6 or ...f7-f5/...f7-f6 and attack the centralized king. Defense will be difficult for White. Attacks the f4-pawn and supports ...f7-f6 as well as ...f7-f5. Nxf1? Rhxf1+- is the nightmare scenario for Black. The bishop is out of play, and the queen is sidelined. White will either conduct an attack on the kingside or win through dominance over the black squares on the queenside.} Qb6 ({An important intermediate check that brings the queen to a protected square. After the immediate} 12... f6 {, White has the resource} 13. Qd2 {. A queen exchange is not in Black's interest, but on the other hand, the knight on d5 is now under attack. In some games, Black therefore tried the piece sacrifice 17...fxe5 18.cxd5 Qxe4 19.Bxa6 exf4 , but with 20.Rhf1! , White is able to cover the infiltration squares on the f-file. After 20...fxg3+ 21.Kxg3 , White has slightly better chances.}) ({Kg2 c5!? A novelty. Black can also play the standard pawn break ...f7-f6 and has no worries. However, I believe that 17...c5 offers better winning chances because the position is not so easy to play for White. With} 12... c5 {, Black opens up the long diagonal for the bishop, which then aims towards the white king. The pawn break ...f7-f6 remains an option, but not the only one, as we will see: The d-pawn can also be used as a lever. The knight could land on d4 via b4 and c6, where it is placed very well and is secured by the c-pawn.}) (12... f6 13. exf6 Nxf6 {(18...gxf6)} 14. Be2 {was played in Mchedlishvili–Abdusattorov [/variation/31423369/#/19/w], Tashkent 2021 (½-½) and here} d5 15. Nxf6+ Rxf6 {would have been stronger.}) 13. Be2 ({This seems to me the most logical. The bishop can go to f3 and defend the long diagonal. Kf2 is one of the engine's suggestions, but since White just played Kf2-g2, it's probably not a very likely choice by a human opponent. Regardless, Black doesn't have any problems after f6 exf6} 13. Nf6+ Nxf6 {Rxf6= .}) 13... Nxb4 {Qc3} ({This is the best square for the queen because from here it protects the f3-square – and thus soon the white bishop. Here too, Qxd7? is not a good idea due to the open king position. Black wins an exchange with Nc2 , because Rac1? Nd4 followed by ...Rad8 and ...Bb7 only makes matters worse. After Qd2 , the game proceeds similarly to 19.Qc3, but it's a slightly better version for Black. d5 exd6} 13... Bb7 14. Bf3 {Nc6 . Now ...Nd4 is threatening, and the white queen should go back to the third rank to cover the bishop on f3.}) {d5! Black gets rid of the weak d-pawn. The pawn can be regained later. If Black plays Nc6 directly, then White has the resource Nd6 . Of course, this is no longer possible if a white pawn occupies that square. exd6 Nc6 The knight is on its way to d4. Paired with the moves ...Bb7 and ...f7-f5, this is a strong threat. White should initiate energetic countermeasures. Rhd1 Increases control over d4. Nd4} 14. Nc5 $1 {Qe5 The knight on e2 is trapped. 23.Qe3? Rac8 24.b4 Bxc4 $17 . Nc3 White cannot yet capture the knight, as this would give up the defense of the c5-knight. Re1!} {The analysis of 24.Rdc1 shows that the rook is needed on the e-file: After Rdc1? , f6! is very strong. The queen is distracted from defending the c5-knight. 25.Qxe6+ Kh8 26.Nxa6 ( 26.Rxc3 Qxc5 is better, but White still has big problems due to their unsafe king position and should still lose.) 26...Rae8 Black switches to a mating attack. If White had played 24.Re1, this move would not be possible due to Qxe8. 27.Qg4 Re2+ 28.Kh3 f5 and White must give up the queen to avoid being checkmated.} Bb7 ({Now,} 14... f6 $2 {doesn't work because of Qxe6+ Kh8} 15. Nxa6 Qxa6 $16 {Qe3 . White wins the knight and keeps at least one extra pawn.}) 15. Nxb7 ({The refutation of} 15. Kf1 $2 {is almost study-like. Bh1!!-+ . Next, ...Qc6 follows with decisive threats.}) 15... Qxb7 {Kg1 Nxa2 The extra piece could no longer be maintained, so it is now time to collect pawns. Rxa2 Qxb3 Rd2 Qxc4 Black is even a pawn up now. At the same time, Black's winning prospects are small, as White's passed pawn commits the black rooks to defensive tasks. The game should end in a draw.} *

