hedlishvili–Abdusattorov [/variation/31423369/#/19/w], Tashkent 2021 (½-½) and here} d5 15. Nxf6+ Rxf6 {would have been stronger.}) 13. Be2 ({This seems to me the most logical. The bishop can go to f3 and defend the long diagonal. Kf2 is one of the engine's suggestions, but since White just played Kf2-g2, it's probably not a very likely choice by a human opponent. Regardless, Black doesn't have any problems after f6 exf6} 13. Nf6+ Nxf6 {Rxf6= .}) 13... Nxb4 {Qc3} ({This is the best square for the queen because from here it protects the f3-square – and thus soon the white bishop. Here too, Qxd7? is not a good idea due to the open king position. Black wins an exchange with Nc2 , because Rac1? Nd4 followed by ...Rad8 and ...Bb7 only makes matters worse. After Qd2 , the game proceeds similarly to 19.Qc3, but it's a slightly better version for Black. d5 exd6} 13... Bb7 14. Bf3 {Nc6 . Now ...Nd4 is threatening, and the white queen should go back to the third rank to cover the bishop on f3.}) ({d5! Black gets rid of the weak d-pawn. The pawn can be regained later. If Black plays Nc6 directly, then White has the resource Nd6 . Of course, this is no longer possible if a white pawn occupies that square. exd6 Nc6 The knight is on its way to d4. Paired with the moves ...Bb7 and ...f7-f5, this is a strong threat. White should initiate energetic countermeasures. b4!? White wants to weaken Black's control over d4, leading to forced play. After the natural Bf3?! Nd4 , White is already in trouble. Next, Black plays ...Bb7 (or exchanges on f3 first) and exerts strong pressure along the long diagonal. Nd4! cxb4? Qd2 followed by c4-c5 is better for White. Black can no longer establish the knight on d4.} 13... Nxb4 $2 {is also a mistake as it opens the b-file.} 14. Bf3 Bb7 15. a3 {and Nc6? doesn't work because of 24.Rab1+- .}) 14. Nc5 $1 ({A temporary sacrifice. Black cannot keep the extra piece. bxc5? Nxe2 cxb6} 14. Nc3 {Nxc3} Bb7 $17 {and White loses an exchange.}) {Nxe2 Qd3 The knight on e2 is trapped.} 14... Bb7 {Seizes the opportunity to exchange the strong knight.} 15. Nxb7 Qxb7 16. Kf2 {Nxf4 After that, material balance will be restored. gxf4 Qxb4 At the end of this long and forced variation, a sharp but equal major piece endgame has arisen. The white connected passed pawns would be quite dangerous in a pure rook endgame. However, with the queens on the board, they are well under control. The exposed position of the white king gives Black good counterplay.} *

