s. Black, at least temporarily, is preventing e4-e5 and threatening ...Bb4 with pressure on the white center. The starting position of the Sicilian Four Knights has now been reached. This method of play was first used in the second half of the 19th century. Early adopters included the masters Schiffers, Blackburne, Mieses, and Janowski. White now has a multitude of options.} 6. Nxc6 ({This initiates one of the sharpest and most complex variations in the Sicilian Four Knights. We will see very unusual positions that are unfamiliar from any other opening. 6.Nxc6 is the second most common move after 6.Ndb5. It is chosen primarily by players who are not comfortable transitioning into the Sveshnikov Variation after} 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bf4 e5 8. Bg5 {.}) 6... bxc6 ({Black would now like to play ...d7-d5 and would then have a solid position with good central control.} 6... dxc6 {leads to a queenless middlegame that is slightly better for White.} 7. Qxd8+ Kxd8 8. Bf4 $14 {. The main problem in Black's position is the passive bishop on c8.}) 7. e5 {The critical move. White prevents ...d7-d5 – the d7 pawn is now backward. In addition, White prepares to put pressure on the weakened d6-square. A third advantage from White's perspective is that a defender of the kingside is driven away, making future attacks there more promising. Of course, the pawn move also has its drawbacks. We will see in the following variations that the pawn on e5 itself becomes a target of Black's counterplay. White will have to accept weaknesses in their own camp to defend the exposed pawn. Alternatives to 7.e5 are discussed in the following chapter [/course/199209/7].} Nd5 8. Ne4 ({White avoids exchanging knights and targets the weakened d6-square. A subsequent c2-c4 could drive the black knight away from its central position and also give the white queen access to d6. The main problem for Black is the bishop on c8, which is blocked by Black's own pawns and cannot be activated easily. In this tabiya, Black has tried a variety of options, some of which have established their place in opening theory.} 8. Nxd5 cxd5 {is examined in chapter 5 [/course/199209/7].}) 8... Qc7 ({The main move. Black attacks the e5-pawn and forces a weakening of White's position. The alternative} 8... Bb7 {is also popular nowadays. Black wants to play ...c6-c5 and quickly solve the problem of the 'bad' light-squared bishop.}) 9. f4 {The queen has fulfilled its purpose on c7 and moves to a better square. On b6, the queen performs a number of functions:  * It controls the weakened a7-g1 diagonal.  * It threatens the double attack 10...Qb4+.  * It attacks the b2-pawn, complicating the development of the c1-bishop.  * It supports ...Ne3.  * It supports the attempt to exchange the light-squared bishops with ...Ba6. c4 Qd3 Obviously the best square for the queen, as it also needs to protect c2.} {I pondered for a long time whether to recommend the knight move or the main line Bb4+ . The latter is discussed at the highest level and, from a theoretical standpoint, Black is in good shape. On the other hand, after Ne3 , White achieves a slightly better position with best play from both sides. Still, I decided on 10...Ne3. The downside of 10...Bb4+ is that the theory is quite far advanced and leads to very complicated positions where one misstep can be fatal. In my opinion, 10...Ne3 is easier to play because the variations resulting from it are more straightforward.} Bb4+ {With this check, Black gains some time. Not only because the bishop is developed with a tempo, but also because after the main move 12.Bd2, the knight on e3 is no longer attacked.} 10. Bd2 Ba6 ({The bishop on d2 is pinned, so Black can leave the knight on e3 for now. ➤} 10... Ba6 {attacks the c4 pawn and forces White to make a decision: defend the pawn or engage in the complications after} 11. Bxb4 {.}) ({➤ The more frequently played} 10... O-O {is less appealing to me because after} 11. Rc1 {(with the threat of c4-c5) Black cannot avoid exchanges and risks being left with a passive light-squared bishop against a strong knight.}) 11. Bxb4 {With this, White demonstrates good theoretical knowledge. White initiates a forced sequence, at the end of which there is an unusual material balance. Qxb4+ Kf2 Qxb2+!} ({Black should engage in the complications. Nxc4? is a tactical mistake. After Qb3 , Black loses a piece, for example Rb8} 11. Bc4 Bxc4 {Qxc4! Qxc4} 12. Nd6+ {.}) {Nf5?! Qc3!? Qxc3 bxc3 . The problem child of the black position is the bishop on a6. I don’t see how it can be activated. White has the advantage. Kxe3 This exchange sacrifice has been tested only once but looks like a logical attempt. Qxa1 Qa3 The black king is prevented from castling and White can continue with Nd6+. Additionally, the bishop on a6 is under attack. Upon closer examination, however, it becomes evident that White's threats only suffice for a perpetual. White's king is also not secure, and both the rook and bishop are not involved in the attack.} 11... c5 $5 {Qxc5? Qe1+ Kd3} ({An ambitious move. Black wants to castle. If White prevents this with 17.Qxc5, the bishop on a6 is no longer attacked. After the alternative Qe1+ , Kf3 should follow and it is likely that one of the sides will soon give a perpetual. 17.Be2?? was played in Midoux–Sulava [/variation/36062685/#/17/w], Calvi 2006 (0-1) probably hoping for a perpetual check. However, Black can avoid this: 17...Qxh1 18.Nd6+ Kd8 19.Nxf7+ Ke8 20.Nxh8 (After 20.Nd6 Kf8! , White has no dangerous discovered attack.) 20...Bb7-+ . Black already has a material advantage, and the knight on h8 is trapped. Kf3?} 11... Bb7 {. This pin is deadly.}) {Rb8 Now, ...Rb2 or ...Rb1 is threatened, after which Black would be on the offensive.} 12. Nd6+ Kd8 ({But not} 12... Kf8 $4 13. Nf5 Kg8 14. Ne7+ Kf8 15. Ng6+ Kg8 {Qf8+! Rxf8} 16. Ne7+ {.}) 13. Nxf7+ Ke8 14. Nd6+ (14. Nxh8 $2 {Rb2 leads to mate.}) 14... Kf8 $1 {A move that can be easily overlooked. If the pawn was still on f7, Black would be checkmated. However, now White doesn't have any dangerous discovered checks. Meanwhile, Black threatens to penetrate with the rook. Black has the advantage.} *

