1. e4 c5 {The Sicilian Opening stands for a sharp fight. Black somewhat neglects their piece development in order to prevent White from establishing a full pawn center with d2-d4.} 2. Nf3 e6 ({The third most common move after} 2... d6 {and}) (2... Nc6 {. With this, Black primarily prepares the development of the dark-squared bishop, but the center push ...d7-d5 becomes a possibility as well.}) (2... Nc6 {is an alternative way to reach the Four Knights Sicilian:} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6 {and we have landed in our repertoire via transposition. I decided against this path because White has a very serious and popular alternative in 3.Bb5 , the Rossolimo Variation. With 2...e6 the Rossolimo Variation is avoided.}) 3. d4 {The Open Sicilian and the starting position of this course. I examine alternatives for White on the second and third moves in a separate course on the Anti-Sicilians. The Open Sicilian is White's most principled attempt to fight for the opening advantage. White has more space and wants to open up the position, relying on rapid piece development. In return, Black gets the semi-open c-file, which can often be used for counterplay later on. Moreover, the exchange of the d-pawn for the c-pawn is a minor positional concession, as White now has only one pawn in the center and therefore can no longer fight quite as well for the important central squares.} cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 ({A very logical move - the knight is developed and simultaneously attacks the e4 pawn. Black takes advantage of the fact that the knight cannot be directly attacked with e4-e5 .} 4... Nc6 {is also possible, but gives White the additional option} 5. Nb5 {.}) 5. Nc3 ({Develops the knight and reinforces White's influence on the central square d5. Moreover, the diagonal a5-e1 is now interrupted, so that e4-e5 becomes a strong threat.} 5. e5 $2 {allows the double attack} Qa5+ {followed by -- Qxe5 .}) 5... Nc6 {Another natural developing move that continues the fight for the central squares. Black, at least temporarily, is preventing e4-e5 and threatening ...Bb4 with pressure on the white center. The starting position of the Sicilian Four Knights has now been reached. This method of play was first used in the second half of the 19th century. Early adopters included the masters Schiffers, Blackburne, Mieses, and Janowski. White now has a multitude of options.} 6. Nxc6 ({This initiates one of the sharpest and most complex variations in the Sicilian Four Knights. We will see very unusual positions that are unfamiliar from any other opening. 6.Nxc6 is the second most common move after 6.Ndb5. It is chosen primarily by players who are not comfortable transitioning into the Sveshnikov Variation after} 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bf4 e5 8. Bg5 {.}) 6... bxc6 ({Black would now like to play ...d7-d5 and would then have a solid position with good central control.} 6... dxc6 {leads to a queenless middlegame that is slightly better for White.} 7. Qxd8+ Kxd8 8. Bf4 $14 {. The main problem in Black's position is the passive bishop on c8.}) 7. e5 {The critical move. White prevents ...d7-d5 – the d7 pawn is now backward. In addition, White prepares to put pressure on the weakened d6-square. A third advantage from White's perspective is that a defender of the kingside is driven away, making future attacks there more promising. Of course, the pawn move also has its drawbacks. We will see in the following variations that the pawn on e5 itself becomes a target of Black's counterplay. White will have to accept weaknesses in their own camp to defend the exposed pawn. Alternatives to 7.e5 are discussed in the following chapter [/course/199209/7].} Nd5 8. Ne4 ({White avoids exchanging knights and targets the weakened d6-square. A subsequent c2-c4 could drive the black knight away from its central position and also give the white queen access to d6. The main problem for Black is the bishop on c8, which is blocked by Black's own pawns and cannot be activated easily. In this tabiya, Black has tried a variety of options, some of which have established their place in opening theory.} 8. Nxd5 cxd5 {is examined in chapter 5 [/course/199209/7].}) 8... Qc7 ({The main move. Black attacks the e5-pawn and forces a weakening of White's position. The alternative} 8... Bb7 {is also popular nowadays. Black wants to play ...c6-c5 and quickly solve the problem of the 'bad' light-squared bishop.}) 9. f4 {The queen has fulfilled its purpose on c7 and moves to a better square. On b6, the queen performs a number of functions:  * It controls the weakened a7-g1 diagonal.  * It threatens the double attack 10...Qb4+.  * It attacks the b2-pawn, complicating the development of the c1-bishop.  * It supports ...Ne3.  * It supports the attempt to exchange the light-squared bishops with ...Ba6. c4 Qd3 Obviously the best square for the queen, as it also needs to protect c2.} {I pondered for a long time whether to recommend the knight move or the main line Bb4+ . The latter is discussed at the highest level and, from a theoretical standpoint, Black is in good shape. On the other hand, after Ne3 , White achieves a slightly better position with best play from both sides. Still, I decided on 10...Ne3. The downside of 10...Bb4+ is that the theory is quite far advanced and leads to very complicated positions where one misstep can be fatal. In my opinion, 10...Ne3 is easier to play because the variations resulting from it are more straightforward.} Bb4+ {With this check, Black gains some time. Not only because the bishop is developed with a tempo, but also because after the main move 12.Bd2, the knight on e3 is no longer attacked.} 10. Bd2 Ba6 ({The bishop on d2 is pinned, so Black can leave the knight on e3 for now. ➤} 10... Ba6 {attacks the c4 pawn and forces White to make a decision: defend the pawn or engage in the complications after} 11. Bxb4 {.}) ({➤ The more frequently played} 10... O-O {is less appealing to me because after} 11. Rc1 {(with the threat of c4-c5) Black cannot avoid exchanges and risks being left with a passive light-squared bishop against a strong knight.}) 11. Bxb4 {With this, White demonstrates good theoretical knowledge. White initiates a forced sequence, at the end of which there is an unusual material balance. Qxb4+ Kf2 Qxb2+!} ({Black should engage in the complications. Nxc4? is a tactical mistake. After Qb3 , Black loses a piece, for example Rb8} 11. Bc4 Bxc4 {Qxc4! Qxc4} 12. Nd6+ {.}) {Nf5?! Qc3!? Qxc3 bxc3 . The problem child of the black position is the bishop on a6. I don’t see how it can be activated. White has the advantage.} 11... Be2 ({Again, Black should not shy away from the complications. After Nf5?! Rab1 Qd4+ Qxd4 Nxd4} 11... Bd3 $16 {, Black may have an extra pawn, but their position is very passive. It's not clear how the bishop on a6 can be activated and White controls the only open file.}) {Rhd1} 12. Qd4 {Nb2} ({The queen is safer here than on b2 and also protects the bishop on a6. After Ke1 or Kg3 , Black can simply play O-O , after which White cannot exploit the pin of the c4-knight and doesn’t have enough play for the two pawns. Therefore, White's response is forced. 16...O-O? looks logical because now White cannot capture on d7. But there follows 17.Rdb1! Nxe5? (relatively best is 17...Qa3 , but even here Black is in trouble after 18.Qb3 $16 with a looming win of material.) 18.Nf6! . This is the point – Black loses the queen. 18...gxf6 19.Qg3+ Ng6 20.Rxb2+- . It's best to give back some material in return for immediately escaping the unpleasant pin. Playable is also} 12. Qd4 {Rxd4 Na3!} Ba6 {Nc2 , which will likely transpose to the line after 17...Nb2.}) ({However, Black should avoid O-O?! due to} 12. Nc5 $1 $16 {. White is threatening to win material, and there is no good way to unpin.}) 12... Ba6 ({White wins two pieces for a rook. Rd2? is bad due to, among other things, Nd3! Rxd3 ( 19.Ke3 Nb4 $17 .)} 12... Bd3 13. Qb6 axb6 14. Bxd3 $17 {. This is a much better version for Black of the same material balance than what we will see after 18.Bxa6. The white knight cannot reach c5 and the a8-rook puts pressure on the a-pawn.}) {Nxd1+} 13. Rd1 {Qxd4+} ({But not Qxa6?? Qxd7+ Kf8} 13. Ng5 {and Black is soon checkmated.}) {Rxd4 Black has a slight material advantage. Still, the initial impression is not very positive: the black rooks are passive, and White is threatening Nc5 – the d7 pawn is very weak. Yet, concrete analysis reveals that Black's position is actually quite sound.} 13... Rb8 $1 ({The precise move. Black is threatening ...Rb2+ with counterplay. After the also played Ke7?! , Black, on the other hand, ends up in a passive position: The bishop blocks the b-file with} 13... Bb7 $1 {Rab8} 14. Nc5 $16 {. This is a better square than d6 for the knight because now d7 is under attack, and Black must also place the h8-rook on a passive square. Rhd8 ( 22...Rbd8? 23.Ra4+- ) Rd6! By blocking the d-pawn, Black is prevented from liberating their position. Without any counterplay, they can only passively await White's winning attempts.}) {Bb7!? Of course, due to the knight fork on d6, Black couldn't take the bishop. With 21...f6, however, Black gets counterplay by exploiting the fact that the bishop is still under attack.} 14. Nc5 ({White must not capture the f-pawn twice: exf6 gxf6} 14. Nf6+ $2 $17 {Ke7 . Both of White's minor pieces are attacked and cannot be defended simultaneously.}) ({White could also leave the knight on e4 for now, for example with Ke3 Rf8! . Here the idea of 21...f6 becomes apparent: Black can capture on e5 and activate the rook along the f-file. Additionally, the rook can defend the d-pawn from the more active square f7 (after White's Nc5). If White preempts the exchange on e5 with exf6 , after gxf6} 14. Nc5 {Rf7= Black has everything protected and faces no problems. White should now resist the temptation to win material: Rxd7? Rxd7 Bxc6} Ke7 15. Nxd7+ {( 27.Bxd7?! Kd6 wins a piece.)} Rxb4 $17 {. The white minor pieces cannot reach safe squares. Black threatens to win a piece with ...Kd6 and has good winning chances here.}) {fxe5 Rxd7 fxe5 Rf8 Ke3 . After other king moves, Black also plays 24...Rf5. Rf5!? (24...Rf7 also leads to an equal position) Kd3!? . ( 25.Ke4? d5 26.Kd3 Ke7 followed by ...Rxe5 is very bad for White.) Black could now either force the issue with 25...Rxe5 or maintain the status quo with a waiting move. If White then captures on d7, ...Rxe5 forces exchanges. In both cases, the position is equal. A) Rxe5 Nxd7 c5!= . B) 25...h5!? 26.Rxd7 Rxe5 . B.1) 27.Rxg7? Kf8 28.Rh7 Kg8-+ . B.2) 27.Bxc6! Rxc5 28.Rb7 Rxc6 29.Rxb8 Ke7 30.Rb7 Kf6 31.Rxa7= .} 14... O-O $1 {Yes, that's still permissible. Black covers the g7-pawn, brings the king to safety, and activates the rook. Next, the f4-pawn can be captured (either with the pawn or with the rook). Chances are balanced, but the position remains complex.} 15. Nxe6 {This is not dangerous: Rf7 Bxc6 Rxd7 Bxd7 Kf7 Now it's White who needs to be cautious, as their minor pieces are not very stable. Black is threatening ...Ke7.} *

