1. e4 c5 {The Sicilian Opening stands for a sharp fight. Black somewhat neglects their piece development in order to prevent White from establishing a full pawn center with d2-d4.} 2. Nf3 e6 ({The third most common move after} 2... d6 {and}) (2... Nc6 {. With this, Black primarily prepares the development of the dark-squared bishop, but the center push ...d7-d5 becomes a possibility as well.}) (2... Nc6 {is an alternative way to reach the Four Knights Sicilian:} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6 {and we have landed in our repertoire via transposition. I decided against this path because White has a very serious and popular alternative in 3.Bb5 , the Rossolimo Variation. With 2...e6 the Rossolimo Variation is avoided.}) 3. d4 {The Open Sicilian and the starting position of this course. I examine alternatives for White on the second and third moves in a separate course on the Anti-Sicilians. The Open Sicilian is White's most principled attempt to fight for the opening advantage. White has more space and wants to open up the position, relying on rapid piece development. In return, Black gets the semi-open c-file, which can often be used for counterplay later on. Moreover, the exchange of the d-pawn for the c-pawn is a minor positional concession, as White now has only one pawn in the center and therefore can no longer fight quite as well for the important central squares.} cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 ({A very logical move - the knight is developed and simultaneously attacks the e4 pawn. Black takes advantage of the fact that the knight cannot be directly attacked with e4-e5 .} 4... Nc6 {is also possible, but gives White the additional option} 5. Nb5 {.}) 5. Nc3 ({Develops the knight and reinforces White's influence on the central square d5. Moreover, the diagonal a5-e1 is now interrupted, so that e4-e5 becomes a strong threat.} 5. e5 $2 {allows the double attack} Qa5+ {followed by -- Qxe5 .}) 5... Nc6 {Another natural developing move that continues the fight for the central squares. Black, at least temporarily, is preventing e4-e5 and threatening ...Bb4 with pressure on the white center. The starting position of the Sicilian Four Knights has now been reached. This method of play was first used in the second half of the 19th century. Early adopters included the masters Schiffers, Blackburne, Mieses, and Janowski. White now has a multitude of options.} 6. Nxc6 ({This initiates one of the sharpest and most complex variations in the Sicilian Four Knights. We will see very unusual positions that are unfamiliar from any other opening. 6.Nxc6 is the second most common move after 6.Ndb5. It is chosen primarily by players who are not comfortable transitioning into the Sveshnikov Variation after} 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bf4 e5 8. Bg5 {.}) 6... bxc6 ({Black would now like to play ...d7-d5 and would then have a solid position with good central control.} 6... dxc6 {leads to a queenless middlegame that is slightly better for White.} 7. Qxd8+ Kxd8 8. Bf4 $14 {. The main problem in Black's position is the passive bishop on c8.}) 7. e5 {The critical move. White prevents ...d7-d5 – the d7 pawn is now backward. In addition, White prepares to put pressure on the weakened d6-square. A third advantage from White's perspective is that a defender of the kingside is driven away, making future attacks there more promising. Of course, the pawn move also has its drawbacks. We will see in the following variations that the pawn on e5 itself becomes a target of Black's counterplay. White will have to accept weaknesses in their own camp to defend the exposed pawn. Alternatives to 7.e5 are discussed in the following chapter [/course/199209/7].} Nd5 8. Ne4 ({White avoids exchanging knights and targets the weakened d6-square. A subsequent c2-c4 could drive the black knight away from its central position and also give the white queen access to d6. The main problem for Black is the bishop on c8, which is blocked by Black's own pawns and cannot be activated easily. In this tabiya, Black has tried a variety of options, some of which have established their place in opening theory.} 8. Nxd5 cxd5 {is examined in chapter 5 [/course/199209/7].}) 8... Qc7 ({The main move. Black attacks the e5-pawn and forces a weakening of White's position. The alternative} 8... Bb7 {is also popular nowadays. Black wants to play ...c6-c5 and quickly solve the problem of the 'bad' light-squared bishop.}) 9. f4 {The queen has fulfilled its purpose on c7 and moves to a better square. On b6, the queen performs a number of functions:  * It controls the weakened a7-g1 diagonal.  * It threatens the double attack 10...Qb4+.  * It attacks the b2-pawn, complicating the development of the c1-bishop.  * It supports ...Ne3.  * It supports the attempt to exchange the light-squared bishops with ...Ba6. c4 Qd3 Obviously the best square for the queen, as it also needs to protect c2.} {I pondered for a long time whether to recommend the knight move or the main line Bb4+ . The latter is discussed at the highest level and, from a theoretical standpoint, Black is in good shape. On the other hand, after Ne3 , White achieves a slightly better position with best play from both sides. Still, I decided on 10...Ne3. The downside of 10...Bb4+ is that the theory is quite far advanced and leads to very complicated positions where one misstep can be fatal. In my opinion, 10...Ne3 is easier to play because the variations resulting from it are more straightforward.} Bb4+ {With this check, Black gains some time. Not only because the bishop is developed with a tempo, but also because after the main move 12.Bd2, the knight on e3 is no longer attacked.} 10. Bd2 Ba6 ({The bishop on d2 is pinned, so Black can leave the knight on e3 for now. ➤} 10... Ba6 {attacks the c4 pawn and forces White to make a decision: defend the pawn or engage in the complications after} 11. Bxb4 {.}) ({➤ The more frequently played} 10... O-O {is less appealing to me because after} 11. Rc1 {(with the threat of c4-c5) Black cannot avoid exchanges and risks being left with a passive light-squared bishop against a strong knight.}) 11. Bxb4 {With this, White demonstrates good theoretical knowledge. White initiates a forced sequence, at the end of which there is an unusual material balance. Qxb4+ Kf2 Qxb2+!} ({Black should engage in the complications. Nxc4? is a tactical mistake. After Qb3 , Black loses a piece, for example Rb8} 11. Bc4 Bxc4 {Qxc4! Qxc4} 12. Nd6+ {.}) {Nf5?! Qc3!? Qxc3 bxc3 . The problem child of the black position is the bishop on a6. I don’t see how it can be activated. White has the advantage.} 11... Be2 {Now the rook on a1 is protected and, in addition to capturing the knight, Rhb1 (or Rab1) is a threat. Nxc4!} ({Again, Black should not shy away from the complications. After Nf5?! Rab1 Qd4+ Qxd4 Nxd4} 11... Bd3 $16 {, Black may have an extra pawn, but their position is very passive. It's not clear how the bishop on a6 can be activated and White controls the only open file.}) 12. Rb1 ({The queen doesn't have a good square, so this piece sacrifice is forced. Black gets a total of four pawns for the piece. Qa3? loses a piece after} 12. Nd6+ {.}) ({After Qxa2? , the calm Rhd1 is most precise. Sooner or later, White wins a piece here as well, as Black has no defense against Ra1. Nd6+ This check leads to a position similar to 17.fxe5 [/variation/%2031423041/#/17/w], but here White wants to prevent Black from castling first. However, the move also has disadvantages. Qxa6?! is inaccurate. After the forced sequence} 12. Qd4 {Kg3 Qxe4 ( 18...Qe3!? 19.Bf3 Nd3 ) fxe5} Qxe5 {, the position is similar to what we will see after 17.fxe5, but with an extra tempo for Black.}) {Ke7 The correct square for the king. On f8, it would be in the way of the rooks. fxe5} 12... Qxe5 {Qxa6} 13. Qd4 {Kf3 Qc3+} {Slightly more precise than the direct Qxd6 . If the white king retreats to the back rank, it obstructs the rooks. If it goes to g3, the d6-knight falls with check. This was not a good moment to capture the knight: Qxd6? Rhd1 . Now Black doesn't have any checks. Qe5 Rxd7+! Kxd7 Qb7+ and White wins.} Bd3 {Kxd6 Through the checks, we have managed to displace White's king and bishop. The bishop is best placed on f3, while the king should hide on the kingside. The black king can go to e7 and if necessary back to e8 (but only after the h8 rook has been 'liberated'!). Black has no problems here. In contrast to the line [/variation/%2031423041/#/17/w] with 17.fxe5, it is not clear how White can win any of Black's pawns.} *

