{Qc5+ Kh1 d5 Rc7 Rxc6 Qxa6 Rxa6 Rfc8 The rook goes to c7 and defends the a7-pawn from there. If White swings the d1-rook to the a-file as well, Black brings the a8-rook over to b7. On the kingside, Black plays ...h7-h5 – at the latest when White plays h2-h4 and could put their own pawn on h5. Since Black has defended the weaknesses and is very solid, the game should end in a draw.} 1. e4 c5 {The Sicilian Opening stands for a sharp fight. Black somewhat neglects their piece development in order to prevent White from establishing a full pawn center with d2-d4.} 2. Nf3 e6 ({The third most common move after} 2... d6 {and}) (2... Nc6 {. With this, Black primarily prepares the development of the dark-squared bishop, but the center push ...d7-d5 becomes a possibility as well.}) (2... Nc6 {is an alternative way to reach the Four Knights Sicilian:} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6 {and we have landed in our repertoire via transposition. I decided against this path because White has a very serious and popular alternative in 3.Bb5 , the Rossolimo Variation. With 2...e6 the Rossolimo Variation is avoided.}) 3. d4 {The Open Sicilian and the starting position of this course. I examine alternatives for White on the second and third moves in a separate course on the Anti-Sicilians. The Open Sicilian is White's most principled attempt to fight for the opening advantage. White has more space and wants to open up the position, relying on rapid piece development. In return, Black gets the semi-open c-file, which can often be used for counterplay later on. Moreover, the exchange of the d-pawn for the c-pawn is a minor positional concession, as White now has only one pawn in the center and therefore can no longer fight quite as well for the important central squares.} cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 ({A very logical move - the knight is developed and simultaneously attacks the e4 pawn. Black takes advantage of the fact that the knight cannot be directly attacked with e4-e5 .} 4... Nc6 {is also possible, but gives White the additional option} 5. Nb5 {.}) 5. Nc3 ({Develops the knight and reinforces White's influence on the central square d5. Moreover, the diagonal a5-e1 is now interrupted, so that e4-e5 becomes a strong threat.} 5. e5 $2 {allows the double attack} Qa5+ {followed by -- Qxe5 .}) 5... Nc6 {Another natural developing move that continues the fight for the central squares. Black, at least temporarily, is preventing e4-e5 and threatening ...Bb4 with pressure on the white center. The starting position of the Sicilian Four Knights has now been reached. This method of play was first used in the second half of the 19th century. Early adopters included the masters Schiffers, Blackburne, Mieses, and Janowski. White now has a multitude of options.} 6. Nxc6 ({This initiates one of the sharpest and most complex variations in the Sicilian Four Knights. We will see very unusual positions that are unfamiliar from any other opening. 6.Nxc6 is the second most common move after 6.Ndb5. It is chosen primarily by players who are not comfortable transitioning into the Sveshnikov Variation after} 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bf4 e5 8. Bg5 {.}) 6... bxc6 ({Black would now like to play ...d7-d5 and would then have a solid position with good central control.} 6... dxc6 {leads to a queenless middlegame that is slightly better for White.} 7. Qxd8+ Kxd8 8. Bf4 $14 {. The main problem in Black's position is the passive bishop on c8.}) 7. e5 {The critical move. White prevents ...d7-d5 – the d7 pawn is now backward. In addition, White prepares to put pressure on the weakened d6-square. A third advantage from White's perspective is that a defender of the kingside is driven away, making future attacks there more promising. Of course, the pawn move also has its drawbacks. We will see in the following variations that the pawn on e5 itself becomes a target of Black's counterplay. White will have to accept weaknesses in their own camp to defend the exposed pawn. Alternatives to 7.e5 are discussed in the following chapter [/course/199209/7].} Nd5 8. Ne4 ({White avoids exchanging knights and targets the weakened d6-square. A subsequent c2-c4 could drive the black knight away from its central position and also give the white queen access to d6. The main problem for Black is the bishop on c8, which is blocked by Black's own pawns and cannot be activated easily. In this tabiya, Black has tried a variety of options, some of which have established their place in opening theory.} 8. Nxd5 cxd5 {is examined in chapter 5 [/course/199209/7].}) 8... Qc7 ({The main move. Black attacks the e5-pawn and forces a weakening of White's position. The alternative} 8... Bb7 {is also popular nowadays. Black wants to play ...c6-c5 and quickly solve the problem of the 'bad' light-squared bishop.}) 9. f4 {The queen has fulfilled its purpose on c7 and moves to a better square. On b6, the queen performs a number of functions:  * It controls the weakened a7-g1 diagonal.  * It threatens the double attack 10...Qb4+.  * It attacks the b2-pawn, complicating the development of the c1-bishop.  * It supports ...Ne3.  * It supports the attempt to exchange the light-squared bishops with ...Ba6. c4 Qd3 Obviously the best square for the queen, as it also needs to protect c2.} {I pondered for a long time whether to recommend the knight move or the main line Bb4+ . The latter is discussed at the highest level and, from a theoretical standpoint, Black is in good shape. On the other hand, after Ne3 , White achieves a slightly better position with best play from both sides. Still, I decided on 10...Ne3. The downside of 10...Bb4+ is that the theory is quite far advanced and leads to very complicated positions where one misstep can be fatal. In my opinion, 10...Ne3 is easier to play because the variations resulting from it are more straightforward.} Bb4+ {With this check, Black gains some time. Not only because the bishop is developed with a tempo, but also because after the main move 12.Bd2, the knight on e3 is no longer attacked.} 10. Bd2 Ba6 ({The bishop on d2 is pinned, so Black can leave the knight on e3 for now. ➤} 10... Ba6 {attacks the c4 pawn and forces White to make a decision: defend the pawn or engage in the complications after} 11. Bxb4 {.}) ({➤ The more frequently played} 10... O-O {is less appealing to me because after} 11. Rc1 {(with the threat of c4-c5) Black cannot avoid exchanges and risks being left with a passive light-squared bishop against a strong knight.}) 11. Bxb4 {With this, White demonstrates good theoretical knowledge. White initiates a forced sequence, at the end of which there is an unusual material balance. Qxb4+ Kf2 Qxb2+!} ({Black should engage in the complications. Nxc4? is a tactical mistake. After Qb3 , Black loses a piece, for example Rb8} 11. Bc4 Bxc4 {Qxc4! Qxc4} 12. Nd6+ {.}) {Nf5?! Qc3!? Qxc3 bxc3 . The problem child of the black position is the bishop on a6. I don’t see how it can be activated. White has the advantage.} 11... Be2 {Now the rook on a1 is protected and, in addition to capturing the knight, Rhb1 (or Rab1) is a threat. Nxc4!} ({Again, Black should not shy away from the complications. After Nf5?! Rab1 Qd4+ Qxd4 Nxd4} 11... Bd3 $16 {, Black may have an extra pawn, but their position is very passive. It's not clear how the bishop on a6 can be activated and White controls the only open file.}) 12. Rb1 ({The queen doesn't have a good square, so this piece sacrifice is forced. Black gets a total of four pawns for the piece. Qa3? loses a piece after} 12. Nd6+ {.}) {After Qxa2? , the calm Rhd1 is most precise. Sooner or later, White wins a piece here as well, as Black has no defense against Ra1. fxe5} 12... Qxe5 $14 {Qxa6 Qxe4 Rhd1 It's important that we have this move, which connects the rooks. White cannot capture on d7 because then the rook on b1 would be unprotected. Bf3! Again, the strongest move. From here, the bishop protects the white king not only against checks on the f-file but also against a possible later attack along the second rank, as now g2 is securely defended. What is more, the bishop itself is on a safe square and thus cannot easily become a target for attack. Qf5 From here, the queen maintains the attack on the rook on b1, so that Rxd7 is still not an option. Additionally, the queen pins the bishop and can swing to c5 if needed. As the forced sequence of moves is now over, it is a good time to take stock: Currently, Black has four pawns for the bishop. However, the d7-pawn is easily attacked, and if it moves to d5, its colleague on c6 falls. The a7-pawn is also weak. Advancing the central pawn mass is not realistic either, because the white pieces are very well prepared for it. Therefore, we must conclude that White has the better position. But can White win? The best chances for this lie in the siege of the a-pawn. If White manages to capture the black a-pawn without losing their own a-pawn, the passed pawn could be hard to stop in many endgames. On the kingside, Black has a very solid position. The best pawn structure is ...g7-g6 and ...h7-h5. This ensures that... 1) White cannot disrupt the black structure by advancing the h- and g-pawns. 2) In endgames, the king can move freely, thereby covering the vulnerable f7-pawn. When I analyzed this position at the end of 2022 for the German course, I was not completely sure yet how to evaluate it, as there were hardly any practical examples (Black quickly went wrong in the only tournament game which had reached this position back then). Now, one year later, I can confidently say that Black is doing fine. In several practical encounters in 2023, Black did not face any particular difficulties and scored 50%. Of course, with optimal play the game should end in a draw, but in a practical game there is still a lot of potential for both sides. Kg1!} ({We have examined the position after Nd6+ Ke7 via the move order [/variation/31423040/#/18/b] 17.Nd6+ Ke7 18.fxe5 Qxe5 . It's best for White to play 21.Kg1 first. This move covers the h2-pawn and prevents Black from generating counterplay against it. The king can later move to h1 where it cannot be attacked. The king move also frees the semi-open f-file for the rook. In the game Blomqvist–Stijve [/variation/21987659/#/25/w], Teplice 2022 (1-0), Rb7?! was played. Black quickly landed in a bad position after Qc2? . (The correct move was 21...Qc5 . The queen is much better here than on c2, as it covers the a7-pawn. 22.Kf1 d5 , and Black has no problems. Next could follow ...Rfb8 or ...e6-e5. On 23.Rc7 , Black gets good counterplay with 23...Qd6 followed by ...Qxh2.) Back to the game: Qe2 Qxe2 Bxe2 d5 Rc1 Rfc8} 12... Ba6 $16 {. Black doesn't have any counterplay, and the rook on b7 is very strong. Later, Black lost the a7-pawn and couldn't defend against the white passed pawn.}) ({g6!? Black still doesn't need to react to the threat on the d7-pawn. With 21...g6, Black makes Luft, which is useful in some variations, and also prepares the best pawn structure on the kingside (only ...h7-h5 is missing). Rfc8 is also playable. By protecting the c-pawn, Black prepares for ...d7-d5. The rook move was chosen in a number of high-level games, most notably the encounter Dominguez Perez-Guseinov [/variation/36055955], Baku 2023 (which was decided by a tragic blunder on the 40th move). Rb7 There are many alternatives, but the active rook move looks most logical. With Qc4 , White prevents ...Qc5+. Black now has a choice: ➤} 12... Rb8 {Rxb8 Rxb8 Rxd7 Qa5 is strong because the queen attacks the a-pawn (which could be attacked again with ...Rb2) and simultaneously covers the e1-square, which means White cannot capture on c6. Black has a lot of activity at the end of this variation and good chances to win the a-pawn. ➤ Besides, there is an option that is more reminiscent of the 22.Rb7 variation: 22...d5 23.Qxc6 Rab8 . This pawn structure is very solid for Black, and even though the engine gives White a slight advantage, the game is most likely to end in a draw. I think the decision for one of these moves is a matter of taste. Personally, I would opt for 22...Rab8 because there is a higher likelihood that White makes a mistake, giving Black winning chances.}) *

