s. Black, at least temporarily, is preventing e4-e5 and threatening ...Bb4 with pressure on the white center. The starting position of the Sicilian Four Knights has now been reached. This method of play was first used in the second half of the 19th century. Early adopters included the masters Schiffers, Blackburne, Mieses, and Janowski. White now has a multitude of options.} 6. Nxc6 ({This initiates one of the sharpest and most complex variations in the Sicilian Four Knights. We will see very unusual positions that are unfamiliar from any other opening. 6.Nxc6 is the second most common move after 6.Ndb5. It is chosen primarily by players who are not comfortable transitioning into the Sveshnikov Variation after} 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bf4 e5 8. Bg5 {.}) 6... bxc6 ({Black would now like to play ...d7-d5 and would then have a solid position with good central control.} 6... dxc6 {leads to a queenless middlegame that is slightly better for White.} 7. Qxd8+ Kxd8 8. Bf4 $14 {. The main problem in Black's position is the passive bishop on c8.}) 7. Bd3 {With this natural developing move, White keeps the option of e4-e5 open for later.} d5 {A recurring theme in this course. Against slow moves by White, Black can often establish a pawn presence in the center and comfortably equalize.} 8. e5 $6 {If White had already castled, Re1 would be possible, but as it is, there is no satisfactory defense for the pawn on e5. Bf4?} Rb8 9. Rb1 Qc7 10. Qe2 {f6! Black wins the e5-pawn and is clearly better.} *

