{Bd7 The position is equal. In the following moves, Black will continue to support the somewhat vulnerable central pawns on e5 and d5, for example with ...Qc7, ...Rad8 and ...Bd6. A possible active idea is ...d5-d4 followed by ...c6-c5. However, Black should be cautious with this plan: if White manages to place the knight on c4 afterwards, they will be better. This position appeared in the game Utsab–Svane [/variation/31423372/#/12/b], Cala Gonone 2022 (0-1).} 1. e4 c5 {The Sicilian Opening stands for a sharp fight. Black somewhat neglects their piece development in order to prevent White from establishing a full pawn center with d2-d4.} 2. Nf3 e6 ({The third most common move after} 2... d6 {and}) (2... Nc6 {. With this, Black primarily prepares the development of the dark-squared bishop, but the center push ...d7-d5 becomes a possibility as well.}) (2... Nc6 {is an alternative way to reach the Four Knights Sicilian:} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6 {and we have landed in our repertoire via transposition. I decided against this path because White has a very serious and popular alternative in 3.Bb5 , the Rossolimo Variation. With 2...e6 the Rossolimo Variation is avoided.}) 3. d4 {The Open Sicilian and the starting position of this course. I examine alternatives for White on the second and third moves in a separate course on the Anti-Sicilians. The Open Sicilian is White's most principled attempt to fight for the opening advantage. White has more space and wants to open up the position, relying on rapid piece development. In return, Black gets the semi-open c-file, which can often be used for counterplay later on. Moreover, the exchange of the d-pawn for the c-pawn is a minor positional concession, as White now has only one pawn in the center and therefore can no longer fight quite as well for the important central squares.} cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 ({A very logical move - the knight is developed and simultaneously attacks the e4 pawn. Black takes advantage of the fact that the knight cannot be directly attacked with e4-e5 .} 4... Nc6 {is also possible, but gives White the additional option} 5. Nb5 {.}) 5. Nc3 ({Develops the knight and reinforces White's influence on the central square d5. Moreover, the diagonal a5-e1 is now interrupted, so that e4-e5 becomes a strong threat.} 5. e5 $2 {allows the double attack} Qa5+ {followed by -- Qxe5 .}) 5... Nc6 {Another natural developing move that continues the fight for the central squares. Black, at least temporarily, is preventing e4-e5 and threatening ...Bb4 with pressure on the white center. The starting position of the Sicilian Four Knights has now been reached. This method of play was first used in the second half of the 19th century. Early adopters included the masters Schiffers, Blackburne, Mieses, and Janowski. White now has a multitude of options.} 6. Nxc6 ({This initiates one of the sharpest and most complex variations in the Sicilian Four Knights. We will see very unusual positions that are unfamiliar from any other opening. 6.Nxc6 is the second most common move after 6.Ndb5. It is chosen primarily by players who are not comfortable transitioning into the Sveshnikov Variation after} 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bf4 e5 8. Bg5 {.}) 6... bxc6 ({Black would now like to play ...d7-d5 and would then have a solid position with good central control.} 6... dxc6 {leads to a queenless middlegame that is slightly better for White.} 7. Qxd8+ Kxd8 8. Bf4 $14 {. The main problem in Black's position is the passive bishop on c8.}) 7. Bd3 {With this natural developing move, White keeps the option of e4-e5 open for later.} d5 {A recurring theme in this course. Against slow moves by White, Black can often establish a pawn presence in the center and comfortably equalize.} 8. O-O {The position now resembles a popular line of the Taimanov Sicilian: 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 e6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nc6 5.Nc3 a6 6.Nxc6 bxc6 7.Bd3 d5 8.O-O Nf6 . Unlike in that line, here Black does not lose a tempo for ...a7-a6 and thus has a significantly better version.} Be7 ({In positions after 7.Bd3, e7 is usually the right square for the bishop. Next, Black wants to castle and has comfortable play. ➤} 8... Bd6 {looks more active, but after} 9. Qe2 {, Black needs to worry about the threat of e4-e5. If Black guards this square with} Qc7 {,} 10. exd5 $1 {follows. Now,} Nxd5 {is necessary because the desirable 10...cxd5? is met with 11.Nb5 and an exchange of the important bishop. After our text move 8….Be7, White lacks the resource 11.Nb5 at this point. On 10...Bxh2? , 11.Kh1 follows, and due to the threats of 12.g3 or 12.f4, Black can't recapture on d5.}) ({➤ After} 8... Bc5 {, the pin} 9. Bg5 {can become annoying.}) 9. Qe2 {b3} ({A sensible setup. The bishop is well placed on the long diagonal, where it oversees the central squares d4 and e5, as well as the black kingside.} 9. e5 Nd7 10. f4 {has the drawback of blocking the diagonal of the c1-bishop. Therefore, we can play} g6 {without fearing a weakening of the dark squares. This is the pragmatic solution, as it neutralizes any kingside attack. Next, ...Nc5 and the exchange on d3 could come, followed by developing the queenside with ...c6-c5 and ...Bb7. The direct 11...Nc5 is also an option. White could try 12.Bxh7+ Kxh7 13.Qh5 Kg8 14.Rf3 , but the attack should at most suffice for perpetual check. After 11.Na4 , I don't see any problems either. A possibility is 11...Nb6 and on 12.Nxb6 , 12...axb6 improves the pawn structure on the queenside. Here, too, we have ...g7-g6 in case White plays for a kingside attack with f2-f4. Otherwise, ...c6-c5 followed by ...Bb7 is a good setup. And if White plays 13.c4 instead, 13...Ba6 is possible.}) ({Re8 Black strengthens control in the center and prepares ...e6-e5. Nd7 is the main continuation. Black wants to play ...Nc5. I'm not so keen on this move due to} 9. Na4 {, with which White prevents ...Nc5 and then aims to play Bb2. It's not entirely clear to me what the best setup for Black's pieces is now. After 11.Bb2 Nc5 , Black can secure the advantage of the bishop pair at their leisure, but there's no rush. Another good idea is ...d5-d4 followed by ...e6-e5 to block the view of the bishop on b2. Gaining space with ...a5-a4 also improves Black's position. Black has the easier game.}) {Bb2} 9... e5 {The idea behind the previous move. Black restricts the influence of the b2-bishop. Rad1} ({White cannot win a pawn: exd5?! cxd5 Qxe5} 9... Ba3 {. White must now give up the queen: Qxe8+ Qxe8 Bxa3 Qc6 followed by ...Ba6 with the exchange of bishops. Black is somewhat better.}) *

