1. e4 c5 {The Sicilian Opening stands for a sharp fight. Black somewhat neglects their piece development in order to prevent White from establishing a full pawn center with d2-d4.} 2. Nf3 e6 ({The third most common move after} 2... d6 {and}) (2... Nc6 {. With this, Black primarily prepares the development of the dark-squared bishop, but the center push ...d7-d5 becomes a possibility as well.}) (2... Nc6 {is an alternative way to reach the Four Knights Sicilian:} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6 {and we have landed in our repertoire via transposition. I decided against this path because White has a very serious and popular alternative in 3.Bb5 , the Rossolimo Variation. With 2...e6 the Rossolimo Variation is avoided.}) 3. d4 {The Open Sicilian and the starting position of this course. I examine alternatives for White on the second and third moves in a separate course on the Anti-Sicilians. The Open Sicilian is White's most principled attempt to fight for the opening advantage. White has more space and wants to open up the position, relying on rapid piece development. In return, Black gets the semi-open c-file, which can often be used for counterplay later on. Moreover, the exchange of the d-pawn for the c-pawn is a minor positional concession, as White now has only one pawn in the center and therefore can no longer fight quite as well for the important central squares.} cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 ({A very logical move - the knight is developed and simultaneously attacks the e4 pawn. Black takes advantage of the fact that the knight cannot be directly attacked with e4-e5 .} 4... Nc6 {is also possible, but gives White the additional option} 5. Nb5 {.}) 5. Nc3 ({Develops the knight and reinforces White's influence on the central square d5. Moreover, the diagonal a5-e1 is now interrupted, so that e4-e5 becomes a strong threat.} 5. e5 $2 {allows the double attack} Qa5+ {followed by -- Qxe5 .}) 5... Nc6 {Another natural developing move that continues the fight for the central squares. Black, at least temporarily, is preventing e4-e5 and threatening ...Bb4 with pressure on the white center. The starting position of the Sicilian Four Knights has now been reached. This method of play was first used in the second half of the 19th century. Early adopters included the masters Schiffers, Blackburne, Mieses, and Janowski. White now has a multitude of options.} 6. Nxc6 ({This initiates one of the sharpest and most complex variations in the Sicilian Four Knights. We will see very unusual positions that are unfamiliar from any other opening. 6.Nxc6 is the second most common move after 6.Ndb5. It is chosen primarily by players who are not comfortable transitioning into the Sveshnikov Variation after} 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bf4 e5 8. Bg5 {.}) 6... bxc6 7. Bg5 $6 {A move quite popular at the lower levels, according to the Database of online games played on Lichess. There is a reason it's rarely chosen by strong players: the bishop is needed to defend White's queenside.} h6 {Bg5 Bb4 Nxc6 bxc6 , which is analyzed in the chapter on White's sidelines on move The text move is even more convincing. By attacking the bishop on g5, we are likely to induce a mistake by our opponents. Bh4? The bishop turns out to be offside on h4. It is needed to defend the queenside.} 8. Bxf6 $2 {is bad as well, as the bishop will be dearly missed defending the dark squares. Black plays} Qxf6 {and later increases the pressure with ...Rb8 and ...Bb4 or ...Bc5. White's best option is the modest retreat 8.Bd2 , but that's hardly the reason they brought the bishop to g5. After 8...d5 Black is slightly better, with play similar to 7.Bd3 d5 . Rb8! Black immediately starts an attack on the dark squares on the queenside, which can no longer be defended by White's bishop. e5?! There was already no convenient solution for White.} 9. Qc1 {or 9.Rb1 would be met by Qa5 . Next, the bishop f8 will join the attack.  9.b3 is even worse: 9...g5 10.Bg3 Bb4 11.Qf3 Qa5 wins the knight, as 12.Kd2 is answered by 12...Bxc3+ 13.Qxc3 Nxe4+ . Rb4 As the engine points out, the piece sacrifice Rxb2! leads to a winning attack. However, I like to avoid unnecessary complications and the text move is good enough. Bg3 If instead exf6 Rxh4 fxg7 Bxg7 , a later attack against b2 and c3 decides the game in favour of Black. The tricky 10.f4 is refuted by 10...g5! , winning. Ne4 a3 White's best defence, forcing exchanges. Nxg3 Taking on c3 is equally good. axb4 hxg3 Rxb2 is winning for Black. Nxh1 Qd4 White has lost a piece, but our knight is trapped. However, we can use the time White needs to win the knight to open the position and gain a decisive positional advantage. Be7-+ -- Next, we castle and play ...f7-f6, activating the rook and the dark-squared bishop. Black is winning. A plausible continuation would be g3 f6 Bg2 fxe5} Qe5 {O-O Bxh1 Qb6 , when once again the attack on the dark squares decides the game.} *

