1. e4 c5 {The Sicilian Opening stands for a sharp fight. Black somewhat neglects their piece development in order to prevent White from establishing a full pawn center with d2-d4.} 2. Nf3 e6 ({The third most common move after} 2... d6 {and}) (2... Nc6 {. With this, Black primarily prepares the development of the dark-squared bishop, but the center push ...d7-d5 becomes a possibility as well.}) (2... Nc6 {is an alternative way to reach the Four Knights Sicilian:} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6 {and we have landed in our repertoire via transposition. I decided against this path because White has a very serious and popular alternative in 3.Bb5 , the Rossolimo Variation. With 2...e6 the Rossolimo Variation is avoided.}) 3. d4 {The Open Sicilian and the starting position of this course. I examine alternatives for White on the second and third moves in a separate course on the Anti-Sicilians. The Open Sicilian is White's most principled attempt to fight for the opening advantage. White has more space and wants to open up the position, relying on rapid piece development. In return, Black gets the semi-open c-file, which can often be used for counterplay later on. Moreover, the exchange of the d-pawn for the c-pawn is a minor positional concession, as White now has only one pawn in the center and therefore can no longer fight quite as well for the important central squares.} cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 ({A very logical move - the knight is developed and simultaneously attacks the e4 pawn. Black takes advantage of the fact that the knight cannot be directly attacked with e4-e5 .} 4... Nc6 {is also possible, but gives White the additional option} 5. Nb5 {.}) 5. Nc3 ({Develops the knight and reinforces White's influence on the central square d5. Moreover, the diagonal a5-e1 is now interrupted, so that e4-e5 becomes a strong threat.} 5. e5 $2 {allows the double attack} Qa5+ {followed by -- Qxe5 .}) 5... Nc6 {Another natural developing move that continues the fight for the central squares. Black, at least temporarily, is preventing e4-e5 and threatening ...Bb4 with pressure on the white center. The starting position of the Sicilian Four Knights has now been reached. This method of play was first used in the second half of the 19th century. Early adopters included the masters Schiffers, Blackburne, Mieses, and Janowski. White now has a multitude of options.} 6. Nxc6 ({This initiates one of the sharpest and most complex variations in the Sicilian Four Knights. We will see very unusual positions that are unfamiliar from any other opening. 6.Nxc6 is the second most common move after 6.Ndb5. It is chosen primarily by players who are not comfortable transitioning into the Sveshnikov Variation after} 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bf4 e5 8. Bg5 {.}) 6... bxc6 ({Black would now like to play ...d7-d5 and would then have a solid position with good central control.} 6... dxc6 {leads to a queenless middlegame that is slightly better for White.} 7. Qxd8+ Kxd8 8. Bf4 $14 {. The main problem in Black's position is the passive bishop on c8.}) 7. e5 {The critical move. White prevents ...d7-d5 – the d7 pawn is now backward. In addition, White prepares to put pressure on the weakened d6-square. A third advantage from White's perspective is that a defender of the kingside is driven away, making future attacks there more promising. Of course, the pawn move also has its drawbacks. We will see in the following variations that the pawn on e5 itself becomes a target of Black's counterplay. White will have to accept weaknesses in their own camp to defend the exposed pawn.} Nd5 8. Nxd5 {This exchange rather helps Black.} cxd5 {The doubled pawn can be resolved at will with ...d7-d6. However, Black does not need to rush this, as the e5-pawn can also serve as a target for the queen. Besides, Black has the other pawn break ...f7-f6, after which the central pawns might become very strong.} 9. Be3 Ba6 ({An important tactical motif in the line with 8.Nxd5. Black forces the exchange of bishops. The black light-squared bishop is obstructed by its own pawns, so this exchange is favorable for Black. It is also possible to delay the exchange, for example with} 9... Qc7 {or}) (9... Be7 {.}) 10. Bxa6 Qa5+ 11. c3 Qxa6 {The position is equal.} *

