s. Black, at least temporarily, is preventing e4-e5 and threatening ...Bb4 with pressure on the white center. The starting position of the Sicilian Four Knights has now been reached. This method of play was first used in the second half of the 19th century. Early adopters included the masters Schiffers, Blackburne, Mieses, and Janowski. White now has a multitude of options.} 6. Nxc6 ({This initiates one of the sharpest and most complex variations in the Sicilian Four Knights. We will see very unusual positions that are unfamiliar from any other opening. 6.Nxc6 is the second most common move after 6.Ndb5. It is chosen primarily by players who are not comfortable transitioning into the Sveshnikov Variation after} 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bf4 e5 8. Bg5 {.}) 6... bxc6 ({Black would now like to play ...d7-d5 and would then have a solid position with good central control.} 6... dxc6 {leads to a queenless middlegame that is slightly better for White.} 7. Qxd8+ Kxd8 8. Bf4 $14 {. The main problem in Black's position is the passive bishop on c8.}) 7. e5 {The critical move. White prevents ...d7-d5 – the d7 pawn is now backward. In addition, White prepares to put pressure on the weakened d6-square. A third advantage from White's perspective is that a defender of the kingside is driven away, making future attacks there more promising. Of course, the pawn move also has its drawbacks. We will see in the following variations that the pawn on e5 itself becomes a target of Black's counterplay. White will have to accept weaknesses in their own camp to defend the exposed pawn.} Nd5 8. Nxd5 {This exchange rather helps Black.} cxd5 {The doubled pawn can be resolved at will with ...d7-d6. However, Black does not need to rush this, as the e5-pawn can also serve as a target for the queen. Besides, Black has the other pawn break ...f7-f6, after which the central pawns might become very strong.} 9. Bd3 Qc7 $5 ({The attack on the e5-pawn is more dangerous than it looks. All defensive moves have drawbacks. ➤ Black should avoid} 9... Be7 $6 10. Qg4 {, which is a typical motif in positions with a white pawn on e5. Black cannot defend the g7-pawn adequately and must therefore play ...g7-g6, leading to a weakening of the dark squares on the kingside. After} O-O $2 11. Bh6 {, White would win at least the exchange, and on 10...g6 , 11.O-O $14 follows.}) ({➤} 9... Ba6 {is playable and objectively equal, but I don’t like the position after} 10. O-O Bxd3 11. cxd3 $1 {much. Black cannot quickly bring the king out of the center because} Be7 $6 {still fails to} 12. Qg4 $14 {.}) 10. f4 $2 {Weakens the g1-a7 diagonal.} Bc5 11. Qe2 Qb6 {The white king is kept in the center. Black will castle and at an opportune moment open the position with ...d7-d6 or ...f7-f6. Black is better.} *

