s. ➤ Black should avoid} 9... Be7 $6 10. Qg4 {, which is a typical motif in positions with a white pawn on e5. Black cannot defend the g7-pawn adequately and must therefore play ...g7-g6, leading to a weakening of the dark squares on the kingside. After} O-O $2 11. Bh6 {, White would win at least the exchange, and on 10...g6 , 11.O-O $14 follows.}) ({➤} 9... Ba6 {is playable and objectively equal, but I don’t like the position after} 10. O-O Bxd3 11. cxd3 $1 {much. Black cannot quickly bring the king out of the center because} Be7 $6 {still fails to} 12. Qg4 $14 {.}) 10. Bf4 Rb8 {Now the b-pawn becomes a source of concern for White. There is no comfortable way to defend it.} 11. Rb1 $6 {This was already played in the classic game Marshall–Mieses [/variation/31423373/#/11/w], Monte Carlo 1903, but it is a tactical error.} Rxb2 12. Rxb2 Qc3+ 13. Ke2 Qxb2 14. Qb1 {White does not have sufficient compensation for the pawn. However, it is important to prevent a white major piece from penetrating on the b-file. Thus, Mieses correctly played 14...Qb6 after 14.Qb1 and later converted the extra pawn into a win.} *

