1. e4 c5 {The Sicilian Opening stands for a sharp fight. Black somewhat neglects their piece development in order to prevent White from establishing a full pawn center with d2-d4.} 2. Nf3 e6 ({The third most common move after} 2... d6 {and}) (2... Nc6 {. With this, Black primarily prepares the development of the dark-squared bishop, but the center push ...d7-d5 becomes a possibility as well.}) (2... Nc6 {is an alternative way to reach the Four Knights Sicilian:} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6 {and we have landed in our repertoire via transposition. I decided against this path because White has a very serious and popular alternative in 3.Bb5 , the Rossolimo Variation. With 2...e6 the Rossolimo Variation is avoided.}) 3. d4 {The Open Sicilian and the starting position of this course. I examine alternatives for White on the second and third moves in a separate course on the Anti-Sicilians. The Open Sicilian is White's most principled attempt to fight for the opening advantage. White has more space and wants to open up the position, relying on rapid piece development. In return, Black gets the semi-open c-file, which can often be used for counterplay later on. Moreover, the exchange of the d-pawn for the c-pawn is a minor positional concession, as White now has only one pawn in the center and therefore can no longer fight quite as well for the important central squares.} cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 ({A very logical move - the knight is developed and simultaneously attacks the e4 pawn. Black takes advantage of the fact that the knight cannot be directly attacked with e4-e5 .} 4... Nc6 {is also possible, but gives White the additional option} 5. Nb5 {.}) 5. Nc3 ({Develops the knight and reinforces White's influence on the central square d5. Moreover, the diagonal a5-e1 is now interrupted, so that e4-e5 becomes a strong threat.} 5. e5 $2 {allows the double attack} Qa5+ {followed by -- Qxe5 .}) 5... Nc6 {Another natural developing move that continues the fight for the central squares. Black, at least temporarily, is preventing e4-e5 and threatening ...Bb4 with pressure on the white center. The starting position of the Sicilian Four Knights has now been reached. This method of play was first used in the second half of the 19th century. Early adopters included the masters Schiffers, Blackburne, Mieses, and Janowski. White now has a multitude of options.} 6. Nxc6 ({This initiates one of the sharpest and most complex variations in the Sicilian Four Knights. We will see very unusual positions that are unfamiliar from any other opening. 6.Nxc6 is the second most common move after 6.Ndb5. It is chosen primarily by players who are not comfortable transitioning into the Sveshnikov Variation after} 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bf4 e5 8. Bg5 {.}) 6... bxc6 ({Black would now like to play ...d7-d5 and would then have a solid position with good central control.} 6... dxc6 {leads to a queenless middlegame that is slightly better for White.} 7. Qxd8+ Kxd8 8. Bf4 $14 {. The main problem in Black's position is the passive bishop on c8.}) 7. e5 {The critical move. White prevents ...d7-d5 – the d7 pawn is now backward. In addition, White prepares to put pressure on the weakened d6-square. A third advantage from White's perspective is that a defender of the kingside is driven away, making future attacks there more promising. Of course, the pawn move also has its drawbacks. We will see in the following variations that the pawn on e5 itself becomes a target of Black's counterplay. White will have to accept weaknesses in their own camp to defend the exposed pawn.} Nd5 8. Nxd5 {This exchange rather helps Black.} cxd5 {The doubled pawn can be resolved at will with ...d7-d6. However, Black does not need to rush this, as the e5-pawn can also serve as a target for the queen. Besides, Black has the other pawn break ...f7-f6, after which the central pawns might become very strong.} 9. Bd3 Qc7 $5 ({The attack on the e5-pawn is more dangerous than it looks. All defensive moves have drawbacks. ➤ Black should avoid} 9... Be7 $6 10. Qg4 {, which is a typical motif in positions with a white pawn on e5. Black cannot defend the g7-pawn adequately and must therefore play ...g7-g6, leading to a weakening of the dark squares on the kingside. After} O-O $2 11. Bh6 {, White would win at least the exchange, and on 10...g6 , 11.O-O $14 follows.}) ({➤} 9... Ba6 {is playable and objectively equal, but I don’t like the position after} 10. O-O Bxd3 11. cxd3 $1 {much. Black cannot quickly bring the king out of the center because} Be7 $6 {still fails to} 12. Qg4 $14 {.}) 10. Bf4 Rb8 {Now the b-pawn becomes a source of concern for White. There is no comfortable way to defend it.} 11. Qc1 g5 $5 ({This prepares ...Qa5. The bishop is now forced to leave the c1-h6 diagonal. Instead, Black could win a pawn with} 11... Bc5 {, as both ...Bd4 and ...Qb6 are threatening, each with a double attack. A)} 12. O-O Bd4 $17 {. B) However, the position after 12.c3 Qb6 13.O-O Qxb2 14.Qd1! is not so straightforward. The white queen will move to the kingside, and the black king does not feel safe.}) 12. Bg3 ({After} 12. Bxg5 $2 Qxe5+ 13. Qe3 Bd6 $17 {, Black will win the b2-pawn.}) 12... Qa5+ 13. c3 $2 Ba6 $1 {After the exchange of bishops, the white king remains in the center. Black is clearly better.} 14. b4 $2 {Now it becomes clear why the interjection of 11...g5 12.Bg3 was important.} Bxb4 $1 15. cxb4 Qxb4+ {If the white bishop were still on f4 (i.e., without the interjection of 11...g5 12.Bg3), White could defend with Bd2. Now, however, Black wins back the piece and keeps two extra pawns.} 16. Ke2 Qe4+ {Black is winning.} *

