s. ➤ Black should avoid} 9... Be7 $6 10. Qg4 {, which is a typical motif in positions with a white pawn on e5. Black cannot defend the g7-pawn adequately and must therefore play ...g7-g6, leading to a weakening of the dark squares on the kingside. After} O-O $2 11. Bh6 {, White would win at least the exchange, and on 10...g6 , 11.O-O $14 follows.}) ({➤} 9... Ba6 {is playable and objectively equal, but I don’t like the position after} 10. O-O Bxd3 11. cxd3 $1 {much. Black cannot quickly bring the king out of the center because} Be7 $6 {still fails to} 12. Qg4 $14 {.}) 10. Bf4 Rb8 {Now the b-pawn becomes a source of concern for White. There is no comfortable way to defend it.} 11. Qc1 g5 $5 ({This prepares ...Qa5. The bishop is now forced to leave the c1-h6 diagonal. Instead, Black could win a pawn with} 11... Bc5 {, as both ...Bd4 and ...Qb6 are threatening, each with a double attack. A)} 12. O-O Bd4 $17 {. B) However, the position after 12.c3 Qb6 13.O-O Qxb2 14.Qd1! is not so straightforward. The white queen will move to the kingside, and the black king does not feel safe.}) 12. Bg3 ({After} 12. Bxg5 $2 Qxe5+ 13. Qe3 Bd6 $17 {, Black will win the b2-pawn.}) 12... Qa5+ 13. Qd2 {Relatively best.} Qxd2+ 14. Kxd2 h5 ({Winning a pawn with} 14... Rxb2 {is possible, but in return, White gains activity. For instance, with} 15. h4 $1 g4 16. h5 {. The pawns on h7 and g4 are now weak, and White is threatening to penetrate on the queenside via the b-file.}) 15. h4 g4 {The position is slightly more comfortable for Black. The white pieces are tied to the defense of the b2- and e5-pawns. Also, the pawn on g2 could become vulnerable after the moves ...Bb7 and ...d5-d4.} *

