s. Black, at least temporarily, is preventing e4-e5 and threatening ...Bb4 with pressure on the white center. The starting position of the Sicilian Four Knights has now been reached. This method of play was first used in the second half of the 19th century. Early adopters included the masters Schiffers, Blackburne, Mieses, and Janowski. White now has a multitude of options.} 6. Nxc6 ({This initiates one of the sharpest and most complex variations in the Sicilian Four Knights. We will see very unusual positions that are unfamiliar from any other opening. 6.Nxc6 is the second most common move after 6.Ndb5. It is chosen primarily by players who are not comfortable transitioning into the Sveshnikov Variation after} 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bf4 e5 8. Bg5 {.}) 6... bxc6 ({Black would now like to play ...d7-d5 and would then have a solid position with good central control.} 6... dxc6 {leads to a queenless middlegame that is slightly better for White.} 7. Qxd8+ Kxd8 8. Bf4 $14 {. The main problem in Black's position is the passive bishop on c8.}) 7. e5 {The critical move. White prevents ...d7-d5 – the d7 pawn is now backward. In addition, White prepares to put pressure on the weakened d6-square. A third advantage from White's perspective is that a defender of the kingside is driven away, making future attacks there more promising. Of course, the pawn move also has its drawbacks. We will see in the following variations that the pawn on e5 itself becomes a target of Black's counterplay. White will have to accept weaknesses in their own camp to defend the exposed pawn.} Nd5 8. Ne4 {White avoids exchanging knights and targets the weakened d6-square. A subsequent c2-c4 could drive the black knight away from its central position and also give the white queen access to d6. The main problem for Black is the bishop on c8, which is blocked by Black's own pawns and cannot be activated easily. In this tabiya, Black has tried a variety of options, some of which have established their place in opening theory.} Qc7 ({The main move. Black attacks the e5-pawn and forces a weakening of White's position. The alternative} 8... Bb7 {is also popular nowadays. Black wants to play ...c6-c5 and quickly solve the problem of the 'bad' light-squared bishop.}) 9. f4 {The queen has fulfilled its purpose on c7 and moves to a better square. On b6, the queen performs a number of functions:  * It controls the weakened a7-g1 diagonal.  * It threatens the double attack 10...Qb4+.  * It attacks the b2-pawn, complicating the development of the c1-bishop.  * It supports ...Ne3.  * It supports the attempt to exchange the light-squared bishops with ...Ba6. a3!? Qd2 The queen is positioned worse here than on d3, as she obstructs the bishop and does not protect the knight on e4. On the other hand, White avoids tactics related to ...Ba6. Nxf1 Rxf1} {We force matters. The aim is now to activate the bishop on c8. For this, Black first exchanges its white counterpart. Good alternatives are a5 and f5 .} c5 {Black aims to attack the knight on e4 with ...Bb7.} 10. f5 {This attack is less dangerous here than with White's queen on d3.} Bb7 ({This is the difference compared to the queen's position on d3. Black gains time by attacking the unprotected knight. A good alternative is} 10... Ba6 {Rf2 exf5 Rxf5 O-O-O!? , resulting in an unclear position.}) 11. Ng5 $5 {White continues to play aggressively. There is a threat of a piece sacrifice on f7.} Be7 12. Nxf7 $1 {There's no turning back for White. After other moves, Black is already better.} Kxf7 ({After that, the game ends in perpetual check by force. Possible as well are} 12... Rf8 {or}) (12... O-O {, each with an unclear position.}) 13. fxe6+ ({Qxd7 Qc6} 13. fxe6+ Kg8 {is a transposition. In this move order though, Black had the additional option of 16...Rhe8!? .}) 13... Kg8 {Qxd7 Qc6! Black could not defend the bishop on e7 and therefore forces a draw. Qxe7 Qe4+ Kd1} 14. Qg4 {Kd2 Qxg2+ Ke1 Qe4+ White cannot escape the checks.} *

