s. Black, at least temporarily, is preventing e4-e5 and threatening ...Bb4 with pressure on the white center. The starting position of the Sicilian Four Knights has now been reached. This method of play was first used in the second half of the 19th century. Early adopters included the masters Schiffers, Blackburne, Mieses, and Janowski. White now has a multitude of options.} 6. Nxc6 ({This initiates one of the sharpest and most complex variations in the Sicilian Four Knights. We will see very unusual positions that are unfamiliar from any other opening. 6.Nxc6 is the second most common move after 6.Ndb5. It is chosen primarily by players who are not comfortable transitioning into the Sveshnikov Variation after} 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bf4 e5 8. Bg5 {.}) 6... bxc6 ({Black would now like to play ...d7-d5 and would then have a solid position with good central control.} 6... dxc6 {leads to a queenless middlegame that is slightly better for White.} 7. Qxd8+ Kxd8 8. Bf4 $14 {. The main problem in Black's position is the passive bishop on c8.}) 7. e5 {The critical move. White prevents ...d7-d5 – the d7 pawn is now backward. In addition, White prepares to put pressure on the weakened d6-square. A third advantage from White's perspective is that a defender of the kingside is driven away, making future attacks there more promising. Of course, the pawn move also has its drawbacks. We will see in the following variations that the pawn on e5 itself becomes a target of Black's counterplay. White will have to accept weaknesses in their own camp to defend the exposed pawn.} Nd5 8. Ne4 {White avoids exchanging knights and targets the weakened d6-square. A subsequent c2-c4 could drive the black knight away from its central position and also give the white queen access to d6. The main problem for Black is the bishop on c8, which is blocked by Black's own pawns and cannot be activated easily. In this tabiya, Black has tried a variety of options, some of which have established their place in opening theory.} Qc7 ({The main move. Black attacks the e5-pawn and forces a weakening of White's position. The alternative} 8... Bb7 {is also popular nowadays. Black wants to play ...c6-c5 and quickly solve the problem of the 'bad' light-squared bishop.}) 9. f4 {The queen has fulfilled its purpose on c7 and moves to a better square. On b6, the queen performs a number of functions:  * It controls the weakened a7-g1 diagonal.  * It threatens the double attack 10...Qb4+.  * It attacks the b2-pawn, complicating the development of the c1-bishop.  * It supports ...Ne3.  * It supports the attempt to exchange the light-squared bishops with ...Ba6. a3!? Qd3 The most natural choice. Nxf1 Rxf1} {We force matters. The aim is now to activate the bishop on c8. For this, Black first exchanges its white counterpart. Good alternatives are a5 and f5 .} Ba6 ({Here,} 9... c5 10. f5 {would be dangerous.}) 10. c4 f5 $1 ({An important move. Only in this way Black can obtain good counterplay. Why is it so crucial to act swiftly? Let's illustrate with a natural developing move:} 10... Be7 $2 11. b4 {. White aims to slowly strengthen the position, for example with Bb2 and O-O-O. Black lacks counterplay. If} f5 {follows now, Black is already too slow:} 12. Nd6+ Bxd6 13. exd6 {. Now,} c5 {is necessary, otherwise the light-squared bishop does not participate in the game, but after} 14. Be3 $16 {, White wins a pawn.}) 11. Nd6+ Bxd6 12. exd6 c5 {Black has achieved their goal: the light-squared bishop can next be activated with ...Bb7. Rf3! , Walsrode Black wants to continue with Rc6 and win the pawn on d6. However, this compromises the king's safety, as castling queenside is no longer possible. Rg3 Rg8 (17...O-O is no alternative, as after 18.b3 followed by Bb2, the attack against the g7-pawn is lethal.)} {½-½} 13. b3 {Rc6 Qd1! Transferring the queen to the kingside. Rxd6 (More solid was 19...g6, but this would have allowed White to defend the d6-pawn with 20.Rd3, after which their pieces are much more active) Qh5+} Kf8 14. Bb2 $1 Qb7 {. Now, White could have defended the f4-pawn with} 15. Be5 $1 {and thus prevented all counterplay. Black has nothing to counter the attack on the kingside. Rg3 Rg8 Avoids weakening the kingside. Instead, O-O (or 17...Kf7) walks into a strong kingside attack after b3 followed by Bb2. b3 White prepares to develop the bishop. It can go to either b2 or e3, depending on the circumstances. Instead, White might try Qd1 , which allows the rook to shift to b3 and the queen to h5.} g6 {( 18...O-O-O would be dangerous, as White can play for an attack with 19.Rb3! Qc6 20.Be3 with the idea of Rb5) 19.b3 O-O-O Since White's pawn occupies the b3-square, it's safe to castle now. Be4 It is useful to force the white queen to decide on a square. On d2, it would obstruct the bishop's path to e3. Qd1 O-O-O= Blacks king isn't as safe as it may seem, as White will sooner or later open a file on the queenside by playing b3-b4. Therefore, Black should hurry to create counterplay against White's king. This is achieved by the pawn breaks ...g7-g5 or ...e6-e5. Black should not be afraid to sacrifice a pawn, as in positions with opposite-colored bishops, the initiative is of far greater importance.} *

