 in turn, is the only good move for White. It's better to capture on e6 with the knight because it generates threats there and keeps the queen safe. After Qxe6+? Kb8 , it's the white king that comes under fire.} 11. Nc3 {gxf6-+ . Black need not rush. The white king is stuck in the center. Black now plans a bishop move followed by Rhe8.}) {Rd7 Black can also capture on c4 or f6, but after Nxe6, the rook would have to move anyway. 16...Rd7 has the advantage of preventing the fork 17.Nf7. Nxe6} 11... gxf6 {Next, Black wants to capture on c4 and then will have regained the material. The position is complex but equal. A possible continuation is:} 12. Be3 {Bd4 Black now wants to capture on c4 with the queen. Rf3!} Bxc4 {Rf2} {Qxc4? Kf2 is the idea behind White's last rook move. The white king goes to g1 and is safe there. The rook can swing to c3, after which White gets an attack.} 13. Qd3 Bxd3 {Bxf6 Rg8 With equality.} *

