1. e4 c5 {The Sicilian Opening stands for a sharp fight. Black somewhat neglects their piece development in order to prevent White from establishing a full pawn center with d2-d4.} 2. Nf3 e6 ({The third most common move after} 2... d6 {and}) (2... Nc6 {. With this, Black primarily prepares the development of the dark-squared bishop, but the center push ...d7-d5 becomes a possibility as well.}) (2... Nc6 {is an alternative way to reach the Four Knights Sicilian:} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6 {and we have landed in our repertoire via transposition. I decided against this path because White has a very serious and popular alternative in 3.Bb5 , the Rossolimo Variation. With 2...e6 the Rossolimo Variation is avoided.}) 3. d4 {The Open Sicilian and the starting position of this course. I examine alternatives for White on the second and third moves in a separate course on the Anti-Sicilians. The Open Sicilian is White's most principled attempt to fight for the opening advantage. White has more space and wants to open up the position, relying on rapid piece development. In return, Black gets the semi-open c-file, which can often be used for counterplay later on. Moreover, the exchange of the d-pawn for the c-pawn is a minor positional concession, as White now has only one pawn in the center and therefore can no longer fight quite as well for the important central squares.} cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 ({A very logical move - the knight is developed and simultaneously attacks the e4 pawn. Black takes advantage of the fact that the knight cannot be directly attacked with e4-e5 .} 4... Nc6 {is also possible, but gives White the additional option} 5. Nb5 {.}) 5. Nc3 ({Develops the knight and reinforces White's influence on the central square d5. Moreover, the diagonal a5-e1 is now interrupted, so that e4-e5 becomes a strong threat.} 5. e5 $2 {allows the double attack} Qa5+ {followed by -- Qxe5 .}) 5... Nc6 {Another natural developing move that continues the fight for the central squares. Black, at least temporarily, is preventing e4-e5 and threatening ...Bb4 with pressure on the white center. The starting position of the Sicilian Four Knights has now been reached. This method of play was first used in the second half of the 19th century. Early adopters included the masters Schiffers, Blackburne, Mieses, and Janowski. White now has a multitude of options.} 6. Nxc6 ({This initiates one of the sharpest and most complex variations in the Sicilian Four Knights. We will see very unusual positions that are unfamiliar from any other opening. 6.Nxc6 is the second most common move after 6.Ndb5. It is chosen primarily by players who are not comfortable transitioning into the Sveshnikov Variation after} 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bf4 e5 8. Bg5 {.}) 6... bxc6 ({Black would now like to play ...d7-d5 and would then have a solid position with good central control.} 6... dxc6 {leads to a queenless middlegame that is slightly better for White.} 7. Qxd8+ Kxd8 8. Bf4 $14 {. The main problem in Black's position is the passive bishop on c8.}) 7. e5 {The critical move. White prevents ...d7-d5 – the d7 pawn is now backward. In addition, White prepares to put pressure on the weakened d6-square. A third advantage from White's perspective is that a defender of the kingside is driven away, making future attacks there more promising. Of course, the pawn move also has its drawbacks. We will see in the following variations that the pawn on e5 itself becomes a target of Black's counterplay. White will have to accept weaknesses in their own camp to defend the exposed pawn.} Nd5 8. Ne4 {White avoids exchanging knights and targets the weakened d6-square. A subsequent c2-c4 could drive the black knight away from its central position and also give the white queen access to d6. The main problem for Black is the bishop on c8, which is blocked by Black's own pawns and cannot be activated easily. In this tabiya, Black has tried a variety of options, some of which have established their place in opening theory.} Qc7 ({The main move. Black attacks the e5-pawn and forces a weakening of White's position. The alternative} 8... Bb7 {is also popular nowadays. Black wants to play ...c6-c5 and quickly solve the problem of the 'bad' light-squared bishop.}) 9. f4 {The queen has fulfilled its purpose on c7 and moves to a better square. On b6, the queen performs a number of functions:  * It controls the weakened a7-g1 diagonal.  * It threatens the double attack 10...Qb4+.  * It attacks the b2-pawn, complicating the development of the c1-bishop.  * It supports ...Ne3.  * It supports the attempt to exchange the light-squared bishops with ...Ba6. a3!? Qd3 The most natural choice. Nxf1 Rxf1} {We force matters. The aim is now to activate the bishop on c8. For this, Black first exchanges its white counterpart. Good alternatives are a5 and f5 .} Ba6 ({Here,} 9... c5 10. f5 {would be dangerous.}) 10. c4 f5 $1 ({An important move. Only in this way Black can obtain good counterplay. Why is it so crucial to act swiftly? Let's illustrate with a natural developing move:} 10... Be7 $2 11. b4 {. White aims to slowly strengthen the position, for example with Bb2 and O-O-O. Black lacks counterplay. If} f5 {follows now, Black is already too slow:} 12. Nd6+ Bxd6 13. exd6 {. Now,} c5 {is necessary, otherwise the light-squared bishop does not participate in the game, but after} 14. Be3 $16 {, White wins a pawn.}) 11. exf6 {d5 A fairly typical idea in the 6.Nxc6 variation. The f-pawn advances, distracting the white e-pawn, so that next the d-pawn can get involved in the action. In this specific position, White faces attacks on e4, c4, and f6. f7+ A natural move. The black king is dragged onto the battlefield, where the f1-rook is ready to join the attack. Grandmasters Paravyan and Alekseenko opted for this direct approach.} Kf7 12. Ng5+ {Paravyan's choice, but this only drives the black king to a safer position. The initiative shifts to Black.} Kg8 13. b3 ({This modest move is necessary to maintain the balance. White protects the c4-pawn. Paravyan, however, played} 13. Qe2 $2 {and after} Re8 {, he could no longer defend the c4-pawn and was already lost. The attempt at an attack with} 14. f5 {led nowhere after} Bxc4 15. Qh5 Re7 16. fxe6 g6 {in Paravyan–Gujrathi [/variation/31423376/#/20/b], Chess.com 2022 (0-1). (Not 20...Bxf1?? 21.Qf7+! Rxf7 22.exf7 .)}) 13... Rb8 {Rf3 Again, it's best to defend the pawn. Qg1+ After the forced 19.Rf1 , Black has a choice between a draw by repetition or 19...Qxg2 20.Qe3! Bc8 with an unclear position.} *

