ing theory.} Qc7 ({The main move. Black attacks the e5-pawn and forces a weakening of White's position. The alternative} 8... Bb7 {is also popular nowadays. Black wants to play ...c6-c5 and quickly solve the problem of the 'bad' light-squared bishop.}) 9. f4 {The queen has fulfilled its purpose on c7 and moves to a better square. On b6, the queen performs a number of functions:  * It controls the weakened a7-g1 diagonal.  * It threatens the double attack 10...Qb4+.  * It attacks the b2-pawn, complicating the development of the c1-bishop.  * It supports ...Ne3.  * It supports the attempt to exchange the light-squared bishops with ...Ba6. a3!? Qd3 The most natural choice. Nxf1 Rxf1} {We force matters. The aim is now to activate the bishop on c8. For this, Black first exchanges its white counterpart. Good alternatives are a5 and f5 .} Ba6 ({Here,} 9... c5 10. f5 {would be dangerous.}) 10. c4 f5 $1 ({An important move. Only in this way Black can obtain good counterplay. Why is it so crucial to act swiftly? Let's illustrate with a natural developing move:} 10... Be7 $2 11. b4 {. White aims to slowly strengthen the position, for example with Bb2 and O-O-O. Black lacks counterplay. If} f5 {follows now, Black is already too slow:} 12. Nd6+ Bxd6 13. exd6 {. Now,} c5 {is necessary, otherwise the light-squared bishop does not participate in the game, but after} 14. Be3 $16 {, White wins a pawn.}) 11. exf6 {d5 A fairly typical idea in the 6.Nxc6 variation. The f-pawn advances, distracting the white e-pawn, so that next the d-pawn can get involved in the action. In this specific position, White faces attacks on e4, c4, and f6. f7+ A natural move. The black king is dragged onto the battlefield, where the f1-rook is ready to join the attack. Grandmasters Paravyan and Alekseenko opted for this direct approach.} Kf7 12. f5 ({This looks deadly, but Black can defend. Let's consider a somewhat careless move to illustrate the dangers: Bxc4 fxe6 Kg8?? (necessary here was 17...Ke8, after which the battle is still open)} 12. Qf3 {. Now, Black can no longer avert checkmate.} h6 {is obviously too late because of Qf7 Kh7 Nf6 .}) ({The focus here is less on preventing Ng5+ (which was not the main threat), but more on securing the king's escape route. In many lines, having a flight square on h7 is crucial. For example, Black is now ready to capture the knight on e4, after which White would have to give perpetual check. The immediate dxe4?? does not work: Qd7 Be7 fxe6 Kg8 Qxe7+- . fxe6+ If White doesn't prevent it, Black can capture the knight and thereby force a perpetual:} 12. b3 {dxe4 Qd7+} Kg8 {Qxe6+ Kh7 Qg6+ Kg8 Qe6+= .}) 12... Kg8 {The king is not immune to perpetual check here, but a mating attack is not in sight. Nf6+} ({The direct attack leads to a draw. The piece sacrifice Be3!? was tested in the engine game SlowChess Blitz 2.5–RubiChess 2.1 [/variation/31423379/#/18/w], CCRL 2021. dxe4 Qxe4 Qb3 . There are other moves here that also end with White giving a perpetual. ( 19...Qa5+ 20.Bd2 Qc5 21.b3 is more complicated but also ends in equality.) e7} 12... Be7 {Qxe7 Qxc4 Rf2 Kh7 . Black is threatening ...Rhe8 with an attack on the king. Therefore, White now has to exchange queens. Afterward, we reach a balanced endgame with opposite-colored bishops, which rightly ended in a draw.}) {gxf6 Qg6+ Bg7 Rxf6 Otherwise, Black consolidates and wins. Qg1+ The only move! Qd4?? Qf7+ Kh7 Rxh6#! . Rf1 Kd2?? Qd4+ Kc2 Qxf6-+ .} 13. Qd4 {Qf7+ White has no better option than to give perpetual check. Kh7 Qf5+ Kg8=} *

