s. Black, at least temporarily, is preventing e4-e5 and threatening ...Bb4 with pressure on the white center. The starting position of the Sicilian Four Knights has now been reached. This method of play was first used in the second half of the 19th century. Early adopters included the masters Schiffers, Blackburne, Mieses, and Janowski. White now has a multitude of options.} 6. Nxc6 ({This initiates one of the sharpest and most complex variations in the Sicilian Four Knights. We will see very unusual positions that are unfamiliar from any other opening. 6.Nxc6 is the second most common move after 6.Ndb5. It is chosen primarily by players who are not comfortable transitioning into the Sveshnikov Variation after} 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bf4 e5 8. Bg5 {.}) 6... bxc6 ({Black would now like to play ...d7-d5 and would then have a solid position with good central control.} 6... dxc6 {leads to a queenless middlegame that is slightly better for White.} 7. Qxd8+ Kxd8 8. Bf4 $14 {. The main problem in Black's position is the passive bishop on c8.}) 7. e5 {The critical move. White prevents ...d7-d5 – the d7 pawn is now backward. In addition, White prepares to put pressure on the weakened d6-square. A third advantage from White's perspective is that a defender of the kingside is driven away, making future attacks there more promising. Of course, the pawn move also has its drawbacks. We will see in the following variations that the pawn on e5 itself becomes a target of Black's counterplay. White will have to accept weaknesses in their own camp to defend the exposed pawn.} Nd5 8. Ne4 {White avoids exchanging knights and targets the weakened d6-square. A subsequent c2-c4 could drive the black knight away from its central position and also give the white queen access to d6. The main problem for Black is the bishop on c8, which is blocked by Black's own pawns and cannot be activated easily. In this tabiya, Black has tried a variety of options, some of which have established their place in opening theory.} Qc7 ({The main move. Black attacks the e5-pawn and forces a weakening of White's position. The alternative} 8... Bb7 {is also popular nowadays. Black wants to play ...c6-c5 and quickly solve the problem of the 'bad' light-squared bishop.}) 9. f4 {The queen has fulfilled its purpose on c7 and moves to a better square. On b6, the queen performs a number of functions:  * It controls the weakened a7-g1 diagonal.  * It threatens the double attack 10...Qb4+.  * It attacks the b2-pawn, complicating the development of the c1-bishop.  * It supports ...Ne3.  * It supports the attempt to exchange the light-squared bishops with ...Ba6. Bd3 The second most common move after 10.c4. White develops the bishop and defends against Black's threats.} Ba6 {The downside of White's last move. Black can now force the exchange of bishops.} 10. c4 $2 {It's too late for that. Qd4-+ Black wins at least one pawn while maintaining the better position. Qe2} ({Hopeless is cxd5} 10. Bd3 Nc3 {Bc5} 11. Qf3 {cxd5-+ . The white king cannot find safety, and Black already has an extra pawn. Roth–Steinhagen [/variation/31423378/#/14/b], Germany 2010 (0-1).}) 10... Rb8 ({This is even stronger than directly winning a pawn with} 10... Nb4 {. White is unable to break free.}) ({If White, after} 10... Rb8 {, prevents ...Nb4 with} 11. a3 {, then} Rb3 12. Nf2 Nxf4 {follows.}) *

