ing theory.} Qc7 ({The main move. Black attacks the e5-pawn and forces a weakening of White's position. The alternative} 8... Bb7 {is also popular nowadays. Black wants to play ...c6-c5 and quickly solve the problem of the 'bad' light-squared bishop.}) 9. f4 {The queen has fulfilled its purpose on c7 and moves to a better square. On b6, the queen performs a number of functions:  * It controls the weakened a7-g1 diagonal.  * It threatens the double attack 10...Qb4+.  * It attacks the b2-pawn, complicating the development of the c1-bishop.  * It supports ...Ne3.  * It supports the attempt to exchange the light-squared bishops with ...Ba6. Bd3 The second most common move after 10.c4. White develops the bishop and defends against Black's threats.} Ba6 {The downside of White's last move. Black can now force the exchange of bishops.} 10. Bxa6 {Qxa6 Qe2 Qxe2+} ({Black should acquiesce to the exchange of queens. Qb6?!} 10. c4 $1 Bb4+ {Kf1 f5 Nf2 is favorable for White. The black knight is driven to a bad square, whereas the white knight can go to d3, where it is placed well.}) {Kxe2} 10... f5 $1 {Black can't do without this move. The knight on e4 is too strong.} 11. Nf2 ({The knight usually ends up on d3 later, where it covers f4 and b4 and can potentially go to c5.} 11. exf6 {is harmless:} Nxf6 {followed by ...d7-d5 and ...Bd6. Black has at least equal chances.}) 11... c5 ({The main move} 11... Rb8 {is playable as well, but it's not so clear yet if the rook belongs there. It also takes away the option to castle queenside. With}) (11... c5 {, Black is threatening ...c5-c4, which would take away the d3 square from the knight. Therefore, White should play c2-c4 themselves.}) 12. c4 Nb4 {There's no other good square for the knight. From b4, it covers d3, so it can be exchanged for the white knight if needed, and it can potentially be transferred to d4 via c2.} 13. Bd2 ({Now, the exchange on b4 is no longer a concern for Black, as they can recapture with the a-pawn. White now appears somewhat more comfortable visually, but there is no breakthrough into Black's very solid position. A draw is the likely outcome. Black should avoid having to recapture on b4 with the c-pawn: After Be7?! Bxb4 cxb4} 13. Nd3 $14 {followed by c4-c5, the b4-pawn would be weak, and White could open the queenside at will with a2-a3. Driving away the knight with 17.a3 leads to a deterioration of White's pawn structure: After 17...Nc6= followed by ...a5-a4, the b2-pawn becomes backward.}) *

