1. e4 c5 {The Sicilian Opening stands for a sharp fight. Black somewhat neglects their piece development in order to prevent White from establishing a full pawn center with d2-d4.} 2. Nf3 e6 ({The third most common move after} 2... d6 {and}) (2... Nc6 {. With this, Black primarily prepares the development of the dark-squared bishop, but the center push ...d7-d5 becomes a possibility as well.}) (2... Nc6 {is an alternative way to reach the Four Knights Sicilian:} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6 {and we have landed in our repertoire via transposition. I decided against this path because White has a very serious and popular alternative in 3.Bb5 , the Rossolimo Variation. With 2...e6 the Rossolimo Variation is avoided.}) 3. d4 {The Open Sicilian and the starting position of this course. I examine alternatives for White on the second and third moves in a separate course on the Anti-Sicilians. The Open Sicilian is White's most principled attempt to fight for the opening advantage. White has more space and wants to open up the position, relying on rapid piece development. In return, Black gets the semi-open c-file, which can often be used for counterplay later on. Moreover, the exchange of the d-pawn for the c-pawn is a minor positional concession, as White now has only one pawn in the center and therefore can no longer fight quite as well for the important central squares.} cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 ({A very logical move - the knight is developed and simultaneously attacks the e4 pawn. Black takes advantage of the fact that the knight cannot be directly attacked with e4-e5 .} 4... Nc6 {is also possible, but gives White the additional option} 5. Nb5 {.}) 5. Nc3 ({Develops the knight and reinforces White's influence on the central square d5. Moreover, the diagonal a5-e1 is now interrupted, so that e4-e5 becomes a strong threat.} 5. e5 $2 {allows the double attack} Qa5+ {followed by -- Qxe5 .}) 5... Nc6 {Another natural developing move that continues the fight for the central squares. Black, at least temporarily, is preventing e4-e5 and threatening ...Bb4 with pressure on the white center. The starting position of the Sicilian Four Knights has now been reached. This method of play was first used in the second half of the 19th century. Early adopters included the masters Schiffers, Blackburne, Mieses, and Janowski. White now has a multitude of options.} 6. Be2 {on a3. In the Four Knights Sicilian, Be2 is typically associated with a pawn sacrifice. After its acceptance, White gets dangerous compensation, but objectively, Black has nothing to fear. However, it is important to know some central ideas to neutralize White's initiative. These ideas are well-known by now, which is why Be2 has lost popularity in grandmaster practice.} Bb4 7. Nxc6 ({Black is threatening to win a pawn on e4. Usually, White ignores this threat and still plays} 7. O-O {. Other moves are not dangerous.}) {Often played, but not dangerous.} 7... bxc6 {It's usually better to capture with the b-pawn to strengthen control in the center. Black now wants to play ...d7-d5.} 8. e5 $6 {Compared to 6.Nxc6 bxc6 7.e5 , the inclusion of the moves Be2 and ...Bb4 is favorable for Black.} Ne4 $1 9. Bd2 ({This is a bit more precise than the more natural-looking 8...Nd5. From e4, the knight also covers the square d2, so} 9. Bd2 {is no longer a satisfactory defense against the attack on c3. 8...Nd5 9.Bd2= .}) 9... Nxd2 10. Qxd2 Qa5 {Black is clearly better. White is missing the dark-squared bishop. Good ideas include ...Rb8 to exert pressure on b2, and castling followed by ...f7-f6, to establish a powerful pawn center.} *

