s. Black, at least temporarily, is preventing e4-e5 and threatening ...Bb4 with pressure on the white center. The starting position of the Sicilian Four Knights has now been reached. This method of play was first used in the second half of the 19th century. Early adopters included the masters Schiffers, Blackburne, Mieses, and Janowski. White now has a multitude of options.} 6. Be2 {on a3. In the Four Knights Sicilian, Be2 is typically associated with a pawn sacrifice. After its acceptance, White gets dangerous compensation, but objectively, Black has nothing to fear. However, it is important to know some central ideas to neutralize White's initiative. These ideas are well-known by now, which is why Be2 has lost popularity in grandmaster practice.} Bb4 7. Nxc6 ({Black is threatening to win a pawn on e4. Usually, White ignores this threat and still plays} 7. O-O {. Other moves are not dangerous.}) {Often played, but not dangerous.} 7... bxc6 {It's usually better to capture with the b-pawn to strengthen control in the center. Black now wants to play ...d7-d5.} 8. e5 $6 {Compared to 6.Nxc6 bxc6 7.e5 , the inclusion of the moves Be2 and ...Bb4 is favorable for Black.} Ne4 $1 9. Qd4 {A small tactic which allows Black to maintain the initiative. Bd2? This defense has been chosen in most games.} Nd2 10. Kxd2 (10. Qxd2 {simply loses a pawn to Qxe5-+ .}) 10... Rb8 {, but even worse for White as their king comes under fire. Black is threatening Bc5 with a double attack on b2 and d4. If White defends against this, it is a good idea to play Be7 followed by f7-f6 to open up the position.} *

