s. Black, at least temporarily, is preventing e4-e5 and threatening ...Bb4 with pressure on the white center. The starting position of the Sicilian Four Knights has now been reached. This method of play was first used in the second half of the 19th century. Early adopters included the masters Schiffers, Blackburne, Mieses, and Janowski. White now has a multitude of options.} 6. Be2 {on a3. In the Four Knights Sicilian, Be2 is typically associated with a pawn sacrifice. After its acceptance, White gets dangerous compensation, but objectively, Black has nothing to fear. However, it is important to know some central ideas to neutralize White's initiative. These ideas are well-known by now, which is why Be2 has lost popularity in grandmaster practice.} Bb4 7. Nxc6 ({Black is threatening to win a pawn on e4. Usually, White ignores this threat and still plays} 7. O-O {. Other moves are not dangerous.}) {Often played, but not dangerous.} 7... bxc6 {It's usually better to capture with the b-pawn to strengthen control in the center. Black now wants to play ...d7-d5.} 8. e5 $6 {Compared to 6.Nxc6 bxc6 7.e5 , the inclusion of the moves Be2 and ...Bb4 is favorable for Black.} Ne4 $1 9. Qd4 ({This is a bit more precise than the more natural-looking 8...Nd5. From e4, the knight also covers the square d2, so} 9. Bd2 {is no longer a satisfactory defense against the attack on c3. 8...Nd5 9.Bd2= .}) 9... Qa5 {A small tactic which allows Black to maintain the initiative.} 10. a3 $1 ({The only satisfactory defense against the threat of ...Nxc3. After} 10. Qxe4 $2 {, of course,} Bxc3+ {follows. If White recaptures, the rook on a1 is lost, and a king move is met with 11...Bxe5.}) 10... Bxc3+ ({After} 10... Nxc3 $2 {,} 11. Qxb4 $16 {follows.}) 11. bxc3 Nxc3 {Black has won a pawn and is slightly better. The game could continue with:} 12. Bd3 {, Saint Petersburg Bf3 was played. The Russian grandmaster immediately deviated from the best path with} {½-½} Nb5+ $2 {. After} 13. Qb4 {, White was better. The strongest continuation was instead 12...Nb1+! 13.Kd1 (best) 13...Nc3+ 14.Ke1 . Draw by repetition? 14...Nd5+ No! The purpose of the two previous checks was to deprive White of the right to castle. 15.Bd2 Qb6 and White has no compensation for the pawn. c5 Qg4 The bishop is very strong on the long diagonal. Therefore, capturing on g7 is not a good idea for White. Black would castle queenside and bring a rook to g8, attacking g2. Bd2 Forced. White was threatening to win material with 15.Qc4. Qxc4? Qxe5+-+ Black retains the extra pawn, and after the knight moves, the rook on a1 will be hanging.} *

