s. Black, at least temporarily, is preventing e4-e5 and threatening ...Bb4 with pressure on the white center. The starting position of the Sicilian Four Knights has now been reached. This method of play was first used in the second half of the 19th century. Early adopters included the masters Schiffers, Blackburne, Mieses, and Janowski. White now has a multitude of options.} 6. Be2 {on a3. In the Four Knights Sicilian, Be2 is typically associated with a pawn sacrifice. After its acceptance, White gets dangerous compensation, but objectively, Black has nothing to fear. However, it is important to know some central ideas to neutralize White's initiative. These ideas are well-known by now, which is why Be2 has lost popularity in grandmaster practice.} Bb4 7. Qd3 ({Black is threatening to win a pawn on e4. Usually, White ignores this threat and still plays} 7. O-O {. Other moves are not dangerous.}) {Protects the pawn on e4. Via the third rank, the queen can also occasionally swing to the kingside to support an attack there.} 7... O-O 8. O-O Ne5 $5 ({With this move, Black maintains a bit more tension in the position than with the typical equalizer} 8... d5 {. After that,} 9. exd5 exd5 {leads to a balanced position with an isolated queen's pawn.}) 9. Qg3 ({The most active square for the queen. However, a downside is that from here, she no longer covers the e4-pawn, making ...Bxc3 followed by ...Nxe4 a possibility again. Another option is} 9. Qe3 {, but the queen is not particularly well-placed here and blocks the c1 bishop. After ...d7-d6, Black has comfortable play. The queenside can be developed, for example with ...Bd7 and ...Rc8.}) 9... d6 {Protects the knight and renews the threat of ...Bxc3 followed by ...Nxe4.} 10. Bg5 {Rad1} ({Clears the way for the rook. Black is ready to apply pressure on the c-file with ...Rc8. After Bxc3 , the intermediate move Bxf6! follows. ( 11.Qxc3?! allows 11...Nxe4! .) Qxf6 Qxc3 , and the position is slightly more comfortable for White. This inconspicuous move covers the knight on d4 and thus poses the dangerous threat of f2-f4. Black must now respond precisely. The direct} 10. f4 $2 {is weak because Black has} Bc5 $1 {and can exploit the pin. The defense of the knight would now be too late: Rad1 Nc6 , winning material.}) 10... Ng6 11. Z0 ({Black takes preventive mesasures against f2-f4. The position is equal. Natural next moves for Black include ...h7-h6, ...Bxc3, or ...Rc8. White is still busy defending the e4-pawn. If White plays} 11. f4 $6 {anyway, Black responds with} Bxc3 $1 12. Bxf6 {( 13.Qxc3? Nxe4 $17 )} Qxf6 13. bxc3 e5 14. fxe5 Qxe5 {and has the better pawn structure. After the careless 11...Rc8? , White gets a strong attack with 12.f4! , for example, 12...Bxc3 ( 12...Ng6 13.f5+- ) 13.bxc3 Nc4 14.Bd3 $16 , threatening e4-e5.}) *

