s. Black, at least temporarily, is preventing e4-e5 and threatening ...Bb4 with pressure on the white center. The starting position of the Sicilian Four Knights has now been reached. This method of play was first used in the second half of the 19th century. Early adopters included the masters Schiffers, Blackburne, Mieses, and Janowski. White now has a multitude of options.} 6. Be2 {on a3. In the Four Knights Sicilian, Be2 is typically associated with a pawn sacrifice. After its acceptance, White gets dangerous compensation, but objectively, Black has nothing to fear. However, it is important to know some central ideas to neutralize White's initiative. These ideas are well-known by now, which is why Be2 has lost popularity in grandmaster practice.} Bb4 7. O-O ({Black should accept the invitation. White was already threatening to exchange on c6 and play e4-e5.} 7. O-O $6 {Nxc6 bxc6} e5 8. Nd5 Nxe4 $16 {. The position resembles the variation 6.Nxc6 bxc6 7.e5 Nd5 8.Ne4 , but it's a favorable version for White. Black has a backward pawn on d7 and problems activating the c8-bishop.}) {Nxc6 dxc6! bxc6?! bxc3 Nxe4?! Qd4! . We already investigated this position [/variation/31423092/#/8/b/0.9] via the move order 7.Nxc6 bxc6 8.O-O Bxc3?! 9.bxc3 Nxe4?! 10.Qd4! . Qxd8+ Kxd8 bxc3} 7... Nxe4 {We analyze this position [/variation/31423096/#/10/b] via the more popular move order 8.bxc3 Nxe4 9.Nxc6 dxc6 10.Qxd8+ Kxd8 .} *

