1. e4 c5 {The Sicilian Opening stands for a sharp fight. Black somewhat neglects their piece development in order to prevent White from establishing a full pawn center with d2-d4.} 2. Nf3 e6 ({The third most common move after} 2... d6 {and}) (2... Nc6 {. With this, Black primarily prepares the development of the dark-squared bishop, but the center push ...d7-d5 becomes a possibility as well.}) (2... Nc6 {is an alternative way to reach the Four Knights Sicilian:} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6 {and we have landed in our repertoire via transposition. I decided against this path because White has a very serious and popular alternative in 3.Bb5 , the Rossolimo Variation. With 2...e6 the Rossolimo Variation is avoided.}) 3. d4 {The Open Sicilian and the starting position of this course. I examine alternatives for White on the second and third moves in a separate course on the Anti-Sicilians. The Open Sicilian is White's most principled attempt to fight for the opening advantage. White has more space and wants to open up the position, relying on rapid piece development. In return, Black gets the semi-open c-file, which can often be used for counterplay later on. Moreover, the exchange of the d-pawn for the c-pawn is a minor positional concession, as White now has only one pawn in the center and therefore can no longer fight quite as well for the important central squares.} cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 ({A very logical move - the knight is developed and simultaneously attacks the e4 pawn. Black takes advantage of the fact that the knight cannot be directly attacked with e4-e5 .} 4... Nc6 {is also possible, but gives White the additional option} 5. Nb5 {.}) 5. Nc3 ({Develops the knight and reinforces White's influence on the central square d5. Moreover, the diagonal a5-e1 is now interrupted, so that e4-e5 becomes a strong threat.} 5. e5 $2 {allows the double attack} Qa5+ {followed by -- Qxe5 .}) 5... Nc6 {Another natural developing move that continues the fight for the central squares. Black, at least temporarily, is preventing e4-e5 and threatening ...Bb4 with pressure on the white center. The starting position of the Sicilian Four Knights has now been reached. This method of play was first used in the second half of the 19th century. Early adopters included the masters Schiffers, Blackburne, Mieses, and Janowski. White now has a multitude of options.} 6. Be2 {on a3. In the Four Knights Sicilian, Be2 is typically associated with a pawn sacrifice. After its acceptance, White gets dangerous compensation, but objectively, Black has nothing to fear. However, it is important to know some central ideas to neutralize White's initiative. These ideas are well-known by now, which is why Be2 has lost popularity in grandmaster practice.} Bb4 7. O-O ({Black should accept the invitation. White was already threatening to exchange on c6 and play e4-e5.} 7. O-O $6 {Nxc6 bxc6} e5 8. Nd5 Nxe4 $16 {. The position resembles the variation 6.Nxc6 bxc6 7.e5 Nd5 8.Ne4 , but it's a favorable version for White. Black has a backward pawn on d7 and problems activating the c8-bishop.}) {bxc3} 7... Nxe4 8. Nxc6 ({Black has won a pawn and is threatening to capture another on c3. However, Black must be cautious: their king is still in the center, and White's pair of bishops can become very powerful. The most popular attempts for White are now} 8. Bd3 {and}) (8. Qd3 {. Additionally, the long-forgotten}) (8. Nxc6 {has been rediscovered in recent years, infusing the 6.Be2 variation with new life.}) {This move was already played by Alekhine in 1918 in one of the early games of the Pawn Sacrifice Variation. More than 100 years later, it is being used again by some strong grandmasters, starting with the blitz game Caruana–Mamedyarov [/variation/31423383/#/9/w], Saint Louis 2021.} 8... dxc6 $1 ({White can now either continue playing for an attack or opt for positional compensation for the pawn in a queenless middlegame. We already know that} 8... bxc6 $6 {is bad due to} 9. Qd4 $1 {. We've looked at this position [/variation/31423092/#/8/b/0.9] via the move order 7.Nxc6 bxc6 8.O-O Bxc3?! 9.bxc3 Nxe4?! 10.Qd4! .}) 9. Qxd8+ {A favorite of the young Uzbek grandmaster Shamsiddin Vokhidov. The strong pair of bishops and the lack of harmony in Black's camp provide White with compensation for the pawn.} Kxd8 10. Bf3 {Forces the knight to make a decision.} Nf6 ({Black would now like to play ...e6-e5. Then, the c8-bishop could be freely developed, and the king would be secure on c7.} 10... Nxc3 {leads to a pawn exchange after Bb2 Nd5 Bxg7 , which is favorable for White. The position is quite open, which benefits the white bishops.}) 11. Re1 {Black aims to play ...e6-e5 and later develop the bishop along the c8-h3 diagonal. Although the knight temporarily blocks the bishop, White has no pawn breaks and thus cannot disrupt Black's plan. c4} Kc7 {Bb2 e5! If White now wins back the pawn, Black will have better chances in the endgame due to a superior pawn structure. If White does not take on e5, Black will play ...f7-f6 and, if possible, ...Nc5 and ...Bf5 or ...Be6. Black is slightly better.} *

