6 {schlecht ist wegen} 9. Qd4 $1 {. Diese Stellung [/variation/21653665/#/8/b/0.9] haben wir über die Zugfolge 7.Nxc6 bxc6 8.O-O Bxc3?! 9.bxc3 Nxe4?! 10.Qd4! betrachtet.}) 9. Qxd8+ {A favorite of the young Uzbek grandmaster Shamsiddin Vokhidov. The strong pair of bishops and the lack of harmony in Black's camp provide White with compensation for the pawn.} Kxd8 10. Bf3 {Forces the knight to make a decision.} Nf6 ({Black would now like to play ...e6-e5. Then, the c8-bishop could be freely developed, and the king would be secure on c7.} 10... Nxc3 {leads to a pawn exchange after Bb2 Nd5 Bxg7 , which is favorable for White. The position is quite open, which benefits the white bishops.}) 11. Rd1+ Bd7 (11... Kc7 $2 {doesn't work due to} 12. Bf4+ {.}) 12. Bf4 {After other moves, White might play something like c3-c4 and would have a dominant position. With the knight move, Black manages to block the d-file and provide the knight with a nice outpost. Bg3} ({This prevents c3-c4 and solidifies the knight on d5. Black is now ready for ...Ke7, after which the rooks can be brought into the game. The bishop can be activated via e8 and g6 (after ...f7-f6). The position is equal. If instead Nxc3 , the black knight is pushed back, and White gets good compensation for the two pawns:} 12. Rd3 Nd5 {c4 Nb6} 13. Rb1 $14 {. Black's position is very passive. White can now transition into a drawish endgame:}) {a4 With this move, White regains the sacrificed pawn. Black must not allow c3-c4 and therefore should not capture on a4.} 12... Ke7 {axb5 cxb5} 13. Bd5 exd5 14. Z0 ({After} 14. Rxd5 {, an endgame with opposite-colored bishops arises, which should result in a draw.}) *

