s. Black, at least temporarily, is preventing e4-e5 and threatening ...Bb4 with pressure on the white center. The starting position of the Sicilian Four Knights has now been reached. This method of play was first used in the second half of the 19th century. Early adopters included the masters Schiffers, Blackburne, Mieses, and Janowski. White now has a multitude of options.} 6. Be2 {on a3. In the Four Knights Sicilian, Be2 is typically associated with a pawn sacrifice. After its acceptance, White gets dangerous compensation, but objectively, Black has nothing to fear. However, it is important to know some central ideas to neutralize White's initiative. These ideas are well-known by now, which is why Be2 has lost popularity in grandmaster practice.} Bb4 7. O-O ({Black should accept the invitation. White was already threatening to exchange on c6 and play e4-e5.} 7. O-O $6 {Nxc6 bxc6} e5 8. Nd5 Nxe4 $16 {. The position resembles the variation 6.Nxc6 bxc6 7.e5 Nd5 8.Ne4 , but it's a favorable version for White. Black has a backward pawn on d7 and problems activating the c8-bishop.}) {bxc3} 7... Nxe4 8. Nxc6 ({Black has won a pawn and is threatening to capture another on c3. However, Black must be cautious: their king is still in the center, and White's pair of bishops can become very powerful. The most popular attempts for White are now} 8. Bd3 {and}) (8. Qd3 {. Additionally, the long-forgotten}) (8. Nxc6 {has been rediscovered in recent years, infusing the 6.Be2 variation with new life.}) {Dieser Zug wurde bereits von Aljechin 1918 in einer der ersten Partien der Bauernopfer-Variante gespielt. Mehr als 100 Jahre später wird der Zug wieder von einigen starken Großmeistern angewendet, angefangen mit der Blitzpartie Caruana–Mamedyarov [/variation/21987671/#/9/w], Saint-Louis 2021.} 8... dxc6 $1 ({Weiß kann nun entweder weiter auf Angriff spielen, oder in einem damenlosen Mittelspiel auf positionelle Kompensation für den Bauern setzen. Wir wissen bereits, dass} 8... bxc6 $6 {schlecht ist wegen} 9. Qd4 $1 {. Diese Stellung [/variation/21653665/#/8/b/0.9] haben wir über die Zugfolge 7.Nxc6 bxc6 8.O-O Bxc3?! 9.bxc3 Nxe4?! 10.Qd4! betrachtet.}) 9. Bd3 {Qg4} {Best. White's bishops are very strong, so it's useful to exchange one of them. Nf6 was played in Alekhine-Verlinsky [/variation/31423382/#/10/b], Odesa 1918 (1-0). White applies pressure on the kingside. Ba3 is not dangerous. After Nxd3 cxd3 , although the black king is temporarily confined to the center, Black can, for instance, play b6 followed by ...c6-c5 and ...O-O. White doesn't have enough attacking resources.} Qf6 ({Instead,} 9... O-O {Ba3 b6 Bxc5 bxc5} 10. Re1 $14 {is dangerous. White is more active.}) 10. Bg5 $1 $13 {White must maintain the initiative, even at the cost of losing another pawn.} Qxc3 {Qg3} ({Prepares for the exchange on d3. ➤ Of course not} 10... O-O $4 {Bxh7 Kxh7 Qxc3+- .}) {➤ After Nxd3 , Rad1! follows.} 11. Bf4 {Nxd3 cxd3 I prefer this over the unclear 15...Rg8. Black is now ready to castle. White can and should recapture the two sacrificed pawns, but must give up the hope of a kingside attack. Be5 Otherwise, Black simply plays ...O-O with an advantage. Qg5 Bxg7} Rg8 12. Bh6 {Qxg3 fxg3} c5 {Once again, an equal endgame with opposite-colored bishops has arisen. Next, the bishop will be developed via d7 or b7.} *

