1. e4 c5 {The Sicilian Opening stands for a sharp fight. Black somewhat neglects their piece development in order to prevent White from establishing a full pawn center with d2-d4.} 2. Nf3 e6 ({The third most common move after} 2... d6 {and}) (2... Nc6 {. With this, Black primarily prepares the development of the dark-squared bishop, but the center push ...d7-d5 becomes a possibility as well.}) (2... Nc6 {is an alternative way to reach the Four Knights Sicilian:} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6 {and we have landed in our repertoire via transposition. I decided against this path because White has a very serious and popular alternative in 3.Bb5 , the Rossolimo Variation. With 2...e6 the Rossolimo Variation is avoided.}) 3. d4 {The Open Sicilian and the starting position of this course. I examine alternatives for White on the second and third moves in a separate course on the Anti-Sicilians. The Open Sicilian is White's most principled attempt to fight for the opening advantage. White has more space and wants to open up the position, relying on rapid piece development. In return, Black gets the semi-open c-file, which can often be used for counterplay later on. Moreover, the exchange of the d-pawn for the c-pawn is a minor positional concession, as White now has only one pawn in the center and therefore can no longer fight quite as well for the important central squares.} cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 ({A very logical move - the knight is developed and simultaneously attacks the e4 pawn. Black takes advantage of the fact that the knight cannot be directly attacked with e4-e5 .} 4... Nc6 {is also possible, but gives White the additional option} 5. Nb5 {.}) 5. Nc3 ({Develops the knight and reinforces White's influence on the central square d5. Moreover, the diagonal a5-e1 is now interrupted, so that e4-e5 becomes a strong threat.} 5. e5 $2 {allows the double attack} Qa5+ {followed by -- Qxe5 .}) 5... Nc6 {Another natural developing move that continues the fight for the central squares. Black, at least temporarily, is preventing e4-e5 and threatening ...Bb4 with pressure on the white center. The starting position of the Sicilian Four Knights has now been reached. This method of play was first used in the second half of the 19th century. Early adopters included the masters Schiffers, Blackburne, Mieses, and Janowski. White now has a multitude of options.} 6. Be2 {on a3. In the Four Knights Sicilian, Be2 is typically associated with a pawn sacrifice. After its acceptance, White gets dangerous compensation, but objectively, Black has nothing to fear. However, it is important to know some central ideas to neutralize White's initiative. These ideas are well-known by now, which is why Be2 has lost popularity in grandmaster practice.} Bb4 7. O-O ({Black should accept the invitation. White was already threatening to exchange on c6 and play e4-e5.} 7. O-O $6 {Nxc6 bxc6} e5 8. Nd5 Nxe4 $16 {. The position resembles the variation 6.Nxc6 bxc6 7.e5 Nd5 8.Ne4 , but it's a favorable version for White. Black has a backward pawn on d7 and problems activating the c8-bishop.}) {bxc3} 7... Nxe4 8. Qd3 ({Black has won a pawn and is threatening to capture another on c3. However, Black must be cautious: their king is still in the center, and White's pair of bishops can become very powerful. The most popular attempts for White are now} 8. Bd3 {and}) (8. Qd3 {. Additionally, the long-forgotten}) (8. Nxc6 {has been rediscovered in recent years, infusing the 6.Be2 variation with new life.}) {The second most popular move. White protects the c3-pawn and attacks the knight.} 8... d5 {Ba3} ({The knight interrupts the a3-f8 diagonal, so Black manages to castle. White should now aim to restore the material balance. More popular is} 8... Qa5 {Nb5 a6 Nd6 Nxd6 Bxd6 , leading to a complicated position.}) 9. Qb5 {Not very strong and rarely played, but it's useful to know the correct response.} Bd7 $1 ({Black should not worry about defending the b-pawn.} 9... Qd7 $6 10. Bd3 $1 {. A prophylactic move against the threat of ...Nxc3. White is better because Black now has no good way of bringing the king to safety. A)} Nxc3 $2 11. Qa5 Ne4 12. Bxe4 dxe4 13. Nb5 {leads to a loss of material. B) 12...O-O? 13.Qxd7 Bxd7 14.Bxe7+- . C) 12...Qxb5? 13.Nxb5 , and the threats Nc7+ or Bxe4 followed by Nd6+ are too strong.}) 10. Qxb7 Rb8 ({Pushes the white queen back.} 10... Nxc3 $6 11. Bd3 {is dangerous for Black.}) 11. Qa6 (11. Qxa7 Ra8 {forces the exchange of queens and leads to a slightly better endgame for Black. After Bxe7 Rxa7 Bxd8 Kxd8 c4 Nc3 , Black is threatening ...e6-e5, winning material.} 12. Re1 $15 {Ra4 Black regains the pawn on c4. White has pawn weaknesses on a2 and c2 and the black knight is very well placed, so Black has a small advantage.}) 11... Nxc3 {Now Black has time to capture this pawn.} 12. Bd3 Qb6 {Forces the exchange of queens. Without queens, Black does not have to worry about king safety anymore.} 13. Qxb6 axb6 {White still needs to demonstrate whether there is enough compensation for the pawn. Black has two good options to bring the king to safety and connect the rooks:  * ...f7-f6 and ...Kf7.  * ...Ne4/...Na4-c5 and ...O-O.} *

