s. Black, at least temporarily, is preventing e4-e5 and threatening ...Bb4 with pressure on the white center. The starting position of the Sicilian Four Knights has now been reached. This method of play was first used in the second half of the 19th century. Early adopters included the masters Schiffers, Blackburne, Mieses, and Janowski. White now has a multitude of options.} 6. Be2 {on a3. In the Four Knights Sicilian, Be2 is typically associated with a pawn sacrifice. After its acceptance, White gets dangerous compensation, but objectively, Black has nothing to fear. However, it is important to know some central ideas to neutralize White's initiative. These ideas are well-known by now, which is why Be2 has lost popularity in grandmaster practice.} Bb4 7. O-O ({Black should accept the invitation. White was already threatening to exchange on c6 and play e4-e5.} 7. O-O $6 {Nxc6 bxc6} e5 8. Nd5 Nxe4 $16 {. The position resembles the variation 6.Nxc6 bxc6 7.e5 Nd5 8.Ne4 , but it's a favorable version for White. Black has a backward pawn on d7 and problems activating the c8-bishop.}) {bxc3} 7... Nxe4 8. Qd3 ({Black has won a pawn and is threatening to capture another on c3. However, Black must be cautious: their king is still in the center, and White's pair of bishops can become very powerful. The most popular attempts for White are now} 8. Bd3 {and}) (8. Qd3 {. Additionally, the long-forgotten}) (8. Nxc6 {has been rediscovered in recent years, infusing the 6.Be2 variation with new life.}) {The second most popular move. White protects the c3-pawn and attacks the knight.} 8... d5 {Ba3} ({The knight interrupts the a3-f8 diagonal, so Black manages to castle. White should now aim to restore the material balance. More popular is} 8... Qa5 {Nb5 a6 Nd6 Nxd6 Bxd6 , leading to a complicated position.}) ({c4 White chips away at the strong black center and gets rid of the pawn weakness on c3. After Bf3} 8... Nd6 {, Black makes it harder for White to play the pawn break c3-c4 and is slightly better.}) {O-O The king is safe. Next, Black wants to play ...Re8 to unpin the knight on e7.} 9. Bf3 {Re8!} ({White doesn't need to rush with the exchange on d5. 12.Bf3 seems a bit more threatening than the most commonly played cxd5 . It's better to first unpin the knight and not cling to the extra pawn. After Ng5 cxd5 exd5} 9. Qe3 $1 {, the pressure on the e7-knight is very uncomfortable.}) {Bxe4 White regains the pawn but must part with the bishop pair in the process. dxe4 Qxe4 Nf5 The passive knight is activated or exchanged. Rfd1} 9... Nxd4 {Rxd4 Qf6= , ICCF The position is equal, and the opposite-colored bishops make a draw likely. Next, Black wants to develop the bishop with e6-e5 and Bf5.} *

