s. Black, at least temporarily, is preventing e4-e5 and threatening ...Bb4 with pressure on the white center. The starting position of the Sicilian Four Knights has now been reached. This method of play was first used in the second half of the 19th century. Early adopters included the masters Schiffers, Blackburne, Mieses, and Janowski. White now has a multitude of options.} 6. Be2 {on a3. In the Four Knights Sicilian, Be2 is typically associated with a pawn sacrifice. After its acceptance, White gets dangerous compensation, but objectively, Black has nothing to fear. However, it is important to know some central ideas to neutralize White's initiative. These ideas are well-known by now, which is why Be2 has lost popularity in grandmaster practice.} Bb4 7. O-O ({Black should accept the invitation. White was already threatening to exchange on c6 and play e4-e5.} 7. O-O $6 {Nxc6 bxc6} e5 8. Nd5 Nxe4 $16 {. The position resembles the variation 6.Nxc6 bxc6 7.e5 Nd5 8.Ne4 , but it's a favorable version for White. Black has a backward pawn on d7 and problems activating the c8-bishop.}) {bxc3} 7... Nxe4 8. Bf3 ({Black has won a pawn and is threatening to capture another on c3. However, Black must be cautious: their king is still in the center, and White's pair of bishops can become very powerful. The most popular attempts for White are now} 8. Bd3 {and}) (8. Qd3 {. Additionally, the long-forgotten}) (8. Nxc6 {has been rediscovered in recent years, infusing the 6.Be2 variation with new life.}) {More often, White places the bishop on d3 to keep the diagonal d1-h5 open for the queen. From f3, the bishop can exert pressure on the queenside.} 8... d5 (8... Nxc3 9. Qd3 Qf6 $1 {is possible, but White gets good play for the pawns after} 10. Be3 {.}) 9. Nxc6 (9. Bxe4 {is analyzed next via the move order [/variation/31423109/#/10/w] 9.Bd3 d5 10.Bxe4 .}) 9... bxc6 {Ba3 Nd6 Blocks the diagonal a3-f8 and prepares for ...O-O.} {The goal is to prevent Black from castling. Bxe4 once again transposes to the 9.Bd3 line, see this variation [/variation/31423111/#/11/w].} 10. Qd4 $1 {White manages to obtain counterplay in time.} O-O ({The king is now definitively safe. A good alternative is the untested} 10... f6 $5 {. This allows Black to retain the extra material, but it weakens the kingside. White has compensation for the pawn.}) 11. Qc5 ({Wins the exchange. Qf4 e5! and now White should revert to} 11. Qxb4 {, which after Nb5 Qxf8 Qxf8 Bxf8 Kxf8 leads to a position similar to the direct 13.Qc5. Instead, 14.Qxe5?! Nc4 15.Qe7 Qxe7 16.Bxe7 Re8 is better for Black. White has pawn weaknesses on the queenside, and the knight is well-placed on an outpost.}) {Nb5 Qxf8+ Qxf8 Bxf8 Kxf8} 11... Z0 ({Currently, Black has a slight material deficit, but the c3-pawn is likely to be lost soon. Additionally, the other white pawns on the queenside are weak. Another trump card for Black is the solid central pawn structure, which doesn't leave much room for the white rooks. White should therefore prepare a rook invasion on the b-file or target the weak a7-pawn. It's often a good idea for Black to move the king towards the queenside to defend against the white rooks. The position is dynamically equal, but I would prefer Black. ➤ If White now tries to hold onto the c-pawn with c4?! , the black knight disturbs the white rooks after} 11... Nxc3 $1 {and cannot be easily driven away, for instance,} 12. a4 Ba6 $1 13. Ra3 d4 14. Bxc6 Rc8 15. Bb5 Bb7 {followed by ...a7-a6 with an advantage for Black. ➤ Stronger is therefore 16.a4 , which led to an equal position after 16...Nd6 in the game Velimirovic–Vukic [/variation/31423389/#/15/b], Worow 1980 (0-1). Also good was 16...Nxc3 17.Ra3 d4 , leading to equality as well.}) *

