s. Black, at least temporarily, is preventing e4-e5 and threatening ...Bb4 with pressure on the white center. The starting position of the Sicilian Four Knights has now been reached. This method of play was first used in the second half of the 19th century. Early adopters included the masters Schiffers, Blackburne, Mieses, and Janowski. White now has a multitude of options.} 6. Be2 {on a3. In the Four Knights Sicilian, Be2 is typically associated with a pawn sacrifice. After its acceptance, White gets dangerous compensation, but objectively, Black has nothing to fear. However, it is important to know some central ideas to neutralize White's initiative. These ideas are well-known by now, which is why Be2 has lost popularity in grandmaster practice.} Bb4 7. O-O ({Black should accept the invitation. White was already threatening to exchange on c6 and play e4-e5.} 7. O-O $6 {Nxc6 bxc6} e5 8. Nd5 Nxe4 $16 {. The position resembles the variation 6.Nxc6 bxc6 7.e5 Nd5 8.Ne4 , but it's a favorable version for White. Black has a backward pawn on d7 and problems activating the c8-bishop.}) {bxc3} 7... Nxe4 8. Bd3 ({Black has won a pawn and is threatening to capture another on c3. However, Black must be cautious: their king is still in the center, and White's pair of bishops can become very powerful. The most popular attempts for White are now} 8. Bd3 {and}) (8. Qd3 {. Additionally, the long-forgotten}) (8. Nxc6 {has been rediscovered in recent years, infusing the 6.Be2 variation with new life.}) {This forceful move is the most popular choice here and has several advantages from White's point of view: The threat of ...Nxc3 is neutralized, as now only the queen would be attacked, not the bishop on e2 at the same time. In addition, from d3 the bishop keeps an eye on the black kingside, and the white queen can also attack the kingside via g4 or h5. Last but not least, the move comes with a tempo, allowing White to maintain the initiative.} 8... d5 {The knight is well placed on e4 and should be maintained there for the time being. Black's next goal is to castle, after which White would have little to show for being a pawn down. The main idea for White, therefore, is to stop Black from castling with Ba3. 10.Ba3 is the most common move, but the prior exchanges on e4 or c6 are also possible.} (8... Nxc3 $6 {is very risky. Black should rather focus on king safety and development.} 9. Nxc6 $5 {appeals to me more than the more popular 10.Qg4. After} dxc6 10. Qh5 {, Black is prevented from castling. In this open position, White's bishops are very strong, and it's not clear how Black can complete development.}) 9. Bxe4 dxe4 {Ba3} ({without the exchange on} 9... dxe4) ({Nxd4 The response} 9... Qa5 $4 {is effective against 10.Ba3, but it does not work here:} 10. Nxc6 bxc6 {( 12...Qxa3 13.Qd8#! ) Qd6 and White wins. The black king cannot find safety anymore.}) ({cxd4 Qa5 Forces a concession. Bd6 Qd5 Ba3 With a repetition of moves. However, Black does not have to agree to a draw.} 9... Bd7 {followed by castling queenside leads to an unclear position.}) *

