ked, not the bishop on e2 at the same time. In addition, from d3 the bishop keeps an eye on the black kingside, and the white queen can also attack the kingside via g4 or h5. Last but not least, the move comes with a tempo, allowing White to maintain the initiative.} 8... d5 {The knight is well placed on e4 and should be maintained there for the time being. Black's next goal is to castle, after which White would have little to show for being a pawn down. The main idea for White, therefore, is to stop Black from castling with Ba3. 10.Ba3 is the most common move, but the prior exchanges on e4 or c6 are also possible.} (8... Nxc3 $6 {is very risky. Black should rather focus on king safety and development.} 9. Nxc6 $5 {appeals to me more than the more popular 10.Qg4. After} dxc6 10. Qh5 {, Black is prevented from castling. In this open position, White's bishops are very strong, and it's not clear how Black can complete development.}) 9. Bxe4 dxe4 {Ba3} ({without the exchange on} 9... dxe4) ({Nxd4 The response} 9... Qa5 $4 {is effective against 10.Ba3, but it does not work here:} 10. Nxc6 bxc6 {( 12...Qxa3 13.Qd8#! ) Qd6 and White wins. The black king cannot find safety anymore.}) *

