1. e4 c5 {The Sicilian Opening stands for a sharp fight. Black somewhat neglects their piece development in order to prevent White from establishing a full pawn center with d2-d4.} 2. Nf3 e6 ({The third most common move after} 2... d6 {and}) (2... Nc6 {. With this, Black primarily prepares the development of the dark-squared bishop, but the center push ...d7-d5 becomes a possibility as well.}) (2... Nc6 {is an alternative way to reach the Four Knights Sicilian:} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6 {and we have landed in our repertoire via transposition. I decided against this path because White has a very serious and popular alternative in 3.Bb5 , the Rossolimo Variation. With 2...e6 the Rossolimo Variation is avoided.}) 3. d4 {The Open Sicilian and the starting position of this course. I examine alternatives for White on the second and third moves in a separate course on the Anti-Sicilians. The Open Sicilian is White's most principled attempt to fight for the opening advantage. White has more space and wants to open up the position, relying on rapid piece development. In return, Black gets the semi-open c-file, which can often be used for counterplay later on. Moreover, the exchange of the d-pawn for the c-pawn is a minor positional concession, as White now has only one pawn in the center and therefore can no longer fight quite as well for the important central squares.} cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 ({A very logical move - the knight is developed and simultaneously attacks the e4 pawn. Black takes advantage of the fact that the knight cannot be directly attacked with e4-e5 .} 4... Nc6 {is also possible, but gives White the additional option} 5. Nb5 {.}) 5. Nc3 ({Develops the knight and reinforces White's influence on the central square d5. Moreover, the diagonal a5-e1 is now interrupted, so that e4-e5 becomes a strong threat.} 5. e5 $2 {allows the double attack} Qa5+ {followed by -- Qxe5 .}) 5... Nc6 {Another natural developing move that continues the fight for the central squares. Black, at least temporarily, is preventing e4-e5 and threatening ...Bb4 with pressure on the white center. The starting position of the Sicilian Four Knights has now been reached. This method of play was first used in the second half of the 19th century. Early adopters included the masters Schiffers, Blackburne, Mieses, and Janowski. White now has a multitude of options.} 6. Be2 {on a3. In the Four Knights Sicilian, Be2 is typically associated with a pawn sacrifice. After its acceptance, White gets dangerous compensation, but objectively, Black has nothing to fear. However, it is important to know some central ideas to neutralize White's initiative. These ideas are well-known by now, which is why Be2 has lost popularity in grandmaster practice.} Bb4 7. O-O ({Black should accept the invitation. White was already threatening to exchange on c6 and play e4-e5.} 7. O-O $6 {Nxc6 bxc6} e5 8. Nd5 Nxe4 $16 {. The position resembles the variation 6.Nxc6 bxc6 7.e5 Nd5 8.Ne4 , but it's a favorable version for White. Black has a backward pawn on d7 and problems activating the c8-bishop.}) {bxc3} 7... Nxe4 8. Bd3 ({Black has won a pawn and is threatening to capture another on c3. However, Black must be cautious: their king is still in the center, and White's pair of bishops can become very powerful. The most popular attempts for White are now} 8. Bd3 {and}) (8. Qd3 {. Additionally, the long-forgotten}) (8. Nxc6 {has been rediscovered in recent years, infusing the 6.Be2 variation with new life.}) {This forceful move is the most popular choice here and has several advantages from White's point of view: The threat of ...Nxc3 is neutralized, as now only the queen would be attacked, not the bishop on e2 at the same time. In addition, from d3 the bishop keeps an eye on the black kingside, and the white queen can also attack the kingside via g4 or h5. Last but not least, the move comes with a tempo, allowing White to maintain the initiative.} 8... d5 {The knight is well placed on e4 and should be maintained there for the time being. Black's next goal is to castle, after which White would have little to show for being a pawn down. The main idea for White, therefore, is to stop Black from castling with Ba3. 10.Ba3 is the most common move, but the prior exchanges on e4 or c6 are also possible.} (8... Nxc3 $6 {is very risky. Black should rather focus on king safety and development.} 9. Nxc6 $5 {appeals to me more than the more popular 10.Qg4. After} dxc6 10. Qh5 {, Black is prevented from castling. In this open position, White's bishops are very strong, and it's not clear how Black can complete development.}) ({Ba3 ➤ Preparing castling with} 8... Ne7 $2 {does not work here:} 9. Bxe4 $16 {dxe4 Nb5 . The black king does not get to safety.}) ({➤ The frequently played} 8... Nxd4 $6 {cxd4 Qa5 also leads to a difficult position for Black after Qc1 or 12.Qf3!? . In the model game chapter, we examine the classic Geller–Khasin [/variation/31423250], which features a typical position with bishops of opposite colors.}) {Qc1 On another occasion, I advised against continuing to play for pawn grabbing. Here, however, it is correct to capture the pawn, especially as it comes with a tempo on the d4-knight. White was already threatening 12.Nb3 followed by c3-c4 to open up the position, which would have quickly become uncomfortable for the centralized black king.} 9. Nxc6 bxc6 {A welcome change in pawn structure. Black is now threatening ...c6-c5 followed by castling. Thus, the next move is practically forced. Bd6 f6! Black cannot castle and therefore brings the king to f7. This works because the white queen is somewhat misplaced and cannot directly reach h5. Qf4 Threatens 15.Bb4 and brings the queen to a more active position.} 10. Nxe4 $1 {The simplest approach. Black gives back one of the extra pawns in exchange for trading off a minor piece. Bxe4} dxe4 {Qxe4 Qd5 Qb4 a5 Qa3 Kf7 The king is safe here and no longer blocks the rooks' connection. White has some activity for the pawn, but the black position is very solid. Black doesn't have any worries.} *

