t for the central squares. Black, at least temporarily, is preventing e4-e5 and threatening ...Bb4 with pressure on the white center. The starting position of the Sicilian Four Knights has now been reached. This method of play was first used in the second half of the 19th century. Early adopters included the masters Schiffers, Blackburne, Mieses, and Janowski. White now has a multitude of options.} 6. Be2 {on a3. In the Four Knights Sicilian, Be2 is typically associated with a pawn sacrifice. After its acceptance, White gets dangerous compensation, but objectively, Black has nothing to fear. However, it is important to know some central ideas to neutralize White's initiative. These ideas are well-known by now, which is why Be2 has lost popularity in grandmaster practice.} Bb4 7. O-O ({Black should accept the invitation. White was already threatening to exchange on c6 and play e4-e5.} 7. O-O $6 {Nxc6 bxc6} e5 8. Nd5 Nxe4 $16 {. The position resembles the variation 6.Nxc6 bxc6 7.e5 Nd5 8.Ne4 , but it's a favorable version for White. Black has a backward pawn on d7 and problems activating the c8-bishop.}) {bxc3} 7... Nxe4 8. Bd3 ({Black has won a pawn and is threatening to capture another on c3. However, Black must be cautious: their king is still in the center, and White's pair of bishops can become very powerful. The most popular attempts for White are now} 8. Bd3 {and}) (8. Qd3 {. Additionally, the long-forgotten}) (8. Nxc6 {has been rediscovered in recent years, infusing the 6.Be2 variation with new life.}) {This forceful move is the most popular choice here and has several advantages from White's point of view: The threat of ...Nxc3 is neutralized, as now only the queen would be attacked, not the bishop on e2 at the same time. In addition, from d3 the bishop keeps an eye on the black kingside, and the white queen can also attack the kingside via g4 or h5. Last but not least, the move comes with a tempo, allowing White to maintain the initiative.} 8... d5 {The knight is well placed on e4 and should be maintained there for the time being. Black's next goal is to castle, after which White would have little to show for being a pawn down. The main idea for White, therefore, is to stop Black from castling with Ba3. 10.Ba3 is the most common move, but the prior exchanges on e4 or c6 are also possible.} (8... Nxc3 $6 {is very risky. Black should rather focus on king safety and development.} 9. Nxc6 $5 {appeals to me more than the more popular 10.Qg4. After} dxc6 10. Qh5 {, Black is prevented from castling. In this open position, White's bishops are very strong, and it's not clear how Black can complete development.}) ({Ba3 ➤ Preparing castling with} 8... Ne7 $2 {does not work here:} 9. Bxe4 $16 {dxe4 Nb5 . The black king does not get to safety.}) ({➤ The frequently played} 8... Nxd4 $6 {cxd4 Qa5 also leads to a difficult position for Black after Qc1 or 12.Qf3!? . In the model game chapter, we examine the classic Geller–Khasin [/variation/31423250], which features a typical position with bishops of opposite colors.}) {Qc1 On another occasion, I advised against continuing to play for pawn grabbing. Here, however, it is correct to capture the pawn, especially as it comes with a tempo on the d4-knight. White was already threatening 12.Nb3 followed by c3-c4 to open up the position, which would have quickly become uncomfortable for the centralized black king.} 9. Nb3 {The knight retreats with tempo, but is somewhat misplaced on b3.} Qc7 {Black is planning ...f7-f6 followed by ...Kf7. The knight on c3 can be defended with ...d5-d4 if necessary.} 10. Qe1 $5 {f4! Against the setup chosen by White, the plan with ...f7-f6 and ...Kf7 is too dangerous. Black therefore prepares for castling queenside. Qh4 Bb7 Black now threatens ...Qd8 followed by ...Qf6 and castling queenside. Rae1!} {After f5? e5 , the position remains closed and Black obtains a strong passed pawn in the center.} Qd8 {Qg3 Qd5} ({Once again threatening to castle queenside. Once Black's king is safe, White has little to show for being two pawns down. Qc7 and} 10... Qd7 {are also good.}) ({Qf6? , however, no longer works:} 10... f5 {e5} 11. Nd4 $1 {. Now the idea behind 16.Rae1 becomes clear. White is winning, for example} Nxd4 {Rxe5+ Kd7 Rfe1 , and White's attack breaks through.}) ({Qh4! White cannot afford to win a pawn with Qxg7? . After O-O-O followed by ...Rhg8, Black achieves a decisive attack against g2, for example Qxf7} 10... Ne5 $1 {or 19.Qg3 Rhg8 20.Qf3 Qxf3 21.Rxf3 Ne5 22.Rf2 Rxg2+ (or 22...Sf3+) 23.Rxg2 Nf3+ 24.Kf2 Nxe1 , winning material.}) ({Qd8 Black does not have to agree to a draw. After the adventurous} 10... Kd7 $5 {Bb2 , a very complicated position with chances for both sides has arisen.}) *

