ings us back to the note on the 6th move: 6...Bb4 7.Bg2 d5?! .}) 8. Nb3 ({White is unable to keep the knight in the center:} 8. Be3 $2 Bxd4 $1 9. Bxd4 e5 10. Bc5 d4 11. Nd5 Nxd5 12. exd5 Bh3 $1 {(12...Qa5+ leads to an advantage as well)} 13. Bxh3 Qxd5 {Due to the double attack, Blacks wins back the piece and is up a pawn. 13.Bf3 Qa5+ wins a pawn for Black as well.}) 8... Bb4 9. O-O ({Again, the e-pawn is under attack. White can either ignore this threat with} 9. O-O {or exchange on d5. Most of the time, both moves lead to the same position.}) 9... Bxc3 {The exchange is necessary to reduce the pressure on the center.} 10. bxc3 {exd5. exd5 exd5 This will be examined next via the move order [/variation/31423126/#/11/b] 10.exd5 exd5 11.bxc3 O-O .} *

[Event "The Venomous Four Knights Sicilian"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "2024.03.13"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) Fianchetto Variation (6.g3"]
[Black "7A | Fianchetto Variation wit"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B40"]
[PlyCount "22"]
[EventDate "2024.??.??"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.co"]

1. e4 c5 {The Sicilian Opening stands for a sharp fight. Black somewhat neglects their piece development in order to prevent White from establishing a full pawn center with d2-d4.} 2. Nf3 e6 ({The third most common move after} 2... d6 {and}) (2... Nc6 {. With this, Black primarily prepares the development of the dark-squared bishop, but the center push ...d7-d5 becomes a possibility as well.}) (2... Nc6 {is an alternative way to reach the Four Knights Sicilian:} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6 {and we have landed in our repertoire via transposition. I decided against this path because White has a very serious and popular alternative in 3.Bb5 , the Rossolimo Variation. With 2...e6 the Rossolimo Variation is avoided.}) 3. d4 {The Open Sicilian and the starting position of this course. I examine alternatives for White on the second and third moves in a separate course on the Anti-Sicilians. The Open Sicilian is White's most principled attempt to fight for the opening advantage. White has more space and wants to open up the position, relying on rapid piece development. In return, Black gets the semi-open c-file, which can often be used for counterplay later on. Moreover, the exchange of the d-pawn for the c-pawn is a minor positional concession, as White now has only one pawn in the center and therefore can no longer fight quite as well for the important central squares.} cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 ({A very logical move - the knight is developed and simultaneously attacks the e4 pawn. Black takes advantage of the fact that the knight cannot be directly attacked with e4-e5 .} 4... Nc6 {is also possible, but gives White the additional option} 5. Nb5 {.}) 5. Nc3 ({Develops the knight and reinforces White's influence on the central square d5. Moreover, the diagonal a5-e1 is now interrupted, so that e4-e5 becomes a strong threat.} 5. e5 $2 {allows the double attack} Qa5+ {followed by -- Qxe5 .}) 5... Nc6 {Another natural developing move that continues the fight for the central squares. Black, at least temporarily, is preventing e4-e5 and threatening ...Bb4 with pressure on the white center. The starting position of the Sicilian Four Knights has now been reached. This method of play was first used in the second half of the 19th century. Early adopters included the masters Schiffers, Blackburne, Mieses, and Janowski. White now has a multitude of options.} 6. g3 {White fianchettoes the bishop. An understandable approach – after many other moves, Black achieves quick pressure against the e4-pawn with ...Bb4. From g2, White's bishop supports the center and counteracts this plan. On the other hand, White uses two moves instead of just one for the bishop's development. Therefore, it's not surprising that this move is not particularly critical.} d5 ({Against most of the sidelines on move six, I recommend either 6...Bb4 or 6...d5. Here,} 6... Bb4 {is the most common move and is perfectly playable, but I find}) (6... d5 {more appealing, as it is more direct. Black accepts an isolated queen's pawn but gains active piece play in return.}) ({➤ After} 6... d5 {, White has two different approaches:} 7. exd5 {, which leads directly to the isolated queen's pawn, and 7.Bg2 , which maintains the tension in the center a bit longer.}) ({➤} 6... Bb4 7. Bg2 {. Black should now focus on development and play} O-O {. The popular 7...d5?! 8.exd5 Nxd5?! is not recommended ( 8...exd5! 9.Qe2! is slightly better for White.), as White can ignore the attack on c3: 9.O-O! . The g2 bishop exerts strong pressure on Black's position. White is clearly better and scores over 70% in practice.}) 7. Bg2 {Protects the e4-pawn and postpones the decision in the center.} Bc5 $1 ({The knight is first driven to a less favorable square before Black increases the pressure on the white center with ...Bb4. ➤ Black should avoid} 7... dxe4 $6 8. Nxc6 Qxd1+ 9. Kxd1 bxc6 10. Nxe4 {, after which the g2-bishop exerts strong pressure on the black queenside.}) ({➤ The direct} 7... Bb4 {is dubious and brings us back to the note on the 6th move: 6...Bb4 7.Bg2 d5?! .}) 8. Nb3 ({White is unable to keep the knight in the center:} 8. Be3 $2 Bxd4 $1 9. Bxd4 e5 10. Bc5 d4 11. Nd5 Nxd5 12. exd5 Bh3 $1 {(12...Qa5+ leads to an advantage as well)} 13. Bxh3 Qxd5 {Due to the double attack, Blacks wins back the piece and is up a pawn. 13.Bf3 Qa5+ wins a pawn for Black as well.}) 8... Bb4 9. O-O ({Again, the e-pawn is under attack. White can either ignore this threat with} 9. O-O {or exchange on d5. Most of the time, both moves lead to the same position.}) 9... Bxc3 {The exchange is necessary to reduce the pressure on the center.} 10. exd5 ({Nxd5? is a positional mistake.} 10. bxc3 O-O {( 11...Nxc3? 12.Qf3 followed by Ba3 gives White a winning position.)} 11. c4 $16 {. The c8-bishop is passive and the knights do not have good outposts. The black queenside is under pressure, as the bishop on g2 is very strong.}) {bxc3} 10... O-O {In contrast to 10...Nxd5 , here Black has good squares for the minor pieces.} 11. Bg5 {Bxf6 Qxf6} Qxd5 {Qxc3 The position is equal. In White's camp, the pawn on c2 is weak, while Black has a weakness on b7.} *

