s. Black, at least temporarily, is preventing e4-e5 and threatening ...Bb4 with pressure on the white center. The starting position of the Sicilian Four Knights has now been reached. This method of play was first used in the second half of the 19th century. Early adopters included the masters Schiffers, Blackburne, Mieses, and Janowski. White now has a multitude of options.} 6. g3 {White fianchettoes the bishop. An understandable approach – after many other moves, Black achieves quick pressure against the e4-pawn with ...Bb4. From g2, White's bishop supports the center and counteracts this plan. On the other hand, White uses two moves instead of just one for the bishop's development. Therefore, it's not surprising that this move is not particularly critical.} d5 ({Against most of the sidelines on move six, I recommend either 6...Bb4 or 6...d5. Here,} 6... Bb4 {is the most common move and is perfectly playable, but I find}) (6... d5 {more appealing, as it is more direct. Black accepts an isolated queen's pawn but gains active piece play in return.}) ({➤ After} 6... d5 {, White has two different approaches:} 7. exd5 {, which leads directly to the isolated queen's pawn, and 7.Bg2 , which maintains the tension in the center a bit longer.}) ({➤} 6... Bb4 7. Bg2 {. Black should now focus on development and play} O-O {. The popular 7...d5?! 8.exd5 Nxd5?! is not recommended ( 8...exd5! 9.Qe2! is slightly better for White.), as White can ignore the attack on c3: 9.O-O! . The g2 bishop exerts strong pressure on Black's position. White is clearly better and scores over 70% in practice.}) 7. exd5 {The most common move. White immediately resolves the tension in the center.} exd5 ({The more frequently played} 7... Nxd5 {gives Black a better pawn structure than 7...exd5, but White gains unpleasant pressure on the queenside:} 8. Bg2 Nxc3 9. bxc3 {. White can intensify the pressure with moves like Rb1 and Bf4. The bishop on g2 is very strong, reminiscent of the Catalan Opening.}) 8. Bg2 {This position can also be reached via two Anti-Sicilian variations: A) 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 e6 3.g3 . My recommendation against this and a possible transposition to the current position is the move sequence 3...d5 4.exd5 exd5 5.d4 cxd4 6.Nxd4 Nc6 7.Nc3 Nf6 8.Bg2 . B) The most common route is via the Closed Sicilian 1.e4 c5 2.Nc3 e6 3.Nge2 Nc6 4.g3 d5 5.exd5 exd5 6.Bg2 Nf6 7.d4 cxd4 8.Nxd4 . The g2-bishop puts pressure on the weak isolated pawn on d5. In the long run, White has the better chances here. Therefore, it's important for Black to play energetically. Black can take advantage of the fact that White has not yet completed development and the white king is still in the center.} Bg4 $1 ({The bishop is developed with tempo. In the analogous position [/variation/31423123/#/7/w] without the prior exchange on d5 (7.Bg2), I recommended ...Bc5. Now, that would be inaccurate due to} 8... Bc5 $6 9. Qe2+ $1 {. Black has no better option than to retreat the bishop.} Be7 10. Be3 $14 {.}) 9. Nde2 {Clears the way for the queen to attack the d5-pawn.} Bb4 {Black wants to exchange on c3. Due to the pin of the e2-knight, White must recapture with the pawn. This not only lessens the pressure on d5 but also leads to pawn weaknesses in White's camp.} 10. h3 {The right moment to exchange, as White cannot recapture with the knight. bxc3} Bf5 ({The best square for the bishop. From f5, it keeps an eye on the e4-square as well as the c2- and h3-pawns. ➤} 10... Bh5 $6 11. Rb1 $14 {. ( 12.Ba3? is premature due to 12...Qa5 $17 .) The b7-pawn is attacked, and Ba3 is a threat, preventing castling. There is now no good defensive move. After} Qd7 $6 {,} 12. Bg5 $16 {follows, and Black has no defense against Bxf6.}) ({➤ As Black has not yet castled,} 10... Bxe2 $6 {is not such a good idea either.} 11. Qxe2+ Qe7 12. Qxe7+ Nxe7 {Ba3 . The bishop pair gives White a slight advantage.}) {Ba3?! Prevents short castling. Qa5 Qc1 A necessary evil. The queen is poorly placed here. O-O-O The king is also safe on the queenside.} 11. O-O Be4 $15 ({The g2-bishop could later become very strong (for example, after exchanging the c3-pawn for the pawn on d5), and it is also an important defender of White's king position. Therefore, it makes sense to exchange it. Black has active, centralized pieces and the better pawn structure. Next, ...Re8 and ...Ne4 could follow. Black is slightly better. Capturing the pawn with} 11... Bxc2 $2 {is not advisable. After} 12. Qxc2 $16 {Qxa3 c4 , the position on the queenside opens up, and the black king gets exposed to an attack.}) *

