 Bg2 {This position can also be reached via two Anti-Sicilian variations: A) 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 e6 3.g3 . My recommendation against this and a possible transposition to the current position is the move sequence 3...d5 4.exd5 exd5 5.d4 cxd4 6.Nxd4 Nc6 7.Nc3 Nf6 8.Bg2 . B) The most common route is via the Closed Sicilian 1.e4 c5 2.Nc3 e6 3.Nge2 Nc6 4.g3 d5 5.exd5 exd5 6.Bg2 Nf6 7.d4 cxd4 8.Nxd4 . The g2-bishop puts pressure on the weak isolated pawn on d5. In the long run, White has the better chances here. Therefore, it's important for Black to play energetically. Black can take advantage of the fact that White has not yet completed development and the white king is still in the center.} Bg4 $1 ({The bishop is developed with tempo. In the analogous position [/variation/31423123/#/7/w] without the prior exchange on d5 (7.Bg2), I recommended ...Bc5. Now, that would be inaccurate due to} 8... Bc5 $6 9. Qe2+ $1 {. Black has no better option than to retreat the bishop.} Be7 10. Be3 $14 {.}) 9. Nde2 {Clears the way for the queen to attack the d5-pawn.} Bb4 {Black wants to exchange on c3. Due to the pin of the e2-knight, White must recapture with the pawn. This not only lessens the pressure on d5 but also leads to pawn weaknesses in White's camp.} 10. h3 Bxc3+ {The right moment to exchange, as White cannot recapture with the knight.} 11. bxc3 Bf5 ({The best square for the bishop. From f5, it keeps an eye on the e4-square as well as the c2- and h3-pawns. ➤} 11... Bh5 $6 12. Rb1 $14 {. ( 12.Ba3? is premature due to 12...Qa5 $17 .) The b7-pawn is attacked, and Ba3 is a threat, preventing castling. There is now no good defensive move. After} Qd7 $6 {,} 13. Bg5 $16 {follows, and Black has no defense against Bxf6.}) ({➤ As Black has not yet castled,} 11... Bxe2 $6 {is not such a good idea either.} 12. Qxe2+ Qe7 13. Qxe7+ Nxe7 14. Ba3 {. The bishop pair gives White a slight advantage.}) 12. O-O ({After} 12. Rb1 {, Black could either sacrifice the b7 pawn or defend it with} Qd7 {. After} 13. Bg5 $6 {, Black can simply respond with} Ne4 {. This is possible with the bishop on f5, but not with the bishop on h5 (after 11...Bh5 12.Rb1 Qd7 13.Bg5 Ne4 ) because then 14.Bxe4 dxe4 15.Qxd7+ Kxd7 16.Rxb7+ would follow.}) 12... Be4 {After the exchange of bishops, Black has comfortable equality and can play against White's weaknesses on the queenside. Without the bishop on g2, White cannot build up strong pressure against the d5-pawn.} 13. f3 $5 {The most dangerous attempt. However, White accepts a weakening of their own king's position and of the e3-square.} Bg6 14. Rb1 ({Black now needs to be careful. The attack against the b7-pawn is not the main threat. The direct} 14. Ba3 $6 {is ineffective due to} Qa5 15. Qc1 O-O-O {.}) 14... O-O $1 ({Black doesn't have time to defend the pawn. White was threatening 15.Ba3, after which the black king would be in danger. ➤} 14... Qd7 $6 15. Bg5 {followed by Bxf6 would cause problems for Black.}) ({➤} 14... b6 $6 15. Ba3 $1 {and Black can no longer castle kingside. Castling queenside is possible, but the king is not very safe there, as Black's queenside has been weakened by ...b7-b6.}) 15. Rxb7 Qa5 {Black has sufficient compensation for the pawn. All of White's pawns on the queenside are weak.} *

