1. e4 c5 {The Sicilian Opening stands for a sharp fight. Black somewhat neglects their piece development in order to prevent White from establishing a full pawn center with d2-d4.} 2. Nf3 e6 ({The third most common move after} 2... d6 {and}) (2... Nc6 {. With this, Black primarily prepares the development of the dark-squared bishop, but the center push ...d7-d5 becomes a possibility as well.}) (2... Nc6 {is an alternative way to reach the Four Knights Sicilian:} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6 {and we have landed in our repertoire via transposition. I decided against this path because White has a very serious and popular alternative in 3.Bb5 , the Rossolimo Variation. With 2...e6 the Rossolimo Variation is avoided.}) 3. d4 {The Open Sicilian and the starting position of this course. I examine alternatives for White on the second and third moves in a separate course on the Anti-Sicilians. The Open Sicilian is White's most principled attempt to fight for the opening advantage. White has more space and wants to open up the position, relying on rapid piece development. In return, Black gets the semi-open c-file, which can often be used for counterplay later on. Moreover, the exchange of the d-pawn for the c-pawn is a minor positional concession, as White now has only one pawn in the center and therefore can no longer fight quite as well for the important central squares.} cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 ({A very logical move - the knight is developed and simultaneously attacks the e4 pawn. Black takes advantage of the fact that the knight cannot be directly attacked with e4-e5 .} 4... Nc6 {is also possible, but gives White the additional option} 5. Nb5 {.}) 5. Nc3 ({Develops the knight and reinforces White's influence on the central square d5. Moreover, the diagonal a5-e1 is now interrupted, so that e4-e5 becomes a strong threat.} 5. e5 $2 {allows the double attack} Qa5+ {followed by -- Qxe5 .}) 5... Nc6 {Another natural developing move that continues the fight for the central squares. Black, at least temporarily, is preventing e4-e5 and threatening ...Bb4 with pressure on the white center. The starting position of the Sicilian Four Knights has now been reached. This method of play was first used in the second half of the 19th century. Early adopters included the masters Schiffers, Blackburne, Mieses, and Janowski. White now has a multitude of options.} 6. g3 {White fianchettoes the bishop. An understandable approach – after many other moves, Black achieves quick pressure against the e4-pawn with ...Bb4. From g2, White's bishop supports the center and counteracts this plan. On the other hand, White uses two moves instead of just one for the bishop's development. Therefore, it's not surprising that this move is not particularly critical.} d5 ({Against most of the sidelines on move six, I recommend either 6...Bb4 or 6...d5. Here,} 6... Bb4 {is the most common move and is perfectly playable, but I find}) (6... d5 {more appealing, as it is more direct. Black accepts an isolated queen's pawn but gains active piece play in return.}) ({➤ After} 6... d5 {, White has two different approaches:} 7. exd5 {, which leads directly to the isolated queen's pawn, and 7.Bg2 , which maintains the tension in the center a bit longer.}) ({➤} 6... Bb4 7. Bg2 {. Black should now focus on development and play} O-O {. The popular 7...d5?! 8.exd5 Nxd5?! is not recommended ( 8...exd5! 9.Qe2! is slightly better for White.), as White can ignore the attack on c3: 9.O-O! . The g2 bishop exerts strong pressure on Black's position. White is clearly better and scores over 70% in practice.}) 7. exd5 {The most common move. White immediately resolves the tension in the center.} exd5 ({The more frequently played} 7... Nxd5 {gives Black a better pawn structure than 7...exd5, but White gains unpleasant pressure on the queenside:} 8. Bg2 Nxc3 9. bxc3 {. White can intensify the pressure with moves like Rb1 and Bf4. The bishop on g2 is very strong, reminiscent of the Catalan Opening.}) 8. Bg2 {This position can also be reached via two Anti-Sicilian variations: A) 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 e6 3.g3 . My recommendation against this and a possible transposition to the current position is the move sequence 3...d5 4.exd5 exd5 5.d4 cxd4 6.Nxd4 Nc6 7.Nc3 Nf6 8.Bg2 . B) The most common route is via the Closed Sicilian 1.e4 c5 2.Nc3 e6 3.Nge2 Nc6 4.g3 d5 5.exd5 exd5 6.Bg2 Nf6 7.d4 cxd4 8.Nxd4 . The g2-bishop puts pressure on the weak isolated pawn on d5. In the long run, White has the better chances here. Therefore, it's important for Black to play energetically. Black can take advantage of the fact that White has not yet completed development and the white king is still in the center.} Bg4 $1 ({The bishop is developed with tempo. In the analogous position [/variation/31423123/#/7/w] without the prior exchange on d5 (7.Bg2), I recommended ...Bc5. Now, that would be inaccurate due to} 8... Bc5 $6 9. Qe2+ $1 {. Black has no better option than to retreat the bishop.} Be7 10. Be3 $14 {.}) 9. Qd3 Bc5 $1 {The next bishop is developed with tempo. White now has to make a concession.} 10. Qe3+ {The queen is not well placed here.} Ne7 (10... Be7 {and}) (10... Kf8 {are also good moves.}) ({But not} 10... Kd7 $6 11. Nxc6 Bxe3 12. Nxd8 Bxc1 13. Rxc1 {. Black retains the weakness on d5 and is somewhat worse.}) 11. O-O O-O {Now ...Nf5 is a threat.} 12. Qd3 Bxd4 ({This exchange allows us to execute the advantageous ...d5-d4.} 12... h6 {is also good.}) 13. Qxd4 Nc6 {Through a curious transposition of moves, we have arrived at a position usually reached via the Vienna Game: 1.e4 e5 2.Nc3 Nf6 3.g3 Bc5 4.Bg2 c6 5.Nge2 d5 6.exd5 cxd5 7.d4 exd4 8.Nxd4 O-O 9.O-O Bg4 10.Qd3 Bxd4 11.Qxd4 Nc6 .} 14. Qf4 Qd7 {Black plans ...Bh3 to exchange the light-squared bishops. The bishop on g2 exerts pressure against the d5 pawn and defends White's king's position.} 15. Re1 Bh3 16. Z0 ({Black is already slightly better. After the exchange of bishops, White's king position and control of the center are weakened. Black can play ...d5-d4 at an opportune moment. If White avoids the exchange of bishops with} 16. Bh1 {, the black bishop on h3 ensures that the white king feels uncomfortable.} Rae8 17. Bd2 Re6 $17 {.}) *

