 Bg2 {This position can also be reached via two Anti-Sicilian variations: A) 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 e6 3.g3 . My recommendation against this and a possible transposition to the current position is the move sequence 3...d5 4.exd5 exd5 5.d4 cxd4 6.Nxd4 Nc6 7.Nc3 Nf6 8.Bg2 . B) The most common route is via the Closed Sicilian 1.e4 c5 2.Nc3 e6 3.Nge2 Nc6 4.g3 d5 5.exd5 exd5 6.Bg2 Nf6 7.d4 cxd4 8.Nxd4 . The g2-bishop puts pressure on the weak isolated pawn on d5. In the long run, White has the better chances here. Therefore, it's important for Black to play energetically. Black can take advantage of the fact that White has not yet completed development and the white king is still in the center.} Bg4 $1 ({The bishop is developed with tempo. In the analogous position [/variation/31423123/#/7/w] without the prior exchange on d5 (7.Bg2), I recommended ...Bc5. Now, that would be inaccurate due to} 8... Bc5 $6 9. Qe2+ $1 {. Black has no better option than to retreat the bishop.} Be7 10. Be3 $14 {.}) 9. Qd3 Bc5 $1 {The next bishop is developed with tempo. White now has to make a concession.} 10. Qe3+ {The queen is not well placed here.} Ne7 (10... Be7 {and}) (10... Kf8 {are also good moves.}) ({But not} 10... Kd7 $6 11. Nxc6 Bxe3 12. Nxd8 Bxc1 13. Rxc1 {. Black retains the weakness on d5 and is somewhat worse.}) 11. O-O O-O {Now ...Nf5 is a threat.} 12. Qd3 Bxd4 ({This exchange allows us to execute the advantageous ...d5-d4.} 12... h6 {is also good.}) 13. Qxd4 Nc6 {Through a curious transposition of moves, we have arrived at a position usually reached via the Vienna Game: 1.e4 e5 2.Nc3 Nf6 3.g3 Bc5 4.Bg2 c6 5.Nge2 d5 6.exd5 cxd5 7.d4 exd4 8.Nxd4 O-O 9.O-O Bg4 10.Qd3 Bxd4 11.Qxd4 Nc6 .} 14. Qc5 d4 {This gains Black space and places the pawn on a square where it is less vulnerable to attack by White's pieces.} 15. Ne4 Nxe4 16. Bxe4 Re8 17. Z0 ({Black has the initiative. The light squares on the kingside are weakened, which can be exploited by moves like ...Ne5-f3+. Additionally, Black can target the c2 pawn with ...Rc8.} 17. Bg5 f6 18. Qd5+ Kh8 $15 {occurred in the game Hinrichs–Schroeder [/variation/31423396/#/18/b], Karlsruhe 2019 (0-1). Exchanging queens now would not relieve White, as the black rook would then penetrate on e2.}) *

