 Bg2 {This position can also be reached via two Anti-Sicilian variations: A) 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 e6 3.g3 . My recommendation against this and a possible transposition to the current position is the move sequence 3...d5 4.exd5 exd5 5.d4 cxd4 6.Nxd4 Nc6 7.Nc3 Nf6 8.Bg2 . B) The most common route is via the Closed Sicilian 1.e4 c5 2.Nc3 e6 3.Nge2 Nc6 4.g3 d5 5.exd5 exd5 6.Bg2 Nf6 7.d4 cxd4 8.Nxd4 . The g2-bishop puts pressure on the weak isolated pawn on d5. In the long run, White has the better chances here. Therefore, it's important for Black to play energetically. Black can take advantage of the fact that White has not yet completed development and the white king is still in the center.} Bg4 $1 ({The bishop is developed with tempo. In the analogous position [/variation/31423123/#/7/w] without the prior exchange on d5 (7.Bg2), I recommended ...Bc5. Now, that would be inaccurate due to} 8... Bc5 $6 9. Qe2+ $1 {. Black has no better option than to retreat the bishop.} Be7 10. Be3 $14 {.}) 9. Qd3 Bc5 $1 {The next bishop is developed with tempo. White now has to make a concession.} 10. Nxc6 {White opts for rapid development with this move. The downside is that Black now 'corrects' the pawn structure.} bxc6 11. O-O O-O 12. Na4 {Other moves are inferior. The knight was no longer well-placed on c3 because d5 is securely defended.} Bd6 13. c4 {Sooner or later, White should opt for this break, as otherwise the effectiveness of the g2-bishop is limited by Black's pawns on c6 and d5.} Re8 {Threatening ...Be2.} 14. Be3 (14. Nc3 Rb8 {is also equal. After} 15. cxd5 Nxd5 {,} 16. Bxd5 $2 {might win a pawn, but it exchanges the defender of the weakened light squares around White's king and is therefore not a good idea. With 16.Nxd5? , White cannot win a pawn because Black has the intermediate move 16...Be2 .}) 14... Qa5 {Clears the way for the rook on a8.} 15. Nc3 Qa6 {Black has no worries and is even a bit more comfortable. ...Rad8 and ...Bd6 are now on the agenda.} *

