s. Black, at least temporarily, is preventing e4-e5 and threatening ...Bb4 with pressure on the white center. The starting position of the Sicilian Four Knights has now been reached. This method of play was first used in the second half of the 19th century. Early adopters included the masters Schiffers, Blackburne, Mieses, and Janowski. White now has a multitude of options.} 6. g3 {White fianchettoes the bishop. An understandable approach – after many other moves, Black achieves quick pressure against the e4-pawn with ...Bb4. From g2, White's bishop supports the center and counteracts this plan. On the other hand, White uses two moves instead of just one for the bishop's development. Therefore, it's not surprising that this move is not particularly critical.} d5 ({Against most of the sidelines on move six, I recommend either 6...Bb4 or 6...d5. Here,} 6... Bb4 {is the most common move and is perfectly playable, but I find}) (6... d5 {more appealing, as it is more direct. Black accepts an isolated queen's pawn but gains active piece play in return.}) ({➤ After} 6... d5 {, White has two different approaches:} 7. exd5 {, which leads directly to the isolated queen's pawn, and 7.Bg2 , which maintains the tension in the center a bit longer.}) ({➤} 6... Bb4 7. Bg2 {. Black should now focus on development and play} O-O {. The popular 7...d5?! 8.exd5 Nxd5?! is not recommended ( 8...exd5! 9.Qe2! is slightly better for White.), as White can ignore the attack on c3: 9.O-O! . The g2 bishop exerts strong pressure on Black's position. White is clearly better and scores over 70% in practice.}) 7. exd5 {The most common move. White immediately resolves the tension in the center.} exd5 ({The more frequently played} 7... Nxd5 {gives Black a better pawn structure than 7...exd5, but White gains unpleasant pressure on the queenside:} 8. Bg2 Nxc3 9. bxc3 {. White can intensify the pressure with moves like Rb1 and Bf4. The bishop on g2 is very strong, reminiscent of the Catalan Opening.}) 8. Bg2 {This position can also be reached via two Anti-Sicilian variations: A) 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 e6 3.g3 . My recommendation against this and a possible transposition to the current position is the move sequence 3...d5 4.exd5 exd5 5.d4 cxd4 6.Nxd4 Nc6 7.Nc3 Nf6 8.Bg2 . B) The most common route is via the Closed Sicilian 1.e4 c5 2.Nc3 e6 3.Nge2 Nc6 4.g3 d5 5.exd5 exd5 6.Bg2 Nf6 7.d4 cxd4 8.Nxd4 . The g2-bishop puts pressure on the weak isolated pawn on d5. In the long run, White has the better chances here. Therefore, it's important for Black to play energetically. Black can take advantage of the fact that White has not yet completed development and the white king is still in the center.} Bg4 $1 ({The bishop is developed with tempo. In the analogous position [/variation/31423123/#/7/w] without the prior exchange on d5 (7.Bg2), I recommended ...Bc5. Now, that would be inaccurate due to} 8... Bc5 $6 9. Qe2+ $1 {. Black has no better option than to retreat the bishop.} Be7 10. Be3 $14 {.}) 9. Qd3 Bc5 $1 {The next bishop is developed with tempo. White now has to make a concession.} 10. Be3 Qb6 $1 {White can no longer maintain the blockade on d4.} 11. h3 Bxd4 12. Qxd4 {hxg4 Qxd3 cxd3 Nxg4 The last few moves were relatively forced. White will recapture the pawn on d5 with an equal position.} *

