1. e4 c5 {The Sicilian Opening stands for a sharp fight. Black somewhat neglects their piece development in order to prevent White from establishing a full pawn center with d2-d4.} 2. Nf3 e6 ({The third most common move after} 2... d6 {and}) (2... Nc6 {. With this, Black primarily prepares the development of the dark-squared bishop, but the center push ...d7-d5 becomes a possibility as well.}) (2... Nc6 {is an alternative way to reach the Four Knights Sicilian:} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6 {and we have landed in our repertoire via transposition. I decided against this path because White has a very serious and popular alternative in 3.Bb5 , the Rossolimo Variation. With 2...e6 the Rossolimo Variation is avoided.}) 3. d4 {The Open Sicilian and the starting position of this course. I examine alternatives for White on the second and third moves in a separate course on the Anti-Sicilians. The Open Sicilian is White's most principled attempt to fight for the opening advantage. White has more space and wants to open up the position, relying on rapid piece development. In return, Black gets the semi-open c-file, which can often be used for counterplay later on. Moreover, the exchange of the d-pawn for the c-pawn is a minor positional concession, as White now has only one pawn in the center and therefore can no longer fight quite as well for the important central squares.} cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 ({A very logical move - the knight is developed and simultaneously attacks the e4 pawn. Black takes advantage of the fact that the knight cannot be directly attacked with e4-e5 .} 4... Nc6 {is also possible, but gives White the additional option} 5. Nb5 {.}) 5. Nc3 ({Develops the knight and reinforces White's influence on the central square d5. Moreover, the diagonal a5-e1 is now interrupted, so that e4-e5 becomes a strong threat.} 5. e5 $2 {allows the double attack} Qa5+ {followed by -- Qxe5 .}) 5... Nc6 {Another natural developing move that continues the fight for the central squares. Black, at least temporarily, is preventing e4-e5 and threatening ...Bb4 with pressure on the white center. The starting position of the Sicilian Four Knights has now been reached. This method of play was first used in the second half of the 19th century. Early adopters included the masters Schiffers, Blackburne, Mieses, and Janowski. White now has a multitude of options.} 6. a3 $5 {White prevents ...Bb4, reducing the possibilities for forcing play. Therefore, the move is particularly popular among players who want to avoid long theoretical battles. However, the downside is also clear: a2-a3 contributes little to White's development. It is therefore not surprising that Black gets good play with simple developing moves.} Be7 ({The main line. Compared to} 6... d6 {, Black thus keeps the option open to push the d-pawn directly to d5.}) 7. Nxc6 {The game now becomes very sharp, and the position is not without danger for Black. This is the reason why I prefer 6...d6.} (7. Be2 {is the most common move.} O-O 8. Be3 {. Now it would probably be best to transpose into a position that we analyze after 6...d6 with} d6 {. The alternative is 8...d5 , but I believe that after 9.exd5 Nxd5 10.Nxd5 Qxd5 11.Bf3 Qa5+ 12.b4 Qc7 13.Nxc6 bxc6 14.Qd3 $14 , White retains some pressure. The c6 pawn is weak.}) 7... bxc6 (7... dxc6 {leads to a slightly inferior endgame.} 8. Qxd8+ Bxd8 9. e5 $14 {, and Black will find it difficult to activate the bishop on c8.}) 8. e5 {The idea behind the previous knight exchange. Black now has hardly any defenders on the kingside.} Nd5 9. Qg4 {A typical move in opening positions with a white pawn on e5. Black has to make a concession to defend the pawn on g7.} g6 ({After} 9... O-O $5 10. Bh6 {, Black must play} g6 {. White could now win the exchange, but Black gets good play on the dark squares in return. Probably better is} 11. h4 {, leading to a sharp, unclear position.}) 10. Qg3 {This defends White against the threat of ...Nxc3. Additionally, the queen covers the pawn on e5. Objectively, Black's position is completely satisfactory. However, the weakened dark squares mean that the king is not safe. White can play for an attack, for example, with h2-h4-h5, Ne4, or Bh6. Great precision is required from Black.} *

