1. e4 c5 {The Sicilian Opening stands for a sharp fight. Black somewhat neglects their piece development in order to prevent White from establishing a full pawn center with d2-d4.} 2. Nf3 e6 ({The third most common move after} 2... d6 {and}) (2... Nc6 {. With this, Black primarily prepares the development of the dark-squared bishop, but the center push ...d7-d5 becomes a possibility as well.}) (2... Nc6 {is an alternative way to reach the Four Knights Sicilian:} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6 {and we have landed in our repertoire via transposition. I decided against this path because White has a very serious and popular alternative in 3.Bb5 , the Rossolimo Variation. With 2...e6 the Rossolimo Variation is avoided.}) 3. d4 {The Open Sicilian and the starting position of this course. I examine alternatives for White on the second and third moves in a separate course on the Anti-Sicilians. The Open Sicilian is White's most principled attempt to fight for the opening advantage. White has more space and wants to open up the position, relying on rapid piece development. In return, Black gets the semi-open c-file, which can often be used for counterplay later on. Moreover, the exchange of the d-pawn for the c-pawn is a minor positional concession, as White now has only one pawn in the center and therefore can no longer fight quite as well for the important central squares.} cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 ({A very logical move - the knight is developed and simultaneously attacks the e4 pawn. Black takes advantage of the fact that the knight cannot be directly attacked with e4-e5 .} 4... Nc6 {is also possible, but gives White the additional option} 5. Nb5 {.}) 5. Nc3 ({Develops the knight and reinforces White's influence on the central square d5. Moreover, the diagonal a5-e1 is now interrupted, so that e4-e5 becomes a strong threat.} 5. e5 $2 {allows the double attack} Qa5+ {followed by -- Qxe5 .}) 5... Nc6 {Another natural developing move that continues the fight for the central squares. Black, at least temporarily, is preventing e4-e5 and threatening ...Bb4 with pressure on the white center. The starting position of the Sicilian Four Knights has now been reached. This method of play was first used in the second half of the 19th century. Early adopters included the masters Schiffers, Blackburne, Mieses, and Janowski. White now has a multitude of options.} 6. a3 $5 {White prevents ...Bb4, reducing the possibilities for forcing play. Therefore, the move is particularly popular among players who want to avoid long theoretical battles. However, the downside is also clear: a2-a3 contributes little to White's development. It is therefore not surprising that Black gets good play with simple developing moves.} d6 {This is only the fourth most common move, but it avoids White's idea of Nxc6 followed by e4-e5 and thus seems simplest to me. The pawn structure in the center (e4 vs. d6+e6) can be reached in many Sicilian variations and is known as the Scheveningen structure. It is famous for complex and dynamic play, as both sides have many ideas and the structure in the center is not yet fixed. For example, Black could play ...e6-e5 or ...d6-d5 at the right moment – an important resource against aggressive flank attacks. From Black's point of view, this is a favorable version of the Scheveningen structure. This becomes clear when compared with the classical Scheveningen Variation: 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 d6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 e6 . In the current position, the additional moves a2-a3 and ...Nc6 are played. While the knight participates in the fight for the center, the pawn move on the edge is almost meaningless. The loss of tempo means that aggressive attacking moves like an early g2-g4 are not as effective here. While in the Scheveningen Variation, the direct 6.g4! is considered the most dangerous continuation, here 7.g4? fails due to the pawn loss after 7...Nxd4 8.Qxd4 Nxg4 . Therefore, White usually opts for the classical setup: Be3, Be2, O-O, and f2-f4. 6...Bc5?! Here the bishop is less well placed because White gains a decisive tempo after 7.Nxc6 bxc6? (better is 7...dxc6) 8.e5 Nd5 9.Ne4+- by attacking the bishop.} 7. Be3 {If White continues with Be2 and O-O, this is one of several ways to reach the main line. However, there are a few additional possibilities.} Be7 8. Be2 O-O 9. Qd3 {in the Candidates Tournament White aims to castle queenside and play for an attack on the kingside. O-O} Qc7 {is the main line. We consider this through the move order [/variation/31423159/#/9/b] 7.Be2 Be7 8.O-O O-O 9.Be3 Qc7 . Bd7 A useful waiting move. Black wants to first see what White plans and can then respond specifically to it. O-O-O Ne5 Qd2 Nfg4 Black takes advantage of the fact that the bishop on e3 cannot move because f2 would then be unprotected. Rc8 is also good. f4 Nxe3 Qxe3 Rc8 -- Black doesn't need to retreat the knight but can place it on the more active square c4. Black has no worries here. fxe5??} 10. Bg5 {loses the queen.} *

