s. Black, at least temporarily, is preventing e4-e5 and threatening ...Bb4 with pressure on the white center. The starting position of the Sicilian Four Knights has now been reached. This method of play was first used in the second half of the 19th century. Early adopters included the masters Schiffers, Blackburne, Mieses, and Janowski. White now has a multitude of options.} 6. a3 $5 {White prevents ...Bb4, reducing the possibilities for forcing play. Therefore, the move is particularly popular among players who want to avoid long theoretical battles. However, the downside is also clear: a2-a3 contributes little to White's development. It is therefore not surprising that Black gets good play with simple developing moves.} d6 {This is only the fourth most common move, but it avoids White's idea of Nxc6 followed by e4-e5 and thus seems simplest to me. The pawn structure in the center (e4 vs. d6+e6) can be reached in many Sicilian variations and is known as the Scheveningen structure. It is famous for complex and dynamic play, as both sides have many ideas and the structure in the center is not yet fixed. For example, Black could play ...e6-e5 or ...d6-d5 at the right moment – an important resource against aggressive flank attacks. From Black's point of view, this is a favorable version of the Scheveningen structure. This becomes clear when compared with the classical Scheveningen Variation: 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 d6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 e6 . In the current position, the additional moves a2-a3 and ...Nc6 are played. While the knight participates in the fight for the center, the pawn move on the edge is almost meaningless. The loss of tempo means that aggressive attacking moves like an early g2-g4 are not as effective here. While in the Scheveningen Variation, the direct 6.g4! is considered the most dangerous continuation, here 7.g4? fails due to the pawn loss after 7...Nxd4 8.Qxd4 Nxg4 . Therefore, White usually opts for the classical setup: Be3, Be2, O-O, and f2-f4. 6...Bc5?! Here the bishop is less well placed because White gains a decisive tempo after 7.Nxc6 bxc6? (better is 7...dxc6) 8.e5 Nd5 9.Ne4+- by attacking the bishop.} 7. Be3 {If White continues with Be2 and O-O, this is one of several ways to reach the main line. However, there are a few additional possibilities.} Be7 8. Be2 O-O 9. Qd3 {in the Candidates Tournament White aims to castle queenside and play for an attack on the kingside. O-O} Qc7 {is the main line. We consider this through the move order [/variation/31423159/#/9/b] 7.Be2 Be7 8.O-O O-O 9.Be3 Qc7 . Bd7 A useful waiting move. Black wants to first see what White plans and can then respond specifically to it. f4 Giri's choice, with which he proves to be well-prepared. Black gains control over the square g4. Nxc6 After} 10. Ndb5 {, Ng4 gives good counterplay. bxc6 O-O-O Ng4 Threatening both ...Nxe3 and ...exf4. Therefore, White should exchange. Bxg4 Bxg4 Rd2 Qa5 -- An important detail. White had threatened to trap the bishop with f4-f5, but this does not work when Black's queen is active on a5. Black is now threatening ...d6-d5 and ...Bxa3. If White prevents this, Black could move the bishop from g4 via c8 to a6, leading to a comfortable position. f5?} d5 $1 {threatening ...d5-d4, but also ...Bxa3 with a deadly attack: A)} 11. h3 Bxa3 $1 {hxg4 Bxb2+-+ . B) 16.exd5 Bxa3! and White is checkmated or loses material.} *

