s. Black, at least temporarily, is preventing e4-e5 and threatening ...Bb4 with pressure on the white center. The starting position of the Sicilian Four Knights has now been reached. This method of play was first used in the second half of the 19th century. Early adopters included the masters Schiffers, Blackburne, Mieses, and Janowski. White now has a multitude of options.} 6. a3 $5 {White prevents ...Bb4, reducing the possibilities for forcing play. Therefore, the move is particularly popular among players who want to avoid long theoretical battles. However, the downside is also clear: a2-a3 contributes little to White's development. It is therefore not surprising that Black gets good play with simple developing moves.} d6 {This is only the fourth most common move, but it avoids White's idea of Nxc6 followed by e4-e5 and thus seems simplest to me. The pawn structure in the center (e4 vs. d6+e6) can be reached in many Sicilian variations and is known as the Scheveningen structure. It is famous for complex and dynamic play, as both sides have many ideas and the structure in the center is not yet fixed. For example, Black could play ...e6-e5 or ...d6-d5 at the right moment – an important resource against aggressive flank attacks. From Black's point of view, this is a favorable version of the Scheveningen structure. This becomes clear when compared with the classical Scheveningen Variation: 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 d6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 e6 . In the current position, the additional moves a2-a3 and ...Nc6 are played. While the knight participates in the fight for the center, the pawn move on the edge is almost meaningless. The loss of tempo means that aggressive attacking moves like an early g2-g4 are not as effective here. While in the Scheveningen Variation, the direct 6.g4! is considered the most dangerous continuation, here 7.g4? fails due to the pawn loss after 7...Nxd4 8.Qxd4 Nxg4 . Therefore, White usually opts for the classical setup: Be3, Be2, O-O, and f2-f4. 6...Bc5?! Here the bishop is less well placed because White gains a decisive tempo after 7.Nxc6 bxc6? (better is 7...dxc6) 8.e5 Nd5 9.Ne4+- by attacking the bishop.} 7. Be3 {If White continues with Be2 and O-O, this is one of several ways to reach the main line. However, there are a few additional possibilities.} Be7 8. Be2 O-O 9. Qd2 ({Similar to} 9. Qd3 {, White aims for queenside castling. However, as we will see, the queen's placement on d2 has disadvantages.}) (9. O-O Qc7 {is the main line. We consider this through the move order [/variation/31423159/#/9/b] 7.Be2 Be7 8.O-O O-O 9.Be3 Qc7 .}) 9... e5 ({Prepares the development of the c8-bishop. Also good is the bishop development to the long diagonal:} 9... Bd7 10. O-O-O Nxd4 $1 11. Bxd4 Bc6 {with a sharp position in the style of the Richter-Rauzer Variation.}) 10. Nb3 (10. Nf3 {is also playable, but it doesn't harmonize well with queenside castling, for example:} Be6 11. O-O-O $6 a6 {followed by ...b7-b5-b4. . Black's attack on the queenside is more dangerous than White's attack on the kingside. Better would be 11.O-O with an equal position.}) 10... Nxe4 $5 ({With this exchange combination, Black resolves all opening problems. Also fine is} 10... Ng4 {with a subsequent exchange on e3, leading to an equal position.}) 11. Nxe4 d5 {White cannot hold on to the extra piece, as after knight moves there follows ...d5-d4 and the bishop on e3 has no retreat square. Black can now freely complete development and doesn't have any pawn weaknesses, thus achieving comfortable equality.} 12. Z0 ({A recent tournament game of mine continued} 12. Bf3 dxe4 13. Qxd8 Rxd8 14. Bxe4 Be6 15. Nc5 $6 {( Doluhanova-Feuerstack [/variation/36055964], Dortmund 2023, 0-1. Better was 15.Rd1= ) Here, I could have already taken over with} Bxc5 16. Bxc5 Bd5 17. Bxd5 Rxd5 18. Be3 f5 {, when Black has the more active position.}) *

