s. Black, at least temporarily, is preventing e4-e5 and threatening ...Bb4 with pressure on the white center. The starting position of the Sicilian Four Knights has now been reached. This method of play was first used in the second half of the 19th century. Early adopters included the masters Schiffers, Blackburne, Mieses, and Janowski. White now has a multitude of options.} 6. a3 $5 {White prevents ...Bb4, reducing the possibilities for forcing play. Therefore, the move is particularly popular among players who want to avoid long theoretical battles. However, the downside is also clear: a2-a3 contributes little to White's development. It is therefore not surprising that Black gets good play with simple developing moves.} d6 {This is only the fourth most common move, but it avoids White's idea of Nxc6 followed by e4-e5 and thus seems simplest to me. The pawn structure in the center (e4 vs. d6+e6) can be reached in many Sicilian variations and is known as the Scheveningen structure. It is famous for complex and dynamic play, as both sides have many ideas and the structure in the center is not yet fixed. For example, Black could play ...e6-e5 or ...d6-d5 at the right moment – an important resource against aggressive flank attacks. From Black's point of view, this is a favorable version of the Scheveningen structure. This becomes clear when compared with the classical Scheveningen Variation: 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 d6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 e6 . In the current position, the additional moves a2-a3 and ...Nc6 are played. While the knight participates in the fight for the center, the pawn move on the edge is almost meaningless. The loss of tempo means that aggressive attacking moves like an early g2-g4 are not as effective here. While in the Scheveningen Variation, the direct 6.g4! is considered the most dangerous continuation, here 7.g4? fails due to the pawn loss after 7...Nxd4 8.Qxd4 Nxg4 . Therefore, White usually opts for the classical setup: Be3, Be2, O-O, and f2-f4. 6...Bc5?! Here the bishop is less well placed because White gains a decisive tempo after 7.Nxc6 bxc6? (better is 7...dxc6) 8.e5 Nd5 9.Ne4+- by attacking the bishop.} 7. f4 Be7 8. Nf3 {An interesting attempt to give the move a2-a3 some purpose. The bishop will be developed to d3, where it cannot be attacked by ...Nb4. However, White's setup is slow and not very threatening.} O-O 9. Bd3 a6 {Prepares the advance of the b-pawn.} 10. O-O b5 $15 11. Qe1 {Nd1 bxa3 bxa3} {Inferior is axb4 Nxb4 . Black can now exchange the bishop on d3 at any time, but there's no rush to do so. One possible idea, for instance, is ...a6-a5 and ...Ba6. Relatively best, but it weakens the pawn structure on the queenside. Rxa3?! d5 .} d5 {Black can also wait with this move and maintain the tension in the center.} 12. e5 Nd7 ({The knight moves to c5 and can then be exchanged for the bishop. Black has no problems. The typical pawn sacrifice} 12... Ne4 $5 {is an option as well. If White captures, Black gets good play on the light squares.}) *

