Bc5?! Here the bishop is less well placed because White gains a decisive tempo after 7.Nxc6 bxc6? (better is 7...dxc6) 8.e5 Nd5 9.Ne4+- by attacking the bishop.} 7. Bc4 {The bishop development to c4 is known from the Fischer-Sozin Attack in the Najdorf Sicilian, which arises after the moves 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 d6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 a6 6.Bc4 . In this setup, the move a2-a3 makes sense because the bishop can potentially retreat to a2, where it cannot be exchanged. White would like to play f2-f4-f5, after which the bishop exerts unpleasant pressure on e6 or f7.} Be7 8. O-O {Both sides first make the sensible developing moves.} O-O 9. Be3 a6 ({Black wants to exchange on d4, play ...b7-b5, and bring the bishop to b7.} 9... Bd7 {is also possible.}) 10. Ba2 {Pre-emptively moves the bishop to safety.} Qc7 {With the idea of ...Ne5-c4. The direct exchange on d4 is also playable.} 11. f4 {Prevents ...Ne5.} Nxd4 12. Qxd4 b5 ({Black wants to develop the bishop to b7. A good plan is then to advance the a- and b-pawns to increase the pressure against e4. Black has equalized. After the direct} 12... Ng4 {, White has} 13. Qb6 {.}) 13. Rad1 $6 ({White should rather play} 13. Kh1 {or}) (13. Qd3 {to have a good response to the following move.}) 13... Ng4 $1 {The bishop cannot move away due to ...d6-d5 with the threat of ...Bc5, and the exchange would be advantageous for Black.} 14. Qb6 $5 Qxb6 15. Bxb6 a5 {Black wants to play ...b5-b4 and has the initiative.} 16. Nxb5 $4 Rb8 {White loses a piece.} *

