Bc5?! Here the bishop is less well placed because White gains a decisive tempo after 7.Nxc6 bxc6? (better is 7...dxc6) 8.e5 Nd5 9.Ne4+- by attacking the bishop.} 7. Bc4 {The bishop development to c4 is known from the Fischer-Sozin Attack in the Najdorf Sicilian, which arises after the moves 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 d6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 a6 6.Bc4 . In this setup, the move a2-a3 makes sense because the bishop can potentially retreat to a2, where it cannot be exchanged. White would like to play f2-f4-f5, after which the bishop exerts unpleasant pressure on e6 or f7.} Be7 8. O-O {Both sides first make the sensible developing moves.} O-O 9. Be3 a6 ({Black wants to exchange on d4, play ...b7-b5, and bring the bishop to b7.} 9... Bd7 {is also possible.}) 10. Ba2 {Bringt den Läufer vorsorglich in Sicherheit.} Qc7 {With the idea of ...Ne5-c4. The direct exchange on d4 is also playable.} 11. f4 {Prevents ...Ne5.} Nxd4 12. Bxd4 e5 13. Be3 Be6 {With this, Black neutralizes the bishop on a2 and White's control over the weakened d5 square. Black has comfortable equality. Next, a good plan can be to work towards the ...d6-d5 advance. Black does not need to fear the doubling of the e-pawns:} 14. Bxe6 $2 fxe6 15. fxe5 dxe5 $17 {Black's e-pawns are rather strong here because they control important squares. Black will exert pressure on the c-file and against the e4-pawn. The knight on c3 cannot leave its defensive position. How should White react to an advance of Black's queenside pawns?} *

