s. Black, at least temporarily, is preventing e4-e5 and threatening ...Bb4 with pressure on the white center. The starting position of the Sicilian Four Knights has now been reached. This method of play was first used in the second half of the 19th century. Early adopters included the masters Schiffers, Blackburne, Mieses, and Janowski. White now has a multitude of options.} 6. a3 $5 {White prevents ...Bb4, reducing the possibilities for forcing play. Therefore, the move is particularly popular among players who want to avoid long theoretical battles. However, the downside is also clear: a2-a3 contributes little to White's development. It is therefore not surprising that Black gets good play with simple developing moves.} d6 {This is only the fourth most common move, but it avoids White's idea of Nxc6 followed by e4-e5 and thus seems simplest to me. The pawn structure in the center (e4 vs. d6+e6) can be reached in many Sicilian variations and is known as the Scheveningen structure. It is famous for complex and dynamic play, as both sides have many ideas and the structure in the center is not yet fixed. For example, Black could play ...e6-e5 or ...d6-d5 at the right moment – an important resource against aggressive flank attacks. From Black's point of view, this is a favorable version of the Scheveningen structure. This becomes clear when compared with the classical Scheveningen Variation: 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 d6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 e6 . In the current position, the additional moves a2-a3 and ...Nc6 are played. While the knight participates in the fight for the center, the pawn move on the edge is almost meaningless. The loss of tempo means that aggressive attacking moves like an early g2-g4 are not as effective here. While in the Scheveningen Variation, the direct 6.g4! is considered the most dangerous continuation, here 7.g4? fails due to the pawn loss after 7...Nxd4 8.Qxd4 Nxg4 . Therefore, White usually opts for the classical setup: Be3, Be2, O-O, and f2-f4. 6...Bc5?! Here the bishop is less well placed because White gains a decisive tempo after 7.Nxc6 bxc6? (better is 7...dxc6) 8.e5 Nd5 9.Ne4+- by attacking the bishop.} 7. Bc4 {The bishop development to c4 is known from the Fischer-Sozin Attack in the Najdorf Sicilian, which arises after the moves 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 d6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 a6 6.Bc4 . In this setup, the move a2-a3 makes sense because the bishop can potentially retreat to a2, where it cannot be exchanged. White would like to play f2-f4-f5, after which the bishop exerts unpleasant pressure on e6 or f7.} Be7 8. O-O {Both sides first make the sensible developing moves.} O-O 9. Ba2 {The most common move. Before committing to a specific plan, White retreats the bishop to a safe square. On c4, it could have been attacked by moves like ...Qc7, ...Ne5, or ...d6-d5.} Nxd4 {The exchange prepares for the development of the bishop.} 10. Qxd4 Bd7 {The bishop will go to c6, from where it exerts pressure against the e4-pawn. A good plan for Black is then to advance the pawns on the queenside (...a7-a5, ...b7-b5, and ...b5-b4) in order to attack the knight on c3. Black could also first improve their major pieces: ...Qc7 and ...Rfd8. In any case, Black has no worries.} 11. f4 $6 {It's worth examining how Black can respond to an attack on the kingside.} Bc6 ({Equally good are the moves} 11... Rc8 {and}) (11... Qc7 {, after which ...d6-d5 followed by ...Bc5 is a threat.}) 12. f5 exf5 $1 13. Rxf5 Ng4 {A typical regrouping. The bishop moves to f6, after which White needs to be careful not to allow the deadly ...Qb6+. The knight can later go to e5, where it cannot be easily dislodged. Black is slightly better.} *

