5 $6 {. The exchange allows Black to get rid of the backward d-pawn and the bishop on e7 becomes more active. Moreover, White can no longer play f4-f5.} dxe5 $15 {.}) 12... a6 ({This is more precise than the immediate exchange on f4. Black prevents Nb5.} 12... exf4 13. Rxf4 Be6 {Covers the d5 square. ( 13...a6? is now too late: 14.Rxf6! Bxf6 15.Nd5 Qd8 16.Bb6 . Black can no longer protect the bishop with the queen and faces a strong attack after 16...Qe8 17.Nxf6+ gxf6 18.Qd4 $16 .)} 14. Nb5 {The knight heads to d4. This is not a big deal, but with}) (12... a6 {, we can prevent this minor improvement in the position of White's pieces.}) 13. Kh1 ({After} 13. f5 {,} b5 {follows. The bishop will move to b7, where it not only exerts pressure on the pawn on e4 but also supports the pawn break ...d6-d5. White is unable to initiate a quick attack on the kingside, so Black is at least not worse.}) 13... exf4 14. Bxf4 (14. Rxf4 {doesn't change much. With} Be6 {, Black aims to play ...Nd7, which would additionally threaten ...Bg5 here.}) 14... Be6 {The position is equal. A typical idea for Black is to relocate the knight to the outpost on e5. This also opens up the possibility of activating the bishop via f6. Of course, Black can also improve their rooks first. The a8 rook usually goes to c8, while the f8 rook has to choose between the equally viable squares e8 and d8.} *

