s. Black, at least temporarily, is preventing e4-e5 and threatening ...Bb4 with pressure on the white center. The starting position of the Sicilian Four Knights has now been reached. This method of play was first used in the second half of the 19th century. Early adopters included the masters Schiffers, Blackburne, Mieses, and Janowski. White now has a multitude of options.} 6. Be3 {After 6.Ndb5 and 6.Nxc6, this is the third most common move in tournament practice. In the database of online games played on Lichess, it is even the most frequent move! White develops their pieces according to a plan familiar from other variations of the Sicilian. For example, the so-called English Attack against the Najdorf Variation is very popular: 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 d6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 a6 6.Be3 and now, for example, 6...e5 7.Nb3 Be6 8.f3 . The white setup includes further moves such as Qd2, O-O-O, and g2-g4 with an attack on the kingside. In the Four Knights Sicilian, 6.Be3 is usually a sign that White is not familiar with the theory. It is practically not seen at the Grandmaster level. The reason for this is that 6.Be3 does nothing against Black's play in the center.} Bb4 {Attacking the pawn on e4.} 7. f3 $6 ({White continues to dream of a kind of 'English Attack', i.e. a setup with quick long castling. That doesn't work here.} 7. Ndb5 $2 {doesn’t combine well with 6.Be3. After} Nxe4 {,} 8. Qg4 {does win back the pawn, but leads to an unfavorable position for White: Nf6! 9.Qxg7 Rg8 10.Qh6 Rg6 11.Qh4 Rg4 12.Qh3 d5 $17 . Black is threatening ….a7-a6 and enjoys a huge advantage, as they have a strong pawn center and White’s position is lacking coordination.}) 7... d5 {The white center comes under pressure. Black is already better. Not only is there a threat to win the pawn with ...d5xe4, but also ...e6-e5 followed by ...d5-d4.} 8. Bb5 {This is stronger than Bd7 , after which White can play Bxc6 followed by 10.e5.} O-O 9. O-O {First, the king should be brought to safety. Now there is a threat of ...e6-e5, which would already win a piece. exd5} Bxc3 {The tactical complications are favorable for Black. However, playable is also 10...exd5. dxc6 Bxb2 cxb7? While this capture avoids the pawn loss, it accelerates the black development. Bxb7} {bxc3 Nxd5 , and Black is clearly better because there are some weaknesses in the white camp: the pawns on c2 and c3, as well as the squares c4 and e3.} 10. Rb1 {Nd5! Attacking the bishop on e3 and threatening a fork on c3. Qd3 Bc3 The engine evaluates the position already as winning for Black. The white pieces lack harmony, and there are several weaknesses. Specifically, there is a threat of ...Nxe3 followed by ...Qc5. Another strong idea is ...Rfd8 with pressure on the d-file.} *

