s. Black, at least temporarily, is preventing e4-e5 and threatening ...Bb4 with pressure on the white center. The starting position of the Sicilian Four Knights has now been reached. This method of play was first used in the second half of the 19th century. Early adopters included the masters Schiffers, Blackburne, Mieses, and Janowski. White now has a multitude of options.} 6. Be3 {After 6.Ndb5 and 6.Nxc6, this is the third most common move in tournament practice. In the database of online games played on Lichess, it is even the most frequent move! White develops their pieces according to a plan familiar from other variations of the Sicilian. For example, the so-called English Attack against the Najdorf Variation is very popular: 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 d6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 a6 6.Be3 and now, for example, 6...e5 7.Nb3 Be6 8.f3 . The white setup includes further moves such as Qd2, O-O-O, and g2-g4 with an attack on the kingside. In the Four Knights Sicilian, 6.Be3 is usually a sign that White is not familiar with the theory. It is practically not seen at the Grandmaster level. The reason for this is that 6.Be3 does nothing against Black's play in the center.} Bb4 {Attacking the pawn on e4.} 7. Nxc6 {This would have been better one move earlier.} bxc6 8. e5 {The comparison with 6.Nxc6 bxc6 7.e5 Nd5 shows that this is a very favorable version for Black. White's 6.Be3 turns out to be a loss of a tempo, while the black bishop on b4 is very well placed and exerts pressure on the knight. Bd2 There is nothing better.} Qc7 {Nxd5} ({Best. White should trade into an equal position. f4} 8... Rb8 {followed by castling is very pleasant for Black. Black can always move the bishop from b4 and attack the pawn on b2. If now Nxd5?! , Black no longer needs to exchange on d2 and is better after cxd5 .}) 9. Bd2 {Qxd2 cxd5 f4} O-O {The position is equal. Next comes ...a7-a5 and ...Ba6, to exchange the 'bad' bishop.} *

