s. Black, at least temporarily, is preventing e4-e5 and threatening ...Bb4 with pressure on the white center. The starting position of the Sicilian Four Knights has now been reached. This method of play was first used in the second half of the 19th century. Early adopters included the masters Schiffers, Blackburne, Mieses, and Janowski. White now has a multitude of options.} 6. Be3 {After 6.Ndb5 and 6.Nxc6, this is the third most common move in tournament practice. In the database of online games played on Lichess, it is even the most frequent move! White develops their pieces according to a plan familiar from other variations of the Sicilian. For example, the so-called English Attack against the Najdorf Variation is very popular: 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 d6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 a6 6.Be3 and now, for example, 6...e5 7.Nb3 Be6 8.f3 . The white setup includes further moves such as Qd2, O-O-O, and g2-g4 with an attack on the kingside. In the Four Knights Sicilian, 6.Be3 is usually a sign that White is not familiar with the theory. It is practically not seen at the Grandmaster level. The reason for this is that 6.Be3 does nothing against Black's play in the center.} Bb4 {Attacking the pawn on e4.} 7. Bd3 d5 {Continues the attack on the white center. Here, Black doesn't even have to accept an isolated pawn. White has nothing better than resolving the tension in the center, after which Black has comfortable play.} 8. exd5 Nxd5 9. Nxc6 bxc6 10. O-O {Quite rarely played, but tricky. White relies on quick development.} Nxe3 ({Securing the bishop pair and creating a weakness on e3 for White. Black should not go pawn grabbing:} 10... Nxc3 11. bxc3 Bxc3 12. Rb1 O-O 13. Rb3 {. The white pieces are more active and directed towards the black kingside, which more than compensates for the lost pawn. In the classic Zukertort–Anderssen [/variation/31423401/#/13/w], Wrocław 1865 (1-0) game, White soon gained a decisive attack:} Ba5 $2 {( 13...Bf6 14.Qf3 $16 )} 14. Bc5 Re8 15. Bxh7+ $1 Kxh7 16. Rh3+ Kg8 17. Qh5 f5 18. Rd1 Bd7 19. Qh7+ Kf7 20. Rg3 {leading to a swift checkmate.}) 11. fxe3 g6 ({Now Black is ready to castle. The position is equal, although I would prefer the black side due to the bishop pair. White was hoping for immediate castling, as} 11... O-O 12. Rxf7 $1 {is quite dangerous for Black: A)} Rxf7 $4 13. Bxh7+ Kxh7 14. Qxd8 {. B) 12...Kxf7 13.Qh5 Ke7 14.Qh4 Kf7 15.Qxb4 $13 . Stockfish evaluates the position as equal, but in a practical game, White would likely have better chances. The vulnerable black king position and the passive bishop on c8 are cause for concern.}) *

