1. e4 c5 {The Sicilian Opening stands for a sharp fight. Black somewhat neglects their piece development in order to prevent White from establishing a full pawn center with d2-d4.} 2. Nf3 e6 ({The third most common move after} 2... d6 {and}) (2... Nc6 {. With this, Black primarily prepares the development of the dark-squared bishop, but the center push ...d7-d5 becomes a possibility as well.}) (2... Nc6 {is an alternative way to reach the Four Knights Sicilian:} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6 {and we have landed in our repertoire via transposition. I decided against this path because White has a very serious and popular alternative in 3.Bb5 , the Rossolimo Variation. With 2...e6 the Rossolimo Variation is avoided.}) 3. d4 {The Open Sicilian and the starting position of this course. I examine alternatives for White on the second and third moves in a separate course on the Anti-Sicilians. The Open Sicilian is White's most principled attempt to fight for the opening advantage. White has more space and wants to open up the position, relying on rapid piece development. In return, Black gets the semi-open c-file, which can often be used for counterplay later on. Moreover, the exchange of the d-pawn for the c-pawn is a minor positional concession, as White now has only one pawn in the center and therefore can no longer fight quite as well for the important central squares.} cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 ({A very logical move - the knight is developed and simultaneously attacks the e4 pawn. Black takes advantage of the fact that the knight cannot be directly attacked with e4-e5 .} 4... Nc6 {is also possible, but gives White the additional option} 5. Nb5 {.}) 5. Nc3 ({Develops the knight and reinforces White's influence on the central square d5. Moreover, the diagonal a5-e1 is now interrupted, so that e4-e5 becomes a strong threat.} 5. e5 $2 {allows the double attack} Qa5+ {followed by -- Qxe5 .}) 5... Nc6 {Another natural developing move that continues the fight for the central squares. Black, at least temporarily, is preventing e4-e5 and threatening ...Bb4 with pressure on the white center. The starting position of the Sicilian Four Knights has now been reached. This method of play was first used in the second half of the 19th century. Early adopters included the masters Schiffers, Blackburne, Mieses, and Janowski. White now has a multitude of options.} 6. Be3 {After 6.Ndb5 and 6.Nxc6, this is the third most common move in tournament practice. In the database of online games played on Lichess, it is even the most frequent move! White develops their pieces according to a plan familiar from other variations of the Sicilian. For example, the so-called English Attack against the Najdorf Variation is very popular: 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 d6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 a6 6.Be3 and now, for example, 6...e5 7.Nb3 Be6 8.f3 . The white setup includes further moves such as Qd2, O-O-O, and g2-g4 with an attack on the kingside. In the Four Knights Sicilian, 6.Be3 is usually a sign that White is not familiar with the theory. It is practically not seen at the Grandmaster level. The reason for this is that 6.Be3 does nothing against Black's play in the center.} Bb4 {Attacking the pawn on e4.} 7. Bd3 d5 {Continues the attack on the white center. Here, Black doesn't even have to accept an isolated pawn. White has nothing better than resolving the tension in the center, after which Black has comfortable play.} 8. Nxc6 bxc6 9. exd5 ({Now there is a threat of ...d5-d4 or ...d5xe4. White must decide between} 9. exd5 {and}) (9. e5 {.}) 9... cxd5 ({Also good is} 9... exd5 {.}) 10. O-O O-O ({Black now threatens to gain space in the center with ...e6-e5. White should not allow that. Of course, not} 10... d4 $2 11. Bxd4 Qxd4 $4 12. Bb5+ {winning the queen.}) 11. Bd4 {From here, the queen supports both ...e6-e5 and the exchange of the active white bishop with ...Bc5. The two central pawns give Black slightly better chances in this position. White must always be prepared for ...e6-e5.} *

