nother natural developing move that continues the fight for the central squares. Black, at least temporarily, is preventing e4-e5 and threatening ...Bb4 with pressure on the white center. The starting position of the Sicilian Four Knights has now been reached. This method of play was first used in the second half of the 19th century. Early adopters included the masters Schiffers, Blackburne, Mieses, and Janowski. White now has a multitude of options.} 6. Be3 {After 6.Ndb5 and 6.Nxc6, this is the third most common move in tournament practice. In the database of online games played on Lichess, it is even the most frequent move! White develops their pieces according to a plan familiar from other variations of the Sicilian. For example, the so-called English Attack against the Najdorf Variation is very popular: 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 d6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 a6 6.Be3 and now, for example, 6...e5 7.Nb3 Be6 8.f3 . The white setup includes further moves such as Qd2, O-O-O, and g2-g4 with an attack on the kingside. In the Four Knights Sicilian, 6.Be3 is usually a sign that White is not familiar with the theory. It is practically not seen at the Grandmaster level. The reason for this is that 6.Be3 does nothing against Black's play in the center.} Bb4 {Attacking the pawn on e4.} 7. Bd3 d5 {Continues the attack on the white center. Here, Black doesn't even have to accept an isolated pawn. White has nothing better than resolving the tension in the center, after which Black has comfortable play.} 8. Nxc6 bxc6 9. e5 ({Another possibility is Nd7 , but after the double attack} 9. Qg4 {, Black would have to play the passive .}) {Bd2 After this, White loses a pawn.} 9... Nd7 ({dxc3 bxc3 with a double attack and regaining the piece is White's idea. But even here, Black is fine after} 9... Ba5 10. exf6 Qxf6 {.}) {Ne4} 10. Bd2 {Qxd2} Nxe5 {If Black manages to castle now, White doesn't have much to show for the sacrificed pawn. Qb4 A strong engine move. The queen is driven to a worse square. Qc5 Qd5! White cannot easily avoid the queen exchange. Black is slightly better. O-O-O Relatively best. The bishop on d3 is defended by the rook. f5 By attacking the knight, Black forces the queen trade under better conditions than after 15...Qxc5. Qxd5 cxd5 Nc5} ({To defend the knight on e5. White was threatening} 10... Z0 {Rhe1 or 18.Bxf5 .}) *

