1. e4 c5 {The Sicilian Opening stands for a sharp fight. Black somewhat neglects their piece development in order to prevent White from establishing a full pawn center with d2-d4.} 2. Nf3 e6 ({The third most common move after} 2... d6 {and}) (2... Nc6 {. With this, Black primarily prepares the development of the dark-squared bishop, but the center push ...d7-d5 becomes a possibility as well.}) (2... Nc6 {is an alternative way to reach the Four Knights Sicilian:} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6 {and we have landed in our repertoire via transposition. I decided against this path because White has a very serious and popular alternative in 3.Bb5 , the Rossolimo Variation. With 2...e6 the Rossolimo Variation is avoided.}) 3. d4 {The Open Sicilian and the starting position of this course. I examine alternatives for White on the second and third moves in a separate course on the Anti-Sicilians. The Open Sicilian is White's most principled attempt to fight for the opening advantage. White has more space and wants to open up the position, relying on rapid piece development. In return, Black gets the semi-open c-file, which can often be used for counterplay later on. Moreover, the exchange of the d-pawn for the c-pawn is a minor positional concession, as White now has only one pawn in the center and therefore can no longer fight quite as well for the important central squares.} cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 ({A very logical move - the knight is developed and simultaneously attacks the e4 pawn. Black takes advantage of the fact that the knight cannot be directly attacked with e4-e5 .} 4... Nc6 {is also possible, but gives White the additional option} 5. Nb5 {.}) 5. Nc3 ({Develops the knight and reinforces White's influence on the central square d5. Moreover, the diagonal a5-e1 is now interrupted, so that e4-e5 becomes a strong threat.} 5. e5 $2 {allows the double attack} Qa5+ {followed by -- Qxe5 .}) 5... Nc6 {Another natural developing move that continues the fight for the central squares. Black, at least temporarily, is preventing e4-e5 and threatening ...Bb4 with pressure on the white center. The starting position of the Sicilian Four Knights has now been reached. This method of play was first used in the second half of the 19th century. Early adopters included the masters Schiffers, Blackburne, Mieses, and Janowski. White now has a multitude of options.} 6. Bc4 {The bishop development to c4 is unusual in Sicilians with an early ...e7-e6. The bishop only looks at a well-protected pawn here and is vulnerable itself.} Bb4 7. Be2 {The pawn on e4 is now under attack.} O-O {This pawn sacrifice is reminiscent of the analogous variation after 6.Be2 and in fact a transition is possible. Bxc3 bxc3 Nxe4 Qg4} ({A double attack on the knight and the g7 pawn. This option is of course not available to White in the 6.Be2 variation. ➤ We examine the position [/variation/31423109/#/9/b] after Bd3} 7... d5 {via the move order 6.Be2 Bb4 7.O-O Bxc3 8.bxc3 Nxe4 9.Bd3 d5 .}) ({➤ Nxc6 bxc6 Bd3} 7... d5 {. This position [/variation/31423111/#/10/b] is also examined in the chapter [/course/199209/8] on 6.Be2.}) 8. O-O $1 {Defends the important g7 pawn. If White captures the knight, Black will win back the piece. Qxe4} d5 9. Nxc6 bxc6 {Qf3 dxc4 Black has regained the piece. The position is balanced, even if Black loses both c-pawns: Ba3 Re8 Qxc6 Bd7 Qxc4 Rc8 , Crawley} *

