{A pawn sacrifice to bring the king to safety. We have analyzed the position [/variation/31423183/#/10/w/0.1] after Qxe4? via the move order 9.Qd4 Qa5 10.Qxe4 Bxc3+ 11.bxc3 .} 1. e4 c5 {The Sicilian Opening stands for a sharp fight. Black somewhat neglects their piece development in order to prevent White from establishing a full pawn center with d2-d4.} 2. Nf3 e6 ({The third most common move after} 2... d6 {and}) (2... Nc6 {. With this, Black primarily prepares the development of the dark-squared bishop, but the center push ...d7-d5 becomes a possibility as well.}) (2... Nc6 {is an alternative way to reach the Four Knights Sicilian:} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6 {and we have landed in our repertoire via transposition. I decided against this path because White has a very serious and popular alternative in 3.Bb5 , the Rossolimo Variation. With 2...e6 the Rossolimo Variation is avoided.}) 3. d4 {The Open Sicilian and the starting position of this course. I examine alternatives for White on the second and third moves in a separate course on the Anti-Sicilians. The Open Sicilian is White's most principled attempt to fight for the opening advantage. White has more space and wants to open up the position, relying on rapid piece development. In return, Black gets the semi-open c-file, which can often be used for counterplay later on. Moreover, the exchange of the d-pawn for the c-pawn is a minor positional concession, as White now has only one pawn in the center and therefore can no longer fight quite as well for the important central squares.} cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 ({A very logical move - the knight is developed and simultaneously attacks the e4 pawn. Black takes advantage of the fact that the knight cannot be directly attacked with e4-e5 .} 4... Nc6 {is also possible, but gives White the additional option} 5. Nb5 {.}) 5. Nc3 ({Develops the knight and reinforces White's influence on the central square d5. Moreover, the diagonal a5-e1 is now interrupted, so that e4-e5 becomes a strong threat.} 5. e5 $2 {allows the double attack} Qa5+ {followed by -- Qxe5 .}) 5... Nc6 {Another natural developing move that continues the fight for the central squares. Black, at least temporarily, is preventing e4-e5 and threatening ...Bb4 with pressure on the white center. The starting position of the Sicilian Four Knights has now been reached. This method of play was first used in the second half of the 19th century. Early adopters included the masters Schiffers, Blackburne, Mieses, and Janowski. White now has a multitude of options.} 6. Bc4 {The bishop development to c4 is unusual in Sicilians with an early ...e7-e6. The bishop only looks at a well-protected pawn here and is vulnerable itself.} Bb4 7. Be2 {The pawn on e4 is now under attack. Nxc6 bxc6} e5 ({Black should avoid the natural} 7... Nd5 {because of Qg4! . The pawn on g7 can only be defended with concessions.}) ({In comparison to} 7... Nxe4 {Qg4 , here Black lacks the resource Qa5 with an attack against c3 and e5.}) ({After} 7... Nd5 {Qg4! , the situation looks different: A) Nxc3 Qxg7 Rf8} 8. a3 {is bad for Black. B) 9...Qa5? 10.Qxg7! Bxc3 11.bxc3! Qxc3 12.Bd2! . With the knight on e4 instead of d5, this wouldn't have been possible. 12...Qxa1 13.Ke2 Qxh1 14.Qxh8 Ke7 15.Bg5 f6 16.exf6 Kd6 17.f7 and White wins.}) ({Qg4 The typical attack on g7. Bxc3+ Or first} 7... Qa5 {.}) {bxc3 Qa5 Counterattack is the best defense!} 8. O-O {Qxe5 The position is unclear. White should have good compensation for the pawn due to the strong pair of bishops, but nothing more. Black now naturally wants to castle as quickly as possible.} *

