1. e4 c5 {The Sicilian Opening stands for a sharp fight. Black somewhat neglects their piece development in order to prevent White from establishing a full pawn center with d2-d4.} 2. Nf3 e6 ({The third most common move after} 2... d6 {and}) (2... Nc6 {. With this, Black primarily prepares the development of the dark-squared bishop, but the center push ...d7-d5 becomes a possibility as well.}) (2... Nc6 {is an alternative way to reach the Four Knights Sicilian:} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6 {and we have landed in our repertoire via transposition. I decided against this path because White has a very serious and popular alternative in 3.Bb5 , the Rossolimo Variation. With 2...e6 the Rossolimo Variation is avoided.}) 3. d4 {The Open Sicilian and the starting position of this course. I examine alternatives for White on the second and third moves in a separate course on the Anti-Sicilians. The Open Sicilian is White's most principled attempt to fight for the opening advantage. White has more space and wants to open up the position, relying on rapid piece development. In return, Black gets the semi-open c-file, which can often be used for counterplay later on. Moreover, the exchange of the d-pawn for the c-pawn is a minor positional concession, as White now has only one pawn in the center and therefore can no longer fight quite as well for the important central squares.} cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 ({A very logical move - the knight is developed and simultaneously attacks the e4 pawn. Black takes advantage of the fact that the knight cannot be directly attacked with e4-e5 .} 4... Nc6 {is also possible, but gives White the additional option} 5. Nb5 {.}) 5. Nc3 ({Develops the knight and reinforces White's influence on the central square d5. Moreover, the diagonal a5-e1 is now interrupted, so that e4-e5 becomes a strong threat.} 5. e5 $2 {allows the double attack} Qa5+ {followed by -- Qxe5 .}) 5... Nc6 {Another natural developing move that continues the fight for the central squares. Black, at least temporarily, is preventing e4-e5 and threatening ...Bb4 with pressure on the white center. The starting position of the Sicilian Four Knights has now been reached. This method of play was first used in the second half of the 19th century. Early adopters included the masters Schiffers, Blackburne, Mieses, and Janowski. White now has a multitude of options.} 6. Bg5 {Now ...Qa5 is threatened. Ndb5?! Played quite frequently, but weak. In the main variation 6.Ndb5, White was able to justify the knight sortie with concrete threats. Here, however, White is too slow because the move ...Bb4 is significantly more useful than Bg5.} h6 ({Black naturally wants to unpin the knight in order to capture on e4. Also good is O-O a3} 6... Be7 $15 {.}) {Nd6+ Ke7 Kf8 is good as well.} 7. Bf4 e5 8. Nf5 {Kf8 The move sequence is reminiscent of the variation 6.Ndb5 Bc5 7.Nd6+ Ke7 8.Bf4 e5 9.Nf5+ Kf8 . The comparison is very much in favor of the current position. The black bishop is on the better square b4 instead of c5, and Black has played the additional move ...h7-h6, preventing Bg5. Bd2 Relatively best.} d5 {Attacks the e4-pawn and the f5-knight.} 9. exd5 (9. Ng3 $6 d4 {followed by ...h6-h5 is very favourable for Black.}) {Bxc3 Bxc3} 9... Nxd5 {The knight on f5 is under attack, so White has to allow ...Nxc3.} 10. Ne3 Nxc3 11. Qxd8+ Nxd8 12. bxc3 Be6 {Black is playing against the pawn weaknesses on the queenside and is slightly better.} *

