s. Black, at least temporarily, is preventing e4-e5 and threatening ...Bb4 with pressure on the white center. The starting position of the Sicilian Four Knights has now been reached. This method of play was first used in the second half of the 19th century. Early adopters included the masters Schiffers, Blackburne, Mieses, and Janowski. White now has a multitude of options.} 6. Bf4 {Ndb5 This position is reached most often via the move order 6.Ndb5 Bb4 7.Bf4 .} Nxe4 {This is the well-known theoretical continuation. Black gets good play but must be very well-versed in the subsequent complications. Since 6.Bf4 is a very rare sideline, in my opinion it's not worth investing the effort required for it.} 7. Qf3 {Attacks the knight on e4 and protects the knight on c3. Now, Black cannot prevent Nc7+. White cannot play directly Nc7+ Kf8 Nxa8? because then Qf6! followed by ...Nxc3 leads to a decisive attack.} d5 {Nc7+ Kf8} 8. Z0 ({Now White has a choice between Nxa8 and} 8. O-O-O {. In both cases, the position is very complicated and gives equal chances to both sides according to current theory.}) *

