5 .}) 5... Nc6 {Another natural developing move that continues the fight for the central squares. Black, at least temporarily, is preventing e4-e5 and threatening ...Bb4 with pressure on the white center. The starting position of the Sicilian Four Knights has now been reached. This method of play was first used in the second half of the 19th century. Early adopters included the masters Schiffers, Blackburne, Mieses, and Janowski. White now has a multitude of options.} 6. Bf4 {Ndb5 This position is reached most often via the move order 6.Ndb5 Bb4 7.Bf4 . O-O!? , which we looked at in the first chapter.} Bd6 ({A trap. Winning the exchange would now be bad for White.} 6... Qb6 {is also good, but gives White the opportunity to force a draw with} 7. Bc7 {( 9.Bxf8? Kxf8 is good for Black!)} Qc5 8. Bd6 {.}) ({Bxf8? Qxf8 Nd4 ➤ a3} 6... Bc5 7. b4 {axb5 bxc5 Qxc5 is also clearly better for Black.}) ({➤ Nc7? is even worse. The knight is lost after} 6... Rb8 {followed by ...Ba5.}) {Nxe4} 7. Nxc6 (7. Qd3 $2 {loses after Nxf2! Kxf2} Nxd4 {. The white king is too exposed. Black wins with moves like ...Nf5, ...d7-d5, and ...Bc5.}) 7... bxc6 8. Qf3 ({Other moves are even worse, for example,} 8. Qd3 $2 {Qc5! with a double attack on f2 and c3.}) ({Nxc3 bxc3 Qc5! cxb4 White cannot protect the pawn c3.} 8. Kd2 {loses to Qd4+ followed by ...Bxc3.}) *

