s. Black, at least temporarily, is preventing e4-e5 and threatening ...Bb4 with pressure on the white center. The starting position of the Sicilian Four Knights has now been reached. This method of play was first used in the second half of the 19th century. Early adopters included the masters Schiffers, Blackburne, Mieses, and Janowski. White now has a multitude of options.} 6. Qd3 $5 {The queen supports the white center from d3 and can, if necessary, swing to the kingside – to g3 or h3. The queen move also prepares for long castling, after which White could attack on the kingside.} d5 {A very concrete approach, with which Black exploits the queen's position on d3.} 7. exd5 Nb4 $1 (7... exd5 8. Be3 $14 {is better for White, who will castle queenside and build strong pressure against the d5-pawn.}) 8. Qg3 ({The logical move. From here, the queen attacks the g7-pawn. In the mentioned game [/variation/31423405/#/7/b], Caruana chose} 8. Qc4 {. However, the queen is not particularly effective here. Grischuk had comfortable play after} Nbxd5 {. Black wants to play ...Bd7 and ...Rc8 and can finish the development unhindered. After the following moves} 9. Bg5 $6 Bb4 10. Bd3 {, Grischuk could have already obtained a slightly better position with} Bxc3+ 11. bxc3 h6 {.}) 8... Bc5 ({Black again resorts to concrete means to solve the opening problems. By attacking the knight, Black gains a tempo for development. Of course, the knight on d4 cannot move now due to the fork on c2. After} 8... Nbxd5 {, the queen on g3 is annoying because Black finds it hard to develop the f8-bishop. White is slightly better, for example after} 9. Nxd5 Nxd5 10. Be2 {followed by short castling.}) 9. Bb5+ {It's not so clear which side benefits more from this intermediate check.} Kf8 ({The only move. The advantage of this is that Black no longer has to worry about the g7-pawn.} 9... Bd7 $2 {is tactically refuted.} 10. dxe6 fxe6 11. Qxg7 Rg8 12. Bxd7+ Qxd7 13. Qxd7+ Kxd7 14. Be3 {and White retains an extra pawn. After} Bxd4 $6 {,} 15. O-O-O {follows, regaining the piece.}) 10. a3 Nbxd5 11. Nde2 (11. Nxd5 $2 {would now be a mistake. Black plays} Qxd5 {and after a move of the knight ...Ne4.}) 11... Bd7 {If White avoids the exchange, the bishop goes to c6.} 12. Bxd7 Qxd7 13. Nxd5 $2 {An unusual misstep for a player of Harikrishna's caliber.} Ne4 {One doesn't always have to take back immediately! This intermediate move is winning for Black.} 14. Qb3 Bxf2+ 15. Kf1 exd5 {Black has not only won a pawn but also ruined the White's king's position. In Harikrishna–Vitiugov [/variation/31423409/#/15/b], Belgrad 2022 (0-1) the Indian super-grandmaster continued to play for a while, but the battle is already hopeless.} *

