s. Black, at least temporarily, is preventing e4-e5 and threatening ...Bb4 with pressure on the white center. The starting position of the Sicilian Four Knights has now been reached. This method of play was first used in the second half of the 19th century. Early adopters included the masters Schiffers, Blackburne, Mieses, and Janowski. White now has a multitude of options.} 6. Qd3 $5 {The queen supports the white center from d3 and can, if necessary, swing to the kingside – to g3 or h3. The queen move also prepares for long castling, after which White could attack on the kingside.} d5 {A very concrete approach, with which Black exploits the queen's position on d3.} 7. exd5 Nb4 $1 (7... exd5 8. Be3 $14 {is better for White, who will castle queenside and build strong pressure against the d5-pawn.}) 8. Qg3 ({The logical move. From here, the queen attacks the g7-pawn. In the mentioned game [/variation/31423405/#/7/b], Caruana chose} 8. Qc4 {. However, the queen is not particularly effective here. Grischuk had comfortable play after} Nbxd5 {. Black wants to play ...Bd7 and ...Rc8 and can finish the development unhindered. After the following moves} 9. Bg5 $6 Bb4 10. Bd3 {, Grischuk could have already obtained a slightly better position with} Bxc3+ 11. bxc3 h6 {.}) 8... Bc5 ({Black again resorts to concrete means to solve the opening problems. By attacking the knight, Black gains a tempo for development. Of course, the knight on d4 cannot move now due to the fork on c2. After} 8... Nbxd5 {, the queen on g3 is annoying because Black finds it hard to develop the f8-bishop. White is slightly better, for example after} 9. Nxd5 Nxd5 10. Be2 {followed by short castling.}) 9. a3 ({Responds to the attack with a counterattack. Of course, not} 9. Qxg7 $2 Rg8 10. Bb5+ Ke7 {with an attack on the queen and the d4-knight. White can still try} 11. d6+ {, but after} Bxd6 12. Qh6 Bc5 {, Black wins material anyway.}) 9... Nbxd5 {White still cannot capture on g7 due to the attack on d4, and Black is ready to castle.} 10. Nxd5 ({White exploits the fact that Black cannot recapture with the knight at the moment. ➤} 10. Ndb5 $2 {only leads to a misplacement of the knight and achieves nothing else. In the game Frolyanov–Safin [/variation/31423407/#/10/w], Cheliabinsk 2020 (1-0),} O-O {followed. A)} 11. Nxd5 $2 Ne4 $1 {. The double attack on g3 and f2 wins for Black. B) 11.Bh6 was apparently the idea of the White player, but after the following typical defensive move, the attack fizzles out. 11...Nh5! 12.Qf3 . Now 12...a6 would have been strong: After 13.Ne4 ( 13.Qxh5?! axb5 $17 ) 13...Bb6 14.Qxh5 axb5 $17 , Black is better developed and threatens not only ...gxh6 but also ...b5-b4.}) ({➤} 10. Bb5+ Kf8 {we consider via the move order [/variation/31423201/#/10/b] 9.Bb5 Kf8 10.a3 Nbxd5 .}) 10... Qxd5 (10... Nxd5 $2 11. Qxg7 {.}) 11. Nb5 ({Threatens a family check.} 11. Qxg7 $2 {is still not a good idea, this time because of the intermediate check} Qe5+ {, after which the knight on f6 is defended: A)} 12. Ne2 Rg8 13. Qh6 Bxf2+ {. B) 12.Be2 Rg8-+ followed by ...Bxd4.}) 11... O-O 12. Z0 ({The king is safe and ...Ne4 is threatened. ➤ Black need not fear the fork on c7:} 12. Nc7 $2 Qe4+ $17 {. Next, Black saves the rook with ...Rb8 from the knight's attack. The knight on c7 is now rather endangered itself, and White is underdeveloped.}) ({➤} 12. Nc3 Qf5 {(also 12...Qd6 and 12...Qh5 are playable.)} 13. Bd3 Qh5 {. We have followed the game Ter Sahakyan–Erigaisi [/variation/31423408/#/13/b], Chennai 2022 (½-½). Both sides have natural development and no weaknesses. Black's next plan is to play ...Bd7-c6. The position is balanced. In the game, there followed} 14. h3 Bd7 15. Bg5 Be7 16. Be2 Qg6 17. Bd3 Qh5 {. Black cannot avoid the repetition of moves.} 18. O-O Bc6 {, and after a long fight, the game ended in a draw.}) *

