1. e4 c5 {The Sicilian Opening stands for a sharp fight. Black somewhat neglects their piece development in order to prevent White from establishing a full pawn center with d2-d4.} 2. Nf3 e6 ({The third most common move after} 2... d6 {and}) (2... Nc6 {. With this, Black primarily prepares the development of the dark-squared bishop, but the center push ...d7-d5 becomes a possibility as well.}) (2... Nc6 {is an alternative way to reach the Four Knights Sicilian:} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6 {and we have landed in our repertoire via transposition. I decided against this path because White has a very serious and popular alternative in 3.Bb5 , the Rossolimo Variation. With 2...e6 the Rossolimo Variation is avoided.}) 3. d4 {The Open Sicilian and the starting position of this course. I examine alternatives for White on the second and third moves in a separate course on the Anti-Sicilians. The Open Sicilian is White's most principled attempt to fight for the opening advantage. White has more space and wants to open up the position, relying on rapid piece development. In return, Black gets the semi-open c-file, which can often be used for counterplay later on. Moreover, the exchange of the d-pawn for the c-pawn is a minor positional concession, as White now has only one pawn in the center and therefore can no longer fight quite as well for the important central squares.} cxd4 4. Bg5 $6 {It seems to me that the main idea of this attack on the queen is to take advantage of premature pre-moves in online games.} Qa5+ 5. c3 (5. Nbd2 Nc6 {. White has no compensation for the pawn.}) 5... dxc3 6. Nxc3 Nf6 {A novelty. The attack on the e4 pawn forces White to make a concession.} 7. Bxf6 gxf6 $15 {While this exchange may have damaged the black pawn structure, in return, Black gains the bishop pair and more control in the center. Next, Black could either prepare short castling by playing ...Bg7, or leave the king in the center for now. On the queenside, a good setup for Black would include ...Nc6, ...a7-a6, ...b7-b5, and ...Bb7. White does not have enough compensation for the pawn.} *

