1. e4 c5 {The Sicilian Opening stands for a sharp fight. Black somewhat neglects their piece development in order to prevent White from establishing a full pawn center with d2-d4.} 2. Nf3 e6 ({The third most common move after} 2... d6 {and}) (2... Nc6 {. With this, Black primarily prepares the development of the dark-squared bishop, but the center push ...d7-d5 becomes a possibility as well.}) (2... Nc6 {is an alternative way to reach the Four Knights Sicilian:} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6 {and we have landed in our repertoire via transposition. I decided against this path because White has a very serious and popular alternative in 3.Bb5 , the Rossolimo Variation. With 2...e6 the Rossolimo Variation is avoided.}) 3. d4 {The Open Sicilian and the starting position of this course. I examine alternatives for White on the second and third moves in a separate course on the Anti-Sicilians. The Open Sicilian is White's most principled attempt to fight for the opening advantage. White has more space and wants to open up the position, relying on rapid piece development. In return, Black gets the semi-open c-file, which can often be used for counterplay later on. Moreover, the exchange of the d-pawn for the c-pawn is a minor positional concession, as White now has only one pawn in the center and therefore can no longer fight quite as well for the important central squares.} cxd4 4. Qxd4 {Against the Sicilian with 2...d6, capturing with the queen is an interesting sideline. Here, it is less dangerous because Black can attack the white center by playing ...d7-d5 without losing a tempo.} Nc6 5. Qd1 {The Latvian Grandmaster Viesturs Meijers has played this with success on a few occasions, using the move order 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 e6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nc6 5.Nf3 . Of course, this cannot be critical for Black's setup as White loses time. One doesn't need to know much here, but it is helpful to remember that an early ...d7-d5 is often not the best approach.} Nf6 6. Bd3 {This position can also be reached via the move order 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 e6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Bd3 Nc6 6.Nf3 . Now, Black has a wide choice. 6.e5? is a well-known mistake. 6...Nxe5 7.Nxe5 Qa5+ $17 gives Black a healthy extra pawn.} Bc5 $5 ({I like this aggressive setup. The bishop is targeting the vulnerable f2 point, opening up potential tactical possibilities. After} 6... d5 7. exd5 Nxd5 {(7...exd5 may be stronger here),} 8. O-O Be7 9. a3 {followed by c2-c4, I slightly prefer White's position as they have the more active pieces.}) 7. O-O Qc7 {From here, the queen controls the square e5. Additionally, ...Ng4 is now a possible motif.} 8. Nc3 {This prevents Nb5 and is in general a useful move, as Black will often play ...b7-b5 and develop the bishop to b7. The position is balanced, but more pleasant for Black to play. White's setup seems somewhat aimless. Bg5 9.Qe2 is the most common move, but that invites 9...Ng4! . Now the threat is ...Nd4, winning the queen. 10.g3 O-O $15 . Black has good control over the central squares and is slightly better.} b5 ({Instead, Black can play} 8... Be7 {, but I don't think it's necessary. The exchange on f6 would give us the bishop pair and better control of the center, so it is nothing to fear.}) *

