{The queen is well placed here and prevents e4-e5. Black can comfortably continue developing with ...Bc5, ...d7-d6 and ...O-O . Bb4 , Caruanas choice against Aronian, is playable as well: Aronian–Caruana [/variation/31423410/#/6/b], Stavanger 2018 (0-1).} 1. e4 c5 {The Sicilian Opening stands for a sharp fight. Black somewhat neglects their piece development in order to prevent White from establishing a full pawn center with d2-d4.} 2. Nf3 e6 ({The third most common move after} 2... d6 {and}) (2... Nc6 {. With this, Black primarily prepares the development of the dark-squared bishop, but the center push ...d7-d5 becomes a possibility as well.}) (2... Nc6 {is an alternative way to reach the Four Knights Sicilian:} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6 {and we have landed in our repertoire via transposition. I decided against this path because White has a very serious and popular alternative in 3.Bb5 , the Rossolimo Variation. With 2...e6 the Rossolimo Variation is avoided.}) 3. d4 {The Open Sicilian and the starting position of this course. I examine alternatives for White on the second and third moves in a separate course on the Anti-Sicilians. The Open Sicilian is White's most principled attempt to fight for the opening advantage. White has more space and wants to open up the position, relying on rapid piece development. In return, Black gets the semi-open c-file, which can often be used for counterplay later on. Moreover, the exchange of the d-pawn for the c-pawn is a minor positional concession, as White now has only one pawn in the center and therefore can no longer fight quite as well for the important central squares.} cxd4 4. Qxd4 {Against the Sicilian with 2...d6, capturing with the queen is an interesting sideline. Here, it is less dangerous because Black can attack the white center by playing ...d7-d5 without losing a tempo.} Nc6 5. Qd3 {I don't see the merits of this move, even though it was played by Aronian in a Blitz game.} Nf6 6. Nc3 *

