1. e4 c5 {The Sicilian Opening stands for a sharp fight. Black somewhat neglects their piece development in order to prevent White from establishing a full pawn center with d2-d4.} 2. Nf3 e6 ({The third most common move after} 2... d6 {and}) (2... Nc6 {. With this, Black primarily prepares the development of the dark-squared bishop, but the center push ...d7-d5 becomes a possibility as well.}) (2... Nc6 {is an alternative way to reach the Four Knights Sicilian:} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6 {and we have landed in our repertoire via transposition. I decided against this path because White has a very serious and popular alternative in 3.Bb5 , the Rossolimo Variation. With 2...e6 the Rossolimo Variation is avoided.}) 3. d4 {The Open Sicilian and the starting position of this course. I examine alternatives for White on the second and third moves in a separate course on the Anti-Sicilians. The Open Sicilian is White's most principled attempt to fight for the opening advantage. White has more space and wants to open up the position, relying on rapid piece development. In return, Black gets the semi-open c-file, which can often be used for counterplay later on. Moreover, the exchange of the d-pawn for the c-pawn is a minor positional concession, as White now has only one pawn in the center and therefore can no longer fight quite as well for the important central squares.} cxd4 4. Qxd4 {Against the Sicilian with 2...d6, capturing with the queen is an interesting sideline. Here, it is less dangerous because Black can attack the white center by playing ...d7-d5 without losing a tempo.} Nc6 5. Qe3 {The queen is not particularly well-placed here. The idea may be to develop the bishop to b2 and castle queenside. However, White is not in time for that plan.} Nf6 {Black carries out the normal developing moves and is now ready for ...d7-d5.} 6. c4 Qb6 {An attack against the pawn on e4, which would no longer be protected after the exchange of queens. Besides, there is a threat of ...Bc5 followed by ...Ng4.} 7. Qxb6 ({Not a bad trade for Black, despite the weakening of the pawn structure: White's e-pawn is not easy to defend and the rook on a8 gets activated. If White instead protects the e-pawn with} 7. Nc3 {, Black starts an attack:} Bc5 8. Qd2 Ng4 {. Now White's best option is to enter the complications after} 9. Qg5 $1 Nxf2 10. Qxg7 Rf8 11. Rg1 {, but Black has the slightly better chances, i.e. after} Be3 {. The other way to protect the e-pawn, 7.Bd3 , doesn't guarantee an equal game either. The simplest is 7...Qxe3+ 8.Bxe3 Ng4 9.Bd2 Nb4 $15 when White has to part with their pair of bishops.}) 7... axb6 8. Nc3 ({The alternatives are worse: A)} 8. Bd3 Nb4 9. Ke2 d5 $5 {(or 9.Nxa2 $15 ). B) 8.e5 Ng4 9.Bf4 Bc5 10.Bg3 Nb4 $17 , when White loses at least a pawn.}) 8... Bb4 {Renews the attack on e4.} 9. Bd2 ({After} 9. Bd3 Bxc3+ 10. bxc3 d5 $15 {, Black gets good play against White's weakened queenside.}) 9... Bxc3 10. Bxc3 Nxe4 11. Bxg7 {Bh6} Nc5 {Black has the initiative. ...Nb4 is threatened.} 12. a3 e5 $15 {Next, Black wants to develop the bishop by playing ...d7-d6 and ...Bg4. White is under pressure, as Black's pieces are more active.} *

