1. e4 c5 {The Sicilian Opening stands for a sharp fight. Black somewhat neglects their piece development in order to prevent White from establishing a full pawn center with d2-d4.} 2. Nf3 e6 ({The third most common move after} 2... d6 {and}) (2... Nc6 {. With this, Black primarily prepares the development of the dark-squared bishop, but the center push ...d7-d5 becomes a possibility as well.}) (2... Nc6 {is an alternative way to reach the Four Knights Sicilian:} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6 {and we have landed in our repertoire via transposition. I decided against this path because White has a very serious and popular alternative in 3.Bb5 , the Rossolimo Variation. With 2...e6 the Rossolimo Variation is avoided.}) 3. d4 {The Open Sicilian and the starting position of this course. I examine alternatives for White on the second and third moves in a separate course on the Anti-Sicilians. The Open Sicilian is White's most principled attempt to fight for the opening advantage. White has more space and wants to open up the position, relying on rapid piece development. In return, Black gets the semi-open c-file, which can often be used for counterplay later on. Moreover, the exchange of the d-pawn for the c-pawn is a minor positional concession, as White now has only one pawn in the center and therefore can no longer fight quite as well for the important central squares.} cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 ({A very logical move - the knight is developed and simultaneously attacks the e4 pawn. Black takes advantage of the fact that the knight cannot be directly attacked with e4-e5 .} 4... Nc6 {is also possible, but gives White the additional option} 5. Nb5 {.}) 5. f3 {This move is common in Sicilians, usually to prepare a setup with Be3, Qd2, and long castling. Since Black has not yet moved the d-pawn here and can attack the white center with ...d7-d5 and (after Nc3) ...Bb4, f2-f3 is not dangerous here.} Nc6 6. c4 $6 {White wants to play the so-called Maroczy structure and make ...d7-d5 more difficult. However, that doesn't work here.} Bb4+ ({Black could also play} 6... d5 {directly.}) 7. Nc3 d5 {White was unable to prevent this move, and now the drawback of f2-f3 is apparent, namely the weakening of the diagonal g1-a7 and the square e3.} 8. cxd5 exd5 9. Bb5 {This attempt requires some accuracy from Black.} O-O $1 ({It is best not to worry about the pawn and instead focus on quick development. Not} 9... Bd7 $2 10. Bxc6 bxc6 11. e5 {, and now White is even slightly better.}) 10. Nxc6 (10. Bxc6 bxc6 11. Nxc6 {( 11.e5? doesn't work anymore because Black has . 12.f4 Qb6-+ .)} Bxc3+ 12. bxc3 Qc7 13. exd5 Ba6 14. Kf2 Rae8 $17 {. Black threatens} 15. Z0 Re2+ {, 15...Qb6 , or 15...Nxd5 16.Qxd5 Bb7 . The white king is too unsafe, and therefore Black has a clear advantage.}) 10... bxc6 11. Bxc6 Nxe4 $1 {It now becomes evident that White has neglected development and king safety.} 12. fxe4 $6 ({After} 12. O-O Qb6+ 13. Kh1 Qxc6 14. fxe4 dxe4 {, White has no compensation for the pawn.}) 12... Qh4+ {Black is winning.} 13. Kd2 ({➤} 13. g3 Qxe4+ 14. Kd2 Ba6 $1 {. The king cannot escape and will soon be checkmated.}) ({➤} 13. Kf1 Qf6+ 14. Qf3 Qxc6 {. Black has regained the piece, and the white king still cannot find safety.}) 13... Bg4 14. Qa4 {After other queen moves, Black has at least ...Qh6+ and ...Qxc6.} Qf2+ {White can no longer escape checkmate.  15.Kd3 dxe4+ 16.Kc4 Be6+ 17.Kxb4 a5+ 18.Ka3 Qc5 , Besson-Geller [/variation/31423413/#/18/w], Cappelle la Grande 2003 0-1.} *

