{Now the bishop could retreat after Nc5 , while keeping the pawn on e4 protected.} 1. e4 c5 {The Sicilian Opening stands for a sharp fight. Black somewhat neglects their piece development in order to prevent White from establishing a full pawn center with d2-d4.} 2. Nf3 e6 ({The third most common move after} 2... d6 {and}) (2... Nc6 {. With this, Black primarily prepares the development of the dark-squared bishop, but the center push ...d7-d5 becomes a possibility as well.}) (2... Nc6 {is an alternative way to reach the Four Knights Sicilian:} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6 {and we have landed in our repertoire via transposition. I decided against this path because White has a very serious and popular alternative in 3.Bb5 , the Rossolimo Variation. With 2...e6 the Rossolimo Variation is avoided.}) 3. d4 {The Open Sicilian and the starting position of this course. I examine alternatives for White on the second and third moves in a separate course on the Anti-Sicilians. The Open Sicilian is White's most principled attempt to fight for the opening advantage. White has more space and wants to open up the position, relying on rapid piece development. In return, Black gets the semi-open c-file, which can often be used for counterplay later on. Moreover, the exchange of the d-pawn for the c-pawn is a minor positional concession, as White now has only one pawn in the center and therefore can no longer fight quite as well for the important central squares.} cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 ({A very logical move - the knight is developed and simultaneously attacks the e4 pawn. Black takes advantage of the fact that the knight cannot be directly attacked with e4-e5 .} 4... Nc6 {is also possible, but gives White the additional option} 5. Nb5 {.}) 5. Nd2 $5 {The advantage of developing the knight to d2 instead of the more natural c3 is that the c-pawn is not blocked, and Black does not have the option of ...Bb4. However, the knight blocks the bishop on c1, so White needs to spend more time on development. White now threatens e4-e5, as Black no longer has the response ...Qa5+.} d6 ({This scheme of development seems easiest to me. ➤ Interesting and unexplored is the alternative} 5... e5 {.}) ({➤} 5... Nc6 6. Nxc6 bxc6 {( 6...dxc6 7.e5 Nd5 8.Ne4 $14 is slightly better for White due to the passive bishop on c8.)} 7. e5 Nd5 {. White could now transition to the analogous variation [/variation/31423003/#/8/w] after 5.Nc3, but here White has additional options such as} 8. c4 {.}) ({➤} 5... d5 {leads to the Tarrasch Variation of the French Defense: 1.e4 e6 2.d4 d5 3.Nd2 c5 4.Ngf3 cxd4 5.Nxd4 Nf6 .}) 6. Bd3 {The most natural square for the bishop.} Nbd7 {The knight is on it's way to c5, from where it attacks the bishop.} 7. c4 {On g7, the bishop puts pressure on the knight, which cannot be protected by Be3 here. The position is equal.} *

