1. e4 c5 {The Sicilian Opening stands for a sharp fight. Black somewhat neglects their piece development in order to prevent White from establishing a full pawn center with d2-d4.} 2. Nf3 e6 ({The third most common move after} 2... d6 {and}) (2... Nc6 {. With this, Black primarily prepares the development of the dark-squared bishop, but the center push ...d7-d5 becomes a possibility as well.}) (2... Nc6 {is an alternative way to reach the Four Knights Sicilian:} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6 {and we have landed in our repertoire via transposition. I decided against this path because White has a very serious and popular alternative in 3.Bb5 , the Rossolimo Variation. With 2...e6 the Rossolimo Variation is avoided.}) 3. d4 {The Open Sicilian and the starting position of this course. I examine alternatives for White on the second and third moves in a separate course on the Anti-Sicilians. The Open Sicilian is White's most principled attempt to fight for the opening advantage. White has more space and wants to open up the position, relying on rapid piece development. In return, Black gets the semi-open c-file, which can often be used for counterplay later on. Moreover, the exchange of the d-pawn for the c-pawn is a minor positional concession, as White now has only one pawn in the center and therefore can no longer fight quite as well for the important central squares.} cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 ({A very logical move - the knight is developed and simultaneously attacks the e4 pawn. Black takes advantage of the fact that the knight cannot be directly attacked with e4-e5 .} 4... Nc6 {is also possible, but gives White the additional option} 5. Nb5 {.}) 5. Bd3 ({White places the bishop on a good square and protects the e-pawn. This natural developing move is the second most popular move after 5.Nc3. Compared to 5.Nc3, the nature of the position is now somewhat slower, as White is not threatening e4-e5.} 5. e5 $2 Qa5+ {wins a pawn.}) 5... Nc6 ({Here as well, this is the correct move. The knight on d4 is facing a decision. White usually exchanges on c6, but other moves are also possible.} 5... d5 $2 {would be a mistake due to} 6. e5 Nfd7 $6 7. Nxe6 $1 {. If White didn't have this pseudo sacrifice, everything would be fine for Black.} fxe6 {(slightly better is 7...Bb4+)} 8. Qh5+ {. A) After} g6 {, of course,} 9. Bxg6+ hxg6 10. Qxg6+ Ke7 11. Bg5+ {is winning. B) 8...Ke7 9.Bg5 Nf6 10.O-O is winning the piece back, and White's attack continues.}) 6. c3 {This protecting move is as harmless as it looks. The pawn takes away the square where the knight would have liked to develop to.} d5 7. exd5 (7. Nxc6 bxc6 {. Black is slightly better. The move c2-c3 does not fit into White's setup. They must now react to the threat against the e4 pawn.} 8. e5 $6 {is usually good only after White has castled.} Nd7 9. f4 Qb6 {. It is not so easy for White to castle now.}) 7... Qxd5 {Attacking the pawn on g2.} 8. O-O Nxd4 9. cxd4 Bd7 {The position resembles a c3- Sicilian, with the difference that a pair of knights has already been exchanged. This favors Black. Specifically, after the last move, ...Bc6 is a threat, and furthermore the pawn on d4 is attacked because White no longer has the discovered check Bb5+. Black already has slightly better chances.} *

