ve. The knight on d4 is facing a decision. White usually exchanges on c6, but other moves are also possible.} 5... d5 $2 {would be a mistake due to} 6. e5 Nfd7 $6 7. Nxe6 $1 {. If White didn't have this pseudo sacrifice, everything would be fine for Black.} fxe6 {(slightly better is 7...Bb4+)} 8. Qh5+ {. A) After} g6 {, of course,} 9. Bxg6+ hxg6 10. Qxg6+ Ke7 11. Bg5+ {is winning. B) 8...Ke7 9.Bg5 Nf6 10.O-O is winning the piece back, and White's attack continues.}) 6. Be3 d5 {Black, of course, does not skip the opportunity to occupy the center, especially as the bishop on e3 can become a target for Black's pieces.} 7. Nxc6 bxc6 {By recapturing, Black strengthens the control in the center. It is now up to White to play accurately.} 8. e5 $2 {f4 This goes along with weakening the black squares, but White had to protect the pawn on e5.} Bc5 $1 {By exchanging the dark-squared bishops and then playing ...Qb6, Black takes advantage of the weaknesses on the dark squares.} 9. Bxc5 $17 {Nxc5 Next comes ...Qb6. The queen not only attacks the pawn on b2, but also prevents White from castling. White is already in significant trouble.} *

