ve. The knight on d4 is facing a decision. White usually exchanges on c6, but other moves are also possible.} 5... d5 $2 {would be a mistake due to} 6. e5 Nfd7 $6 7. Nxe6 $1 {. If White didn't have this pseudo sacrifice, everything would be fine for Black.} fxe6 {(slightly better is 7...Bb4+)} 8. Qh5+ {. A) After} g6 {, of course,} 9. Bxg6+ hxg6 10. Qxg6+ Ke7 11. Bg5+ {is winning. B) 8...Ke7 9.Bg5 Nf6 10.O-O is winning the piece back, and White's attack continues.}) 6. Be3 d5 {Black, of course, does not skip the opportunity to occupy the center, especially as the bishop on e3 can become a target for Black's pieces.} 7. Nxc6 bxc6 {By recapturing, Black strengthens the control in the center. It is now up to White to play accurately.} 8. Nd2 {Black has a comfortable game. As we have seen before in this structure, ...a7-a5 and ...Ba6 is a good plan, allowing Black to exchange their weakest piece.} *

