ve. The knight on d4 is facing a decision. White usually exchanges on c6, but other moves are also possible.} 5... d5 $2 {would be a mistake due to} 6. e5 Nfd7 $6 7. Nxe6 $1 {. If White didn't have this pseudo sacrifice, everything would be fine for Black.} fxe6 {(slightly better is 7...Bb4+)} 8. Qh5+ {. A) After} g6 {, of course,} 9. Bxg6+ hxg6 10. Qxg6+ Ke7 11. Bg5+ {is winning. B) 8...Ke7 9.Bg5 Nf6 10.O-O is winning the piece back, and White's attack continues.}) 6. Be3 d5 {Black, of course, does not skip the opportunity to occupy the center, especially as the bishop on e3 can become a target for Black's pieces.} 7. exd5 (7. Nc3 Bb4 {is a transition to the variations examined in the chapter [/course/199209/11] on 6.Be3 ( 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 e6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 Nc6 6.Be3 Bb4 7.Bd3 d5 ) .}) 7... Nxd5 ({The most active recapture, as the knight attacks the bishop. Black accepts a pawn weakness in return.} 7... Qxd5 {is also good.}) 8. Nxc6 bxc6 9. Bd2 {The most common move. The bishop avoids the trade and supports the development of the knight to c3.} Rb8 $1 {White has trouble protecting the b2-pawn.} 10. b3 $2 {This weakens the black squares.} Qf6 $1 {Forces White's answer.} 11. c3 {Now, it will be hard for White to develop the knight.} Bd6 {Black has a more harmonious piece development and therefore is better. The light-squared bishop can be brought to the long diagonal after ...c6-c5, or developed on the c8-h3 diagonal after ...e6-e5. The bishop on d2 and the knight on b1 in White's camp are poorly placed. Rearranging these pieces is not easy since the pawn on c3 is under attack.} *

