1. e4 c5 {The Sicilian Opening stands for a sharp fight. Black somewhat neglects their piece development in order to prevent White from establishing a full pawn center with d2-d4.} 2. Nf3 e6 ({The third most common move after} 2... d6 {and}) (2... Nc6 {. With this, Black primarily prepares the development of the dark-squared bishop, but the center push ...d7-d5 becomes a possibility as well.}) (2... Nc6 {is an alternative way to reach the Four Knights Sicilian:} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6 {and we have landed in our repertoire via transposition. I decided against this path because White has a very serious and popular alternative in 3.Bb5 , the Rossolimo Variation. With 2...e6 the Rossolimo Variation is avoided.}) 3. d4 {The Open Sicilian and the starting position of this course. I examine alternatives for White on the second and third moves in a separate course on the Anti-Sicilians. The Open Sicilian is White's most principled attempt to fight for the opening advantage. White has more space and wants to open up the position, relying on rapid piece development. In return, Black gets the semi-open c-file, which can often be used for counterplay later on. Moreover, the exchange of the d-pawn for the c-pawn is a minor positional concession, as White now has only one pawn in the center and therefore can no longer fight quite as well for the important central squares.} cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 ({A very logical move - the knight is developed and simultaneously attacks the e4 pawn. Black takes advantage of the fact that the knight cannot be directly attacked with e4-e5 .} 4... Nc6 {is also possible, but gives White the additional option} 5. Nb5 {.}) 5. Bd3 ({White places the bishop on a good square and protects the e-pawn. This natural developing move is the second most popular move after 5.Nc3. Compared to 5.Nc3, the nature of the position is now somewhat slower, as White is not threatening e4-e5.} 5. e5 $2 Qa5+ {wins a pawn.}) 5... Nc6 ({Here as well, this is the correct move. The knight on d4 is facing a decision. White usually exchanges on c6, but other moves are also possible.} 5... d5 $2 {would be a mistake due to} 6. e5 Nfd7 $6 7. Nxe6 $1 {. If White didn't have this pseudo sacrifice, everything would be fine for Black.} fxe6 {(slightly better is 7...Bb4+)} 8. Qh5+ {. A) After} g6 {, of course,} 9. Bxg6+ hxg6 10. Qxg6+ Ke7 11. Bg5+ {is winning. B) 8...Ke7 9.Bg5 Nf6 10.O-O is winning the piece back, and White's attack continues.}) 6. Be3 d5 {Black, of course, does not skip the opportunity to occupy the center, especially as the bishop on e3 can become a target for Black's pieces.} 7. exd5 (7. Nc3 Bb4 {is a transition to the variations examined in the chapter [/course/199209/11] on 6.Be3 ( 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 e6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 Nc6 6.Be3 Bb4 7.Bd3 d5 ) .}) 7... Nxd5 ({The most active recapture, as the knight attacks the bishop. Black accepts a pawn weakness in return.} 7... Qxd5 {is also good.}) 8. Nxc6 bxc6 9. Bd2 {The most common move. The bishop avoids the trade and supports the development of the knight to c3.} Rb8 $1 {White has trouble protecting the b2-pawn.} 10. O-O {It is likely best to directly abandon the pawn.} Rxb2 11. c4 Nf6 12. Qf3 {In exchange for the pawn, White has active piece play. The main idea is Bc3, putting pressure on f6.} Be7 ({It is best for Black to not worry about the pawn on c6, as White would otherwise develop a strong initiative with Bc3. White now has sufficient compensation for the pawn, but no more.} 12... c5 $6 13. Bc3 Bb7 14. Qh3 Rb6 15. Ba5 {was slightly better for White in Sahl-Mikhalevski [/variation/31423414/#/15/w], Caleta 2018 (0-1).}) 13. Bc3 (13. Qxc6+ Qd7 14. Qxd7+ Nxd7 {. Black has a slight advantage because the pawn on c4 is weak.} 15. Bc3 {is answered by} Bf6 $1 $15 {.}) 13... Rb7 {Followed by ...Rd7 and ...O-O.} *

