ve. The knight on d4 is facing a decision. White usually exchanges on c6, but other moves are also possible.} 5... d5 $2 {would be a mistake due to} 6. e5 Nfd7 $6 7. Nxe6 $1 {. If White didn't have this pseudo sacrifice, everything would be fine for Black.} fxe6 {(slightly better is 7...Bb4+)} 8. Qh5+ {. A) After} g6 {, of course,} 9. Bxg6+ hxg6 10. Qxg6+ Ke7 11. Bg5+ {is winning. B) 8...Ke7 9.Bg5 Nf6 10.O-O is winning the piece back, and White's attack continues.}) 6. Nb3 {I find it hard to explain the idea behind this move. White loses a tempo and the knight on b3 is not particularly well placed. However, it has already been played in several hundred games, including by strong grandmasters.} d5 {The battle for the center is an easy road to equality.} 7. exd5 Nxd5 {I also like 7...exd5. The knight on b3 is somewhat misplaced in the isolated queen's pawn position.} 8. a3 {The bishop goes to g7, where it exerts pressure on the white queenside. The other bishop could later be fianchettoed as well. The knight on b3 is poorly placed, so Black's position is preferable.} *

