ve. The knight on d4 is facing a decision. White usually exchanges on c6, but other moves are also possible.} 5... d5 $2 {would be a mistake due to} 6. e5 Nfd7 $6 7. Nxe6 $1 {. If White didn't have this pseudo sacrifice, everything would be fine for Black.} fxe6 {(slightly better is 7...Bb4+)} 8. Qh5+ {. A) After} g6 {, of course,} 9. Bxg6+ hxg6 10. Qxg6+ Ke7 11. Bg5+ {is winning. B) 8...Ke7 9.Bg5 Nf6 10.O-O is winning the piece back, and White's attack continues.}) 6. Nb3 {I find it hard to explain the idea behind this move. White loses a tempo and the knight on b3 is not particularly well placed. However, it has already been played in several hundred games, including by strong grandmasters.} d5 {The battle for the center is an easy road to equality.} 7. exd5 Nxd5 {I also like 7...exd5. The knight on b3 is somewhat misplaced in the isolated queen's pawn position.} 8. O-O Ndb4 $5 {This secures the bishop pair for Black. There was also nothing wrong with the simple development with ...Be7 and ...O-O.} 9. Be4 ({White can maintain the bishop pair with} 9. Be2 {, but after} Qxd1 10. Bxd1 e5 $15 {, they end up in a passive position, as demonstrated by my club mate FM Rüdiger Breyther over 40 years ago. Fecht-Breyther [/variation/31423415/#/10/b], Bad Neuenahr 1980 (½-½).}) 9... Qxd1 10. Rxd1 f5 11. Z0 ({That was the idea behind the knight sortie in the eighth move. White now has to part with the bishop. The position is balanced, but with the bishop pair, Black has long-term chances to fight for the full point. A)} 11. Bxc6+ Nxc6 {leads to a balanced position. B) 11.c3 fxe4 12.cxb4 Nxb4 13.Nc3 was the game Marquardt-Luther [/variation/31423416/#/13/w], Ditzingen 2012 (0-1). Now I like developing the bishop with 13...Bd7 14.Nxe4 Bc6= the most.}) *

