ve. The knight on d4 is facing a decision. White usually exchanges on c6, but other moves are also possible.} 5... d5 $2 {would be a mistake due to} 6. e5 Nfd7 $6 7. Nxe6 $1 {. If White didn't have this pseudo sacrifice, everything would be fine for Black.} fxe6 {(slightly better is 7...Bb4+)} 8. Qh5+ {. A) After} g6 {, of course,} 9. Bxg6+ hxg6 10. Qxg6+ Ke7 11. Bg5+ {is winning. B) 8...Ke7 9.Bg5 Nf6 10.O-O is winning the piece back, and White's attack continues.}) 6. Nxc6 ({We analyzed the position after} 6. Nf3 Bc5 {via the move order [/variation/31423210/#/6/b] 4.Qxd4 Nc6 5.Qd1 Nf6 6.Bd3 Bc5 .}) 6... bxc6 {Next, Black wants to fight for the center with d7-d5. c4 White wants to develop the knight to c3 without blocking the c-pawn. d5 cxd5?! The most common move leads to a slightly better position for Black. Better is exd5 cxd5} 7. O-O {. We examine this via the move order [/variation/31423235/#/9/w] 7.O-O d5 8.exd5 cxd5 9.c4 . cxd5 e5?! Qe2 Qc7 Bf4 g5! Bxg5 Qxe5 Black will build pressure against the b2 pawn and has the better position.} *

