ve. The knight on d4 is facing a decision. White usually exchanges on c6, but other moves are also possible.} 5... d5 $2 {would be a mistake due to} 6. e5 Nfd7 $6 7. Nxe6 $1 {. If White didn't have this pseudo sacrifice, everything would be fine for Black.} fxe6 {(slightly better is 7...Bb4+)} 8. Qh5+ {. A) After} g6 {, of course,} 9. Bxg6+ hxg6 10. Qxg6+ Ke7 11. Bg5+ {is winning. B) 8...Ke7 9.Bg5 Nf6 10.O-O is winning the piece back, and White's attack continues.}) 6. Nxc6 ({We analyzed the position after} 6. Nf3 Bc5 {via the move order [/variation/31423210/#/6/b] 4.Qxd4 Nc6 5.Qd1 Nf6 6.Bd3 Bc5 .}) 6... bxc6 {Next, Black wants to fight for the center with d7-d5. c4 White wants to develop the knight to c3 without blocking the c-pawn. d5 cxd5?! The most common move leads to a slightly better position for Black. Better is exd5 cxd5} 7. O-O {. We examine this via the move order [/variation/31423235/#/9/w] 7.O-O d5 8.exd5 cxd5 9.c4 . cxd5 exd5 Nc3 dxe4} Nxe4 $15 {Bb4+! . The knight must now retreat. Black has the freer game. Qxd5 O-O? With this natural move, White overlooks a tactical detail. Bb7 The mating threat on g2 puts White under pressure. f3? After this, White is already lost. Necessary is} 8. Qf3 {, which after Qxf3 gxf3} Bd6 {leads to a significant advantage for Black. 12...Bxf3 is also possible but allows 13.Bb5 . Rd8 The bishop cannot move now because then 12...Qc5+ wins the queen. Qa4+ The only chance. Bc6 Qa6 By attacking the c6-bishop, White was able to avoid losing a piece, but... Bc5+ Kh1 Nh5! Black has a mating attack and wins. Bf4 Bb6! The best attempt. After Nxf4 , White wins back the piece with} 9. Bxe4 {. ➤ 15.Be4 ignores the opponent's threat: 15...Ng3! 16.hxg3 Qh5# . ➤ 15.g4 allows for a different mating idea: 15...Qxf3! 16.Rxf3 Bxf3 . With this quiet move, Black attacks both bishops as the bishop on c6 is no longer under attack from the queen. Be4 Bb5! Now the rook is also under attack. Qa3 Qc5 New Delhi} *

