1. e4 c5 {The Sicilian Opening stands for a sharp fight. Black somewhat neglects their piece development in order to prevent White from establishing a full pawn center with d2-d4.} 2. Nf3 e6 ({The third most common move after} 2... d6 {and}) (2... Nc6 {. With this, Black primarily prepares the development of the dark-squared bishop, but the center push ...d7-d5 becomes a possibility as well.}) (2... Nc6 {is an alternative way to reach the Four Knights Sicilian:} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6 {and we have landed in our repertoire via transposition. I decided against this path because White has a very serious and popular alternative in 3.Bb5 , the Rossolimo Variation. With 2...e6 the Rossolimo Variation is avoided.}) 3. d4 {The Open Sicilian and the starting position of this course. I examine alternatives for White on the second and third moves in a separate course on the Anti-Sicilians. The Open Sicilian is White's most principled attempt to fight for the opening advantage. White has more space and wants to open up the position, relying on rapid piece development. In return, Black gets the semi-open c-file, which can often be used for counterplay later on. Moreover, the exchange of the d-pawn for the c-pawn is a minor positional concession, as White now has only one pawn in the center and therefore can no longer fight quite as well for the important central squares.} cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 ({A very logical move - the knight is developed and simultaneously attacks the e4 pawn. Black takes advantage of the fact that the knight cannot be directly attacked with e4-e5 .} 4... Nc6 {is also possible, but gives White the additional option} 5. Nb5 {.}) 5. Bd3 ({White places the bishop on a good square and protects the e-pawn. This natural developing move is the second most popular move after 5.Nc3. Compared to 5.Nc3, the nature of the position is now somewhat slower, as White is not threatening e4-e5.} 5. e5 $2 Qa5+ {wins a pawn.}) 5... Nc6 ({Here as well, this is the correct move. The knight on d4 is facing a decision. White usually exchanges on c6, but other moves are also possible.} 5... d5 $2 {would be a mistake due to} 6. e5 Nfd7 $6 7. Nxe6 $1 {. If White didn't have this pseudo sacrifice, everything would be fine for Black.} fxe6 {(slightly better is 7...Bb4+)} 8. Qh5+ {. A) After} g6 {, of course,} 9. Bxg6+ hxg6 10. Qxg6+ Ke7 11. Bg5+ {is winning. B) 8...Ke7 9.Bg5 Nf6 10.O-O is winning the piece back, and White's attack continues.}) 6. Nxc6 ({We analyzed the position after} 6. Nf3 Bc5 {via the move order [/variation/31423210/#/6/b] 4.Qxd4 Nc6 5.Qd1 Nf6 6.Bd3 Bc5 .}) 6... bxc6 7. Bf4 {A relatively fresh idea, introduced by Vahap Sanal into grandmaster practice in 2021 and repeated by some strong players since. White prepares against the central attack ...d7-d5.} d5 8. Nd2 {After 7.O-O d5 8.Nd2 , the dark-squared bishop is locked in and must be awkwardly developed via b2. Here, on the other hand, it is already well-placed. White thus achieves a harmonious piece setup.} g6 ({Reveals a hidden drawback of White's piece setup: Black threatens to secure the bishop pair with ...Nh5, as the f4-bishop has no safe retreat. Additionally, new perspectives are opened for Black's own dark-squared bishop. Instead,} 8... Bd6 $2 {runs into} 9. e5 Bc7 10. Qf3 Nd7 11. Qg3 $16 {, while after 8...Be7 , White plays 9.O-O O-O 10.c4 or 10.e5 and has the freer game.}) 9. c3 ({Prophylaxis against the threat ...Nh5. After} 9. O-O Nh5 10. Be5 {( 10.Be3?? d4-+ ) 10...f6 11.Bg3 Bh6 Black is at least not worse.}) 9... Nh5 ({The developing move} 9... Bg7 {is playable as well, but has the disadvantage that White might prevent us from castling with} 10. Qa4 $5 Qb6 11. exd5 exd5 12. Bd6 {.}) 10. Be3 {Now this is possible, as White has taken control over d4 with 9.c3.} Bd6 ({Together with the knight, the bishop eyes the f4-square. After} 10... Bg7 {, White could once again disturb our development with} 11. Bc5 {.}) 11. O-O (11. Nf3 {is best met with} Qc7 {, preventing White from playing e4-e5.}) 11... O-O 12. Z0 ({Black has equalized. Next, the light-squared bishop could be activated with a7-a5 followed by ...Ba6 or e6-e5. In the game Lavrencic-Lagarde [/variation/36055963], Tegernsee 2023 (0-1), White tried to play on the dark squares with} 12. b4 $6 {, but now Black could have taken over the initiative with} a5 $1 {and if} 13. a3 Nf4 $1 {.}) *

