ve. The knight on d4 is facing a decision. White usually exchanges on c6, but other moves are also possible.} 5... d5 $2 {would be a mistake due to} 6. e5 Nfd7 $6 7. Nxe6 $1 {. If White didn't have this pseudo sacrifice, everything would be fine for Black.} fxe6 {(slightly better is 7...Bb4+)} 8. Qh5+ {. A) After} g6 {, of course,} 9. Bxg6+ hxg6 10. Qxg6+ Ke7 11. Bg5+ {is winning. B) 8...Ke7 9.Bg5 Nf6 10.O-O is winning the piece back, and White's attack continues.}) 6. Nxc6 ({We analyzed the position after} 6. Nf3 Bc5 {via the move order [/variation/31423210/#/6/b] 4.Qxd4 Nc6 5.Qd1 Nf6 6.Bd3 Bc5 .}) 6... bxc6 {Next, Black wants to fight for the center with d7-d5. O-O} 7. Nc3 d5 {. This position is included in the chapter [/course/199209/7] on the sidelines after 6.Nxc6 ( 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 e6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 Nc6 6.Nxc6 bxc6 7.Bd3 d5 ). d5 We reach the typical pawn structure in this variation. White must now respond to the attack on the e4-pawn. e5 Re1 a5= Black would certainly like to castle, but after Be7 ,} 8. Qg4 {is strong, which would force Black to weaken their position on the kingside. An alternative option is the bishop development with} g6 {, but that weakens the black squares and the bishop on g7 is not necessarily well placed. I therefore like the pawn move, with which Black plans to exchange bishops with ...Ba6 and to gain space with ...a5-a4. The development of the kingside can then be approached later, depending on White's setup. It is not clear how White can strengthen their position now. The chances are equal. Nd2 ➤ c4 allows for the bishop development with tempo. Bb4 Nc3} 9. O-O {. Black has managed to castle and has no problems. Pranesh–Shyam [/variation/31423418/#/11/b], Spengenberg 2022 (0-1). ➤ With c3?! , White wants to preserve the bishop on d3 from the exchange. Now,} Ba6 {Bc2 Qb8! exposes a tactical drawback of White's idea: the e5 pawn cannot be well defended. ( 12.f4? Bc5 13.Kh1 Bf2 wins the exchange. ) Thus, Qd4 , and in the game Dinger–Faerman [/variation/31423420/#/12/w], Pardubice 2008 (1-0), Black could have developed a strong initiative with Bc5} 10. Qf4 $15 {f6! exf6 O-O! . The rook and bishop are targeting the pawn on f2. Ba6 Qg4 , the grandmaster chose: g6 While this move weakens the black squares, it allows the bishop to develop to g7, where it can attack the pawn on e5. Another option is} Bxd3 11. cxd3 h5 $5 {Nf3 Bg7 h4 Qg3 Bxd3 White had already threatened a piece sacrifice on g6, so it was futile to wait further with the exchange. cxd3 c5 A good positional move. Black makes it difficult for White to play d3-d4, making the pawns on e5 and d3 potential targets. This led to a complex battle with equal chances. Black is worse on the kingside but has good counterplay against White's pawns in the center and on the queenside. You can study the remainder of the game Meijers-Ehlvest [/variation/31423252] with my comments in the model game section [/course/199209/14] .} *

