ve. The knight on d4 is facing a decision. White usually exchanges on c6, but other moves are also possible.} 5... d5 $2 {would be a mistake due to} 6. e5 Nfd7 $6 7. Nxe6 $1 {. If White didn't have this pseudo sacrifice, everything would be fine for Black.} fxe6 {(slightly better is 7...Bb4+)} 8. Qh5+ {. A) After} g6 {, of course,} 9. Bxg6+ hxg6 10. Qxg6+ Ke7 11. Bg5+ {is winning. B) 8...Ke7 9.Bg5 Nf6 10.O-O is winning the piece back, and White's attack continues.}) 6. Nxc6 ({We analyzed the position after} 6. Nf3 Bc5 {via the move order [/variation/31423210/#/6/b] 4.Qxd4 Nc6 5.Qd1 Nf6 6.Bd3 Bc5 .}) 6... bxc6 {Next, Black wants to fight for the center with d7-d5. O-O} 7. Nc3 d5 {. This position is included in the chapter [/course/199209/7] on the sidelines after 6.Nxc6 ( 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 e6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 Nc6 6.Nxc6 bxc6 7.Bd3 d5 ). d5 We reach the typical pawn structure in this variation. White must now respond to the attack on the e4-pawn. Nd2 The main move. The knight is less likely to be attacked on d2 than on c3, and it does not block the c-pawn. White can later develop the dark-squared bishop to b2. Nc3 Be7 is a transposition [/variation/31423049/#/8/b] to 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 e6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 Nc6 6.Nxc6 bxc6 7.Bd3 d5 8.O-O Be7 . Bd6 I prefer this here over the more passive Be7 . For one thing, White cannot play e4-e5. For another, Black can later play ...e6-e5 themselves. This can be advantageous, for example, if White develops the bishop to b2. After Be7 , I am bothered by} 8. e5 Nd7 9. Qh5 $5 $15 {or 10.Qg4 . Qe2 Prevents e4-e5 and attacks the h2-pawn. Nf3?! This allows the white-squared bishop to be exchanged, which White should avoid. dxe4 Bxe4 Nxe4 Qxe4 Bb7 Next, Black plays ...c6-c5, activating the bishop on b7. The black bishops are very strong and exert pressure on the white kingside. Black has a slight advantage.} *

