1. e4 c5 {The Sicilian Opening stands for a sharp fight. Black somewhat neglects their piece development in order to prevent White from establishing a full pawn center with d2-d4.} 2. Nf3 e6 ({The third most common move after} 2... d6 {and}) (2... Nc6 {. With this, Black primarily prepares the development of the dark-squared bishop, but the center push ...d7-d5 becomes a possibility as well.}) (2... Nc6 {is an alternative way to reach the Four Knights Sicilian:} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6 {and we have landed in our repertoire via transposition. I decided against this path because White has a very serious and popular alternative in 3.Bb5 , the Rossolimo Variation. With 2...e6 the Rossolimo Variation is avoided.}) 3. d4 {The Open Sicilian and the starting position of this course. I examine alternatives for White on the second and third moves in a separate course on the Anti-Sicilians. The Open Sicilian is White's most principled attempt to fight for the opening advantage. White has more space and wants to open up the position, relying on rapid piece development. In return, Black gets the semi-open c-file, which can often be used for counterplay later on. Moreover, the exchange of the d-pawn for the c-pawn is a minor positional concession, as White now has only one pawn in the center and therefore can no longer fight quite as well for the important central squares.} cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 ({A very logical move - the knight is developed and simultaneously attacks the e4 pawn. Black takes advantage of the fact that the knight cannot be directly attacked with e4-e5 .} 4... Nc6 {is also possible, but gives White the additional option} 5. Nb5 {.}) 5. Bd3 ({White places the bishop on a good square and protects the e-pawn. This natural developing move is the second most popular move after 5.Nc3. Compared to 5.Nc3, the nature of the position is now somewhat slower, as White is not threatening e4-e5.} 5. e5 $2 Qa5+ {wins a pawn.}) 5... Nc6 ({Here as well, this is the correct move. The knight on d4 is facing a decision. White usually exchanges on c6, but other moves are also possible.} 5... d5 $2 {would be a mistake due to} 6. e5 Nfd7 $6 7. Nxe6 $1 {. If White didn't have this pseudo sacrifice, everything would be fine for Black.} fxe6 {(slightly better is 7...Bb4+)} 8. Qh5+ {. A) After} g6 {, of course,} 9. Bxg6+ hxg6 10. Qxg6+ Ke7 11. Bg5+ {is winning. B) 8...Ke7 9.Bg5 Nf6 10.O-O is winning the piece back, and White's attack continues.}) 6. Nxc6 ({We analyzed the position after} 6. Nf3 Bc5 {via the move order [/variation/31423210/#/6/b] 4.Qxd4 Nc6 5.Qd1 Nf6 6.Bd3 Bc5 .}) 6... bxc6 {Next, Black wants to fight for the center with d7-d5. O-O} 7. Nc3 d5 {. This position is included in the chapter [/course/199209/7] on the sidelines after 6.Nxc6 ( 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 e6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 Nc6 6.Nxc6 bxc6 7.Bd3 d5 ). d5 We reach the typical pawn structure in this variation. White must now respond to the attack on the e4-pawn. Nd2 The main move. The knight is less likely to be attacked on d2 than on c3, and it does not block the c-pawn. White can later develop the dark-squared bishop to b2. Nc3 Be7 is a transposition [/variation/31423049/#/8/b] to 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 e6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 Nc6 6.Nxc6 bxc6 7.Bd3 d5 8.O-O Be7 . Bd6 I prefer this here over the more passive Be7 . For one thing, White cannot play e4-e5. For another, Black can later play ...e6-e5 themselves. This can be advantageous, for example, if White develops the bishop to b2. After Be7 , I am bothered by} 8. e5 Nd7 9. Qh5 $5 {or 10.Qg4 . Qe2 Prevents e4-e5 and attacks the h2-pawn. h3 O-O c4 White increases the pressure on the black center. Bb7 Black has completed development and has achieved comfortable equality. The bishop could be activated through a later ...c6-c5. If necessary, ...e6-e5 is a good idea, especially when White threatens e4-e5 themselves. Another possible improvement of the position is the maneuver ...Nd7-c5. b3?! Most commonly played, with the obvious intention of placing the bishop on b2. After Re1 , Black can choose between e5 and 12...Nd7 , both resulting in an equal position. d4! After this novelty, the bishop on b2 is no longer well placed as it is blocked by the black pawn. Black will play ...c6-c5 next and later have the pawn lever ...a7-a5-a4, with better chances. Note that ...d5-d4 is only a good move because White has already played c2-c4. If the pawn was still on c2, White would have a nice square c4 for the knight and the pawn lever c2-c3.} *

