{Rfc8-+ . Nxd4! . Both players miss this tactical shot, which complicated Black's win. Nxd4? Re7 is the idea.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 {Ndb5} Bc5 6. Bf4 O-O 7. Bc7 Qe7 8. Bd6 Bxd6 {Qxd6 Qd8 O-O-O a6 Nd4 Ne7} 9. f3 {a3 Prophylaxis against ...b5-b4 – not a bad move, but it does have the disadvantage of opening up the queenside if black does manage to play ...b5-b4 after all.} Ne8 {The typical approach, expelling the queen from her active location. Qg3 Qb6 The black position is easier to play, as there are many moves that can be used to strengthen their position on the queenside and in the center. The right plan for White, on the other hand, is not so clear.} 10. Nb3 {This retreat is probably intended to prepare Bd3. d6 A typical idea for Black is now ...e6-e5 and ...Be6. With their next move White apparently wants to prevent this. f4?!} ({I like} 10. Bd3 {better. In case Black plays} e5 {(other moves like 17...Bb7 or 17...Nc6 are better ) White can still play} 11. f4 $1 {and get counterplay on the kingside.}) ({Bd7 Now it's already difficult for White to come up with a defense against the imminent ...a6-a5 and ...b5-b4. Kb1? That is of course too slow.} 10. Qd3 $1 $15 {is better. By attacking b5, White stops the direct ...a6-a5, and Qd4 and e4-e5 can be useful resources. After Bc6 , however, the black position is still preferable. The idea is ...Rb8 followed by ...a6-a5.}) 10... a5 {White's position is already barely salvageable.} 11. Bd3 a4 $6 $17 ({Allows White some counterplay. I like the natural b4! better. After axb4 axb4 Ne2 the knight on b3 still defends the white king against a direct mating attack on the a-file. But after a quiet move like} 11... Nf6 {it's unclear what White should do. Black will slowly involve the previously uninvolved pieces in the attack on the queenside.}) 12. Nd2 {b4 Nc4! Qc5 axb4 Qxb4 Qe1 Rb8 Na2 Qb7 Qc3 White is forced to protect b2. Black was threatening ...d6-d5. d5 exd5 exd5 Ne5 Be6 Rhe1} {Stronger was Qf2 with the threat of Qb6. Rb8 Qa7 Nf6 .} Nf6 $6 {The knight’s prospects are considerably brighter on d6. Qa3 Generally speaking, it's no good news if the queen is tied to the protection of a pawn. d4 Involving the e6-bishop in the attack.} 13. Nc4 {Nf5? Bxf5 Black wanted to exchange on c4 and subsequently place a knight on e3. Bxc4 Bd3? Be6 f5 Bd5 g4 An act of desperation. Otherwise, Black would have brought more pieces to the queenside.} {A mistake that was not punished. Black should have protected the d-pawn first: Rfd8-+ . Following this ...Nf5 is a good idea. After that, the position is lost again. From now on, Dreev leaves nothing to chance, even if he doesn't always find the most direct moves. After the simple Rxd4 White would have been very much back in the game: Bxa2+ Kxa2 Qxg2= . Rfc8-+ .} Ng4 14. Rg1 {Rde1 Nc1 Be4 Ne2 Bxd3 cxd3 Nxf5? Nf4 Qb3 Qxb3+ Rxb3 Nh5 Kf7 Ref1 Rxf5 gxf5 Rg7+ Ke6 Nf4+ Ke5 Ne2 Rfb8 Not a flawless game, but it effectively demonstrates how an attack on the queenside can be conducted against indecisive play.} 0-1

