{~ Kreuzholz – Feuerstack ~ 2. German League 2014} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 {Ndb5} Bc5 6. Bf4 O-O 7. Bc7 Qe7 8. Bd6 Bxd6 {Qxd6 Qd8} 9. Qd2 {exd5 exd5 I suggested the novelty} Nd5 {The text move presents a viable alternative and leads to a more complex position.} 10. O-O-O {Logical and best. White prevents ...d5-d4. As we'll see in this game, the advance of the black d-pawn is an important theme in this type of position. Be6 The bishop protects the pawn on d5, but is quite passive. Black would therefore like to play ...d5-d4 or ...d5xe4 (after ...Ne4) . f3!} ({A good move. On the one hand it prepares g2-g4, on the other it permanently prevents ...Ne4. Nd4 was an alternative, for example Qa5} 10. f3 {Nxd4 Qxd4} b5 $132 {. Strategically, White has the upper hand thanks to the stable blockade on d4. But the pawn sacrifice gives Black counterplay against the kingside position. In the game Onslow, A (2059) – Cramling Bellon, A (2013), Caleta 2019 (½-½)} 11. Bxb5 {Rab8 followed. Black has strong compensation. ...Rfc8 could follow next. White's decision is therefore justified: Qa4 Qb6 Qd4 Qa5 Qa4 with repetition.}) {Rc8 Qa5 was possible and would probably have led to the previous remark after Nd4 . g4 Nd4 was probably more precise. Qa5 The pawn sacrifice d4!? was interesting. After Nxd4 Nxd4 Qxd4 Qa5 , Black has excellent play on the queenside. With 15.Nd4 , White could have removed this possibility from the position. a3 Black had threatened ...d5-d4 with an attack on the a2-pawn, so White dodges the attack.} 10... Rd8 {...d5-d4 is now a strong threat, because then the knight on b5 no longer has a safe square to retreat to. Nd4 Nd7! It seemed as if White had everything under control and successfully secured a small advantage without any real counterplay. But the regrouping of the black knight shows that the position is quite double-edged. My opponent didn't yet recognize the danger and quickly ended up in a bad position.} {Qe3 was also possible, but what could be more natural than occupying the blockade square with the knight?} 11. Be2 $2 {Directed against ...Nde5, this move overlooks the idea behind the knight move. It was better to strengthen the blockade on d4 with 18.Nce2 . After 18...Qb6 19.Qf4 Nde5 the position is equal. Nxd4!} ({Nde5?!} 11. Nxe6 fxe6 12. f4 {Nd7 Rhe1 is slightly better for White.}) ({Qxd4 Nb8! Black is already a little better! The knight threatens to go to c6 and push through the long-awaited ...d5-d4 advance. f4 White opts for counterplay on the kingside.} 11. Qe3 $5 Nc6 {Nb5! a6 Nd4 . White has succeeded in renewing the blockade, but after Qc5 there are tactical weaknesses in the white position. Black threatens ...Nxd4 with an attack on c2 and after c3 Bxg4! fxg4 Re8 Qf2 Nxd4 Rxd4 Rxe2} 12. Qe2 {Qxd4 Black has comfortable play with an extra pawn.}) 11... Nc6 {Qd2?} ({After this move, the white position is already beyond saving. Qa4 was necessary, but after Qc7! (or ...Qb6) White can't prevent ...d5-d4 in the long run either. After} 11... f5 $17 {Bd7 follows because} 12. Nxd5 {fails to Nd4! .}) ({d4 Black now manages to mount a decisive attack against the white king. Ne4 Nb1 is no better, e.g. Qb6} 11... f5 $2 {Na5-+ and the threat ...Nb3# costs White the queen.}) {Qd5} 12. Qd3 f6 $6 ({Prevents 24.Ng5 and gives the light-squared bishop a square to retreat to. Stronger was} 12... Na5 $1 {, but I had discarded that because of Ng5 . Black must now find Rxc2+! and correctly evaluate the position after Qxc2 ( 25.Kxc2? Rc8 26.Kd2 Nb3+ 27.Ke1 Qxh1+-+ ) Rc8} 13. Nxe6 Nb3+ 14. Kb1 {Rxc2 Kxc2} fxe6 {as won. Queen and knight are known to be a strong attacking duo and here they are supported by the two central pawns (the f4-pawn will soon fall).}) {Qa2? Ng5 gives White counterplay.} 13. Bf3 $2 ({With} 13. b3 $17 {White could have prevented the queen from entering, thus staying in the game. Still, White would have had to contend with a very bad position.}) {Qa2 Now it's over. Black simultaneously threatens ...Na5 (followed by ...Nb3), ...Qa1+ (followed by ...Qxb2) and ...Bc4 (when the white queen has no square as after Qd2 follows ...Qa1#). Nc5 Qe4 Qa1+ Kd2 Qxb2 Rb1 Qc3+ Kd1} 13... Re8 14. Na4 {I like this game because it highlights the dynamic potential of the black position. One moment of carelessness was enough to turn the seemingly safe white position into a pile of rubble.} 0-1

