{~ Piorun – Abasov ~ Prague Chess festival 2020} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3 Nf6 6. Ndb5 Bc5 7. Nd6+ Ke7 8. Bf4 e5 9. Nf5+ Kf8 10. Bg5 {Bd3} h6 11. Bxf6 Qxf6 12. Nd5 Qd8 13. c3 g6 14. Nfe3 a6 {, I suggested Be6 . The text move is logical as well. Black wants to keep the dark-squared bishop after b2-b4 and therefore opens up a retreat square on a7. h4 This aggressive approach doesn't seem to be the best plan. White now cannot easily castle kingside, as this would leave the h-pawn unprotected. On the queenside, however, the white king is less secure. O-O looks more positionally correct, after which White can follow up with the f2-f4 pawn break, or alternatively advance the pawns on the queenside. We have examined similar positions in the corresponding theory chapter. h5 White wanted to play h4-h5, and Black puts a permanent stop to this endeavor. In addition, control of g4 could prove useful later. Qe2 Be6 g3 White covers the pawn on h4, but the main intention behind this move is probably different: f2-f4-f5 and an attack on the black king. Strangely enough, however, both players ignore this possibility in what follows. Kg7?! The move fits into the black setup, but I think it would have been better to do something against f2-f4 first. In this structure} 15. Ne7 {is usually a good move. By exchanging pieces Black weakens White's control over the important square d5. What is more, without the two knights, White cannot build up a strong attack against the black king. After Bc4 many of the minor pieces in the center will probably be exchanged later. The position is roughly equal. O-O-O?! 19.f4?! is already no good: 19...Nxd5 20.Nxd5 (Oder 20.exd5 Bd7 $15 .) 20...Kg7 $15 . White has no chance of attacking the black king. Black has the bishop pair and is already slightly better. Apparently White had already made this plan with his sixteenth move. Here White would have been better off waiting and focusing on the kingside first. Perhaps he thought that f2-f4 wouldn't run away, but speed is an important factor here. With f4 White would have secured slightly better chances, threatening f4-f5. In case of} Nxe7 $14 {White, after Nxe7 Qxe7 can play f5 . b5!? Black goes for counterplay. Another possibility was once again Ne7 , similar to the comment on the previous move. The move b5 aims to push the pawn to b4 and attack White’s c3-pawn. If the c3-pawn moves away or is exchanged, Black’s knight gains access to the d4-square. 19...b5 also clears the 7th rank for the black major pieces. a3 Understandably, White prevents b5-b4. After} 16. f4 $132 {, b4 could have followed. The position is very sharp, both sides are playing for an attack on the other’s king. This was probably would have been White's best chance. Ne7! Once again the right idea. Exchanges are good for Black, who has a good chance of emerging with the better bishop and pawn structure. Bc2?! This is too slow. White should still rely on rapid play on the kingside. Nxe7 Qxe7} exf4 {was better, but after Qa7! Rhe1 (the knight cannot move because of 23...Bg4) Bd7 , with the idea ...a6-a5 and ...b5-b4, Black has the upper hand. a5! This shows a good positional understanding. The b-pawn can be sacrificed in exchange for open files. b4? A well-known defensive idea that prevents the pawn break ...b5-b4. However, it doesn't work here because there are too many weaknesses in the white position. It was better to capture the pawn: Qxb5 Rb8} 17. Qe2 Nd5 18. Nxd5 $17 {Qd7 . However, it's understandable that White didn't want to go for that. Black brings his major pieces to the queenside and has a strong attack. White could still have played for counterchances on the kingside: f4 b4 .However, Black is quicker with his attack. Nxe7} Qe7 $17 {f5 Ba2 . This unusual move allows the bishop to remain on the active diagonal. axb4 axb4 cxb4 Bd4-+ is no better. Bxe3+! Black doesn’t lose any time. Qxe3 Bxd5 The second exchange was not necessary. The direct Ra2 would have led to a decisive attack. The text move is more of a positional nature: as we'll see, the white bishop is clearly inferior to the knight. exd5 Ra2-+ Poses the deadly threat ...Qa8-a3. The white response is therefore forced. Bb3 Qe1 Ra7 White has fought back the direct onslaught, but the position is still hopeless. Black now threatens to bring additional forces to the attack with ...Qb6 and ...Rha8. Kb2 In order to play Ra1. Qb6 Targets the f-pawn. The white queen is now tied to its defense. Qd2 e4 Opens a second front. Also very strong was Rha8 Ra1 Nh6-+ followed by ...Ng4. White cannot simultaneously defend the a-file and the pawn on f2. Ra1 Re7 Rhe1 Rhe8 Bc2 e3 The decisive breakthrough. White has too many weaknesses. fxe3 Nxe3 Bd3 Re5 Re2 Rxd5 The rest is easy. Kb3 Nc4 Qc2 Rxe2 Qxe2 Re5 Qg2 d5 Rd1 Qe6 0-1} 0-1

