{~ Bilych – Risteski ~ U18 European Youth Team Championship, Thessaloniki 2022} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 {bxc6} 6. e5 Nd5 7. Ne4 {f4 c4 Qd3} Bb4+ 8. Bd2 {Ba6 Rc1 Rxc4 Nxc4 Qxc4} Bxd2+ 9. Nxd2 {Qxb2 Bd3} O-O 10. Ke2 Rb8 {Up to this point, we have examined the moves in the theory section [/variation/31423007/#/18/b] . Qe4 g6 Bc4 f6 As is so often the case, this pawn break is desirable to make the d-pawn mobile again. Qd3 Qxd7 exf4} ({Black is alert. The main threat was not 22.Qxd7. Rf7?? Rb1 traps the queen. Now after Rb1? , Qd4 follows. Rxf4 was also possible and would probably have led to an early perpetual, for example after Qxe6+} 10... Kh8 11. Rb1 {Rf2+! Kxf2 Qxd2+ Kg3 Qf4+ Kh3 Qh6+ Kg3 Qf4+= .}) {Qxe6+ Kh8} 11. Rb1 {This was forced, Black was threatening ...Re8.} Re8 {Queen moves would have been met with a rook exchange, after which ...Re8 would no longer have been a threat. The text move exchanges queens and rooks, giving rise to an equal endgame. Rxb2 Rxe6+ Bxe6 Rxb2 Bb3! The rook on b2 is almost trapped. Black must have already seen how to resolve this predicament when playing 24...Rfe8. c5!} 12. Kd3 {c4+ White had threatened 29.Kc3 with a win. Black liberates the rook at the cost of a pawn. Bxc4 Rb8 The material is balanced and neither side has any weaknesses (the pawn on f4 can be protected with ...g6-g5). The draw is only a matter of time. a4 Kg7} {Now Kc3? leads to a lost pawn endgame: Rxd2 Kxd2 cxb3 axb3-+ .} a5 {Rd8+} 13. Ke2 {Rd4 a6} g5 {Be6 h5} 14. h3 {Kf6 Bc8 Ra4 Bb7} g4 15. hxg4 {hxg4 Ne4+ Ke5} Nc3+ {Nb5 Kf1 Ra1+ Kf2 Ra2+ Kf1 Ra1+ Kf2 Ra2+ A flawless game from both players.} 1/2-1/2

