{~ Degraeve – Müller ~ Bundesliga 2007/08} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 {bxc6} 6. e5 Nd5 7. Ne4 {f4 c4 Qd3} Bb4+ 8. Bd2 {Ba6 b3} O-O 9. Bxb4 {Qxb4+ Kf2 Nd5 g3} Qb6 {Kf3 c5 I recommended the more direct f6 . The text move c5 is less precise, but also logical. The pawn leaves the long diagonal and clears the way for the light-squared bishop, which will have soon fulfilled its task on a6. Bg2 White’s light-squared bishop is already defending the long diagonal. Black had planned ...Nb4 and ...Bb7. Nb4 Qd2 This is not yet a mistake, but White is making life difficult for themselves. On other squares the queen would have worked more effectively against Black’s idea. A) The easiest was Qd6 . By blocking the black d-pawn White avoids getting caught in an attack. Bb7 Kf2 Bxe4! is best, otherwise White plays Rhd1 and besieges the weak d-pawn. That's why Black wants to exchange on d6 such that White has to recapture with the pawn. A.1) Qxb6 axb6 Bxe4 Rxa2= . A.2) 21.Bxe4 Qxd6 22.exd6 Rac8= . So after 23.a3 Blacks has Nc6 . The position is dynamically equal. B) Qc3 f6 Rhd1! or 19.Qe2 f6 20.exf6 d5 21.Ng5 Rxf6 22.Kf2 were also playable. C) But not Qxd7? Rad8 Qe7 Bb7 because the white king is too vulnerable while the queen is offside. f6! Things are getting uncomfortable for the king on f3. exf6? Ke3! is the engine suggestion, according to which everything is fine with White. From a human point of view this is far from obvious, so I'm not surprised that Degraeve chose a different move. d5! A typical idea in the variation with 6.Nxc6: As soon as the white pawn is no longer on e5, the knight can be driven off e4. The pawn on f6 can be captured later. gxf6? is too harmless. Here, Black can no longer use the f-file for the rook. With} 10. Nd6 {White blocks the d-pawn and doesn’t have any problems. cxd5? This leads to a further opening of the position, which the white king cannot survive. The only defense was f7! Rxf7 Ng5 . The pawn sacrifice has forced the black rook to a square where it can be attacked by the white knight. Rf6 a3} h6 $1 $17 {. Black maintains the upper hand amid the complications, but unless you have an engine at hand it's hard to tell. Nh7! is best, stopping the black h-pawn from appearing on g5 from where it could support the attack. Kxh7 axb4 e5 . The king remains the problem of the white position. exd5 Nf2 After f7+ Rxf7 Ng5 Rf6} 11. a3 {, Nd3-+ would have already been possible. d4 There were other good moves, but I like Karsten Müller's energetic play. The pawn on f6 is secondary. Black opens the long diagonal for the bishop and also threatens ...Rae8 followed by ... Re3+. g4 Creates an escape square for the king. Bb7+ Now was a good time to capture the pawn: Qxf6! . White won't be able to defend against all threats, for example Kg3 Rae8 . A) Rae1 Re3! Rxe3 Qxf4-+ B) 25.Ne4 Qg6-+ followed by ...Nd5. Kg3 Bxg2 fxg7? White should have immediately recaptured on g2. The intermediate move only forces the rook onto a better square. Rfe8 Kxg2 Qc6+ Kg1 Kg3 Re3+-+ . Qf3 The white position is completely hopeless. The king is vulnerable, and the rook on h1 is not participating in the game. Qc1 Re2 Qc4+ Nd5 Rf1 Rae8 b4 Rxf2 Rxf2 Re1+ Rf1 Qe3+ After 34.Kg2 , 34...Re2+ would have followed, winning the queen and mating soon after. The game shows how strong Black's pawn breaks can be when White’s king is in the center. White cannot afford to be careless, as they were in this game. 0-1} 0-1

