{~ Geller – Khasin ~ 28. USSR Championship, Moscow 1961} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6 6. Be2 Bb4 7. O-O Bxc3 8. bxc3 Nxe4 9. Bd3 {Ba3 This game is one of the first in this variation and the subtleties were not yet known. cxd4 Qa5 Qc1 Qf3!? . Bd7 This was the main variation for a long time. The bishop goes to c6 and Black can castle queenside. Rb1 Bc6 Bb4?! The most common move, but not the strongest. Better is f3} Nf6 {and now, for example, Bb4 Qc7 . By inserting 14.f3, White has ensured that the black knight moves to f6 rather than d6.} 10. Re1 $15 {and White is better because Black cannot castle kingside. Castling queenside is possible, but the king is not very safe there. O-O-O Qa3 . Qc7 Qa3?! Prevents Black from ...Nd6 or ...O-O-O. What used to be a well-established theoretical variation doesn’t stand up to the test of a modern engine. a5! ...axb4 is not yet a threat because the a-pawn is pinned. However, once Black manages to protect the rook (for example by ...b7-b5 or ...Qd8), the white bishop would have to leave the a3-f8 diagonal and Black could play ...Nd6 and ...O-O. White therefore has nothing better than to exchange the knight. Bxe4 f3 Qd8! Be1 Nd6 . dxe4 We have now arrived at a typical position with opposite-colored bishops. It's worth studying this type of position, because even if we don't reach this specific one, the ideas are similar to many variations that can arise from our repertoire. c4 The black king is in the center, but White cannot exploit this straight away. With c2-c4 Geller prepares the pawn break d4-d5, after which the position opens up and the king's safety could become the decisive factor. f6! An important move. Black prepares ...Kf7, after which the rooks are connected and the king is relatively safe. Bd6 Qd7 Rfd1 Other moves have also been tried here, for example Rfe1 Kf7 f3 Sutovsky, E (2465) – Ankerst, M (2285), Ljubljana 1994 (1-0), and now Black should have secured the e4-pawn with Rhd8 Bc5 f5! ( 21...exf3? 22.d5 $16 ) . White does not have enough compensation for the pawn. Kf7 Bc5?! With his previous move Geller had evidently prepared d4-d5, but now he changes his mind, even though the pawn move would have been the best chance.} d5 {exd5 cxd5} 11. Bb5 {Bg3 . The passed d-pawn gives White quite good compensation here. Rhc8 Now White can no longer achieve d4-d5 and has little to show for being a pawn down. The direct b5! was also strong. Rb6 Rd8 h3 a4 White's position is quite solid and it is difficult for Black to make progress. Rbb1 b5 White didn't have to allow that. Now Black gets control of the d5-square and no longer needs to worry about d4-d5. Bb6 Rdc8 c5? Only this is the mistake. The protected passed pawn isn't worth anything here because it's reliably blocked. On the other hand, the white bishop is now excluded from the game and there are no open files, so White has no counterplay. The correct move was cxb5 . Perhaps Geller thought Black couldn't make any progress now, but Khasin finds the correct plan. Qd5 Rd2 Rab8 Qe3 Rb7 a3 Rd7 Re1 Qf5 Qg3 h5! Ba5 g5! Black will open a file on the kingside and attack with the major pieces. White is defenseless against this. Bc3 Rg8 Rde2 h4 Qh2 g4 hxg4 Rxg4 It is becoming increasingly clear that White's position is hopeless. Black will target the g2-pawn. All that is needed is some precision to make sure that White doesn't get any counterplay against the black king. Re3 Kg8 Qb8+ Kh7 Qh2 Rdg7 g3 An inaccuracy. Now White could have put up some resistance with Rg3! . Kg8 R1e2 Qg6 Kf1 Bd5 Ke1 f5 Kd1 hxg3? Up to this point Black has played a very strong game, which he now unfortunately spoils with a series of mistakes, eventually leading to a draw. Rh7 would have won easily. fxg3 Rxg3? Now White gets counterplay against the black king. Still, Rh7 was stronger. Be1! Presumably this is what Khasin had overlooked. If the rook moves, the white queen invades on b8. f4? After that the black pawns are no longer mobile and the white position is probably defensible. After Rxe3 Black is still winning. Perhaps Khasin thought White had a perpetual after Qb8+ , but this is not the case. Kf7} Qc7 $15 {Kf8 Qd8+ ( 48.Qd6+ Re7-+ ) 48...Qe8-+ . Bxg3 fxe3 Rxe3 Be1 . Qf6 Qd2 Qf1+ Be1 Rg1 Qh2 Bb3+ Black hurries to give a perpetual, because now his own king is also very exposed. Kc1 Qc4+ Kb1 Rxe1+ Rxe1 Qd3+ Kb2 Qxd4+ Kb1} 1/2-1/2

