{~ Nguyen – So ~ Asian Continental Chess Championship, Ho Chi Minh City 2009} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 {Be2} Nc6 {bxc6 O-O d5 exd5 cxd5 Nb5 O-O} ({White would like to move the c-pawn and moves the knight to unblock it. The knight later goes to d4. However, it would have been more accurate to strengthen control of the center first. Bf4 O-O and only now Nb5 keeps the balance. Instead,} 5... a6 $15 {would have exploited the opponent's inaccuracy. We now have two possible continuations: A) Nd4 Bd6 . Black thus prevents 12.Bf4 and threatens ...e6-e5. B) 11.c3 Be7 12.Nd4 Qc7 $15 . Black threatens to control even more space in the center after ...e6-e5.}) {c4?! Understandable. Black has two pawns in the center, so White wants to exchange one of them. However, it was better to play Bf4 to block the opponent's center. a6 Nd4 Qc7 Prevents 13.Bf4 and attacks the c-pawn. cxd5} 6. Nd5 {By exchanging, White has ensured that Black does not get a strong pawn center. The problem is now different: the black pieces are more active and can put pressure on both wings. First Black sets his sights on the kingside with ...Bb7 and ...Bd6. Bf3 Bb7 Qa4?!} ({There was already no simple solution, but Nguyen is neglecting his queenside development. Better was} 6. Bd2 Bd6 {and now Stockfish suggests the pawn sacrifice} 7. Rc1 $5 {. A)} Bxh2 {Kh1 Qe5 Ne2 is unclear. The bishop on h2 is in danger of being trapped. B) 16...Qb6 17.Qa4! ( 17.Nb3?! a5 forces White back into a very passive position) 17...Qxb2 18.Rc2 . B.1) After 18...Qb6 19.Ba5 Qa7 20.Nc6 Bxc6 21.Rxc6 White has good compensation for the pawn. B.2) 18...Qa3 19.Qxa3 Bxa3 20.Rb1 . White does have some play on the queenside for the pawn, although Black is still slightly better.}) 6... Bd6 7. g3 Be5 $1 {It's now not easy for White to develop the queenside. The bishop puts pressure on the knight and - if it moves away - on the b2-pawn.} 8. Bg2 ({Directed against ...Nb6, as White’s light-squared bishop is now protected. After} 8. Bd2 {Nb6! White would have to resort to Ba5! but loses a pawn. ( 18.Qb4? loses a piece: 18...Bxd4! 19.Bxb7 Qxb7 20.Qxd4 Rfd8 . The queen is being chased and can't keep the bishop protected, for example 21.Qf4 e5! 22.Qb4 ( 22.Qe3 Nc4-+ ) 22...a5 23.Qc3 Rac8! 24.Qxa5 Rd5 25.Qb4 Rc4 followed by ...Rxd2.) Back to 18.Ba5!: Nxa4} Bc7 $17 {Bxd4 Bxb7 Ra7 Bc6 Nxb2 .}) ({Rfc8 Renews the threat ...Nb6 and increases the pressure on the queenside. After} 8. Nb6 {White now has Qc2 .}) {Nf3 Bf6 The situation for White is not easy. The c1-bishop cannot be developed because it is tied to the defense of the b2-pawn. To add insult to injury, Black threatens to increase the pressure on the b-pawn with ...Rab8. Rb1 Bc6! Qg4? After that White can no longer get back into the game. The queen had to be kept on the queenside in order to prevent the following bishop maneuver. Bb5 Rd1 Be2 Re1 Bd3 Ra1} 8... Rb8 {The pawn on b2 cannot be saved.} 9. a3 {Qc2 Ng5 Bf5 Qf3} Bxd4 {Ne4 Bxe4 Rxe4 Bxb2 Bxb2 Qxb2 The next target is the a-pawn. Ree1} 10. Nc3 {h4} h6 {Qe3 Rb3 Qa7? White’s search for counterplay is understandable, but this attempt fails tactically.} 11. Ne2 {Kh2 Nc1! Black wins an exchange. Raxc1 Rxc1 Rxc1 Qxc1-+ Qa8+ Kh7 Qe4+} {Qxa6 Rbb8 does no help either.} g6 {h5 Qg5 hxg6+ Qxg6 Qh4 Qg5 Qe4+ Kg7} 12. Qxd4 {Qf6 Qg4+ Kh8 Qa4 Rb2 f4} e5 0-1

