{~ Meijers – Ehlvest ~ Zonal tournament Mežezers 2000} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Bd3 Nc6 6. Nxc6 bxc6 7. O-O d5 8. e5 {Re1} a5 9. Nd2 Ba6 10. Qg4 {We have deliberately waited with the development of the f8-bishop so that this queen move does not attack the g7-pawn. However, now White has run out of clearly useful moves and decides to play Qg4 anyway. But perhaps they would have been better off exchanging on a6 first. As we'll see in the game, the change in pawn structure that comes with an exchange on d3 gives Black additional options on the queenside.} g6 ({This weakens the black squares, but the bishop can be developed to g7, from where it attacks the pawn on e5. There were many good alternatives, of which I particularly like the double-edged} 10... Bxd3 11. cxd3 h5 12. Qg3 {(after other queen moves the bishop can be developed)} g5 $5 {. Black gains space on the kingside and will focus their play on the pawn weaknesses e5 and d3.}) 11. Nf3 Bg7 12. h4 {Qg3} Bxd3 {White had already threatened a piece sacrifice on g6, so there was no point in deferring the bishop exchange further.} 13. cxd3 c5 {A good positional move. Black makes d3-d4 more difficult, which leaves the pawns e5 and d3 as targets. We are still familiar with this position from the theory section [/variation/31423252/#/15/b].} 14. Bg5 Qb8 {Re2 Ra6 While White's play on the kingside has led to nothing, Black is slowly developing threats on the queenside and in the center. Black has the initiative.} 15. Qf4 $17 {Rb6 b3?!} ({This gives Black the pawn break ...a5-a4. Stronger was} 15. Qa4+ {, which would have preserved equal chances for White.}) {Rb4 Qe3} 15... a4 {bxa4 Rxa4 Now the a-pawn is weak. Rc1 White is looking for counterplay against the black c-pawn. There is an impending exchange sacrifice ...Rxc5. Qa7 Rb2?} ({Up to this point White had defended well, but now he miscalculates. Necessary was Rec2 was necessary, with the idea of} 15... O-O {Be7 . White wins the c-pawn, Black the a-pawn. The position is equal. After 23...Rxa2 24.Rxa2 Qxa2 25.Rxc5! follows, !, after which White is slightly better. Black must not take the rook: 25...Nxc5? 26.Qxc5 . The mating threats on e7 and c8 are decisive. A more promising attempt for Black was thus the preparatory 23...Ra5 .}) {O-O The second rook now also joins the game. White's pawn weaknesses are almost impossible to defend. Be7 A very forcing move. A passive defense doesn't fare any better, for example: Rcc2 Rb8 . Black puts pressure on the pawns a2, e5 and d3 and has very good winning chances. Nxe5! Bxf8? The decisive mistake. I am not so sure what Meijers could have overlooked in the following sequence. Necessary was Bxc5 Nxf3+ Qxf3 . Black now has many ways to hold on to the advantage, for example Bxb2 (26...Da8 is also good, the white pawns remain weak) Bxa7 Bxc1 . Black is better, but it's not so clear to me whether that's enough to secure the full point. Nxf3+ Qxf3 Bxb2 Bxc5 Qa5} 16. Z0 ({White now loses more material or gets mated. The game was ultimately decided by a gross mistake, but I don't think that this came about by chance: GM Ehlvest built up strong positional pressure and forced his opponent into a difficult defense. White's attempts to attack on the kingside were easily fended off. A possible finish would have been: Rc2 Qe1+} 16. Kh2 {Be5+ g3 Rxh4+ Kg2 Qh1 .}) 0-1

