{In this chapter, you will find a selection of exercises. They are all taken from practical games, and I made sure to choose exercises that are relevant to our repertoire. Solving them will give you the opportunity to test and train your intuition in the Sicilian Four Knights Variation. Before you begin, here are some guidelines: 1) Although this is a repertoire for Black, many of the exercises are presented from the perspective of White. This is because, over the board, we should not only focus on our own ideas but also be familiar with our opponents' ressources. 2) About half of the exercises are tactical in nature, while the other half involve positional decisions. Sometimes, a winning move is sought, and other times, it might be the correct exchange of a piece. You won't know what to expect, just like in a practical game! 3) All exercises have been carefully checked with the engine, and I made sure that the solutions are as clear as possible. However, in the positional exercises, there may be only slight differences in evaluations between different moves. In such cases, the choice of move may come down to personal preference. If you disagree with a proposed solution, feel free to use the comment function. We can then discuss your alternative solution. 4) The exercises are roughly sorted in ascending order of difficulty. In conclusion, I would like to thank my chess friends from Hamburg IM Dirk Sebastian and FM Martin Voigt, whose help was instrumental in creating this chapter. They provided me with a database of potential exercises, greatly facilitating my search for suitable material. If you enjoy the concept of thematic exercises, I highly recommend the excellent collections that Dirk and Martin have published here on Chessable! Now, have fun solving the exercises!} 1. Z0 *

