1... Rxc3 $1 {The exchange sacrifice should come naturally here. Otherwise, Black would have to defend a passive and slightly worse position.} 2. bxc3 Qxa3+ {Even though there is no forced continuation, it is clear that the sacrifice has paid off. Black has gained a pawn for the exchange, and the white king is vulnerable. In the game, 26.Kd2 Nd6!? was played, and now White should have embraced the complications with 27.Rxd5! (which Stockfish assesses as equal). The move played in the game, 27.Bf1 , was a mistake and could have been punished with 27...Rc8-+ . There is no good defence of the c3-pawn, as after 28.Re3 or ( 28.Qe3 , the fork 28...Nf5 follows.} *

