{The point. The white queen is overloaded with the defense of the knight and the rook. Black is winning because the weak white pawns will soon fall. Here we see why it was necessary to play 25...d5 first: If the pawn was still on e4, White could play f2-f4 and interrupt the attack of the black queen on the rook. Now, f4? would be simply met by Rxf4 .} {Should black exchange bishops?} 24... Bxc4 $1 {From a positional point of view, this would not be a good trade for Black as they would be giving up control over the important d5-square. However, there is a hidden tactical idea.} 25. Nxc4 ({After} 25. Qxc4 Nd4 {back wins material: A)} 26. f4 Rxc4 27. fxg5 Rxc3 $17 {. B) 26.Qd3 Nf3+ 27.Kh1 Nxd2 $17 .}) 25... d5 $1 {As we will see later, an important intermediate move.} 26. exd5 {cxb4} (26. f4 {Nxd3 fxg5 Rxc4 Rxd3} dxe4 {.}) {Rxc4-+} 26... Z0 *

